// MedMasters: Gynae & Obs Paper 2: Maternal Pharmacology - Complete (Q1-Q600)
// 600 MCQs
(function(){
  if(!window.MM) window.MM={};
  window.MM['gynae_p2_pharma'] = [
    {q:'A 24-year-old pregnant woman at 7 weeks gestation is exposed to a drug that causes limb reduction defects by inhibiting angiogenesis during early embryogenesis. Which drug is most likely responsible?',o:['Warfarin','Methotrexate','Isotretinoin','Thalidomide'],a:3,
    e:`Thalidomide is the classical teratogen causing limb reduction defects (phocomelia) by inhibiting angiogenesis during early embryogenesis. The critical window is approximately days 20 to 36 of gestation.<br><br>The mechanism involves anti-angiogenic activity that disrupts vascular development of the developing limb buds, producing characteristic upper limb defects ranging from amelia to phocomelia. Thalidomide also affects ear, cardiac and gastrointestinal development.<br><br>D (Thalidomide) is correct because its anti-angiogenic action precisely matches the question stem. A (Warfarin) is wrong because it causes warfarin embryopathy (nasal hypoplasia, stippled epiphyses), not angiogenesis-related limb defects. B (Methotrexate) is wrong because it causes folate antagonism with craniofacial and skeletal anomalies. C (Isotretinoin) is wrong because it causes retinoid embryopathy with craniofacial and cardiac defects.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Special Aspects of Perinatal Pharmacology)</em>`},
    {q:'A woman treated for acne becomes pregnant while taking a medication that causes craniofacial abnormalities, thymic hypoplasia, and cardiac defects. Which drug is the likely cause?',o:['Tetracycline','Valproic acid','Isotretinoin','Carbamazepine'],a:2,
    e:`Isotretinoin is a retinoic acid derivative that produces retinoid embryopathy when used during pregnancy. The triad includes craniofacial abnormalities, thymic hypoplasia, and cardiac (conotruncal) defects.<br><br>Retinoids disrupt neural crest cell migration and differentiation, affecting structures derived from neural crest including the face, thymus and cardiac outflow tract. The drug requires strict pregnancy-prevention programmes during use.<br><br>C (Isotretinoin) is correct because the described triad is the hallmark of retinoid embryopathy. A (Tetracycline) is wrong because it causes tooth discoloration and bone growth inhibition rather than craniofacial-thymic-cardiac defects. B (Valproic acid) is wrong because it produces neural tube defects, not the conotruncal-thymic pattern. D (Carbamazepine) is wrong because it is associated with neural tube defects and craniofacial features distinct from retinoid embryopathy.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics; Chapter: Teratology, Teratogens, and Fetotoxic Agents)</em>`},
    {q:'A pregnant woman at 10 weeks gestation has been taking an anticoagulant for a prosthetic heart valve. The fetus is at risk of nasal hypoplasia and stippled epiphyses. Which drug exposure explains this finding?',o:['Warfarin','Aspirin','Heparin','Clopidogrel'],a:0,
    e:`Warfarin during weeks 6 to 9 of gestation produces warfarin embryopathy, characterised by nasal hypoplasia and stippled epiphyses (chondrodysplasia punctata). Warfarin readily crosses the placenta and inhibits vitamin K-dependent calcium-binding proteins essential for bone development.<br><br>Later exposure can cause CNS abnormalities and fetal haemorrhage. Heparin is preferred during the first trimester because it does not cross the placenta. Prosthetic valve management may switch back to warfarin in the second trimester after the embryopathy window has passed.<br><br>A (Warfarin) is correct because the described pattern of nasal hypoplasia and stippled epiphyses is classic warfarin embryopathy. B (Aspirin) is wrong because low-dose aspirin is generally considered safe in pregnancy and does not cause this pattern. C (Heparin) is wrong because heparin does not cross the placenta and is therefore non-teratogenic. D (Clopidogrel) is wrong because it is not associated with this characteristic embryopathy.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics; Chapter: Teratology, Teratogens, and Fetotoxic Agents)</em>`},
    {q:'A woman with epilepsy becomes pregnant while taking valproate. Which congenital anomaly is most strongly associated with this exposure?',o:['Renal agenesis','Neural tube defects','Limb reduction defects','Duodenal atresia'],a:1,
    e:`Sodium valproate is the antiepileptic most strongly associated with neural tube defects (spina bifida and anencephaly) when taken during the first trimester. The risk is dose-dependent, with rates of around 1 to 2 percent.<br><br>The mechanism involves inhibition of folate metabolism and direct interference with neural tube closure between days 21 and 28 of gestation. High-dose folic acid supplementation (5 mg/day) is recommended in women of childbearing age on valproate, and switching to safer agents like lamotrigine is preferred when feasible.<br><br>B (Neural tube defects) is correct because valproate-induced disruption of folate metabolism and neural tube closure is the classic association. A (Renal agenesis) is wrong because this is the ACE inhibitor pattern, not valproate. C (Limb reduction defects) is wrong because this is thalidomide\'s signature. D (Duodenal atresia) is wrong because it is not associated with valproate exposure.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Antiseizure Drugs)</em>`},
    {q:'A pregnant woman treated with tetracycline for acne during the second trimester may cause which fetal complication?',o:['Cataracts','Cardiac septal defects','Limb hypoplasia','Tooth discoloration and inhibition of bone growth'],a:3,
    e:`Tetracyclines bind calcium ions and chelate to developing bone and teeth, causing permanent yellow-brown discoloration of deciduous and permanent teeth and inhibition of fetal bone growth when used after the fourth month of gestation.<br><br>The drug crosses the placenta freely and concentrates in calcifying tissues. Tetracyclines are also avoided during breastfeeding for the same reason. Penicillins, cephalosporins and erythromycin are safer alternatives for most maternal infections.<br><br>D (Tooth discoloration and inhibition of bone growth) is correct because calcium chelation by tetracycline in calcifying fetal tissues is the well-established effect. A (Cataracts) is wrong because tetracyclines do not cause cataracts. B (Cardiac septal defects) is wrong because they are not a tetracycline effect. C (Limb hypoplasia) is wrong because limb defects are characteristic of thalidomide, not tetracycline.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Tetracyclines, Macrolides, Clindamycin, Chloramphenicol, Streptogramins, and Oxazolidinones)</em>`},
    {q:'A woman with bipolar disorder becomes pregnant while taking lithium. Which fetal anomaly is most associated with lithium exposure in early pregnancy?',o:['Tetralogy of Fallot','Transposition of great arteries','Ebstein anomaly','Ventricular septal defect'],a:2,
    e:`Lithium exposure in the first trimester is classically associated with Ebstein anomaly, a congenital cardiac malformation with apical displacement of the tricuspid valve and atrialisation of the right ventricle.<br><br>The absolute risk is small (approximately 1 in 1000) but considerably higher than the background population rate. Fetal echocardiography is recommended for women exposed to lithium in early pregnancy. Where possible, lithium is replaced with safer mood stabilisers preconceptionally.<br><br>C (Ebstein anomaly) is correct because the lithium-Ebstein association is a classic teaching point in obstetric pharmacology. A (Tetralogy of Fallot) is wrong because it is not specifically linked to lithium. B (Transposition of great arteries) is wrong because it is associated with maternal diabetes, not lithium. D (Ventricular septal defect) is wrong because it is the most common cardiac anomaly overall but not specifically linked to lithium.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics; Chapter: Teratology, Teratogens, and Fetotoxic Agents)</em>`},
    {q:'A pregnant woman with epilepsy requires treatment. Which of the following antiepileptic drugs is considered relatively safer during pregnancy compared with valproate?',o:['Valproic acid','Lamotrigine','Phenytoin','Carbamazepine'],a:1,
    e:`Lamotrigine is considered one of the safer antiepileptic drugs in pregnancy compared with valproate. Major malformation rates are similar to baseline at typical doses, though higher doses may slightly increase risk.<br><br>Levetiracetam is also relatively safe. Valproate carries the highest teratogenic risk among common antiepileptics (10 percent major malformations). Carbamazepine and phenytoin carry intermediate risk. Switching to lamotrigine or levetiracetam pre-pregnancy is preferred when seizure control allows.<br><br>B (Lamotrigine) is correct because it is the established safer choice with the lowest teratogenic profile among major antiepileptics. A (Valproic acid) is wrong because it is the most teratogenic, the very drug being avoided. C (Phenytoin) is wrong because it produces fetal hydantoin syndrome. D (Carbamazepine) is wrong because it carries higher neural tube defect risk than lamotrigine.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Antiseizure Drugs)</em>`},
    {q:'A fetus develops growth restriction and microcephaly after maternal exposure to alcohol during pregnancy. What is the underlying mechanism of alcohol teratogenicity?',o:['Disruption of neural crest cell migration','Increased placental blood flow','Excess fetal insulin production','Increased estrogen synthesis'],a:0,
    e:`Alcohol teratogenicity is mediated principally through disruption of neural crest cell migration during early embryogenesis, producing the characteristic facial dysmorphism, growth restriction and CNS dysfunction of fetal alcohol syndrome.<br><br>Additional mechanisms include oxidative stress, apoptosis of neural crest cells, and inhibition of cell adhesion molecules. The teratogenic effect is dose-dependent but no safe threshold has been established, so abstinence is recommended throughout pregnancy.<br><br>A (Disruption of neural crest cell migration) is correct because this is the established mechanism of alcohol\'s effects on midline facial development and CNS structures. B (Increased placental blood flow) is wrong because alcohol reduces, not increases, placental perfusion. C (Excess fetal insulin production) is wrong because this is the mechanism in maternal diabetes, not alcohol. D (Increased estrogen synthesis) is wrong because it is unrelated to alcohol teratogenicity.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics; Chapter: Teratology, Teratogens, and Fetotoxic Agents)</em>`},
    {q:'A pregnant woman taking ACE inhibitors during the second trimester exposes the fetus to which complication?',o:['Neural tube defect','Renal dysgenesis and oligohydramnios','Limb reduction defects','Cleft palate'],a:1,
    e:`ACE inhibitor exposure in the second and third trimesters causes fetal renal dysgenesis with consequent oligohydramnios. Reduced fetal renal perfusion impairs urine production, depleting amniotic fluid which is largely fetal urine after the first trimester.<br><br>The full ACE inhibitor fetopathy includes oligohydramnios, pulmonary hypoplasia (from low fluid), limb contractures, calvarial hypoplasia and neonatal renal failure. Angiotensin receptor blockers cause similar effects. Methyldopa, labetalol and nifedipine are safer pregnancy alternatives.<br><br>B (Renal dysgenesis and oligohydramnios) is correct because reduced fetal angiotensin II activity impairs renal development and urine output. A (Neural tube defect) is wrong because ACE inhibitors are not first-trimester teratogens of this type. C (Limb reduction defects) is wrong because that is the thalidomide pattern. D (Cleft palate) is wrong because it is not a recognised ACE inhibitor effect.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics; Chapter: Teratology, Teratogens, and Fetotoxic Agents)</em>`},
    {q:'A woman with prosthetic valve anticoagulation becomes pregnant. Which anticoagulant is considered safer during pregnancy as it does not cross the placenta?',o:['Warfarin','Dabigatran','Heparin','Rivaroxaban'],a:2,
    e:`Heparin is preferred for anticoagulation in pregnancy because it is a large, polar, highly charged molecule that does not cross the placenta, making it non-teratogenic. Low-molecular-weight heparin is generally favoured over unfractionated heparin.<br><br>Warfarin crosses the placenta and causes warfarin embryopathy at 6 to 9 weeks (nasal hypoplasia, stippled epiphyses) and CNS abnormalities later. Direct oral anticoagulants such as dabigatran and rivaroxaban are not recommended in pregnancy due to limited safety data.<br><br>C (Heparin) is correct because its inability to cross the placenta makes it the safe anticoagulant of choice. A (Warfarin) is wrong because it crosses the placenta and is teratogenic. B (Dabigatran) is wrong because direct oral anticoagulants are contraindicated in pregnancy. D (Rivaroxaban) is wrong because it crosses the placenta and is contraindicated.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Drugs Used in Disorders of Coagulation)</em>`},
    {q:'A pregnant woman treated with methotrexate early in pregnancy is at risk of fetal anomalies primarily due to inhibition of which biochemical pathway?',o:['DNA methylation','Fatty acid synthesis','Glycolysis','Folate metabolism'],a:3,
    e:`Methotrexate exerts its teratogenic effect by inhibiting dihydrofolate reductase, blocking the conversion of dihydrofolate to tetrahydrofolate and disrupting folate metabolism. This impairs DNA synthesis and cell division during organogenesis.<br><br>Methotrexate teratogenicity (aminopterin syndrome) includes craniofacial anomalies, skeletal defects and CNS malformations. The drug is also used as an abortifacient in ectopic pregnancy management. Folic acid supplementation does not fully protect against the antifolate effect at therapeutic methotrexate doses.<br><br>D (Folate metabolism) is correct because methotrexate is a folate antagonist via dihydrofolate reductase inhibition. A (DNA methylation) is wrong because methotrexate does not directly target methylation pathways. B (Fatty acid synthesis) is wrong because it is unrelated to methotrexate. C (Glycolysis) is wrong because it is not a methotrexate target.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Cancer Chemotherapy)</em>`},
    {q:'A fetus exposed to phenytoin during pregnancy may develop fetal hydantoin syndrome. Which feature is characteristic of this syndrome?',o:['Microcephaly and facial dysmorphism','Limb reduction defects','Macrocephaly','Renal agenesis'],a:0,
    e:`Fetal hydantoin syndrome from phenytoin exposure is characterised by microcephaly, facial dysmorphism (broad nasal bridge, hypertelorism, cleft lip/palate), digital hypoplasia, growth restriction and developmental delay.<br><br>The mechanism involves phenytoin\'s epoxide intermediates, which exert oxidative damage on developing tissues, particularly with deficient epoxide hydrolase activity. Risk is approximately 5 to 10 percent for full syndrome and higher for individual features. Folic acid supplementation is recommended.<br><br>A (Microcephaly and facial dysmorphism) is correct because these are the hallmark features of fetal hydantoin syndrome. B (Limb reduction defects) is wrong because they are characteristic of thalidomide. C (Macrocephaly) is wrong because hydantoin syndrome causes microcephaly, not macrocephaly. D (Renal agenesis) is wrong because it is the ACE inhibitor pattern.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Antiseizure Drugs)</em>`},
    {q:'A pregnant woman treated with aminoglycosides for infection exposes the fetus to which risk?',o:['Congenital cataracts','Neural tube defects','Limb reduction defects','Ototoxicity'],a:3,
    e:`Aminoglycosides such as streptomycin, gentamicin and amikacin cause fetal ototoxicity by damaging the developing eighth cranial nerve, leading to congenital sensorineural deafness. The risk is greatest with prolonged exposure.<br><br>Streptomycin is the most documented offender historically, particularly in tuberculosis treatment. The drug accumulates in the fetal inner ear and renal cortex. Aminoglycosides are reserved for serious infections in pregnancy when no safer alternative exists.<br><br>D (Ototoxicity) is correct because aminoglycoside damage to the developing cochlear and vestibular apparatus is the classical fetal effect. A (Congenital cataracts) is wrong because they are associated with rubella, not aminoglycosides. B (Neural tube defects) is wrong because they relate to valproate and folate antagonists. C (Limb reduction defects) is wrong because these are caused by thalidomide.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Aminoglycosides)</em>`},
    {q:'A woman with hypertension during pregnancy requires pharmacologic therapy. Which drug is considered safest in pregnancy?',o:['Enalapril','Losartan','Methyldopa','Captopril'],a:2,
    e:`Methyldopa is a centrally acting α₂-adrenergic agonist with the longest safety record in pregnancy and is widely used as first-line therapy for chronic hypertension and pregnancy-induced hypertension.<br><br>Methyldopa decreases central sympathetic outflow without significantly affecting uteroplacental blood flow. Side effects include sedation, depression and rarely haemolytic anaemia. Labetalol and nifedipine are also widely used. ACE inhibitors and angiotensin receptor blockers are contraindicated.<br><br>C (Methyldopa) is correct because of its long-established safety profile and first-line status in pregnancy. A (Enalapril) is wrong because ACE inhibitors are contraindicated due to fetal renal dysgenesis. B (Losartan) is wrong because angiotensin receptor blockers cause similar fetal effects to ACE inhibitors. D (Captopril) is wrong because it is also an ACE inhibitor and contraindicated.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics; Chapter: Hypertensive Disorders)</em>`},
    {q:'Exposure to diethylstilbestrol (DES) during pregnancy is associated with which complication in female offspring?',o:['Turner syndrome','Clear cell adenocarcinoma of the vagina','Ovarian teratoma','Endometrial hyperplasia'],a:1,
    e:`Diethylstilbestrol (DES), a synthetic non-steroidal oestrogen used between 1940 and 1971 to prevent miscarriage, causes clear cell adenocarcinoma of the vagina and cervix in female offspring (DES daughters), typically presenting in adolescence or young adulthood.<br><br>Other DES-associated effects include cervical and uterine structural abnormalities (T-shaped uterus, cervical hood), increased preterm birth risk, and infertility. In male offspring, DES is associated with hypospadias and testicular abnormalities.<br><br>B (Clear cell adenocarcinoma of the vagina) is correct because this is the iconic DES-associated malignancy. A (Turner syndrome) is wrong because it is a chromosomal disorder unrelated to drug exposure. C (Ovarian teratoma) is wrong because it is a germ cell tumour with no DES association. D (Endometrial hyperplasia) is wrong because it is not the characteristic DES pathology in offspring.<br><br><em>(Shaw\'s Textbook of Gynaecology; Chapter: Hormones in Gynaecology)</em>`},
    {q:'A pregnant woman treated with sulfonamides near term exposes the neonate to which complication?',o:['Kernicterus','Cataracts','Limb defects','Cardiac septal defects'],a:0,
    e:`Sulfonamides given near term displace bilirubin from albumin binding sites in the neonate, increasing free unconjugated bilirubin. Free bilirubin can cross the immature blood-brain barrier and deposit in basal ganglia, causing kernicterus.<br><br>Risk is greatest in preterm infants and those with neonatal hyperbilirubinaemia. Sulfonamides are therefore avoided in the third trimester and during breastfeeding of jaundiced or premature neonates. Earlier in pregnancy, sulfonamides are not contraindicated.<br><br>A (Kernicterus) is correct because bilirubin displacement from albumin by sulfonamides is the established mechanism. B (Cataracts) is wrong because they are not a sulfonamide effect. C (Limb defects) is wrong because limb anomalies are seen with thalidomide. D (Cardiac septal defects) is wrong because they are not a recognised sulfonamide effect.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Sulfonamides, Trimethoprim, and Quinolones)</em>`},
    {q:'Which anti-tuberculosis drug is considered relatively safe for use in pregnancy?',o:['Streptomycin','Isoniazid','Ethionamide','Kanamycin'],a:1,
    e:`Isoniazid is considered relatively safe for tuberculosis treatment in pregnancy. It crosses the placenta but has not been shown to cause major teratogenic effects, and treatment of active TB protects mother and fetus.<br><br>Pyridoxine (vitamin B6) supplementation at 25 to 50 mg daily is recommended to prevent isoniazid-induced peripheral neuropathy. Rifampicin and ethambutol are also acceptable. Streptomycin is contraindicated due to fetal ototoxicity, and pyrazinamide use varies by guideline.<br><br>B (Isoniazid) is correct because of its established safety with pyridoxine cover. A (Streptomycin) is wrong because it is an aminoglycoside causing fetal ototoxicity. C (Ethionamide) is wrong because it is teratogenic and avoided in pregnancy. D (Kanamycin) is wrong because it is also an aminoglycoside causing ototoxicity.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Antimycobacterial Drugs)</em>`},
    {q:'A fetus exposed to carbamazepine during early pregnancy is most at risk for which anomaly?',o:['Polydactyly','Cleft palate only','Renal agenesis','Neural tube defects'],a:3,
    e:`Carbamazepine exposure during organogenesis is associated with neural tube defects (particularly spina bifida), craniofacial abnormalities, fingernail hypoplasia and developmental delay. Risk for neural tube defects is approximately 0.5 to 1 percent above baseline.<br><br>Mechanism involves carbamazepine\'s epoxide metabolites and folate antagonism. High-dose folic acid (5 mg/day) is recommended preconceptionally and through the first trimester. Lamotrigine or levetiracetam are preferred where seizure control allows.<br><br>D (Neural tube defects) is correct because carbamazepine is most strongly associated with spina bifida among its teratogenic effects. A (Polydactyly) is wrong because it is not a carbamazepine effect. B (Cleft palate only) is wrong because cleft palate may occur but is not the characteristic finding. C (Renal agenesis) is wrong because it is the ACE inhibitor pattern.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics; Chapter: Neurological Disorders)</em>`},
    {q:'A pregnant woman treated with misoprostol during early gestation for ulcer disease may cause which fetal abnormality?',o:['Limb defects and Möbius sequence','Neural tube defects','Renal agenesis','Cataracts'],a:0,
    e:`Misoprostol (PGE1 analogue) used as an abortifacient or attempted abortifacient that fails to terminate pregnancy is associated with limb defects and Möbius sequence (congenital facial nerve and abducens palsies) due to vascular disruption.<br><br>The proposed mechanism is uterine contraction-induced fetal vascular hypoperfusion during a critical developmental window, causing brain stem ischaemia (Möbius) and limb-reduction-type defects. Risk is highest with first-trimester exposure.<br><br>A (Limb defects and Möbius sequence) is correct because vascular disruption from misoprostol-induced uterine contractions causes this characteristic pattern. B (Neural tube defects) is wrong because they are not associated with misoprostol. C (Renal agenesis) is wrong because it is the ACE inhibitor pattern. D (Cataracts) is wrong because cataracts are not associated with misoprostol exposure.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics; Chapter: Teratology, Teratogens, and Fetotoxic Agents)</em>`},
    {q:'Which antibiotic is considered the safest first-line therapy for urinary tract infection during pregnancy?',o:['Ciprofloxacin','Tetracycline','Nitrofurantoin','Chloramphenicol'],a:2,
    e:`Nitrofurantoin is widely used as first-line therapy for uncomplicated UTI in pregnancy due to its safety in the first and second trimesters and its activity against common urinary pathogens, especially E. coli.<br><br>Nitrofurantoin is avoided in late third trimester and during labour because it can cause neonatal haemolysis in G6PD-deficient infants. Cephalexin and amoxicillin are also acceptable. Ciprofloxacin (cartilage toxicity), tetracycline (tooth staining) and chloramphenicol (gray baby syndrome) are avoided.<br><br>C (Nitrofurantoin) is correct because it is the established first-line UTI agent in pregnancy outside late term. A (Ciprofloxacin) is wrong because fluoroquinolones cause cartilage toxicity in animal studies and are avoided. B (Tetracycline) is wrong because it causes tooth discoloration. D (Chloramphenicol) is wrong because it can cause gray baby syndrome.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Common medical disorders in pregnancy)</em>`},
    {q:'A pregnant woman exposed to retinoic acid derivatives during organogenesis is most likely to produce which fetal abnormality?',o:['Neural tube closure failure only','Craniofacial and cardiac malformations','Polycystic kidneys','Gastroschisis'],a:1,
    e:`Retinoic acid derivatives (isotretinoin, etretinate, acitretin) cause retinoid embryopathy with the classic combination of craniofacial malformations (microtia, micrognathia, cleft palate), cardiac defects (conotruncal anomalies), and CNS abnormalities (hydrocephalus).<br><br>Retinoids disrupt neural crest cell migration. Isotretinoin half-life is short but contraception is required for one month after stopping. Etretinate has a much longer half-life requiring contraception for 2 to 3 years after discontinuation.<br><br>B (Craniofacial and cardiac malformations) is correct because the combination of these defects is the hallmark of retinoid embryopathy. A (Neural tube closure failure only) is wrong because retinoids cause a broader pattern with cardiac and craniofacial features. C (Polycystic kidneys) is wrong because they are not characteristic of retinoid exposure. D (Gastroschisis) is wrong because it is associated with cocaine and young maternal age, not retinoids.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics; Chapter: Teratology, Teratogens, and Fetotoxic Agents)</em>`},
    {q:'A fetus exposed to high doses of radiation during the period of organogenesis is most likely to develop which complication?',o:['Structural congenital malformations','Preterm labour only','Placental abruption','Macrosomia'],a:0,
    e:`High-dose ionising radiation during organogenesis (weeks 2 to 8 post-conception) causes structural congenital malformations including microcephaly, growth restriction, eye anomalies and intellectual disability. The minimum threshold for human teratogenicity is approximately 100 mGy.<br><br>Diagnostic imaging exposures are typically far below this threshold (a single chest X-ray ~0.1 mGy). Effects depend on dose and gestational age: pre-implantation period shows all-or-none effect, organogenesis is most teratogenic, and later periods cause growth restriction and CNS effects.<br><br>A (Structural congenital malformations) is correct because high-dose radiation during organogenesis is the established cause of structural anomalies. B (Preterm labour only) is wrong because radiation does not primarily cause preterm labour. C (Placental abruption) is wrong because it is not a radiation effect. D (Macrosomia) is wrong because radiation causes growth restriction, not macrosomia.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics; Chapter: Teratology, Teratogens, and Fetotoxic Agents)</em>`},
    {q:'A pregnant patient with malaria requires treatment. Which drug is considered safe during pregnancy?',o:['Primaquine','Doxycycline','Chloroquine','Tetracycline'],a:2,
    e:`Chloroquine is considered safe for malaria treatment and prophylaxis in pregnancy, including the first trimester. Decades of use show no consistent teratogenic effect at antimalarial doses.<br><br>Chloroquine remains effective in chloroquine-sensitive areas; quinine, mefloquine and artemisinin combinations are used for resistant strains. Doxycycline (tooth staining) and primaquine (haemolysis in G6PD-deficient fetus) are contraindicated in pregnancy.<br><br>C (Chloroquine) is correct because of its long established safety record in pregnancy. A (Primaquine) is wrong because it can cause haemolysis in G6PD-deficient fetuses and is avoided. B (Doxycycline) is wrong because tetracyclines cause tooth discoloration. D (Tetracycline) is wrong for the same reason as doxycycline.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Antiprotozoal Drugs)</em>`},
    {q:'Which analgesic should generally be avoided in the third trimester because of risk of premature closure of the ductus arteriosus?',o:['Paracetamol','Tramadol','Codeine','Ibuprofen'],a:3,
    e:`Ibuprofen and other NSAIDs are avoided in the third trimester (after 30 weeks) because they inhibit prostaglandin synthesis and can cause premature closure of the fetal ductus arteriosus, leading to pulmonary hypertension and right heart failure.<br><br>NSAIDs may also cause oligohydramnios via reduced fetal renal perfusion and prolong labour by inhibiting uterine contractions. Paracetamol is preferred for pain and fever throughout pregnancy. NSAIDs may be used cautiously in the first and second trimesters.<br><br>D (Ibuprofen) is correct because COX inhibition reduces prostaglandin maintenance of ductal patency, causing premature closure. A (Paracetamol) is wrong because it has minimal COX inhibition and is safe in pregnancy. B (Tramadol) is wrong because it is an opioid, not an NSAID, and does not cause this effect. C (Codeine) is wrong because it is also an opioid without prostaglandin effects.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Nonsteroidal Anti-Inflammatory Drugs)</em>`},
    {q:'A fetus exposed to high doses of maternal corticosteroids during early pregnancy may develop which complication?',o:['Renal agenesis','Neural tube defects','Cleft palate','Limb absence'],a:2,
    e:`High-dose maternal corticosteroid exposure in the first trimester is associated with a small increased risk of cleft palate. The absolute risk increase is small (approximately 0.1 to 0.3 percent) and the benefit of treating maternal disease usually outweighs this risk.<br><br>Corticosteroids do cross the placenta to varying degrees. Prednisolone is largely metabolised by placental 11β-hydroxysteroid dehydrogenase, limiting fetal exposure. Betamethasone and dexamethasone cross more readily and are used therapeutically for fetal lung maturation in preterm labour.<br><br>C (Cleft palate) is correct because the small but recognised teratogenic effect of high-dose first-trimester steroids is on palatal closure. A (Renal agenesis) is wrong because it is the ACE inhibitor pattern. B (Neural tube defects) is wrong because they are not a steroid effect. D (Limb absence) is wrong because limb defects are caused by thalidomide.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics; Chapter: Teratology, Teratogens, and Fetotoxic Agents)</em>`},
    {q:'A pregnant woman requires treatment for hyperthyroidism. Which drug is preferred during the first trimester?',o:['Propylthiouracil','Methimazole','Carbimazole','Radioiodine'],a:0,
    e:`Propylthiouracil (PTU) is preferred over methimazole/carbimazole during the first trimester for treating hyperthyroidism in pregnancy, because methimazole is associated with aplasia cutis and methimazole embryopathy (choanal/oesophageal atresia).<br><br>After the first trimester, methimazole or carbimazole is preferred because PTU carries a higher risk of maternal hepatotoxicity. Both drugs cross the placenta and can cause fetal hypothyroidism and goitre at high doses, so the lowest effective dose is used.<br><br>A (Propylthiouracil) is correct because it avoids the methimazole-related embryopathy in the critical first trimester. B (Methimazole) is wrong because it is associated with aplasia cutis and embryopathy if used in the first trimester. C (Carbimazole) is wrong because it is the prodrug of methimazole and shares the same teratogenicity. D (Radioiodine) is wrong because it is absolutely contraindicated and ablates the fetal thyroid.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics; Chapter: Endocrine Disorders)</em>`},
    {q:'Which drug used for migraine prophylaxis is contraindicated in pregnancy due to uterine vasoconstriction and fetal hypoxia?',o:['Paracetamol','Ergotamine','Propranolol','Metoclopramide'],a:1,
    e:`Ergotamine and dihydroergotamine are contraindicated in pregnancy because they cause uterine vasoconstriction, increasing the risk of fetal hypoxia, growth restriction and pregnancy loss. They also have potent oxytocic effects that can stimulate preterm labour.<br><br>Migraine in pregnancy is managed with paracetamol, occasional codeine, beta-blockers (propranolol) for prophylaxis, and lifestyle measures. Triptans have limited but reassuring data and may be used cautiously when essential.<br><br>B (Ergotamine) is correct because uterine and uteroplacental vasoconstriction precisely matches the question stem. A (Paracetamol) is wrong because it is the safest analgesic in pregnancy. C (Propranolol) is wrong because beta-blockers are widely used in pregnancy migraine prophylaxis. D (Metoclopramide) is wrong because it is used as an antiemetic and is not a vasoconstrictor.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Histamine, Serotonin, and the Ergot Alkaloids)</em>`},
    {q:'A pregnant woman exposed to chloramphenicol near term risks causing which neonatal syndrome?',o:['Hydantoin syndrome','Blue baby syndrome','Fetal alcohol syndrome','Gray baby syndrome'],a:3,
    e:`Chloramphenicol given near term causes gray baby syndrome in neonates, characterised by pallor (gray colour), abdominal distension, vomiting, hypotension and circulatory collapse, often fatal if not recognised.<br><br>Mechanism is failure to glucuronidate chloramphenicol due to immature neonatal liver enzymes (UDP-glucuronosyltransferase) and reduced renal excretion, leading to drug accumulation. Chloramphenicol also inhibits mitochondrial protein synthesis. Use is therefore avoided in late pregnancy and neonates.<br><br>D (Gray baby syndrome) is correct because the syndrome is the well-described chloramphenicol effect in neonates. A (Hydantoin syndrome) is wrong because it is caused by phenytoin. B (Blue baby syndrome) is wrong because it refers to congenital cyanotic heart disease, not a drug effect. C (Fetal alcohol syndrome) is wrong because it is caused by alcohol.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Tetracyclines, Macrolides, Clindamycin, Chloramphenicol, Streptogramins, and Oxazolidinones)</em>`},
    {q:'Which antibiotic is safest for treating syphilis during pregnancy?',o:['Doxycycline','Penicillin','Azithromycin','Tetracycline'],a:1,
    e:`Penicillin (typically benzathine penicillin G) is the drug of choice for treating syphilis in pregnancy. It crosses the placenta and effectively treats both maternal and fetal infection, preventing congenital syphilis.<br><br>Penicillin-allergic pregnant women should undergo desensitisation rather than receive alternative drugs, because doxycycline is contraindicated (tetracycline class) and erythromycin does not reliably treat fetal infection. Treatment must be completed at least 30 days before delivery.<br><br>B (Penicillin) is correct because it is the only effective treatment for fetal syphilis and is safe in pregnancy. A (Doxycycline) is wrong because it is a tetracycline causing tooth discoloration. C (Azithromycin) is wrong because resistance is rising and it does not reliably cross the placenta to treat fetal infection. D (Tetracycline) is wrong because it is contraindicated in pregnancy.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Perinatal infections)</em>`},
    {q:'Exposure to high doses of vitamin A derivatives during pregnancy is most associated with which congenital abnormality?',o:['Congenital cataracts','Polydactyly','Hypospadias','Craniofacial malformations'],a:3,
    e:`High-dose vitamin A (retinoid) exposure during pregnancy is associated with craniofacial malformations as part of the retinoid embryopathy spectrum. Doses above 10,000 IU/day are considered potentially teratogenic.<br><br>The mechanism involves disruption of neural crest cell migration. Beta-carotene (provitamin A) is not teratogenic because conversion to retinol is regulated. Pregnant women are advised to avoid liver and high-dose vitamin A supplements.<br><br>D (Craniofacial malformations) is correct because high-dose vitamin A causes the same retinoid embryopathy pattern as isotretinoin, with craniofacial features prominent. A (Congenital cataracts) is wrong because they are associated with rubella, not vitamin A. B (Polydactyly) is wrong because it is not a retinoid effect. C (Hypospadias) is wrong because it is not a vitamin A effect.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics; Chapter: Teratology, Teratogens, and Fetotoxic Agents)</em>`},
    {q:'A pregnant woman with hypertension develops pre-eclampsia and requires seizure prophylaxis. Which drug is used safely in pregnancy for this purpose?',o:['Phenytoin','Diazepam','Magnesium sulfate','Valproate'],a:2,
    e:`Magnesium sulfate is the drug of choice for seizure prophylaxis in pre-eclampsia and treatment of eclampsia. It also has neuroprotective effects in preterm infants.<br><br>Mechanism involves NMDA receptor antagonism, calcium channel modulation and cerebral vasodilation. Loading dose is typically 4 g IV followed by maintenance infusion of 1 g/hour. Toxicity (loss of deep tendon reflexes, respiratory depression) is reversed with calcium gluconate.<br><br>C (Magnesium sulfate) is correct because it is the established first-line agent for eclampsia prophylaxis and treatment. A (Phenytoin) is wrong because magnesium is superior in preventing eclamptic seizures. B (Diazepam) is wrong because it has poor efficacy compared to magnesium and causes neonatal floppy infant syndrome. D (Valproate) is wrong because it is teratogenic and not indicated for eclampsia prophylaxis.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics; Chapter: Hypertensive Disorders)</em>`},
    {q:'Which drug used in diabetes management is considered safest during pregnancy?',o:['Insulin','Metformin','Glyburide','Pioglitazone'],a:0,
    e:`Insulin is the safest drug for diabetes management in pregnancy because it does not cross the placenta and provides precise glycaemic control. It is the gold standard for both pregestational diabetes and gestational diabetes when diet and exercise are insufficient.<br><br>Metformin is increasingly used in gestational diabetes and PCOS-related pregnancy and is generally considered safe, though it does cross the placenta. Glyburide is an option but with mixed safety data. Pioglitazone (thiazolidinedione) is avoided due to limited safety data.<br><br>A (Insulin) is correct because it is the gold standard with no placental transfer. B (Metformin) is wrong because, though acceptable, it crosses the placenta unlike insulin. C (Glyburide) is wrong because safety data are mixed and it is no longer first-line. D (Pioglitazone) is wrong because thiazolidinediones are avoided in pregnancy.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Pancreatic Hormones and Antidiabetic Drugs)</em>`},
    {q:'A fetus exposed to ACE inhibitors late in pregnancy may develop which complication?',o:['Limb reduction','Cleft palate','Neural tube defect','Oligohydramnios sequence'],a:3,
    e:`ACE inhibitor exposure late in pregnancy causes the oligohydramnios sequence: reduced fetal renal perfusion impairs urine production, depleting amniotic fluid (largely fetal urine after the first trimester), with consequent pulmonary hypoplasia, limb contractures and Potter-like facies.<br><br>The full ACE inhibitor fetopathy includes neonatal renal failure, calvarial hypoplasia and persistent pulmonary hypertension. Effects are reversible if the drug is stopped early in second-trimester exposure. Methyldopa, labetalol and nifedipine are safer alternatives.<br><br>D (Oligohydramnios sequence) is correct because reduced fetal angiotensin II activity impairs renal output, depleting amniotic fluid. A (Limb reduction) is wrong because that is the thalidomide pattern. B (Cleft palate) is wrong because it is associated with corticosteroids. C (Neural tube defect) is wrong because it is the valproate/carbamazepine pattern.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics; Chapter: Teratology, Teratogens, and Fetotoxic Agents)</em>`},
    {q:'A pregnant woman with tuberculosis receives treatment. Which drug is avoided due to risk of fetal ototoxicity?',o:['Rifampicin','Isoniazid','Streptomycin','Ethambutol'],a:2,
    e:`Streptomycin is an aminoglycoside that causes irreversible fetal ototoxicity (sensorineural deafness) by damaging the developing eighth cranial nerve. It is therefore avoided throughout pregnancy in tuberculosis treatment.<br><br>Other aminoglycosides (kanamycin, amikacin, gentamicin) carry similar risk but streptomycin has the most documented cases. Isoniazid, rifampicin and ethambutol are the standard safe drugs in pregnancy. Pyridoxine 25 to 50 mg/day prevents isoniazid neuropathy.<br><br>C (Streptomycin) is correct because aminoglycoside ototoxicity is the established fetal effect. A (Rifampicin) is wrong because it is considered safe in pregnancy with hepatic monitoring. B (Isoniazid) is wrong because it is the cornerstone of safe TB therapy in pregnancy. D (Ethambutol) is wrong because it is also considered safe in pregnancy.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Antimycobacterial Drugs)</em>`},
    {q:'Which antiemetic is widely used and considered relatively safe for hyperemesis gravidarum?',o:['Doxylamine-pyridoxine combination','Metoclopramide','Ondansetron','Chlorpromazine'],a:0,
    e:`Doxylamine-pyridoxine combination is widely used and considered safe as first-line pharmacotherapy for hyperemesis gravidarum and severe nausea and vomiting of pregnancy. Doxylamine is an H1 antihistamine and pyridoxine is vitamin B6.<br><br>Decades of use including the original Bendectin formulation support its safety profile. Metoclopramide and ondansetron are second-line options. Ondansetron use in early pregnancy has been linked to a small increase in cleft palate and cardiac defects in some studies.<br><br>A (Doxylamine-pyridoxine combination) is correct because of the strong safety record and first-line guideline status. B (Metoclopramide) is wrong because it is a second-line agent, not first-line. C (Ondansetron) is wrong because of small associations with first-trimester cardiac defects in some studies. D (Chlorpromazine) is wrong because it is rarely used and has more side effects.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics; Chapter: Gastrointestinal Disorders)</em>`},
    {q:'A pregnant woman requires treatment for bacterial vaginosis. Which drug is considered safe during pregnancy?',o:['Tetracycline','Metronidazole','Ciprofloxacin','Doxycycline'],a:1,
    e:`Metronidazole is considered safe in pregnancy for treating bacterial vaginosis and trichomoniasis. Decades of use including in the first trimester have not shown teratogenic effects, despite earlier theoretical concerns.<br><br>Metronidazole acts by being reduced to a reactive intermediate that damages DNA in anaerobic organisms. Treatment of symptomatic bacterial vaginosis in pregnancy may reduce preterm birth risk. Topical (vaginal) treatment is also acceptable.<br><br>B (Metronidazole) is correct because it is the established first-line agent for BV and trichomoniasis in pregnancy. A (Tetracycline) is wrong because tetracyclines cause tooth discoloration. C (Ciprofloxacin) is wrong because fluoroquinolones cause cartilage toxicity in animal studies. D (Doxycycline) is wrong because it is a tetracycline.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Antiprotozoal Drugs)</em>`},
    {q:'A fetus exposed to maternal cocaine use during pregnancy is most likely to develop which complication?',o:['Renal agenesis','Neural tube defects','Placental abruption and fetal growth restriction','Limb hypoplasia'],a:2,
    e:`Cocaine causes vasoconstriction via blockade of norepinephrine reuptake, leading to placental abruption (most characteristic obstetric complication), fetal growth restriction, preterm birth and stillbirth.<br><br>Other effects include congenital anomalies (genitourinary, limb defects), neurobehavioural disturbances and increased risk of sudden infant death syndrome. Cocaine readily crosses the placenta and remains active in fetal circulation for prolonged periods.<br><br>C (Placental abruption and fetal growth restriction) is correct because vasoconstriction-induced abruption and growth restriction are the most consistent cocaine-related complications. A (Renal agenesis) is wrong because it is the ACE inhibitor pattern. B (Neural tube defects) is wrong because they are not a primary cocaine effect. D (Limb hypoplasia) is wrong because limb defects are more characteristic of thalidomide.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics; Chapter: Teratology, Teratogens, and Fetotoxic Agents)</em>`},
    {q:'A pregnant woman requires treatment for asthma. Which drug is considered safe and commonly used during pregnancy?',o:['Ergotamine','Salbutamol','Methotrexate','Isotretinoin'],a:1,
    e:`Salbutamol (albuterol) is a β₂-agonist widely used and considered safe for asthma during pregnancy. Inhaled administration produces minimal systemic absorption and limited fetal exposure.<br><br>Maintaining good asthma control in pregnancy is important because uncontrolled asthma carries higher risks (preeclampsia, preterm birth, growth restriction) than the medications. Inhaled corticosteroids (budesonide preferred) are also safe and recommended for persistent asthma.<br><br>B (Salbutamol) is correct because it is the established safe rescue bronchodilator in pregnancy. A (Ergotamine) is wrong because it is a uterine vasoconstrictor unrelated to asthma. C (Methotrexate) is wrong because it is a teratogenic folate antagonist. D (Isotretinoin) is wrong because it causes severe retinoid embryopathy.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Drugs Used in Asthma)</em>`},
    {q:'Which antifungal drug is considered safe for vaginal candidiasis during pregnancy?',o:['Topical clotrimazole','Fluconazole high dose','Griseofulvin','Ketoconazole oral'],a:0,
    e:`Topical clotrimazole and other topical azoles are preferred for vaginal candidiasis in pregnancy. Topical application produces minimal systemic absorption and is considered safe throughout pregnancy.<br><br>Oral fluconazole at high doses (≥400 mg/day) is associated with craniofacial and skeletal abnormalities in case reports and is avoided. Single low-dose oral fluconazole (150 mg) carries minimal risk but topical therapy remains preferred. Griseofulvin and ketoconazole are avoided in pregnancy.<br><br>A (Topical clotrimazole) is correct because topical therapy avoids systemic exposure and is established first-line. B (Fluconazole high dose) is wrong because high-dose oral fluconazole is teratogenic. C (Griseofulvin) is wrong because it is teratogenic and contraindicated. D (Ketoconazole oral) is wrong because oral ketoconazole is hepatotoxic and avoided in pregnancy.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Antifungal Agents)</em>`},
    {q:'A pregnant woman exposed to radiation during the first trimester is at highest risk for which fetal complication?',o:['Fetal goitre','Polyhydramnios','Macrosomia','Structural congenital malformations'],a:3,
    e:`High-dose ionising radiation during the first trimester (organogenesis) carries the highest risk of structural congenital malformations, including microcephaly, growth restriction, eye anomalies and intellectual disability. The threshold is approximately 100 mGy.<br><br>Radiation effects vary by gestational stage: pre-implantation produces all-or-none effects; organogenesis (weeks 2 to 8) is most teratogenic for structural defects; later periods cause growth restriction and CNS effects, especially weeks 8 to 25 for the developing brain.<br><br>D (Structural congenital malformations) is correct because organogenesis-period radiation produces structural defects. A (Fetal goitre) is wrong because it is associated with iodine and antithyroid drugs, not radiation alone. B (Polyhydramnios) is wrong because radiation does not increase amniotic fluid. C (Macrosomia) is wrong because radiation causes growth restriction.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics; Chapter: Teratology, Teratogens, and Fetotoxic Agents)</em>`},
    {q:'Which antihypertensive drug is contraindicated in pregnancy due to fetal renal failure risk?',o:['ACE inhibitors','Labetalol','Methyldopa','Hydralazine'],a:0,
    e:`ACE inhibitors are contraindicated throughout pregnancy because they cause fetal renal failure and oligohydramnios, particularly with second and third trimester exposure. The ACE inhibitor fetopathy includes oligohydramnios, pulmonary hypoplasia, calvarial hypoplasia and limb contractures.<br><br>Angiotensin receptor blockers cause similar fetal effects and are also contraindicated. Methyldopa, labetalol and nifedipine are first-line antihypertensives in pregnancy. Hydralazine is used IV for hypertensive emergencies.<br><br>A (ACE inhibitors) is correct because of the established fetal renal failure risk. B (Labetalol) is wrong because it is widely used as first-line in pregnancy hypertension. C (Methyldopa) is wrong because it is the most established safe first-line agent. D (Hydralazine) is wrong because it is used IV for severe hypertension in pregnancy.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics; Chapter: Hypertensive Disorders)</em>`},
    {q:'Which drug used for epilepsy is strongly associated with neural tube defects and should generally be avoided in pregnancy?',o:['Levetiracetam','Lamotrigine','Valproate','Gabapentin'],a:2,
    e:`Sodium valproate is the antiepileptic most strongly associated with neural tube defects (1 to 2 percent risk) and overall has the highest teratogenic potential among major antiepileptics (~10 percent major malformations).<br><br>Valproate also carries risks of facial dysmorphism, cardiac defects and significantly impaired neurodevelopment in exposed children. It is avoided in women of reproductive age unless other agents have failed. Lamotrigine and levetiracetam are preferred safer alternatives.<br><br>C (Valproate) is correct because of its strong neural tube defect association and high overall teratogenicity. A (Levetiracetam) is wrong because it has one of the lowest teratogenic profiles. B (Lamotrigine) is wrong because it is one of the safest antiepileptics in pregnancy. D (Gabapentin) is wrong because it is generally considered relatively safe.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Antiseizure Drugs)</em>`},
    {q:'A pregnant woman exposed to benzodiazepines in late pregnancy may cause which neonatal complication?',o:['Limb hypoplasia','Neural tube defects','Renal agenesis','Floppy infant syndrome'],a:3,
    e:`Benzodiazepines used in late pregnancy or labour cause floppy infant syndrome (neonatal hypotonia, lethargy, poor feeding, hypothermia, respiratory depression) due to drug accumulation across the placenta with limited neonatal metabolism.<br><br>Chronic third-trimester use can also produce neonatal withdrawal syndrome with tremors and hyperreflexia. First-trimester use carries small reported associations with cleft lip/palate. Diazepam in particular is avoided near delivery.<br><br>D (Floppy infant syndrome) is correct because neonatal CNS depression from benzodiazepine accumulation is the established late-pregnancy effect. A (Limb hypoplasia) is wrong because limb defects are characteristic of thalidomide. B (Neural tube defects) is wrong because they relate to valproate and folate antagonists. C (Renal agenesis) is wrong because it is the ACE inhibitor pattern.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Sedative-Hypnotic Drugs)</em>`},
    {q:'Which drug used for acne is absolutely contraindicated in pregnancy due to severe teratogenicity?',o:['Erythromycin','Isotretinoin','Azelaic acid','Benzoyl peroxide'],a:1,
    e:`Isotretinoin is absolutely contraindicated in pregnancy due to severe retinoid embryopathy (craniofacial anomalies, conotruncal cardiac defects, thymic hypoplasia, CNS malformations). Pregnancy must be excluded before starting and effective contraception used during and for one month after treatment.<br><br>Risk of major malformation with first-trimester exposure approaches 25 to 35 percent. Etretinate has a much longer half-life requiring contraception for 2 to 3 years. Topical retinoids (tretinoin, adapalene) are not recommended but carry far lower risk than systemic retinoids.<br><br>B (Isotretinoin) is correct because it is the most severely teratogenic acne therapy. A (Erythromycin) is wrong because it is safe in pregnancy and used topically and orally for acne. C (Azelaic acid) is wrong because it is considered safe in pregnancy. D (Benzoyl peroxide) is wrong because topical use has minimal absorption and is considered safe.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics; Chapter: Teratology, Teratogens, and Fetotoxic Agents)</em>`},
    {q:'A fetus exposed to maternal smoking during pregnancy most commonly develops which complication?',o:['Limb reduction','Neural tube defects','Congenital cataracts','Fetal growth restriction'],a:3,
    e:`Maternal smoking during pregnancy most consistently causes fetal growth restriction (low birth weight). Carbon monoxide reduces oxygen delivery (forming carboxyhaemoglobin) and nicotine causes uteroplacental vasoconstriction.<br><br>Smoking also increases risks of preterm birth, placental abruption, placenta praevia, stillbirth, sudden infant death syndrome and orofacial clefts. The growth restriction is dose-dependent and largely reversible if smoking ceases before the third trimester.<br><br>D (Fetal growth restriction) is correct because reduced fetal oxygen delivery and uteroplacental vasoconstriction directly impair fetal growth. A (Limb reduction) is wrong because limb defects are characteristic of thalidomide. B (Neural tube defects) is wrong because they relate to valproate and folate deficiency. C (Congenital cataracts) is wrong because they are associated with rubella, not smoking.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics; Chapter: Fetal Growth Disorders)</em>`},
    {q:'A pregnant woman with bacterial infection requires antibiotic therapy. Which class is generally safest during pregnancy?',o:['Penicillins','Aminoglycosides','Tetracyclines','Fluoroquinolones'],a:0,
    e:`Penicillins are considered the safest antibiotic class during pregnancy, with decades of use showing no teratogenic effects. They cross the placenta but are non-toxic to the fetus and effective against many maternal infections.<br><br>Cephalosporins are similarly safe. Macrolides (erythromycin, azithromycin) are also acceptable. Aminoglycosides (ototoxicity), tetracyclines (tooth staining), fluoroquinolones (cartilage toxicity in animals), chloramphenicol (gray baby syndrome) and sulfonamides near term (kernicterus) all carry recognised risks.<br><br>A (Penicillins) is correct because of the long-established safety record. B (Aminoglycosides) is wrong because they cause fetal ototoxicity. C (Tetracyclines) is wrong because they cause permanent tooth staining and bone growth inhibition. D (Fluoroquinolones) is wrong because of cartilage toxicity in animal studies and limited human data.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Beta-Lactam and Other Cell Wall- and Membrane-Active Antibiotics)</em>`},
    {q:'Which drug used for hyperthyroidism should be avoided in the first trimester due to risk of aplasia cutis?',o:['Propylthiouracil','Methimazole','Levothyroxine','Iodine solution'],a:1,
    e:`Methimazole (and its prodrug carbimazole) is associated with aplasia cutis congenita (scalp skin defects) and methimazole embryopathy (choanal atresia, oesophageal atresia, athelia, dysmorphic facies) when used in the first trimester. It is therefore avoided early in pregnancy.<br><br>Propylthiouracil (PTU) is preferred during the first trimester because it lacks this embryopathy. After the first trimester, methimazole is preferred because PTU carries a higher risk of severe maternal hepatotoxicity. Both drugs cross the placenta and can cause fetal hypothyroidism at high doses.<br><br>B (Methimazole) is correct because of the aplasia cutis association in the first trimester. A (Propylthiouracil) is wrong because it is the preferred first-trimester agent. C (Levothyroxine) is wrong because it is thyroid replacement, not antithyroid. D (Iodine solution) is wrong because while iodine excess can cause fetal goitre, it is not associated with aplasia cutis.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Thyroid and Antithyroid Drugs)</em>`},
    {q:'Which analgesic is considered safest for pain management throughout pregnancy?',o:['Ibuprofen','Diclofenac','Paracetamol','Aspirin'],a:2,
    e:`Paracetamol (acetaminophen) is considered the safest analgesic throughout pregnancy at therapeutic doses. It has minimal anti-inflammatory effect and does not significantly inhibit COX in peripheral tissues.<br><br>NSAIDs are avoided in the third trimester because they may cause premature ductus arteriosus closure, oligohydramnios and prolonged labour. Aspirin at antiplatelet doses (75 to 150 mg) is used for pre-eclampsia prevention but full doses are avoided. Opioids carry risks of neonatal withdrawal and respiratory depression near delivery.<br><br>C (Paracetamol) is correct because of its minimal teratogenic potential and pregnancy-wide safety. A (Ibuprofen) is wrong because it is avoided in the third trimester due to ductal closure risk. B (Diclofenac) is wrong because it is also an NSAID with the same third-trimester concerns. D (Aspirin) is wrong because full analgesic doses are avoided in late pregnancy.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Common medical disorders in pregnancy)</em>`},
    {q:'A pregnant woman treated with antimalarial drugs receives a medication associated with hemolysis in G6PD deficiency but generally safe in pregnancy. Which drug is this?',o:['Chloroquine','Primaquine','Doxycycline','Tetracycline'],a:0,
    e:`Chloroquine is generally safe in pregnancy and carries minimal G6PD-related haemolysis risk at antimalarial doses. The agent classically associated with significant haemolysis in G6PD deficiency is primaquine, which is contraindicated in pregnancy precisely because it can cross the placenta and cause fetal haemolysis.<br><br>Chloroquine remains effective in chloroquine-sensitive areas. Quinine, mefloquine and artemisinin combinations are alternatives in resistant strains. Doxycycline is contraindicated as a tetracycline.<br><br>A (Chloroquine) is correct because at antimalarial doses it is generally safe in pregnancy and the question stem asks for the safe-in-pregnancy option. B (Primaquine) is wrong because it causes severe haemolysis in G6PD deficiency and is contraindicated in pregnancy. C (Doxycycline) is wrong because tetracyclines cause tooth discoloration. D (Tetracycline) is wrong for the same reason.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Antiprotozoal Drugs)</em>`},
    {q:'A fetus exposed to maternal antiepileptic drugs may benefit from maternal supplementation with which vitamin to reduce neural tube defect risk?',o:['Vitamin B12','Vitamin D','Vitamin K','Folic acid'],a:3,
    e:`Folic acid supplementation reduces the risk of neural tube defects in fetuses exposed to antiepileptic drugs that interfere with folate metabolism (valproate, carbamazepine, phenytoin). High-dose folic acid (5 mg/day) is recommended preconceptionally and through the first trimester.<br><br>Folate is essential for DNA synthesis and methylation reactions during neural tube closure (days 21 to 28 of gestation). Standard preconceptional supplementation is 0.4 mg/day for women without risk factors and 5 mg/day for women on antiepileptics or with previous NTD-affected pregnancy.<br><br>D (Folic acid) is correct because it directly addresses the antiepileptic-induced impairment of folate metabolism. A (Vitamin B12) is wrong because while it works with folate in DNA synthesis, it is not the primary supplement for NTD prevention. B (Vitamin D) is wrong because it has no role in NTD prevention. C (Vitamin K) is wrong because it is given to neonates of mothers on enzyme-inducing antiepileptics to prevent haemorrhage, not for NTDs.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Antenatal care)</em>`},
    {q:'A woman with epilepsy controlled on sodium valproate presents at 6 weeks of pregnancy. Which fetal malformation is classically associated with first-trimester exposure to this drug?',o:['Holoprosencephaly','Tracheoesophageal fistula','Neural tube defect','Omphalocele'],a:2,
    e:`Sodium valproate exposure in the first trimester is classically associated with neural tube defects (predominantly spina bifida). The critical period of neural tube closure is days 21 to 28 of gestation, and risk is approximately 1 to 2 percent.<br><br>The mechanism involves inhibition of folate metabolism. Valproate also has the highest overall teratogenicity among antiepileptics with risks for facial dysmorphism, cardiac defects and impaired neurodevelopment. High-dose folate (5 mg/day) is recommended.<br><br>C (Neural tube defect) is correct because the valproate-NTD association is the classical teaching point. A (Holoprosencephaly) is wrong because it is not a typical valproate effect. B (Tracheoesophageal fistula) is wrong because it is associated with VACTERL association, not valproate. D (Omphalocele) is wrong because it is not characteristic of valproate exposure.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Antiseizure Drugs)</em>`},
    {q:'A pregnant woman with mechanical heart valve requires anticoagulation. Which drug is preferred during the first trimester to minimize teratogenic risk?',o:['Warfarin','Low molecular weight heparin','Rivaroxaban','Dabigatran'],a:1,
    e:`Low-molecular-weight heparin (LMWH) is preferred during the first trimester for women with mechanical heart valves because it does not cross the placenta and avoids warfarin embryopathy (nasal hypoplasia, stippled epiphyses) at 6 to 9 weeks.<br><br>Some guidelines allow continued warfarin throughout pregnancy in women with high-risk valves (e.g. mitral position) at lower warfarin doses (≤5 mg/day) due to maternal thromboembolic risk with heparin. Choice depends on valve type, dose required, and patient preference. Direct oral anticoagulants are contraindicated.<br><br>B (Low molecular weight heparin) is correct because it does not cross the placenta and avoids first-trimester embryopathy. A (Warfarin) is wrong because it is teratogenic in the first trimester. C (Rivaroxaban) is wrong because direct oral anticoagulants are contraindicated. D (Dabigatran) is wrong for the same reason.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics; Chapter: Cardiovascular Disorders)</em>`},
    {q:'A fetus exposed to warfarin during weeks 6-9 of gestation may develop which classic syndrome?',o:['Warfarin embryopathy','Fetal hydantoin syndrome','Potter sequence','Alcohol embryopathy'],a:0,
    e:`Warfarin embryopathy results from exposure during weeks 6 to 9 of gestation. Classic features include nasal hypoplasia (depressed nasal bridge, choanal atresia), stippled epiphyses (chondrodysplasia punctata), low birth weight and developmental delay.<br><br>Warfarin inhibits vitamin K-dependent γ-carboxylation, including of bone matrix proteins (osteocalcin) and growth-plate Gla proteins, disrupting bone development. Later second and third trimester exposure causes CNS abnormalities and fetal/maternal haemorrhage.<br><br>A (Warfarin embryopathy) is correct because the syndrome is classically associated with this drug and exposure window. B (Fetal hydantoin syndrome) is wrong because it is caused by phenytoin. C (Potter sequence) is wrong because it results from oligohydramnios (e.g. ACE inhibitors). D (Alcohol embryopathy) is wrong because it is fetal alcohol syndrome with different features.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Drugs Used in Disorders of Coagulation)</em>`},
    {q:'A pregnant woman with hypertension presents at 14 weeks gestation. Which antihypertensive is most commonly recommended as first-line therapy during pregnancy?',o:['Captopril','Enalapril','Losartan','Methyldopa'],a:3,
    e:`Methyldopa is the most established first-line antihypertensive for chronic hypertension in pregnancy due to its long safety record. It is a centrally acting α₂-adrenergic agonist that reduces sympathetic outflow.<br><br>Side effects include sedation, depression and rarely positive Coombs test or haemolytic anaemia. Labetalol and nifedipine are also widely used as first-line options. ACE inhibitors and angiotensin receptor blockers are contraindicated.<br><br>D (Methyldopa) is correct because of its long safety record and first-line status. A (Captopril) is wrong because ACE inhibitors are contraindicated. B (Enalapril) is wrong for the same reason. C (Losartan) is wrong because angiotensin receptor blockers cause similar fetal effects to ACE inhibitors.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Hypertensive disorders)</em>`},
    {q:'Which antiepileptic drug is strongly associated with fetal hydantoin syndrome?',o:['Carbamazepine','Phenytoin','Valproate','Topiramate'],a:1,
    e:`Phenytoin causes fetal hydantoin syndrome, characterised by microcephaly, facial dysmorphism (broad nasal bridge, hypertelorism, cleft lip/palate), digital and nail hypoplasia, growth restriction and developmental delay.<br><br>The mechanism involves phenytoin\'s epoxide intermediates that exert oxidative damage on developing tissues, particularly with deficient epoxide hydrolase activity. Risk for full syndrome is approximately 5 to 10 percent.<br><br>B (Phenytoin) is correct because the syndrome bears its name and the classic features are well established. A (Carbamazepine) is wrong because it has its own teratogenic profile (NTDs, fingernail hypoplasia) but does not cause hydantoin syndrome. C (Valproate) is wrong because it is associated with NTDs and valproate embryopathy. D (Topiramate) is wrong because it causes cleft lip/palate but not the hydantoin syndrome.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Antiseizure Drugs)</em>`},
    {q:'A fetus exposed to ACE inhibitors in the second trimester may develop which characteristic complication?',o:['Limb reduction defects','Craniosynostosis','Oligohydramnios with renal failure','Gastroschisis'],a:2,
    e:`ACE inhibitor exposure in the second trimester causes oligohydramnios with fetal renal failure. Reduced fetal angiotensin II activity impairs renal blood flow and urine production, depleting amniotic fluid (which is largely fetal urine after 16 weeks).<br><br>Consequences of resulting oligohydramnios include pulmonary hypoplasia, limb contractures, calvarial hypoplasia and Potter-like facies. Effects may be reversible if the drug is stopped early. Methyldopa, labetalol and nifedipine are safer alternatives.<br><br>C (Oligohydramnios with renal failure) is correct because this is the established ACE inhibitor fetopathy. A (Limb reduction defects) is wrong because that is the thalidomide pattern. B (Craniosynostosis) is wrong because it is not a recognised ACE inhibitor effect. D (Gastroschisis) is wrong because it is associated with cocaine and young maternal age.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics; Chapter: Teratology, Teratogens, and Fetotoxic Agents)</em>`},
    {q:'A woman taking isotretinoin becomes pregnant. Which combination of abnormalities is most characteristic of retinoid embryopathy?',o:['Neural tube defect and renal agenesis','Diaphragmatic hernia and cataract','Limb reduction with polydactyly','Cardiac outflow defects with craniofacial anomalies'],a:3,
    e:`Retinoid (isotretinoin) embryopathy classically combines cardiac outflow tract (conotruncal) defects with craniofacial anomalies. The full pattern includes microtia/anotia, micrognathia, cleft palate, conotruncal cardiac defects and CNS malformations.<br><br>Mechanism involves disruption of neural crest cell migration to derivatives in the face, thymus and cardiac outflow tract. Risk of major malformation with first-trimester exposure approaches 25 to 35 percent. Pregnancy prevention programmes are mandatory.<br><br>D (Cardiac outflow defects with craniofacial anomalies) is correct because this combination defines retinoid embryopathy. A (Neural tube defect and renal agenesis) is wrong because neither is the characteristic retinoid pattern. B (Diaphragmatic hernia and cataract) is wrong because they are not retinoid features. C (Limb reduction with polydactyly) is wrong because limb defects are characteristic of thalidomide.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics; Chapter: Teratology, Teratogens, and Fetotoxic Agents)</em>`},
    {q:'A pregnant patient requires treatment for hyperthyroidism at 8 weeks gestation. Which drug is preferred during the first trimester?',o:['Carbimazole','Methimazole','Propylthiouracil','Radioactive iodine'],a:2,
    e:`Propylthiouracil (PTU) is preferred over methimazole/carbimazole in the first trimester for hyperthyroidism in pregnancy because methimazole is associated with aplasia cutis and methimazole embryopathy (choanal/oesophageal atresia).<br><br>After the first trimester, methimazole is preferred because PTU carries higher maternal hepatotoxicity risk. Both drugs cross the placenta and can cause fetal hypothyroidism at high doses, so the lowest effective dose is used. Radioactive iodine is absolutely contraindicated.<br><br>C (Propylthiouracil) is correct because it is the established first-trimester antithyroid in pregnancy. A (Carbimazole) is wrong because it is the prodrug of methimazole and shares the embryopathy. B (Methimazole) is wrong because it causes aplasia cutis when used early. D (Radioactive iodine) is wrong because it ablates the fetal thyroid.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Thyroid and Antithyroid Drugs)</em>`},
    {q:'Which antibiotic exposure during pregnancy is most strongly associated with permanent discoloration of teeth and inhibition of fetal bone growth?',o:['Tetracycline','Chloramphenicol','Penicillin','Erythromycin'],a:0,
    e:`Tetracyclines (tetracycline, doxycycline, minocycline) bind calcium and chelate to developing bone and teeth from approximately the fourth month of gestation, causing permanent yellow-brown tooth discoloration and inhibition of fetal bone growth.<br><br>The drug is therefore avoided in pregnancy and during breastfeeding, and in children under 8 years. Penicillins, cephalosporins and macrolides are safer alternatives for most maternal infections.<br><br>A (Tetracycline) is correct because its calcium-chelating effect on calcifying tissues is the established mechanism. B (Chloramphenicol) is wrong because it causes gray baby syndrome, not tooth staining. C (Penicillin) is wrong because it is safe in pregnancy. D (Erythromycin) is wrong because it is also safe and used as a tetracycline alternative.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Tetracyclines, Macrolides, Clindamycin, Chloramphenicol, Streptogramins, and Oxazolidinones)</em>`},
    {q:'A fetus exposed to maternal alcohol consumption may develop which classical triad of abnormalities?',o:['Cataract, deafness, cardiac defects','Microcephaly, facial anomalies, growth restriction','Neural tube defect, hydrocephalus, limb reduction','Cleft palate, renal agenesis, polydactyly'],a:1,
    e:`Fetal alcohol syndrome (FAS) is characterised by the classical triad of microcephaly, characteristic facial dysmorphism (smooth philtrum, thin upper lip, short palpebral fissures) and pre- and postnatal growth restriction, plus CNS dysfunction.<br><br>Mechanism involves disruption of neural crest cell migration, oxidative stress and apoptosis. There is no established safe threshold of alcohol consumption, so abstinence is recommended throughout pregnancy. FAS is the most common preventable cause of intellectual disability.<br><br>B (Microcephaly, facial anomalies, growth restriction) is correct because this is the classical FAS triad. A (Cataract, deafness, cardiac defects) is wrong because that is congenital rubella syndrome. C (Neural tube defect, hydrocephalus, limb reduction) is wrong because these features are not the FAS triad. D (Cleft palate, renal agenesis, polydactyly) is wrong because none is characteristic of FAS.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics; Chapter: Teratology, Teratogens, and Fetotoxic Agents)</em>`},
    {q:'Which drug used in tuberculosis treatment is contraindicated during pregnancy due to risk of congenital deafness?',o:['Isoniazid','Rifampicin','Streptomycin','Ethambutol'],a:2,
    e:`Streptomycin is contraindicated in pregnancy because it is an aminoglycoside that crosses the placenta and damages the developing eighth cranial nerve, causing congenital sensorineural deafness in the fetus.<br><br>All aminoglycosides (kanamycin, amikacin, gentamicin) carry similar risk but streptomycin has the most documented cases. Isoniazid, rifampicin and ethambutol are the standard safe drugs in pregnancy. Pyridoxine 25 to 50 mg/day prevents isoniazid-induced peripheral neuropathy.<br><br>C (Streptomycin) is correct because aminoglycoside ototoxicity is the established fetal effect. A (Isoniazid) is wrong because it is the cornerstone of safe TB therapy in pregnancy. B (Rifampicin) is wrong because it is considered safe with hepatic monitoring. D (Ethambutol) is wrong because it is also considered safe in pregnancy.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Antimycobacterial Drugs)</em>`},
    {q:'A pregnant woman treated with high-dose NSAIDs late in pregnancy exposes the fetus to which risk?',o:['Premature closure of ductus arteriosus','Patent ductus arteriosus','Ventricular septal defect','Tetralogy of Fallot'],a:0,
    e:`High-dose NSAIDs in late pregnancy (after 30 weeks) inhibit prostaglandin synthesis, causing premature closure of the fetal ductus arteriosus. This leads to right ventricular hypertrophy, pulmonary hypertension and right heart failure.<br><br>Other late-pregnancy NSAID risks include oligohydramnios (reduced fetal renal perfusion) and prolongation of labour (uterine relaxation). Paracetamol is preferred for analgesia and antipyresis throughout pregnancy.<br><br>A (Premature closure of ductus arteriosus) is correct because COX inhibition removes prostaglandin-mediated maintenance of ductal patency. B (Patent ductus arteriosus) is wrong because NSAIDs close, not maintain, the ductus (in fact, indomethacin is used postnatally to close PDA). C (Ventricular septal defect) is wrong because it is a structural defect unrelated to NSAIDs. D (Tetralogy of Fallot) is wrong because it is a conotruncal defect not associated with NSAIDs.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Nonsteroidal Anti-Inflammatory Drugs)</em>`},
    {q:'A woman exposed to methotrexate during early pregnancy is at risk of fetal anomalies primarily because the drug inhibits which enzyme?',o:['Thymidylate synthase','Dihydrofolate reductase','DNA polymerase','RNA polymerase'],a:1,
    e:`Methotrexate inhibits dihydrofolate reductase (DHFR), the enzyme that converts dihydrofolate to tetrahydrofolate. Tetrahydrofolate is essential for one-carbon transfers in DNA and amino acid synthesis.<br><br>The resulting depletion of tetrahydrofolate impairs purine and thymidylate synthesis, blocking DNA replication and cell division during organogenesis. Aminopterin syndrome (methotrexate embryopathy) includes craniofacial anomalies, skeletal defects and CNS malformations. Methotrexate is also used in ectopic pregnancy management.<br><br>B (Dihydrofolate reductase) is correct because this is the direct molecular target of methotrexate. A (Thymidylate synthase) is wrong because it is the target of 5-fluorouracil, not methotrexate. C (Topoisomerase) is wrong because it is targeted by drugs like etoposide. D (DNA polymerase) is wrong because it is not directly inhibited by methotrexate.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Cancer Chemotherapy)</em>`},
    {q:'A pregnant woman with epilepsy requires drug therapy. Which antiepileptic drug has the lowest teratogenic risk among commonly used agents?',o:['Valproate','Phenytoin','Phenobarbital','Lamotrigine'],a:3,
    e:`Lamotrigine has the lowest teratogenic risk among commonly used antiepileptic drugs at typical doses, with major malformation rates similar to baseline population rates. Levetiracetam is also relatively safe.<br><br>Valproate (~10 percent major malformations), carbamazepine (3 to 5 percent), phenytoin (5 to 10 percent including hydantoin syndrome) and topiramate (cleft lip/palate) carry higher risks. Switching to lamotrigine or levetiracetam preconceptionally is preferred when seizure control allows.<br><br>A (Lamotrigine) is correct because of its established lower teratogenic profile. B (Valproate) is wrong because it has the highest teratogenic risk. C (Phenytoin) is wrong because it causes fetal hydantoin syndrome. D (Carbamazepine) is wrong because it carries higher NTD risk than lamotrigine.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics; Chapter: Neurological Disorders)</em>`},
    {q:'A fetus exposed to maternal lithium therapy in early pregnancy is particularly at risk for which congenital cardiac anomaly?',o:['Tetralogy of Fallot','Ebstein anomaly','Coarctation of aorta','Atrial septal defect'],a:1,
    e:`Lithium exposure in the first trimester is particularly associated with Ebstein anomaly of the tricuspid valve, characterised by apical displacement of the septal and posterior tricuspid leaflets with atrialisation of the right ventricle.<br><br>The absolute risk is small (~1 in 1000) but considerably higher than the background rate. Fetal echocardiography is recommended for women exposed to lithium in early pregnancy. Where possible, lithium is replaced with safer mood stabilisers preconceptionally.<br><br>C (Ebstein anomaly) is correct because the lithium-Ebstein anomaly association is a classic teaching point. A (Tetralogy of Fallot) is wrong because it is not lithium-associated. B (Transposition of great arteries) is wrong because it is associated with maternal diabetes. D (Ventricular septal defect) is wrong because while the most common cardiac defect, it is not specifically linked to lithium.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Antipsychotic Agents and Lithium)</em>`},
    {q:'A pregnant woman receives aminoglycoside therapy. Which fetal complication is most likely?',o:['Neural tube defect','Cataracts','Sensorineural deafness','Limb hypoplasia'],a:2,
    e:`Aminoglycosides (streptomycin, gentamicin, kanamycin, amikacin) cause fetal ototoxicity by damaging the developing eighth cranial nerve, leading to congenital sensorineural deafness. The drug accumulates in the fetal inner ear and renal cortex.<br><br>Streptomycin has the most documented fetal cases. Aminoglycosides are reserved for serious maternal infections in pregnancy when no safer alternative exists, with careful monitoring of drug levels and renal function.<br><br>A (Ototoxicity) is correct because aminoglycoside damage to the cochlear and vestibular apparatus is the classical fetal effect. B (Cardiac defect) is wrong because aminoglycosides do not cause cardiac anomalies. C (Limb reduction) is wrong because limb defects are characteristic of thalidomide. D (Renal agenesis) is wrong because that is the ACE inhibitor pattern.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Aminoglycosides)</em>`},
    {q:'Which medication used in acne therapy is absolutely contraindicated during pregnancy due to severe teratogenicity involving neural crest cells?',o:['Benzoyl peroxide','Azelaic acid','Clindamycin','Isotretinoin'],a:3,
    e:`Isotretinoin causes severe retinoid embryopathy through disruption of neural crest cell migration. The classic pattern includes craniofacial anomalies (microtia, micrognathia, cleft palate), conotruncal cardiac defects, thymic hypoplasia and CNS malformations.<br><br>Risk of major malformation with first-trimester exposure approaches 25 to 35 percent. Effective contraception is mandatory during treatment and for one month after stopping. Etretinate has a much longer half-life requiring contraception for 2 to 3 years.<br><br>D (Isotretinoin) is correct because of severe retinoid embryopathy via neural crest cell disruption, exactly matching the question stem. A (Benzoyl peroxide) is wrong because topical use has minimal absorption and is considered safe. B (Azelaic acid) is wrong because it is considered safe in pregnancy. C (Clindamycin) is wrong because topical clindamycin is acceptable in pregnancy.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics; Chapter: Teratology, Teratogens, and Fetotoxic Agents)</em>`},
    {q:'A fetus exposed to carbamazepine during organogenesis is particularly at risk of which anomaly?',o:['Spina bifida','Gastroschisis','Congenital cataract','Renal agenesis'],a:0,
    e:`Carbamazepine exposure during organogenesis is particularly associated with spina bifida (a neural tube defect), with risk approximately 0.5 to 1 percent above baseline. Other features include craniofacial anomalies, fingernail hypoplasia and developmental delay.<br><br>Mechanism involves carbamazepine\'s epoxide metabolites and folate antagonism. High-dose folic acid (5 mg/day) is recommended preconceptionally and through the first trimester. Lamotrigine or levetiracetam are preferred where seizure control allows.<br><br>A (Spina bifida) is correct because it is the characteristic carbamazepine-associated NTD. B (Gastroschisis) is wrong because it is associated with cocaine and young maternal age. C (Congenital cataract) is wrong because cataracts are associated with rubella. D (Renal agenesis) is wrong because it is the ACE inhibitor pattern.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Antiseizure Drugs)</em>`},
    {q:'Which antimalarial drug is generally considered safe during pregnancy?',o:['Doxycycline','Chloroquine','Primaquine','Tetracycline'],a:1,
    e:`Chloroquine is generally considered safe for malaria treatment and prophylaxis throughout pregnancy. Decades of use have not shown consistent teratogenic effects at antimalarial doses, including in the first trimester.<br><br>Chloroquine remains effective in chloroquine-sensitive areas. Quinine, mefloquine and artemisinin combination therapies are alternatives for chloroquine-resistant strains. Doxycycline and tetracycline are contraindicated, and primaquine is avoided due to G6PD-related haemolysis.<br><br>B (Chloroquine) is correct because of its long established safety record. A (Doxycycline) is wrong because tetracyclines cause tooth discoloration. C (Primaquine) is wrong because it can cause haemolysis in G6PD-deficient fetuses. D (Tetracycline) is wrong for the same reason as doxycycline.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Antiprotozoal Drugs)</em>`},
    {q:'Which antibiotic is considered the safest treatment for syphilis during pregnancy?',o:['Penicillin','Doxycycline','Azithromycin','Ciprofloxacin'],a:0,
    e:`Penicillin (typically benzathine penicillin G) is the drug of choice for syphilis in pregnancy. It crosses the placenta and effectively treats both maternal and fetal infection, preventing congenital syphilis.<br><br>Penicillin-allergic pregnant women should be desensitised rather than given alternative drugs, because doxycycline is contraindicated (tetracycline) and erythromycin does not reliably treat fetal infection. Treatment must be completed at least 30 days before delivery to prevent congenital syphilis.<br><br>A (Penicillin) is correct because it is the only effective and safe treatment for fetal syphilis. B (Doxycycline) is wrong because it is a tetracycline causing tooth discoloration. C (Azithromycin) is wrong because it does not reliably treat fetal infection and resistance is rising. D (Ciprofloxacin) is wrong because fluoroquinolones are avoided in pregnancy.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Perinatal infections)</em>`},
    {q:'A fetus exposed to maternal benzodiazepine use near delivery may present with which neonatal syndrome?',o:['Gray baby syndrome','Potter sequence','Hydantoin syndrome','Floppy infant syndrome'],a:3,
    e:`Benzodiazepines used near delivery cause floppy infant syndrome (neonatal hypotonia, lethargy, poor feeding, hypothermia, respiratory depression) due to drug accumulation across the placenta with limited neonatal metabolism.<br><br>Diazepam in particular has a long half-life and active metabolites that accumulate in the neonate. Chronic third-trimester use can also produce neonatal benzodiazepine withdrawal syndrome with tremors and hyperreflexia.<br><br>D (Floppy infant syndrome) is correct because this is the established late-pregnancy benzodiazepine effect. A (Gray baby syndrome) is wrong because it is caused by chloramphenicol. B (Potter sequence) is wrong because it is caused by oligohydramnios from ACE inhibitors or renal anomalies. C (Hydantoin syndrome) is wrong because it is caused by phenytoin.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Sedative-Hypnotic Drugs)</em>`},
    {q:'A pregnant woman receives chloramphenicol near term. Which neonatal complication may develop?',o:['Blue baby syndrome','Meconium aspiration','Gray baby syndrome','Neonatal tetany'],a:2,
    e:`Chloramphenicol given near term causes gray baby syndrome in neonates: pallor (gray colour), abdominal distension, vomiting, hypotension and circulatory collapse, often fatal if not recognised early.<br><br>Mechanism is failure to glucuronidate chloramphenicol due to immature neonatal liver enzymes (UDP-glucuronosyltransferase) and reduced renal excretion, leading to drug accumulation. Chloramphenicol also inhibits mitochondrial protein synthesis. Use is therefore avoided in late pregnancy and neonates.<br><br>C (Gray baby syndrome) is correct because it is the established chloramphenicol toxicity in neonates. A (Blue baby syndrome) is wrong because it refers to congenital cyanotic heart disease. B (Meconium aspiration) is wrong because it is unrelated to chloramphenicol. D (Neonatal tetany) is wrong because it relates to hypocalcaemia, not chloramphenicol.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Tetracyclines, Macrolides, Clindamycin, Chloramphenicol, Streptogramins, and Oxazolidinones)</em>`},
    {q:'Which drug used in diabetes management is considered the gold standard for glycemic control during pregnancy?',o:['Insulin','Glyburide','Metformin','Pioglitazone'],a:0,
    e:`Insulin is the gold standard for glycaemic control in pregnancy. It does not cross the placenta and provides precise titration of glucose control without direct fetal exposure to drug.<br><br>Multiple daily injections or continuous subcutaneous infusion (insulin pump) provide best control mimicking physiological secretion. Metformin and glyburide are alternatives in gestational diabetes but cross the placenta. Pioglitazone is avoided due to limited safety data.<br><br>A (Insulin) is correct because of its lack of placental transfer and precise control. B (Glyburide) is wrong because it crosses the placenta and has mixed safety data. C (Metformin) is wrong because while acceptable, it does cross the placenta unlike insulin. D (Pioglitazone) is wrong because thiazolidinediones are avoided in pregnancy.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics; Chapter: Diabetes Mellitus)</em>`},
    {q:'A fetus exposed to cocaine during pregnancy is particularly at risk for which obstetric complication?',o:['Placenta previa','Placental abruption','Hydramnios','Macrosomia'],a:1,
    e:`Cocaine causes vasoconstriction via blockade of norepinephrine reuptake, producing intense uteroplacental vasospasm. The most characteristic obstetric complication is placental abruption, with rates significantly elevated in cocaine users.<br><br>Other complications include fetal growth restriction, preterm birth, stillbirth, neonatal withdrawal syndrome and increased risk of sudden infant death syndrome. Cocaine readily crosses the placenta and remains active in fetal circulation for prolonged periods.<br><br>B (Placental abruption) is correct because cocaine-induced vasoconstriction is the classical cause of premature placental separation. A (Placenta previa) is wrong because it is a placental implantation site abnormality unrelated to cocaine. C (Hydramnios) is wrong because cocaine does not cause polyhydramnios. D (Macrosomia) is wrong because cocaine causes growth restriction, not macrosomia.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics; Chapter: Teratology, Teratogens, and Fetotoxic Agents)</em>`},
    {q:'Which drug historically caused clear cell adenocarcinoma of the vagina in daughters exposed in utero?',o:['Tamoxifen','Progesterone','Estradiol','Diethylstilbestrol'],a:3,
    e:`Diethylstilbestrol (DES), a synthetic non-steroidal oestrogen used between 1940 and 1971 to prevent miscarriage, caused clear cell adenocarcinoma of the vagina and cervix in female offspring (DES daughters), typically presenting in adolescence or young adulthood.<br><br>Other effects in DES daughters include cervical and uterine structural anomalies (T-shaped uterus, cervical hood), increased preterm birth and infertility. In male offspring, DES is associated with hypospadias and testicular abnormalities. DES use was banned in pregnancy in 1971.<br><br>D (Diethylstilbestrol) is correct because the DES-clear cell adenocarcinoma association is well established and historical. A (Tamoxifen) is wrong because it has different effects and is contraindicated in pregnancy. B (Progesterone) is wrong because progesterone supplementation is widely used and not associated with vaginal cancer in offspring. C (Estradiol) is wrong because while it is an oestrogen, it is not the historical agent of this teratogenic association.<br><br><em>(Shaw\'s Textbook of Gynaecology; Chapter: Hormones in Gynaecology)</em>`},
    {q:'A pregnant woman receives high-dose corticosteroids early in gestation. Which congenital anomaly has been reported with such exposure?',o:['Limb agenesis','Neural tube defect','Cleft palate','Diaphragmatic hernia'],a:2,
    e:`High-dose maternal corticosteroid exposure in early gestation has been reported to be associated with a small increased risk of cleft palate. Absolute risk increase is small (~0.1 to 0.3 percent) and the benefit of treating maternal disease usually outweighs this risk.<br><br>Prednisolone is largely metabolised by placental 11β-hydroxysteroid dehydrogenase, limiting fetal exposure. Betamethasone and dexamethasone cross more readily and are used therapeutically for fetal lung maturation in preterm labour.<br><br>C (Cleft palate) is correct because it is the small but documented teratogenic effect of high-dose first-trimester corticosteroids. A (Limb agenesis) is wrong because limb defects are characteristic of thalidomide. B (Neural tube defect) is wrong because they relate to valproate and folate antagonists. D (Diaphragmatic hernia) is wrong because it is not associated with corticosteroids.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics; Chapter: Teratology, Teratogens, and Fetotoxic Agents)</em>`},
    {q:'Which antiemetic combination is widely used and considered safe for nausea and vomiting in pregnancy?',o:['Ondansetron and dexamethasone','Doxylamine and pyridoxine','Metoclopramide and domperidone','Chlorpromazine and haloperidol'],a:1,
    e:`Doxylamine and pyridoxine combination is widely used and considered safe as first-line pharmacotherapy for nausea and vomiting in pregnancy. Doxylamine is an H1 antihistamine and pyridoxine is vitamin B6.<br><br>Decades of use including the original Bendectin formulation support its safety profile. Metoclopramide and ondansetron are second-line options. Ondansetron use in early pregnancy has been linked to a small increase in cleft palate and cardiac defects in some studies.<br><br>B (Doxylamine and pyridoxine) is correct because of its strong safety record and first-line guideline status. A (Ondansetron and dexamethasone) is wrong because of small early-pregnancy associations with cardiac and cleft defects in some studies. C (Metoclopramide and domperidone) is wrong because these are second-line and combination is uncommon. D (Chlorpromazine and haloperidol) is wrong because these are rarely used and have more side effects.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics; Chapter: Gastrointestinal Disorders)</em>`},
    {q:'A fetus exposed to maternal smoking during pregnancy most commonly demonstrates which growth pattern?',o:['Symmetrical macrosomia','Asymmetrical growth restriction','Intrauterine growth restriction','Postmaturity syndrome'],a:2,
    e:`Maternal smoking during pregnancy most consistently produces intrauterine growth restriction (IUGR). Carbon monoxide reduces oxygen delivery (forming carboxyhaemoglobin) and nicotine causes uteroplacental vasoconstriction.<br><br>The growth restriction is dose-dependent. Other effects include preterm birth, placental abruption, placenta praevia, stillbirth and increased risk of sudden infant death syndrome. Smoking cessation before 30 weeks largely reverses the effects on birth weight.<br><br>C (Intrauterine growth restriction) is correct because reduced fetal oxygen delivery is the established cause of growth restriction in maternal smokers. A (Symmetrical macrosomia) is wrong because smoking causes growth restriction, not macrosomia. B (Asymmetrical growth restriction) is wrong because smoking can produce both symmetric and asymmetric patterns; IUGR is the broader and correct answer. D (Postmaturity syndrome) is wrong because smoking does not cause postmaturity.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics; Chapter: Fetal Growth Disorders)</em>`},
    {q:'Which antibiotic is commonly recommended for treatment of urinary tract infection during pregnancy due to its relative safety profile?',o:['Nitrofurantoin','Ciprofloxacin','Tetracycline','Chloramphenicol'],a:0,
    e:`Nitrofurantoin is widely used as first-line therapy for uncomplicated UTI in pregnancy due to its safety in the first and second trimesters and activity against common urinary pathogens, especially E. coli.<br><br>Nitrofurantoin is avoided in late third trimester and during labour because it can cause neonatal haemolysis in G6PD-deficient infants. Cephalexin and amoxicillin are also acceptable. Ciprofloxacin (cartilage toxicity), tetracycline (tooth staining) and chloramphenicol (gray baby syndrome) are avoided.<br><br>A (Nitrofurantoin) is correct because of its established first-line status outside late term. B (Ciprofloxacin) is wrong because fluoroquinolones cause cartilage toxicity in animals. C (Tetracycline) is wrong because it causes tooth discoloration. D (Chloramphenicol) is wrong because it causes gray baby syndrome.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Common medical disorders in pregnancy)</em>`},
    {q:'A pregnant woman with asthma requires bronchodilator therapy. Which drug is considered safe for acute relief during pregnancy?',o:['Misoprostol','Ergotamine','Methotrexate','Salbutamol'],a:3,
    e:`Salbutamol (albuterol) is a β₂-agonist widely used and considered safe for asthma in pregnancy. Inhaled administration produces minimal systemic absorption and limited fetal exposure.<br><br>Maintaining asthma control is important because uncontrolled asthma carries higher risks (preeclampsia, preterm birth, growth restriction) than the medications. Inhaled corticosteroids (budesonide preferred) are also safe for persistent asthma. Avoid drugs like ergotamine, methotrexate and isotretinoin.<br><br>D (Salbutamol) is correct because it is the established safe rescue bronchodilator. A (Misoprostol) is wrong because it causes Möbius sequence and limb defects. B (Ergotamine) is wrong because it causes uterine vasoconstriction and is contraindicated. C (Methotrexate) is wrong because it is a teratogenic folate antagonist.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Drugs Used in Asthma)</em>`},
    {q:'Exposure to misoprostol during early pregnancy has been associated with which congenital abnormality?',o:['Möbius sequence','Turner syndrome','Down syndrome','Edwards syndrome'],a:0,
    e:`Misoprostol (PGE1 analogue) used in early pregnancy is associated with Möbius sequence (congenital facial nerve and abducens palsies) and limb reduction defects, due to vascular disruption from drug-induced uterine contractions.<br><br>The proposed mechanism is brain stem ischaemia (Möbius) and limb hypoperfusion during a critical developmental window. Risk is highest with first-trimester exposure during attempted abortion that fails to terminate pregnancy.<br><br>A (Möbius sequence) is correct because vascular disruption from misoprostol-induced uterine contractions causes this characteristic facial-nerve palsy pattern. B (Turner syndrome) is wrong because it is a chromosomal disorder unrelated to drug exposure. C (Down syndrome) is wrong for the same reason. D (Edwards syndrome) is wrong because it is trisomy 18, not drug-induced.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics; Chapter: Teratology, Teratogens, and Fetotoxic Agents)</em>`},
    {q:'A fetus exposed to high-dose radiation during organogenesis is most likely to develop which complication?',o:['Polyhydramnios','Macrosomia','Structural congenital malformations','Gestational diabetes'],a:2,
    e:`High-dose ionising radiation during organogenesis (weeks 2 to 8 post-conception) causes structural congenital malformations including microcephaly, growth restriction, eye anomalies and intellectual disability. The threshold for human teratogenicity is approximately 100 mGy.<br><br>Diagnostic imaging exposures are typically far below this threshold. Effects depend on dose and gestational age: pre-implantation has all-or-none effect, organogenesis is most teratogenic for structural defects, and later periods cause growth restriction and CNS effects (especially weeks 8 to 25 for the developing brain).<br><br>C (Structural congenital malformations) is correct because high-dose organogenesis-period radiation produces structural anomalies. A (Polyhydramnios) is wrong because radiation does not increase amniotic fluid. B (Macrosomia) is wrong because radiation causes growth restriction. D (Gestational diabetes) is wrong because it is unrelated to radiation.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics; Chapter: Teratology, Teratogens, and Fetotoxic Agents)</em>`},
    {q:'Which analgesic is considered the safest throughout pregnancy for mild to moderate pain?',o:['Aspirin','Ibuprofen','Diclofenac','Paracetamol'],a:3,
    e:`Paracetamol (acetaminophen) is the safest analgesic for mild to moderate pain throughout pregnancy. It has minimal anti-inflammatory effect and does not significantly inhibit COX in peripheral tissues.<br><br>NSAIDs (aspirin, ibuprofen, diclofenac) are avoided in the third trimester due to risk of premature ductus arteriosus closure, oligohydramnios and prolonged labour. Aspirin at low doses (75 to 150 mg) is used for pre-eclampsia prevention but full analgesic doses are avoided.<br><br>D (Paracetamol) is correct because of its minimal teratogenic potential and pregnancy-wide safety. A (Aspirin) is wrong because full analgesic doses are avoided in late pregnancy. B (Ibuprofen) is wrong because it is avoided in the third trimester. C (Diclofenac) is wrong because it is also an NSAID with the same third-trimester concerns.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Common medical disorders in pregnancy)</em>`},
    {q:'Which class of antibiotics is considered safest during pregnancy and widely used for various infections?',o:['Aminoglycosides','Penicillins','Fluoroquinolones','Tetracyclines'],a:1,
    e:`Penicillins are considered the safest antibiotic class during pregnancy, with decades of use showing no teratogenic effects. They cross the placenta but are non-toxic to the fetus and effective against many maternal infections.<br><br>Cephalosporins are similarly safe. Macrolides (erythromycin, azithromycin) are also acceptable. Aminoglycosides (ototoxicity), tetracyclines (tooth staining), fluoroquinolones (cartilage toxicity in animals), chloramphenicol (gray baby syndrome) and sulfonamides near term (kernicterus) all carry recognised risks.<br><br>B (Penicillins) is correct because of the long-established safety record. A (Aminoglycosides) is wrong because they cause fetal ototoxicity. C (Fluoroquinolones) is wrong because of cartilage toxicity in animal studies. D (Tetracyclines) is wrong because they cause tooth staining and bone growth inhibition.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Beta-Lactam and Other Cell Wall- and Membrane-Active Antibiotics)</em>`},
    {q:'A pregnant woman exposed to thalidomide early in gestation may give birth to a baby with which characteristic defect?',o:['Gastroschisis','Hydrocephalus','Omphalocele','Phocomelia'],a:3,
    e:`Thalidomide exposure in early pregnancy (days 20 to 36 of gestation) causes phocomelia (severe limb shortening with hand or foot attached directly to trunk) by inhibiting angiogenesis in developing limb buds.<br><br>The drug also affects ear development (microtia, anotia), cardiac structures and gastrointestinal tract. Thalidomide is one of the most teratogenic drugs known, with risk of major malformation approaching 50 percent in exposed pregnancies during the critical window. Strict pregnancy prevention programmes are required for current therapeutic uses.<br><br>D (Phocomelia) is correct because limb reduction with seal-like flippers is the iconic thalidomide defect. A (Gastroschisis) is wrong because it is associated with cocaine and young maternal age. B (Hydrocephalus) is wrong because it is not a thalidomide signature. C (Omphalocele) is wrong because it is a midline defect not associated with thalidomide.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics; Chapter: Teratology, Teratogens, and Fetotoxic Agents)</em>`},
    {q:'A fetus exposed to sulfonamides near term may develop which complication due to bilirubin displacement?',o:['Neonatal tetany','Kernicterus','Hypocalcemia','Polycythemia'],a:1,
    e:`Sulfonamides given near term displace bilirubin from albumin binding sites in the neonate, increasing free unconjugated bilirubin. Free bilirubin can cross the immature blood-brain barrier and deposit in basal ganglia, causing kernicterus.<br><br>Risk is greatest in preterm infants and those with neonatal hyperbilirubinaemia. Sulfonamides are therefore avoided in the third trimester and during breastfeeding of jaundiced or premature neonates. Earlier in pregnancy, sulfonamides are not contraindicated.<br><br>B (Kernicterus) is correct because bilirubin displacement from albumin by sulfonamides is the established mechanism. A (Neonatal tetany) is wrong because tetany relates to hypocalcaemia, not sulfonamides. C (Hypocalcemia) is wrong because it is not a sulfonamide effect. D (Polycythemia) is wrong because polycythaemia is associated with chronic fetal hypoxia, not sulfonamides.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Sulfonamides, Trimethoprim, and Quinolones)</em>`},
    {q:'Which antihypertensive drug is commonly used intravenously for severe hypertension in pregnancy?',o:['Hydralazine','Enalapril','Losartan','Captopril'],a:0,
    e:`Hydralazine is commonly used intravenously for severe hypertension in pregnancy. It is a direct arteriolar vasodilator that lowers systemic vascular resistance and is given as 5 to 10 mg IV boluses repeated every 20 to 30 minutes as needed.<br><br>IV labetalol and oral nifedipine are also first-line for severe hypertension in pregnancy. Hydralazine causes reflex tachycardia and may cause maternal headache, nausea and a lupus-like syndrome on chronic use. ACE inhibitors and ARBs are contraindicated.<br><br>A (Hydralazine) is correct because it is an established IV first-line agent for severe hypertension in pregnancy. B (Enalapril) is wrong because ACE inhibitors are contraindicated. C (Losartan) is wrong because angiotensin receptor blockers are contraindicated. D (Captopril) is wrong because it is also an ACE inhibitor.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics; Chapter: Hypertensive Disorders)</em>`},
    {q:'Which vitamin supplementation reduces the risk of neural tube defects in women taking antiepileptic drugs?',o:['Vitamin C','Vitamin A','Folic acid','Vitamin D'],a:2,
    e:`Folic acid supplementation reduces the risk of neural tube defects, particularly in women on antiepileptic drugs that interfere with folate metabolism (valproate, carbamazepine, phenytoin). High-dose folic acid (5 mg/day) is recommended preconceptionally and through the first trimester.<br><br>Folate is essential for DNA synthesis and methylation reactions during neural tube closure (days 21 to 28 of gestation). Standard preconceptional supplementation is 0.4 mg/day; women on antiepileptics or with previous NTD-affected pregnancy receive 5 mg/day.<br><br>C (Folic acid) is correct because it directly addresses the antiepileptic-induced impairment of folate metabolism. A (Vitamin C) is wrong because it has no role in NTD prevention. B (Vitamin A) is wrong because high doses are teratogenic, not preventive. D (Vitamin D) is wrong because it has no NTD-prevention role.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Antenatal care)</em>`},
    {q:'Which antiepileptic drug is particularly associated with craniofacial anomalies and developmental delay in fetal hydantoin syndrome?',o:['Topiramate','Valproate','Carbamazepine','Phenytoin'],a:3,
    e:`Phenytoin causes fetal hydantoin syndrome, with craniofacial anomalies (broad nasal bridge, hypertelorism, cleft lip/palate), digital and nail hypoplasia, microcephaly, growth restriction and developmental delay.<br><br>Mechanism involves phenytoin\'s epoxide intermediates that exert oxidative damage on developing tissues, particularly in fetuses with deficient epoxide hydrolase activity. Risk for full syndrome is approximately 5 to 10 percent.<br><br>D (Phenytoin) is correct because the hydantoin syndrome bears its name and the craniofacial-developmental features are classic. A (Topiramate) is wrong because it is associated with cleft lip/palate but not the full hydantoin syndrome. B (Valproate) is wrong because valproate causes valproate embryopathy with NTDs and different features. C (Carbamazepine) is wrong because it has its own pattern (NTDs, fingernail hypoplasia).<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Antiseizure Drugs)</em>`},
    {q:'Which drug used in migraine therapy is contraindicated during pregnancy because it causes uterine vasoconstriction?',o:['Metoclopramide','Paracetamol','Ergotamine','Propranolol'],a:2,
    e:`Ergotamine is contraindicated in pregnancy because it causes uterine vasoconstriction, increasing the risk of fetal hypoxia, growth restriction and pregnancy loss. It also has potent oxytocic effects that can stimulate preterm labour.<br><br>Migraine in pregnancy is managed with paracetamol, occasional codeine, beta-blockers (propranolol) for prophylaxis and lifestyle measures. Triptans have limited but reassuring data and may be used cautiously when essential.<br><br>C (Ergotamine) is correct because uterine and uteroplacental vasoconstriction precisely matches the question stem. A (Metoclopramide) is wrong because it is used as an antiemetic and is not vasoconstrictive. B (Paracetamol) is wrong because it is the safest analgesic in pregnancy. D (Propranolol) is wrong because beta-blockers are widely used in pregnancy migraine prophylaxis.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Histamine, Serotonin, and the Ergot Alkaloids)</em>`},
    {q:'Which antithyroid drug exposure in early pregnancy may cause aplasia cutis in the fetus?',o:['Methimazole','Propylthiouracil','Levothyroxine','Iodine'],a:0,
    e:`Methimazole exposure in early pregnancy is associated with aplasia cutis (scalp skin defects) and methimazole embryopathy (choanal atresia, oesophageal atresia, athelia, dysmorphic facies). It is therefore avoided in the first trimester.<br><br>Propylthiouracil (PTU) is preferred during the first trimester because it lacks this embryopathy. After the first trimester, methimazole is preferred because PTU carries a higher risk of severe maternal hepatotoxicity.<br><br>A (Methimazole) is correct because of the aplasia cutis association in the first trimester. B (Propylthiouracil) is wrong because it is the preferred first-trimester agent. C (Levothyroxine) is wrong because it is thyroid replacement, not antithyroid. D (Iodine) is wrong because while iodine excess can cause fetal goitre, it is not associated with aplasia cutis.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Thyroid and Antithyroid Drugs)</em>`},
    {q:'A fetus exposed to maternal cocaine use may develop which growth abnormality?',o:['Macrosomia','Growth restriction','Postmaturity','Hydramnios'],a:1,
    e:`Cocaine causes intense vasoconstriction via blockade of norepinephrine reuptake, producing uteroplacental vasospasm and reducing fetal oxygen and nutrient delivery. The result is fetal growth restriction.<br><br>Other complications include placental abruption (most characteristic), preterm birth, stillbirth, neurobehavioural disturbances and increased risk of sudden infant death syndrome. Cocaine readily crosses the placenta and remains active in fetal circulation for prolonged periods.<br><br>B (Growth restriction) is correct because vasoconstriction-induced reduction in placental perfusion impairs fetal growth. A (Macrosomia) is wrong because cocaine causes growth restriction, not macrosomia. C (Postmaturity) is wrong because cocaine does not cause postmaturity. D (Hydramnios) is wrong because it is unrelated to cocaine exposure.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics; Chapter: Teratology, Teratogens, and Fetotoxic Agents)</em>`},
    {q:'Which antituberculous drug is considered relatively safe during pregnancy with appropriate pyridoxine supplementation?',o:['Isoniazid','Streptomycin','Kanamycin','Amikacin'],a:0,
    e:`Isoniazid is considered relatively safe for tuberculosis treatment in pregnancy with appropriate pyridoxine (vitamin B6) supplementation. It crosses the placenta but has not been shown to cause major teratogenic effects.<br><br>Pyridoxine 25 to 50 mg/day prevents isoniazid-induced peripheral neuropathy in mother and fetus. Rifampicin and ethambutol are also acceptable. Streptomycin is contraindicated due to fetal ototoxicity. Treatment of active TB in pregnancy is essential to protect both mother and fetus.<br><br>A (Isoniazid) is correct because of its established safety with pyridoxine cover. B (Streptomycin) is wrong because it is an aminoglycoside causing fetal ototoxicity. C (Kanamycin) is wrong because it is also an aminoglycoside. D (Amikacin) is wrong for the same reason.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Antimycobacterial Drugs)</em>`},
    {q:'A pregnant woman treated with NSAIDs in late pregnancy may cause which fetal circulatory change?',o:['Persistent ductus arteriosus','Ventricular hypertrophy','Premature ductus arteriosus closure','Pulmonary atresia'],a:2,
    e:`NSAIDs in late pregnancy inhibit prostaglandin synthesis (especially PGE2 maintaining ductal patency), causing premature closure of the fetal ductus arteriosus. The resulting right ventricular hypertrophy and pulmonary hypertension can lead to right heart failure.<br><br>NSAIDs are therefore avoided after 30 weeks gestation. Other late-pregnancy concerns include oligohydramnios (reduced fetal renal perfusion) and prolonged labour (uterine relaxation). Paracetamol is preferred for analgesia and antipyresis throughout pregnancy.<br><br>C (Premature ductus arteriosus closure) is correct because COX inhibition removes prostaglandin maintenance of ductal patency. A (Persistent ductus arteriosus) is wrong because NSAIDs close, not open, the ductus (indomethacin is used postnatally to close PDA). B (Ventricular hypertrophy) is wrong because the structural defect is ductus closure, with hypertrophy as a downstream consequence. D (Pulmonary atresia) is wrong because it is unrelated to NSAID exposure.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Nonsteroidal Anti-Inflammatory Drugs)</em>`},
    {q:'Which antifungal therapy is preferred for treatment of vulvovaginal candidiasis during pregnancy?',o:['Oral ketoconazole','Topical azoles','Oral fluconazole high dose','Griseofulvin'],a:1,
    e:`Topical azoles (clotrimazole, miconazole) are preferred for vulvovaginal candidiasis in pregnancy. Topical application produces minimal systemic absorption and is considered safe throughout pregnancy.<br><br>Oral fluconazole at high doses (≥400 mg/day) is associated with craniofacial and skeletal abnormalities and is avoided. Single low-dose oral fluconazole (150 mg) carries minimal risk but topical therapy remains preferred. Griseofulvin and oral ketoconazole are avoided in pregnancy.<br><br>B (Topical azoles) is correct because topical therapy avoids systemic exposure and is the established first-line for VVC in pregnancy. A (Oral ketoconazole) is wrong because oral ketoconazole is hepatotoxic and avoided. C (Oral fluconazole high dose) is wrong because high-dose fluconazole is teratogenic. D (Griseofulvin) is wrong because it is teratogenic and contraindicated.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Antifungal Agents)</em>`},
    {q:'A fetus exposed to maternal alcohol use may demonstrate which facial feature classically associated with fetal alcohol syndrome?',o:['Prominent chin','Large mandible','Broad nasal bridge','Smooth philtrum'],a:3,
    e:`Smooth philtrum is a classical facial feature of fetal alcohol syndrome (FAS), part of the diagnostic facial dysmorphism that also includes thin upper lip and short palpebral fissures.<br><br>FAS additionally features microcephaly, growth restriction and CNS dysfunction (intellectual disability, behavioural problems). Mechanism involves disruption of neural crest cell migration. There is no established safe threshold for alcohol in pregnancy, so abstinence is advised throughout.<br><br>D (Smooth philtrum) is correct because it is one of the three diagnostic facial features of FAS. A (Prominent chin) is wrong because micrognathia (small chin), not a prominent one, is the FAS finding. B (Large mandible) is wrong because mandibular hypoplasia is the FAS feature. C (Broad nasal bridge) is wrong because it is more characteristic of fetal hydantoin syndrome.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics; Chapter: Teratology, Teratogens, and Fetotoxic Agents)</em>`},
    {q:'Which drug used for hypertension is contraindicated in pregnancy due to risk of fetal renal dysgenesis?',o:['Methyldopa','Labetalol','ACE inhibitors','Hydralazine'],a:2,
    e:`ACE inhibitors are contraindicated in pregnancy due to fetal renal dysgenesis and the ACE inhibitor fetopathy: oligohydramnios, pulmonary hypoplasia, calvarial hypoplasia and limb contractures. Risk is greatest in the second and third trimesters.<br><br>Angiotensin receptor blockers cause similar effects and are also contraindicated. Methyldopa, labetalol and nifedipine are first-line. Hydralazine is used IV for hypertensive emergencies.<br><br>C (ACE inhibitors) is correct because of the established fetal renal dysgenesis risk. A (Methyldopa) is wrong because it is the most established safe first-line agent. B (Labetalol) is wrong because it is widely used as first-line. D (Hydralazine) is wrong because it is used IV for severe hypertension.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics; Chapter: Hypertensive Disorders)</em>`},
    {q:'Which drug exposure during pregnancy causes inhibition of angiogenesis leading to limb defects?',o:['Penicillin','Thalidomide','Paracetamol','Metformin'],a:1,
    e:`Thalidomide is the prototypical drug causing limb reduction defects through inhibition of angiogenesis. The critical window is days 20 to 36 of gestation, during which the developing limb buds are highly vascular and dependent on angiogenesis.<br><br>The mechanism involves anti-angiogenic activity disrupting vascular development of the limb buds, producing characteristic upper limb defects from amelia to phocomelia. The drug also affects ear, cardiac and gastrointestinal development.<br><br>B (Thalidomide) is correct because anti-angiogenic limb defects are the iconic thalidomide effect. A (Penicillin) is wrong because it is safe in pregnancy. C (Paracetamol) is wrong because it is the safest analgesic in pregnancy. D (Metformin) is wrong because it is generally considered safe in pregnancy.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Special Aspects of Perinatal Pharmacology)</em>`},
    {q:'A fetus exposed to maternal retinoid therapy most commonly develops which category of anomalies?',o:['Limb polydactyly','Neural tube defects only','Renal agenesis','Craniofacial and cardiac defects'],a:3,
    e:`Maternal retinoid (isotretinoin, etretinate) therapy most commonly causes craniofacial and cardiac defects. The classic retinoid embryopathy includes microtia/anotia, micrognathia, cleft palate, conotruncal cardiac defects, thymic hypoplasia and CNS malformations.<br><br>Mechanism involves disruption of neural crest cell migration. Risk of major malformation with first-trimester exposure approaches 25 to 35 percent. Effective contraception is mandatory during use and for one month after stopping isotretinoin.<br><br>D (Craniofacial and cardiac defects) is correct because this combination defines retinoid embryopathy. A (Limb polydactyly) is wrong because it is not a retinoid effect. B (Neural tube defects only) is wrong because retinoid embryopathy is broader. C (Renal agenesis) is wrong because that is the ACE inhibitor pattern.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics; Chapter: Teratology, Teratogens, and Fetotoxic Agents)</em>`},
    {q:'A pregnant woman requires treatment for severe pre-eclampsia to prevent seizures. Which drug is used for seizure prophylaxis?',o:['Magnesium sulfate','Diazepam','Phenytoin','Valproate'],a:0,
    e:`Magnesium sulfate is the drug of choice for seizure prophylaxis and treatment in severe pre-eclampsia and eclampsia. It is superior to phenytoin and diazepam in preventing eclamptic seizures.<br><br>Mechanism involves NMDA receptor antagonism, calcium channel modulation and cerebral vasodilation. Loading dose is typically 4 g IV followed by maintenance infusion of 1 g/hour. Toxicity (loss of deep tendon reflexes, respiratory depression) is reversed with calcium gluconate. Magnesium also has neuroprotective effects in preterm infants.<br><br>A (Magnesium sulfate) is correct because of its established superiority in eclampsia prophylaxis. B (Diazepam) is wrong because it has poor efficacy compared to magnesium and causes neonatal floppy infant syndrome. C (Phenytoin) is wrong because magnesium is superior. D (Valproate) is wrong because it is teratogenic and not indicated for eclampsia prophylaxis.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics; Chapter: Hypertensive Disorders)</em>`},
    {q:'Which period of pregnancy is most critical for teratogenic drug exposure leading to structural congenital anomalies?',o:['0-2 weeks gestation','3-8 weeks gestation','9-20 weeks gestation','Third trimester'],a:1,
    e:`The most critical period for teratogenic drug exposure leading to structural congenital anomalies is 3 to 8 weeks gestation (organogenesis), during which major organ systems form and are most vulnerable.<br><br>Earlier (0 to 2 weeks, pre-implantation) exposure produces all-or-none effects: either complete recovery or pregnancy loss. Later exposure (after 8 weeks, fetogenesis) typically affects functional development, growth and CNS maturation rather than producing structural defects.<br><br>B (3-8 weeks gestation) is correct because organogenesis is the period of highest vulnerability to structural teratogenesis. A (0-2 weeks gestation) is wrong because pre-implantation exposure produces all-or-none effects, not malformations. C (9-20 weeks gestation) is wrong because the major structural defects have already formed; this period affects growth and CNS. D (Third trimester) is wrong because this period mostly affects function and growth.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics; Chapter: Teratology, Teratogens, and Fetotoxic Agents)</em>`},
    {q:'Which drug is most classically associated with limb reduction defects when taken during early pregnancy?',o:['Thalidomide','Penicillin','Metformin','Paracetamol'],a:0,
    e:`Thalidomide is the most classical teratogen associated with limb reduction defects. Exposure during days 20 to 36 of gestation (the limb development critical window) inhibits angiogenesis in developing limb buds.<br><br>The classical defect is phocomelia (severe limb shortening with hand or foot attached directly to trunk). Thalidomide also affects ear (microtia), cardiac and gastrointestinal development. Major malformation risk approaches 50 percent during the critical window.<br><br>A (Thalidomide) is correct because phocomelia is the iconic thalidomide effect. B (Penicillin) is wrong because penicillins are safe in pregnancy. C (Metformin) is wrong because it is generally considered safe in pregnancy. D (Paracetamol) is wrong because it is the safest analgesic in pregnancy.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Special Aspects of Perinatal Pharmacology)</em>`},
    {q:'Which anticoagulant does NOT cross the placenta and is therefore considered safer during pregnancy?',o:['Warfarin','Rivaroxaban','Heparin','Dabigatran'],a:2,
    e:`Heparin (both unfractionated and low-molecular-weight) does not cross the placenta because it is a large, polar, highly charged molecule. It is therefore non-teratogenic and the anticoagulant of choice in pregnancy.<br><br>Warfarin crosses the placenta and causes warfarin embryopathy at 6 to 9 weeks (nasal hypoplasia, stippled epiphyses) and CNS abnormalities later. Direct oral anticoagulants are not recommended in pregnancy due to limited safety data.<br><br>C (Heparin) is correct because of its inability to cross the placenta. A (Warfarin) is wrong because it crosses and is teratogenic. B (Rivaroxaban) is wrong because direct oral anticoagulants are contraindicated. D (Dabigatran) is wrong for the same reason.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Drugs Used in Disorders of Coagulation)</em>`},
    {q:'Which vitamin supplementation is recommended in pregnancy to reduce the risk of neural tube defects?',o:['Vitamin A','Vitamin C','Vitamin D','Folic acid'],a:3,
    e:`Folic acid supplementation reduces the risk of neural tube defects. Standard preconceptional supplementation is 0.4 mg/day for women without risk factors and 5 mg/day for women on antiepileptics or with previous NTD-affected pregnancy.<br><br>Folate is essential for DNA synthesis and methylation reactions during neural tube closure (days 21 to 28 of gestation). Supplementation should ideally start before conception and continue through the first trimester.<br><br>D (Folic acid) is correct because it is the established NTD-preventive vitamin. A (Vitamin A) is wrong because high-dose vitamin A is teratogenic, not preventive. B (Vitamin C) is wrong because it has no role in NTD prevention. C (Vitamin D) is wrong because it has no NTD-prevention role.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Antenatal care)</em>`},
    {q:'Which analgesic is considered the safest option for mild pain during pregnancy?',o:['Paracetamol','Diclofenac','Aspirin','Ibuprofen'],a:0,
    e:`Paracetamol is the safest analgesic for mild pain throughout pregnancy. It has minimal anti-inflammatory effect and does not significantly inhibit COX in peripheral tissues.<br><br>NSAIDs (aspirin, ibuprofen, diclofenac) are avoided in the third trimester due to risk of premature ductus arteriosus closure, oligohydramnios and prolonged labour. Aspirin at antiplatelet doses (75 to 150 mg) is used for pre-eclampsia prevention but full doses are avoided.<br><br>A (Paracetamol) is correct because of its minimal teratogenic potential and pregnancy-wide safety. B (Diclofenac) is wrong because it is an NSAID with third-trimester concerns. C (Aspirin) is wrong because full analgesic doses are avoided. D (Ibuprofen) is wrong because it is also an NSAID.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Common medical disorders in pregnancy)</em>`},
    {q:'Which antibiotic group is generally considered safe for use during pregnancy?',o:['Fluoroquinolones','Tetracyclines','Penicillins','Aminoglycosides'],a:2,
    e:`Penicillins are considered the safest antibiotic class during pregnancy, with decades of use showing no teratogenic effects. They cross the placenta but are non-toxic to the fetus and effective against many maternal infections.<br><br>Cephalosporins are similarly safe. Macrolides (erythromycin, azithromycin) are also acceptable. Aminoglycosides (ototoxicity), tetracyclines (tooth staining), fluoroquinolones (cartilage toxicity) and chloramphenicol (gray baby syndrome) carry recognised risks.<br><br>C (Penicillins) is correct because of the long-established safety record. A (Fluoroquinolones) is wrong because of cartilage toxicity in animal studies. B (Tetracyclines) is wrong because they cause tooth staining. D (Aminoglycosides) is wrong because they cause fetal ototoxicity.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Beta-Lactam and Other Cell Wall- and Membrane-Active Antibiotics)</em>`},
    {q:'Which drug used for acne is strongly teratogenic and contraindicated in pregnancy?',o:['Benzoyl peroxide','Isotretinoin','Azelaic acid','Clindamycin'],a:1,
    e:`Isotretinoin is strongly teratogenic and absolutely contraindicated in pregnancy. It causes severe retinoid embryopathy with craniofacial anomalies, conotruncal cardiac defects, thymic hypoplasia and CNS malformations through disruption of neural crest cell migration.<br><br>Risk of major malformation with first-trimester exposure approaches 25 to 35 percent. Effective contraception is mandatory during use and for one month after stopping. Etretinate has a much longer half-life requiring contraception for 2 to 3 years.<br><br>B (Isotretinoin) is correct because it is the most severely teratogenic acne therapy. A (Benzoyl peroxide) is wrong because topical use has minimal absorption and is considered safe. C (Azelaic acid) is wrong because it is considered safe. D (Clindamycin) is wrong because topical clindamycin is acceptable.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics; Chapter: Teratology, Teratogens, and Fetotoxic Agents)</em>`},
    {q:'Which antiepileptic drug is strongly associated with neural tube defects in the fetus?',o:['Gabapentin','Lamotrigine','Levetiracetam','Valproate'],a:3,
    e:`Sodium valproate is the antiepileptic most strongly associated with neural tube defects in the fetus. Risk is approximately 1 to 2 percent for NTDs (predominantly spina bifida), and overall major malformation risk is around 10 percent.<br><br>The mechanism involves inhibition of folate metabolism and direct interference with neural tube closure. High-dose folate (5 mg/day) is recommended preconceptionally. Lamotrigine and levetiracetam are preferred safer alternatives.<br><br>D (Valproate) is correct because of its strong NTD association. A (Gabapentin) is wrong because it is generally considered relatively safe. B (Lamotrigine) is wrong because it is one of the safest antiepileptics. C (Levetiracetam) is wrong because it has one of the lowest teratogenic profiles.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Antiseizure Drugs)</em>`},
    {q:'A pregnant woman treated with tetracycline during pregnancy exposes the fetus to which complication?',o:['Cataract','Neural tube defect','Tooth discoloration','Limb hypoplasia'],a:2,
    e:`Tetracyclines bind calcium and chelate to developing bone and teeth from approximately the fourth month of gestation, causing permanent yellow-brown tooth discoloration and inhibition of fetal bone growth.<br><br>The drug crosses the placenta freely and concentrates in calcifying tissues. It is therefore avoided in pregnancy and during breastfeeding, and in children under 8 years. Penicillins, cephalosporins and macrolides are safer alternatives.<br><br>C (Tooth discoloration) is correct because calcium chelation by tetracycline in calcifying fetal tissues is the established mechanism. A (Cataract) is wrong because cataracts are associated with rubella, not tetracycline. B (Neural tube defect) is wrong because they relate to valproate and folate antagonists. D (Limb hypoplasia) is wrong because limb defects are characteristic of thalidomide.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Tetracyclines, Macrolides, Clindamycin, Chloramphenicol, Streptogramins, and Oxazolidinones)</em>`},
    {q:'Which antihypertensive drug is widely used as first-line therapy in pregnancy?',o:['Methyldopa','Enalapril','Losartan','Captopril'],a:0,
    e:`Methyldopa is the most established first-line antihypertensive for chronic hypertension in pregnancy due to its long safety record. It is a centrally acting α₂-adrenergic agonist that reduces sympathetic outflow.<br><br>Side effects include sedation, depression and rarely positive Coombs test or haemolytic anaemia. Labetalol and nifedipine are also widely used as first-line options. ACE inhibitors and angiotensin receptor blockers are contraindicated.<br><br>A (Methyldopa) is correct because of its long safety record and first-line status. B (Enalapril) is wrong because ACE inhibitors are contraindicated. C (Losartan) is wrong because angiotensin receptor blockers cause similar fetal effects. D (Captopril) is wrong because it is also an ACE inhibitor.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics; Chapter: Hypertensive Disorders)</em>`},
    {q:'Which drug exposure in pregnancy is associated with Ebstein anomaly of the tricuspid valve?',o:['Valproate','Lithium','Carbamazepine','Methotrexate'],a:1,
    e:`Lithium exposure in the first trimester is classically associated with Ebstein anomaly of the tricuspid valve, characterised by apical displacement of the septal and posterior tricuspid leaflets with atrialisation of the right ventricle.<br><br>The absolute risk is small (~1 in 1000) but considerably higher than the background rate. Fetal echocardiography is recommended for women exposed to lithium in early pregnancy. Where possible, lithium is replaced with safer mood stabilisers preconceptionally.<br><br>B (Lithium) is correct because the lithium-Ebstein anomaly association is the classical teaching point. A (Valproate) is wrong because it causes NTDs and valproate embryopathy. C (Carbamazepine) is wrong because it causes NTDs and craniofacial anomalies. D (Methotrexate) is wrong because it causes aminopterin syndrome.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Antipsychotic Agents and Lithium)</em>`},
    {q:'Which antibiotic is avoided in pregnancy because it can cause permanent tooth discoloration in the fetus?',o:['Penicillin','Erythromycin','Amoxicillin','Tetracycline'],a:3,
    e:`Tetracycline causes permanent yellow-brown tooth discoloration in the fetus when used after the fourth month of gestation. Calcium chelation in calcifying tissues binds the drug to enamel and dentine.<br><br>The same mechanism inhibits fetal bone growth. Tetracyclines are avoided in pregnancy, breastfeeding and children under 8 years. Penicillins, cephalosporins and macrolides are safer alternatives for most maternal infections.<br><br>D (Tetracycline) is correct because calcium chelation by tetracycline in fetal calcifying tissues is the established mechanism. A (Penicillin) is wrong because it is safe in pregnancy. B (Erythromycin) is wrong because it is also safe. C (Amoxicillin) is wrong because it is a penicillin and safe in pregnancy.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Tetracyclines, Macrolides, Clindamycin, Chloramphenicol, Streptogramins, and Oxazolidinones)</em>`},
    {q:'Which antimalarial drug is generally considered safe in pregnancy?',o:['Doxycycline','Primaquine','Chloroquine','Tetracycline'],a:2,
    e:`Chloroquine is generally considered safe for malaria treatment and prophylaxis throughout pregnancy. Decades of use have not shown consistent teratogenic effects at antimalarial doses, including in the first trimester.<br><br>Chloroquine remains effective in chloroquine-sensitive areas. Quinine, mefloquine and artemisinin combinations are alternatives in resistant strains. Doxycycline (tooth staining) and primaquine (G6PD haemolysis) are contraindicated in pregnancy.<br><br>C (Chloroquine) is correct because of its long established safety record. A (Doxycycline) is wrong because tetracyclines cause tooth discoloration. B (Primaquine) is wrong because it can cause haemolysis in G6PD-deficient fetuses. D (Tetracycline) is wrong for the same reason as doxycycline.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Antiprotozoal Drugs)</em>`},
    {q:'Which drug used in pregnancy-induced hypertension is commonly used intravenously in severe cases?',o:['Captopril','Losartan','Enalapril','Hydralazine'],a:3,
    e:`Hydralazine is a direct arteriolar vasodilator commonly used IV for severe hypertension in pregnancy, given as 5 to 10 mg IV boluses repeated every 20 to 30 minutes as needed for blood pressure control.<br><br>IV labetalol and oral nifedipine are also first-line for severe hypertension in pregnancy. Hydralazine causes reflex tachycardia and may cause maternal headache, nausea and a lupus-like syndrome on chronic use. ACE inhibitors and ARBs are contraindicated.<br><br>D (Hydralazine) is correct because it is an established IV first-line agent. A (Captopril) is wrong because ACE inhibitors are contraindicated. B (Losartan) is wrong because ARBs are contraindicated. C (Enalapril) is wrong because it is an ACE inhibitor.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics; Chapter: Hypertensive Disorders)</em>`},
    {q:'Which drug is used for seizure prophylaxis in severe pre-eclampsia?',o:['Diazepam','Magnesium sulfate','Phenytoin','Carbamazepine'],a:1,
    e:`Magnesium sulfate is the drug of choice for seizure prophylaxis in severe pre-eclampsia and treatment of eclampsia. It is superior to phenytoin and diazepam in preventing eclamptic seizures.<br><br>Mechanism involves NMDA receptor antagonism, calcium channel modulation and cerebral vasodilation. Loading dose is typically 4 g IV followed by maintenance infusion of 1 g/hour. Toxicity (loss of deep tendon reflexes, respiratory depression) is reversed with calcium gluconate.<br><br>B (Magnesium sulfate) is correct because of its established superiority for eclampsia prophylaxis. A (Diazepam) is wrong because it has poor efficacy and causes neonatal floppy infant syndrome. C (Phenytoin) is wrong because magnesium is superior. D (Carbamazepine) is wrong because it is teratogenic and not indicated for eclampsia.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics; Chapter: Hypertensive Disorders)</em>`},
    {q:'Exposure to NSAIDs in late pregnancy may cause which fetal complication?',o:['Premature closure of ductus arteriosus','Patent ductus arteriosus','Ventricular septal defect','Coarctation of aorta'],a:0,
    e:`NSAIDs in late pregnancy inhibit prostaglandin synthesis (especially PGE2 maintaining ductal patency), causing premature closure of the fetal ductus arteriosus, with consequent right ventricular hypertrophy and pulmonary hypertension.<br><br>NSAIDs are therefore avoided after 30 weeks gestation. Other late-pregnancy concerns include oligohydramnios (reduced fetal renal perfusion) and prolonged labour. Paracetamol is preferred for analgesia and antipyresis throughout pregnancy.<br><br>A (Premature closure of ductus arteriosus) is correct because COX inhibition removes prostaglandin maintenance of ductal patency. B (Patent ductus arteriosus) is wrong because NSAIDs close, not open, the ductus. C (Ventricular septal defect) is wrong because it is unrelated to NSAIDs. D (Coarctation of aorta) is wrong because it is unrelated to NSAIDs.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Nonsteroidal Anti-Inflammatory Drugs)</em>`},
    {q:'Which antithyroid drug is preferred in the first trimester of pregnancy?',o:['Methimazole','Propylthiouracil','Carbimazole','Radioactive iodine'],a:1,
    e:`Propylthiouracil (PTU) is preferred over methimazole/carbimazole during the first trimester for hyperthyroidism in pregnancy. Methimazole is associated with aplasia cutis and methimazole embryopathy (choanal/oesophageal atresia).<br><br>After the first trimester, methimazole is preferred because PTU carries a higher risk of severe maternal hepatotoxicity. Both drugs cross the placenta and can cause fetal hypothyroidism at high doses, so the lowest effective dose is used. Radioactive iodine is absolutely contraindicated.<br><br>B (Propylthiouracil) is correct because it avoids methimazole embryopathy in the first trimester. A (Methimazole) is wrong because it causes aplasia cutis when used early. C (Carbimazole) is wrong because it is the prodrug of methimazole and shares the embryopathy. D (Radioactive iodine) is wrong because it ablates the fetal thyroid.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Thyroid and Antithyroid Drugs)</em>`},
    {q:'Which drug used in tuberculosis treatment should be avoided during pregnancy because it can cause fetal deafness?',o:['Isoniazid','Rifampicin','Streptomycin','Ethambutol'],a:2,
    e:`Streptomycin is contraindicated in pregnancy because it is an aminoglycoside that crosses the placenta and damages the developing eighth cranial nerve, causing congenital sensorineural deafness in the fetus.<br><br>All aminoglycosides (kanamycin, amikacin, gentamicin) carry similar risk but streptomycin has the most documented cases. Isoniazid, rifampicin and ethambutol are the standard safe drugs in pregnancy. Pyridoxine 25 to 50 mg/day prevents isoniazid-induced peripheral neuropathy.<br><br>C (Streptomycin) is correct because aminoglycoside ototoxicity is the established fetal effect. A (Isoniazid) is wrong because it is the cornerstone of safe TB therapy. B (Rifampicin) is wrong because it is considered safe with hepatic monitoring. D (Ethambutol) is wrong because it is also considered safe.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Antimycobacterial Drugs)</em>`},
    {q:'Which antifungal treatment is preferred for vaginal candidiasis during pregnancy?',o:['Oral ketoconazole','Oral fluconazole high dose','Griseofulvin','Topical azoles'],a:3,
    e:`Topical azoles (clotrimazole, miconazole) are preferred for vaginal candidiasis in pregnancy. Topical application produces minimal systemic absorption and is considered safe throughout pregnancy.<br><br>Oral fluconazole at high doses (≥400 mg/day) is associated with craniofacial and skeletal abnormalities and is avoided. Single low-dose oral fluconazole (150 mg) carries minimal risk but topical therapy remains preferred. Griseofulvin and oral ketoconazole are avoided in pregnancy.<br><br>D (Topical azoles) is correct because topical therapy avoids systemic exposure and is the established first-line. A (Oral ketoconazole) is wrong because oral ketoconazole is hepatotoxic and avoided. B (Oral fluconazole high dose) is wrong because high-dose fluconazole is teratogenic. C (Griseofulvin) is wrong because it is teratogenic and contraindicated.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Antifungal Agents)</em>`},
    {q:'Which drug exposure in pregnancy historically caused clear cell adenocarcinoma of the vagina in female offspring?',o:['Diethylstilbestrol','Progesterone','Estradiol','Tamoxifen'],a:0,
    e:`Diethylstilbestrol (DES), a synthetic non-steroidal oestrogen used between 1940 and 1971 to prevent miscarriage, caused clear cell adenocarcinoma of the vagina and cervix in female offspring (DES daughters), typically presenting in adolescence or young adulthood.<br><br>Other DES-associated effects include cervical and uterine structural abnormalities (T-shaped uterus, cervical hood), increased preterm birth risk and infertility. In male offspring, DES is associated with hypospadias and testicular abnormalities.<br><br>A (Diethylstilbestrol) is correct because the DES-vaginal cancer association is well established. B (Progesterone) is wrong because progesterone supplementation is widely used and not associated. C (Estradiol) is wrong because while it is an oestrogen, it is not the historical agent. D (Tamoxifen) is wrong because it is a SERM with different effects.<br><br><em>(Shaw\'s Textbook of Gynaecology; Chapter: Hormones in Gynaecology)</em>`},
    {q:'A lactating mother requires analgesia after delivery. Which drug is considered safest for use during breastfeeding?',o:['Aspirin','Codeine','Paracetamol','Indomethacin'],a:2,
    e:`Paracetamol is considered the safest analgesic during breastfeeding. Only small amounts pass into breast milk and at therapeutic doses no adverse effects on the infant have been observed.<br><br>NSAIDs (especially ibuprofen) are also compatible with breastfeeding. Aspirin is generally avoided due to theoretical Reye syndrome risk. Codeine carries variable risk based on maternal CYP2D6 metabolism.<br><br>C (Paracetamol) is correct because of minimal infant exposure and excellent safety record. A (Aspirin) is wrong because of Reye syndrome risk. B (Codeine) is wrong because some mothers (ultra-rapid metabolisers) produce excess morphine. D (Indomethacin) is wrong because it is best avoided due to limited infant data.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics; Chapter: The Puerperium)</em>`},
    {q:'Which pharmacokinetic property of a drug most strongly increases its transfer into breast milk?',o:['High lipid solubility','High molecular weight','High protein binding','Strong ionization'],a:0,
    e:`High lipid solubility most strongly increases drug transfer into breast milk. Lipid-soluble drugs cross cell membranes (mammary alveolar epithelium) more readily and concentrate in the lipid-rich milk.<br><br>Other key factors are low molecular weight (under 200 daltons), low protein binding (free drug crosses), and weak base nature (ion-trapped in slightly acidic milk vs maternal plasma). High protein binding and high molecular weight reduce transfer.<br><br>A (High lipid solubility) is correct because lipophilic drugs partition into milk fat and cross alveolar membranes readily. B (High molecular weight) is wrong because large molecules cross less easily. C (High protein binding) is wrong because bound drug stays in plasma. D (Strong ionization) is wrong because heavily ionised drugs cross membranes poorly.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Special Aspects of Perinatal Pharmacology)</em>`},
    {q:'Which factor favors greater drug concentration in breast milk compared with maternal plasma?',o:['High maternal plasma protein binding','Weakly basic drug nature','Low lipid solubility','Large molecular size'],a:1,
    e:`Weakly basic drugs concentrate in breast milk through ion trapping. Breast milk is slightly more acidic (pH ~7.0) than maternal plasma (pH ~7.4), so weak bases become protonated (ionised) in milk and trapped there.<br><br>Other factors favouring milk transfer include high lipid solubility, low molecular weight (under 200 daltons) and low maternal plasma protein binding. The milk-to-plasma drug concentration ratio (M/P ratio) is used to predict infant exposure.<br><br>B (Weakly basic drug nature) is correct because weak bases ionise and trap in slightly acidic milk. A (High maternal plasma protein binding) is wrong because protein-bound drug stays in plasma. C (Low lipid solubility) is wrong because hydrophilic drugs cross the milk barrier poorly. D (Large molecular size) is wrong because large molecules cross alveolar epithelium less readily.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Special Aspects of Perinatal Pharmacology)</em>`},
    {q:'A lactating woman takes aspirin regularly. Which adverse effect may occur in the breastfed infant?',o:['Spina bifida','Neural tube defect','Congenital cataract','Reye syndrome'],a:3,
    e:`Aspirin in breast milk may cause Reye syndrome in the infant, particularly during a viral infection. Reye syndrome features acute encephalopathy and hepatic dysfunction, with significant mortality.<br><br>The mechanism involves mitochondrial dysfunction triggered by salicylates during viral illness. Aspirin is therefore avoided in lactating women, especially during infant viral illness. Paracetamol or ibuprofen are safer alternatives.<br><br>D (Reye syndrome) is correct because salicylates can trigger Reye syndrome in infants exposed via breast milk. A (Spina bifida) is wrong because it is a teratogenic effect. B (Neural tube defect) is wrong for the same reason. C (Congenital cataract) is wrong because cataracts are associated with rubella.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Nonsteroidal Anti-Inflammatory Drugs)</em>`},
    {q:'Which drug is contraindicated during breastfeeding due to risk of infant hypothyroidism?',o:['Carbimazole high dose','Propylthiouracil','Levothyroxine','Iodine solution'],a:0,
    e:`High-dose carbimazole during breastfeeding can cause infant hypothyroidism because carbimazole and its active metabolite methimazole pass into breast milk and inhibit infant thyroid hormone synthesis.<br><br>At low to moderate doses (≤15 mg/day carbimazole), thyroid suppression is minimal and breastfeeding is generally compatible with infant TSH monitoring. Propylthiouracil has lower milk transfer and is also acceptable.<br><br>A (Carbimazole high dose) is correct because high doses cause significant infant thyroid suppression. B (Propylthiouracil) is wrong because it has lower milk transfer and is generally compatible. C (Levothyroxine) is wrong because it is thyroid replacement and is safe. D (Iodine solution) is wrong because while iodine excess can affect thyroid function, this is usually short-term.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Thyroid and Antithyroid Drugs)</em>`},
    {q:'A breastfeeding mother treated with chloramphenicol exposes the infant to which potential complication?',o:['Hemolytic anemia','Blue baby syndrome','Neonatal tetany','Gray baby syndrome'],a:3,
    e:`Chloramphenicol passes into breast milk and may cause gray baby syndrome in the infant, particularly in neonates with immature hepatic glucuronidation. The syndrome features pallor, abdominal distension, vomiting and circulatory collapse.<br><br>Chloramphenicol also inhibits mitochondrial protein synthesis and may cause idiosyncratic bone marrow suppression. Use is therefore avoided in lactating mothers of young infants. Penicillins, cephalosporins and macrolides are safer alternatives.<br><br>D (Gray baby syndrome) is correct because chloramphenicol accumulation in the infant produces this characteristic syndrome. A (Hemolytic anemia) is wrong because it is not the chloramphenicol effect. B (Blue baby syndrome) is wrong because it refers to congenital cyanotic heart disease. C (Neonatal tetany) is wrong because it relates to hypocalcaemia.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Tetracyclines, Macrolides, Clindamycin, Chloramphenicol, Streptogramins, and Oxazolidinones)</em>`},
    {q:'Which drug used for migraine should be avoided during breastfeeding due to risk of vomiting and diarrhea in the infant?',o:['Paracetamol','Ibuprofen','Ergotamine','Sumatriptan'],a:2,
    e:`Ergotamine is contraindicated during breastfeeding because it passes into breast milk and may cause vomiting, diarrhoea and convulsions in the infant. It also suppresses prolactin secretion and reduces milk production.<br><br>Migraine in lactating women is managed with paracetamol, ibuprofen or sumatriptan (compatible with breastfeeding). Beta-blockers (propranolol) are also acceptable for prophylaxis. Triptans have generally favourable lactation data.<br><br>C (Ergotamine) is correct because of milk-transferred infant toxicity and prolactin suppression. A (Paracetamol) is wrong because it is the safest analgesic in lactation. B (Ibuprofen) is wrong because it is also safe. D (Sumatriptan) is wrong because it is generally compatible with breastfeeding.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Histamine, Serotonin, and the Ergot Alkaloids)</em>`},
    {q:'Which antihypertensive drug is considered compatible with breastfeeding?',o:['Atenolol high dose','Methyldopa','Reserpine','Amiodarone'],a:1,
    e:`Methyldopa is considered compatible with breastfeeding. It passes into milk in small amounts and has not been associated with significant adverse effects in the infant.<br><br>Other antihypertensives compatible with breastfeeding include labetalol, nifedipine and propranolol (in moderate doses). High-dose atenolol can cause infant bradycardia and hypotension. ACE inhibitors are also compatible postnatally.<br><br>B (Methyldopa) is correct because of its established compatibility with breastfeeding. A (Atenolol high dose) is wrong because it can cause infant bradycardia and hypotension. C (Reserpine) is wrong because it can cause infant nasal congestion, lethargy and diarrhoea. D (Amiodarone) is wrong because it concentrates in milk and risks infant thyroid toxicity.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics; Chapter: The Puerperium)</em>`},
    {q:'Which antibiotic is considered safe during breastfeeding with minimal transfer into breast milk?',o:['Penicillin','Chloramphenicol','Tetracycline prolonged therapy','Ciprofloxacin'],a:0,
    e:`Penicillin and other beta-lactam antibiotics show minimal transfer into breast milk and are considered safe during breastfeeding. Small amounts of drug in milk may rarely cause infant diarrhoea, rash or candidiasis but are generally well tolerated.<br><br>Cephalosporins and macrolides (erythromycin, azithromycin) are also compatible. Tetracyclines should be avoided long-term due to tooth staining. Chloramphenicol is contraindicated due to gray baby syndrome and bone marrow suppression risk.<br><br>A (Penicillin) is correct because of minimal milk transfer and excellent safety. B (Chloramphenicol) is wrong because of gray baby syndrome and bone marrow risks. C (Tetracycline prolonged therapy) is wrong because of risk of infant tooth staining. D (Ciprofloxacin) is wrong because of cartilage toxicity in animal studies.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Beta-Lactam and Other Cell Wall- and Membrane-Active Antibiotics)</em>`},
    {q:'Which drug taken by a lactating mother may cause tooth discoloration in the breastfed infant if used long-term?',o:['Penicillin','Erythromycin','Tetracycline','Cephalexin'],a:2,
    e:`Tetracycline taken long-term by a lactating mother may cause yellow-brown tooth discoloration in the breastfed infant due to calcium chelation in calcifying teeth. Short-term use (under 21 days) is generally considered acceptable.<br><br>Tetracycline also chelates with calcium in milk and forms inactive complexes, reducing drug absorption by the infant. However, prolonged exposure remains a concern. Doxycycline has similar risks.<br><br>C (Tetracycline) is correct because long-term use causes infant tooth staining. A (Penicillin) is wrong because it is safe. B (Erythromycin) is wrong because it is also safe. D (Cephalexin) is wrong because cephalosporins are compatible with breastfeeding.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Tetracyclines, Macrolides, Clindamycin, Chloramphenicol, Streptogramins, and Oxazolidinones)</em>`},
    {q:'A lactating mother receiving benzodiazepines may cause which effect in the infant?',o:['Hyperactivity','Hypertension','Seizures','Excessive sedation'],a:3,
    e:`Benzodiazepines (especially long-acting agents like diazepam) cause excessive sedation in the breastfed infant due to drug accumulation. Infant immature hepatic metabolism prolongs drug elimination.<br><br>Diazepam and its active metabolites (desmethyldiazepam) accumulate over days. Short-acting benzodiazepines (lorazepam, oxazepam) at low doses are considered compatible. Single doses are usually well tolerated; chronic use should be avoided.<br><br>D (Excessive sedation) is correct because benzodiazepine accumulation in the infant causes sedation and poor feeding. A (Hyperactivity) is wrong because the effect is sedation, not stimulation. B (Hypertension) is wrong because benzodiazepines do not raise blood pressure. C (Seizures) is wrong because they are antiepileptic, not seizure-causing.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Sedative-Hypnotic Drugs)</em>`},
    {q:'Which antiepileptic drug commonly passes into breast milk but is generally considered compatible with breastfeeding with monitoring?',o:['Methotrexate','Valproate','Cyclophosphamide','Chloramphenicol'],a:1,
    e:`Valproate passes into breast milk in small amounts (around 1 to 10 percent of maternal dose) and is generally considered compatible with breastfeeding with infant monitoring for sedation, poor feeding or thrombocytopenia.<br><br>Other antiepileptics compatible with breastfeeding include carbamazepine, phenytoin (in moderate doses) and lamotrigine. Benzodiazepines and barbiturates may cause infant sedation. Cytotoxic drugs and chloramphenicol are absolutely contraindicated.<br><br>B (Valproate) is correct because the milk transfer is low and breastfeeding is generally compatible with infant monitoring. A (Methotrexate) is wrong because it is absolutely contraindicated in lactation. C (Cyclophosphamide) is wrong because it is also absolutely contraindicated. D (Chloramphenicol) is wrong because of gray baby and bone marrow risks.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Antiseizure Drugs)</em>`},
    {q:'Which drug used in chemotherapy is absolutely contraindicated during breastfeeding?',o:['Paracetamol','Amoxicillin','Methotrexate','Metronidazole single dose'],a:2,
    e:`Methotrexate is absolutely contraindicated during breastfeeding. As a folate antagonist and cytotoxic drug, it can cause bone marrow suppression, immunosuppression and growth disturbance in the infant.<br><br>Other absolute contraindications during breastfeeding include cyclophosphamide, doxorubicin, radioiodine, lithium and ciclosporin. Chemotherapy regimens generally require formula feeding. Methotrexate has a long terminal half-life requiring extended cessation of breastfeeding.<br><br>C (Methotrexate) is correct because it is absolutely contraindicated due to cytotoxicity. A (Paracetamol) is wrong because it is safe in breastfeeding. B (Amoxicillin) is wrong because penicillins are compatible. D (Metronidazole single dose) is wrong because single-dose metronidazole is generally acceptable with brief feeding interruption.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Cancer Chemotherapy)</em>`},
    {q:'Which characteristic of drugs reduces their transfer into breast milk?',o:['High lipid solubility','Low molecular weight','Weak base nature','High plasma protein binding'],a:3,
    e:`High plasma protein binding reduces drug transfer into breast milk because only the unbound fraction can cross the alveolar epithelium. Highly protein-bound drugs therefore reach lower milk concentrations.<br><br>Other factors that reduce milk transfer include large molecular weight (above 500 daltons), low lipid solubility, high ionisation at maternal plasma pH and acidic drug nature.<br><br>D (High plasma protein binding) is correct because protein-bound drug stays in plasma. A (High lipid solubility) is wrong because it increases transfer. B (Low molecular weight) is wrong because small molecules cross more easily. C (Weak base nature) is wrong because weak bases ion-trap into milk.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Special Aspects of Perinatal Pharmacology)</em>`},
    {q:'Which antibiotic in breastfeeding mothers may cause diarrhea and candidiasis in the infant?',o:['Broad-spectrum antibiotics','Penicillin','Cephalosporins','Amoxicillin'],a:0,
    e:`Broad-spectrum antibiotics in lactating mothers may cause diarrhoea and candidiasis in the infant by altering the infant\'s gut microflora. The drug itself may also directly cause loose stools.<br><br>Effects are usually mild and resolve when antibiotics are stopped. Probiotics may help. Penicillins and cephalosporins are generally well tolerated. Tetracyclines (long-term), chloramphenicol and ciprofloxacin are best avoided in lactation.<br><br>A (Broad-spectrum antibiotics) is correct because of gut flora alteration causing diarrhoea and candidiasis. B (Penicillin) is wrong because narrow-spectrum penicillins cause less flora disturbance. C (Cephalosporins) is wrong because they are generally well tolerated. D (Amoxicillin) is wrong because it is typically well tolerated as a focused option.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Beta-Lactam and Other Cell Wall- and Membrane-Active Antibiotics)</em>`},
    {q:'Which drug used for hyperthyroidism is generally considered safe in breastfeeding at moderate doses?',o:['Radioiodine','Propylthiouracil','Iodine solution high dose','Methotrexate'],a:1,
    e:`Propylthiouracil (PTU) is generally considered safe in breastfeeding at moderate doses (≤300 mg/day) because milk transfer is low. Infant thyroid function is monitored with periodic TSH measurement.<br><br>Methimazole and carbimazole at moderate doses are also acceptable. Higher doses of any antithyroid drug warrant infant TSH monitoring. Radioactive iodine is absolutely contraindicated.<br><br>B (Propylthiouracil) is correct because it has the lowest milk transfer at moderate doses. A (Radioiodine) is wrong because it is absolutely contraindicated. C (Iodine solution high dose) is wrong because high-dose iodine can cause infant thyroid suppression. D (Methotrexate) is wrong because it is absolutely contraindicated and not used for hyperthyroidism.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Thyroid and Antithyroid Drugs)</em>`},
    {q:'Which drug taken by the mother may suppress lactation due to dopamine agonist activity?',o:['Bromocriptine','Metoclopramide','Domperidone','Oxytocin'],a:0,
    e:`Bromocriptine is a dopamine agonist that suppresses prolactin secretion from the anterior pituitary, reducing milk production. It was historically used to suppress lactation but has fallen out of favour due to maternal cardiovascular and CNS side effects.<br><br>Cabergoline (another dopamine agonist) is now preferred when pharmacological lactation suppression is needed. Metoclopramide and domperidone are dopamine antagonists that increase prolactin and may stimulate milk production.<br><br>A (Bromocriptine) is correct because dopamine agonism suppresses prolactin and lactation. B (Metoclopramide) is wrong because it is a dopamine antagonist that may increase prolactin. C (Domperidone) is wrong for the same reason. D (Oxytocin) is wrong because it stimulates milk ejection (let-down), not synthesis suppression.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Hypothalamic and Pituitary Hormones)</em>`},
    {q:'Which antimalarial drug is generally considered compatible with breastfeeding?',o:['Primaquine','Chloroquine','Doxycycline','Tetracycline'],a:1,
    e:`Chloroquine is generally considered compatible with breastfeeding for malaria treatment and prophylaxis. Milk transfer is low and infant exposure is below therapeutic doses.<br><br>Mefloquine and atovaquone-proguanil are also acceptable. Doxycycline should be avoided long-term in lactation due to risk of tooth staining. Primaquine is contraindicated in G6PD-deficient infants because of haemolysis risk.<br><br>B (Chloroquine) is correct because of low milk transfer and good infant tolerance. A (Primaquine) is wrong because of haemolysis risk in G6PD-deficient infants. C (Doxycycline) is wrong because long-term use causes tooth staining. D (Tetracycline) is wrong for the same reason.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Antiprotozoal Drugs)</em>`},
    {q:'Which drug in breast milk may cause hemolysis in infants with G6PD deficiency?',o:['Cephalosporins','Penicillin','Sulfonamides','Azithromycin'],a:2,
    e:`Sulfonamides may cause haemolysis in G6PD-deficient breastfed infants because they generate oxidative stress that overwhelms the limited reducing capacity of G6PD-deficient red cells.<br><br>Sulfonamides also displace bilirubin from albumin and may cause kernicterus in jaundiced or premature neonates. They are therefore avoided in lactation when the infant has G6PD deficiency or is jaundiced/premature. Penicillins and cephalosporins are safer.<br><br>C (Sulfonamides) is correct because oxidative stress causes haemolysis in G6PD-deficient infants. A (Cephalosporins) is wrong because they are compatible with breastfeeding. B (Penicillin) is wrong because it is also compatible. D (Azithromycin) is wrong because macrolides are compatible.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Sulfonamides, Trimethoprim, and Quinolones)</em>`},
    {q:'A breastfeeding infant develops irritability and tachycardia after maternal medication use. Which maternal drug is the likely cause?',o:['Insulin','Paracetamol','Amoxicillin','Caffeine'],a:3,
    e:`Caffeine in maternal milk can cause infant irritability and tachycardia when consumed in large amounts (more than 5 cups of coffee per day). Caffeine is a CNS stimulant with a long half-life in neonates (about 80 hours).<br><br>Moderate maternal caffeine intake (under 300 mg/day, equivalent to 2 to 3 cups of coffee) is considered compatible with breastfeeding. Premature infants are most susceptible to caffeine accumulation due to immature hepatic metabolism.<br><br>D (Caffeine) is correct because of CNS stimulation in the infant. A (Insulin) is wrong because insulin does not pass into milk in significant amounts. B (Paracetamol) is wrong because it is the safest analgesic in lactation. C (Amoxicillin) is wrong because it does not cause CNS stimulation.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Drugs of Abuse)</em>`},
    {q:'Which drug taken by a breastfeeding mother may cause drowsiness and respiratory depression in the infant?',o:['Morphine','Ibuprofen','Paracetamol','Amoxicillin'],a:0,
    e:`Morphine and other opioids in breast milk may cause drowsiness, poor feeding and respiratory depression in the breastfed infant, particularly in neonates and premature infants with immature drug metabolism.<br><br>Codeine is converted to morphine by CYP2D6, and ultra-rapid metaboliser mothers may produce excess morphine, with reports of infant deaths. Single doses for postpartum analgesia are usually safe; prolonged use should be avoided.<br><br>A (Morphine) is correct because of milk-mediated infant respiratory depression risk. B (Ibuprofen) is wrong because it is one of the safest analgesics in lactation. C (Paracetamol) is wrong because it is the safest first-line analgesic. D (Amoxicillin) is wrong because it does not cause respiratory depression.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Opioid Analgesics and Antagonists)</em>`},
    {q:'Which drug class is generally considered safest for analgesia during lactation?',o:['Morphine','Aspirin high dose','Codeine high dose','NSAIDs like ibuprofen'],a:3,
    e:`NSAIDs such as ibuprofen are generally considered the safest analgesic class during lactation, with very low milk transfer and no significant adverse effects on the infant at therapeutic maternal doses.<br><br>Paracetamol is also first-line. High-dose aspirin is avoided due to Reye syndrome risk. Codeine carries variable risk based on maternal CYP2D6 metabolism. Morphine in single doses is acceptable but chronic use risks infant respiratory depression.<br><br>D (NSAIDs like ibuprofen) is correct because of low milk transfer and excellent infant safety. A (Morphine) is wrong because of risk of infant sedation and respiratory depression. B (Aspirin high dose) is wrong because of Reye syndrome risk. C (Codeine high dose) is wrong because of CYP2D6-related morphine accumulation in some mothers.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Nonsteroidal Anti-Inflammatory Drugs)</em>`},
    {q:'Which drug used in maternal psychiatric illness may cause sedation in a breastfed infant?',o:['Insulin','Diazepam','Metformin','Paracetamol'],a:1,
    e:`Diazepam and other benzodiazepines pass into breast milk and may cause sedation, poor feeding and lethargy in the breastfed infant due to drug accumulation. Diazepam in particular has a long half-life and active metabolites.<br><br>Short-acting benzodiazepines (lorazepam, oxazepam) at low doses are better tolerated. Single doses are usually well tolerated. Chronic use in lactation should generally be avoided or alternative agents considered.<br><br>B (Diazepam) is correct because long half-life and active metabolites accumulate in the infant. A (Insulin) is wrong because insulin does not pass into milk in significant amounts. C (Metformin) is wrong because it is generally compatible with breastfeeding. D (Paracetamol) is wrong because it is safe in lactation.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Sedative-Hypnotic Drugs)</em>`},
    {q:'Which drug should be avoided in breastfeeding due to risk of infant bone marrow suppression?',o:['Amoxicillin','Penicillin','Chloramphenicol','Cephalexin'],a:2,
    e:`Chloramphenicol should be avoided in breastfeeding because it can cause idiosyncratic bone marrow suppression in the infant in addition to gray baby syndrome from drug accumulation.<br><br>Bone marrow suppression is dose-independent and can be fatal. The drug also inhibits mitochondrial protein synthesis. Penicillins, cephalosporins and macrolides are safer alternatives. Chloramphenicol is reserved for rare situations where no alternative exists.<br><br>C (Chloramphenicol) is correct because of bone marrow suppression and gray baby syndrome risks. A (Amoxicillin) is wrong because it is safe in breastfeeding. B (Penicillin) is wrong because it is safe. D (Cephalexin) is wrong because cephalosporins are compatible.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Tetracyclines, Macrolides, Clindamycin, Chloramphenicol, Streptogramins, and Oxazolidinones)</em>`},
    {q:'Which drug taken by a breastfeeding mother may cause hypotension and lethargy in the infant?',o:['Metformin','Paracetamol','Insulin','Beta-blockers'],a:3,
    e:`Beta-blockers passing into breast milk may cause hypotension, bradycardia and lethargy in the breastfed infant, particularly with high-dose atenolol or nadolol which have higher milk transfer.<br><br>Labetalol, propranolol and metoprolol have lower milk transfer and are considered compatible with breastfeeding at moderate doses. Atenolol has the highest milk-to-plasma ratio among beta-blockers and is best avoided.<br><br>D (Beta-blockers) is correct because of milk-mediated infant cardiovascular effects. A (Metformin) is wrong because it is generally compatible with breastfeeding. B (Paracetamol) is wrong because it is the safest analgesic. C (Insulin) is wrong because insulin does not pass into milk in significant amounts.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Adrenoceptor Antagonist Drugs)</em>`},
    {q:'Which property of drugs promotes their concentration in breast milk through ion trapping?',o:['High protein binding','Weak base nature','Large molecular weight','Strong acidity'],a:1,
    e:`Weak base nature promotes drug concentration in breast milk through ion trapping. Breast milk is slightly more acidic (pH ~7.0) than maternal plasma (pH ~7.4), so weak bases become protonated (ionised) in milk and trapped there.<br><br>Other factors favouring milk transfer include high lipid solubility, low molecular weight (under 200 daltons) and low maternal plasma protein binding. The milk-to-plasma drug concentration ratio (M/P ratio) is used to predict infant exposure.<br><br>B (Weak base nature) is correct because weak bases ionise and trap in slightly acidic milk. A (High protein binding) is wrong because protein-bound drug stays in plasma. C (Large molecular weight) is wrong because large molecules cross alveolar epithelium less easily. D (Strong acidity) is wrong because strong acids ionise in plasma and stay there.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Special Aspects of Perinatal Pharmacology)</em>`},
    {q:'Which antidepressant is considered relatively safe during breastfeeding?',o:['Clozapine','Lithium','Sertraline','Methotrexate'],a:2,
    e:`Sertraline is considered relatively safe during breastfeeding among antidepressants. Milk transfer is low (M/P ratio under 1) and infant plasma levels are generally undetectable.<br><br>Paroxetine is also a good choice. Fluoxetine has higher milk transfer and a long-acting metabolite, with occasional reports of infant irritability or colic. SSRIs are generally preferred over tricyclic antidepressants in lactation. Lithium is contraindicated.<br><br>C (Sertraline) is correct because of low milk transfer and excellent infant safety. A (Clozapine) is wrong because it carries risk of infant agranulocytosis. B (Lithium) is wrong because it concentrates in milk and risks infant toxicity. D (Methotrexate) is wrong because it is absolutely contraindicated and not an antidepressant.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Antidepressant Agents)</em>`},
    {q:'Which drug used for migraine prophylaxis may cause vomiting and diarrhea in breastfed infants?',o:['Ergotamine','Paracetamol','Ibuprofen','Metoclopramide'],a:0,
    e:`Ergotamine for migraine prophylaxis or treatment is contraindicated in breastfeeding because it passes into milk and may cause vomiting, diarrhoea and convulsions in the infant. It also suppresses prolactin and reduces milk production.<br><br>Migraine in lactating women is managed with paracetamol, ibuprofen or sumatriptan (compatible with breastfeeding). Beta-blockers (propranolol) are also acceptable for prophylaxis. Triptans have generally favourable lactation data.<br><br>A (Ergotamine) is correct because of milk-transferred infant toxicity. B (Paracetamol) is wrong because it is the safest analgesic in lactation. C (Ibuprofen) is wrong because it is also safe. D (Metoclopramide) is wrong because while it raises prolactin and milk supply, infant exposure is generally well tolerated.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Histamine, Serotonin, and the Ergot Alkaloids)</em>`},
    {q:'Which drug exposure in breastfeeding infants may cause cyanosis due to methemoglobinemia?',o:['Penicillin','Nitrates','Cephalosporins','Amoxicillin'],a:1,
    e:`Nitrate exposure (e.g. through contaminated water or some medications) can cause methemoglobinemia in breastfed infants because their immature methaemoglobin reductase systems cannot efficiently reduce methaemoglobin back to haemoglobin.<br><br>Methaemoglobin cannot carry oxygen, leading to cyanosis (blue baby) and tissue hypoxia. Treatment is with methylene blue and high-flow oxygen. Infants under 6 months are particularly susceptible due to fetal haemoglobin and immature reductase activity.<br><br>B (Nitrates) is correct because of methaemoglobinaemia risk in immature infants. A (Penicillin) is wrong because it does not cause methaemoglobinaemia. C (Cephalosporins) is wrong for the same reason. D (Amoxicillin) is wrong for the same reason.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Vasodilators and the Treatment of Angina Pectoris)</em>`},
    {q:'Which drug class used by mothers may cause infant irritability and poor sleep during breastfeeding?',o:['Paracetamol','Insulin','Stimulants','Amoxicillin'],a:2,
    e:`Stimulants (caffeine, amphetamines, pseudoephedrine, methylphenidate) used by mothers may cause infant irritability, poor sleep and feeding difficulties through CNS stimulation transmitted via breast milk.<br><br>Effects depend on dose, frequency and infant age. Premature infants are most susceptible due to immature hepatic metabolism. Moderate caffeine intake (under 300 mg/day) is generally compatible. Heavy stimulant use should be avoided.<br><br>C (Stimulants) is correct because of CNS effects in the infant. A (Paracetamol) is wrong because it is the safest analgesic. B (Insulin) is wrong because insulin does not pass into milk in significant amounts. D (Amoxicillin) is wrong because it does not cause CNS stimulation.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Drugs of Abuse)</em>`},
    {q:'Which drug taken by breastfeeding mothers may cause diarrhea in infants due to alteration of gut flora?',o:['Antibiotics','Insulin','Paracetamol','Metformin'],a:0,
    e:`Antibiotics taken by breastfeeding mothers may cause infant diarrhoea by altering the infant\'s gut microflora. Broad-spectrum antibiotics produce greater flora disturbance than narrow-spectrum agents.<br><br>Effects are usually mild and resolve when antibiotics stop. Probiotics may help. Penicillins, cephalosporins and macrolides are generally well tolerated. Tetracyclines (long-term), chloramphenicol and ciprofloxacin are best avoided in lactation.<br><br>A (Antibiotics) is correct because of gut flora alteration causing diarrhoea. B (Insulin) is wrong because it does not pass into milk in significant amounts. C (Paracetamol) is wrong because it is safe and does not affect gut flora. D (Metformin) is wrong because it is compatible and does not cause significant infant diarrhoea.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Beta-Lactam and Other Cell Wall- and Membrane-Active Antibiotics)</em>`},
    {q:'Which maternal medication is known to increase milk production and is sometimes used therapeutically?',o:['Estrogen','Bromocriptine','Cabergoline','Domperidone'],a:3,
    e:`Domperidone is a peripheral dopamine D2 receptor antagonist that increases prolactin secretion and is sometimes used off-label as a galactagogue to increase milk supply in mothers with low production.<br><br>Metoclopramide has similar prolactin-raising properties but crosses the blood-brain barrier and may cause maternal extrapyramidal effects. Domperidone is preferred for galactagogue use due to its peripheral action. Bromocriptine and cabergoline (dopamine agonists) suppress lactation.<br><br>D (Domperidone) is correct because of its established galactagogue effect through prolactin elevation. A (Estrogen) is wrong because oestrogen suppresses milk production. B (Bromocriptine) is wrong because it is a dopamine agonist that suppresses lactation. C (Cabergoline) is wrong for the same reason.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Hypothalamic and Pituitary Hormones)</em>`},
    {q:'Which drug used in maternal thyroid disease is contraindicated in breastfeeding because of radioactive exposure to the infant?',o:['Carbimazole','Propylthiouracil','Radioiodine','Levothyroxine'],a:2,
    e:`Radioiodine (I-131) is contraindicated during breastfeeding because it concentrates in breast milk and exposes the infant\'s thyroid to radiation, with risk of permanent thyroid damage and increased thyroid cancer risk.<br><br>Breastfeeding must be discontinued before treatment and not resumed for the affected pregnancy. Diagnostic radioiodine scans similarly require temporary cessation of breastfeeding. Carbimazole and propylthiouracil at moderate doses are compatible with breastfeeding.<br><br>C (Radioiodine) is correct because radiation concentration in milk damages the infant thyroid. A (Carbimazole) is wrong because moderate doses are compatible with breastfeeding. B (Propylthiouracil) is wrong because it has the lowest milk transfer. D (Levothyroxine) is wrong because it is thyroid replacement and is safe in breastfeeding.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Thyroid and Antithyroid Drugs)</em>`},
    {q:'Which maternal medication may cause constipation and sedation in a breastfed infant?',o:['Insulin','Opioids','Paracetamol','Penicillin'],a:1,
    e:`Opioids in breast milk may cause sedation and constipation in the breastfed infant due to drug accumulation. Premature infants and neonates are most susceptible due to immature drug metabolism.<br><br>Codeine carries variable risk based on maternal CYP2D6 metabolism, with reports of infant deaths in mothers who are ultra-rapid metabolisers. Single doses are usually safe; prolonged use should be avoided. Morphine causes more milk-mediated sedation than codeine.<br><br>B (Opioids) is correct because of milk-transferred CNS depression. A (Insulin) is wrong because it does not pass into milk in significant amounts. C (Paracetamol) is wrong because it is the safest analgesic. D (Penicillin) is wrong because penicillins do not cause sedation or constipation.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Opioid Analgesics and Antagonists)</em>`},
    {q:'Which drug used for acne is contraindicated during breastfeeding due to risk of severe toxicity in infants?',o:['Isotretinoin systemic therapy','Benzoyl peroxide topical','Clindamycin topical','Azelaic acid'],a:0,
    e:`Systemic isotretinoin is contraindicated during breastfeeding because of the risk of severe retinoid toxicity in the infant. Although milk transfer data are limited, the drug\'s known severe toxicity profile and high lipophilicity warrant strict avoidance.<br><br>Topical retinoids may also be best avoided over wide skin areas. Topical benzoyl peroxide, azelaic acid and topical clindamycin are considered acceptable for acne in lactating women.<br><br>A (Isotretinoin systemic therapy) is correct because of severe potential infant toxicity. B (Benzoyl peroxide topical) is wrong because topical use has minimal absorption and is considered safe. C (Clindamycin topical) is wrong because topical clindamycin is acceptable. D (Azelaic acid) is wrong because it is considered safe in lactation.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics; Chapter: The Puerperium)</em>`},
    {q:'Which drug taken by a breastfeeding mother may cause irritability and insomnia in the infant due to CNS stimulation?',o:['Insulin','Paracetamol','Penicillin','Caffeine'],a:3,
    e:`Caffeine is a CNS stimulant that passes into breast milk and may cause irritability and insomnia in the breastfed infant when consumed in large amounts. Caffeine has a very long half-life in neonates (~80 hours).<br><br>Moderate maternal intake (under 300 mg/day, 2 to 3 cups of coffee) is considered compatible with breastfeeding. Premature infants are most susceptible due to immature hepatic metabolism. Other dietary sources include tea, cola and chocolate.<br><br>D (Caffeine) is correct because of CNS stimulation in the infant. A (Insulin) is wrong because it does not pass into milk in significant amounts. B (Paracetamol) is wrong because it is safe in lactation. C (Penicillin) is wrong because it does not cause CNS stimulation.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Drugs of Abuse)</em>`},
    {q:'Which antibiotic used during breastfeeding may cause infant diarrhea and rash but is generally safe?',o:['Tetracycline prolonged therapy','Chloramphenicol','Amoxicillin','Doxycycline'],a:2,
    e:`Amoxicillin is generally considered safe during breastfeeding. Small amounts pass into milk and may cause infant diarrhoea, rash or candidiasis from gut flora alteration, but these effects are mild and rarely require treatment cessation.<br><br>Other beta-lactams (penicillin, cephalosporins) and macrolides are similarly compatible. Tetracyclines (long-term), chloramphenicol and ciprofloxacin are best avoided. Maternal benefit usually outweighs minor infant side effects.<br><br>C (Amoxicillin) is correct because of low milk transfer and minor self-limiting infant side effects. A (Tetracycline prolonged therapy) is wrong because of infant tooth staining risk. B (Chloramphenicol) is wrong because of bone marrow suppression and gray baby syndrome. D (Doxycycline) is wrong because it is also a tetracycline.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Beta-Lactam and Other Cell Wall- and Membrane-Active Antibiotics)</em>`},
    {q:'Which drug used in epilepsy may cause mild sedation in breastfed infants but is usually compatible with breastfeeding?',o:['Chloramphenicol','Methotrexate','Cyclophosphamide','Carbamazepine'],a:3,
    e:`Carbamazepine passes into breast milk in small amounts (M/P ratio ~0.4) and is generally considered compatible with breastfeeding. Mild infant sedation can occur and warrants monitoring.<br><br>Other antiepileptics generally compatible with breastfeeding include valproate, phenytoin (in moderate doses) and lamotrigine. Benzodiazepines and barbiturates may cause more infant sedation. Cytotoxic drugs are absolutely contraindicated.<br><br>D (Carbamazepine) is correct because of low milk transfer and acceptable infant tolerance. A (Chloramphenicol) is wrong because of gray baby and bone marrow risks. B (Methotrexate) is wrong because it is absolutely contraindicated. C (Cyclophosphamide) is wrong because it is also absolutely contraindicated.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Antiseizure Drugs)</em>`},
    {q:'Which drug used by mothers with hypertension is generally considered compatible with breastfeeding?',o:['Atenolol high dose','Labetalol','Amiodarone','Lithium'],a:1,
    e:`Labetalol is considered compatible with breastfeeding for maternal hypertension. Milk transfer is low (M/P ratio ~0.5 to 1.5) and infant exposure remains below pharmacological levels.<br><br>Other antihypertensives compatible with breastfeeding include methyldopa, propranolol, metoprolol and nifedipine. Atenolol at high doses can cause infant bradycardia and is best avoided. ACE inhibitors are also acceptable postnatally.<br><br>B (Labetalol) is correct because of low milk transfer and good infant tolerance. A (Atenolol high dose) is wrong because of higher milk transfer and risk of infant bradycardia. C (Amiodarone) is wrong because it concentrates in milk and risks infant thyroid toxicity. D (Lithium) is wrong because it is contraindicated in lactation.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics; Chapter: The Puerperium)</em>`},
    {q:'Which drug taken by breastfeeding mothers may cause thyroid suppression in infants?',o:['Excess iodine','Paracetamol','Penicillin','Insulin'],a:0,
    e:`Excess iodine in lactating mothers (from supplements, contrast media or topical antiseptics) concentrates in breast milk and may cause infant thyroid suppression (Wolff-Chaikoff effect) and goitre.<br><br>The infant thyroid is particularly sensitive to iodine excess. Brief exposure (e.g. povidone-iodine wound dressings) is usually well tolerated. Prolonged or high-dose iodine should be avoided. Routine iodine supplementation at recommended doses is safe and beneficial.<br><br>A (Excess iodine) is correct because milk-concentrated iodine suppresses the infant thyroid. B (Paracetamol) is wrong because it does not affect the thyroid. C (Penicillin) is wrong for the same reason. D (Insulin) is wrong because insulin does not pass into milk in significant amounts.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Thyroid and Antithyroid Drugs)</em>`},
    {q:'Which drug used in maternal psychiatric illness is contraindicated during breastfeeding because of risk of infant toxicity?',o:['Sertraline','Lithium','Paroxetine','Fluoxetine'],a:1,
    e:`Lithium is contraindicated during breastfeeding because it concentrates in breast milk (M/P ratio ~0.5) and may cause infant toxicity, including hypothyroidism, lethargy, hypotonia and ECG changes (T-wave flattening).<br><br>Infant lithium clearance is reduced. If lithium must be continued, mothers may bottle-feed. Sertraline, paroxetine and other SSRIs are preferred for psychiatric illness in lactating women. Valproate is generally compatible.<br><br>B (Lithium) is correct because of significant milk transfer and infant toxicity risk. A (Sertraline) is wrong because it is one of the safest antidepressants in lactation. C (Paroxetine) is wrong because it is also a safe SSRI choice. D (Fluoxetine) is wrong because while it has higher milk transfer than sertraline, it is generally compatible.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Antipsychotic Agents and Lithium)</em>`},
    {q:'Which factor in the infant increases the risk of drug toxicity from breast milk?',o:['Full-term birth','Older age','Prematurity','Mature liver function'],a:2,
    e:`Prematurity in the infant increases the risk of drug toxicity from breast milk because preterm infants have immature hepatic metabolism, reduced renal clearance, lower plasma protein binding and immature blood-brain barrier.<br><br>These factors prolong drug half-life, increase free drug concentration and increase CNS exposure. Drug doses transferred via milk that are well tolerated by full-term infants may cause toxicity in preterm infants. Caution is required with all maternal medications.<br><br>C (Prematurity) is correct because immature elimination systems increase drug accumulation. A (Full-term birth) is wrong because full-term infants have more mature elimination. B (Older age) is wrong because older infants metabolise more efficiently. D (Mature liver function) is wrong because mature liver function reduces toxicity risk.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Special Aspects of Perinatal Pharmacology)</em>`},
    {q:'Which maternal drug may cause decreased milk production due to estrogenic effect?',o:['Insulin','Paracetamol','Penicillin','Combined oral contraceptives'],a:3,
    e:`Combined oral contraceptives may decrease milk production due to the oestrogen component. Oestrogen suppresses prolactin\'s action on mammary epithelium and reduces milk volume, particularly in the early postpartum period.<br><br>Progestin-only methods (mini-pill, depot, IUD, implants) do not significantly affect milk supply and are preferred for contraception during breastfeeding. Combined contraceptives may be considered after 6 months when lactation is well established.<br><br>D (Combined oral contraceptives) is correct because oestrogen suppresses milk production. A (Insulin) is wrong because insulin does not affect lactation. B (Paracetamol) is wrong for the same reason. C (Penicillin) is wrong for the same reason.<br><br><em>(Shaw\'s Textbook of Gynaecology; Chapter: Contraception)</em>`},
    {q:'Which drug used in breastfeeding mothers may cause infant bradycardia if transferred through milk?',o:['Beta-blockers','Paracetamol','Insulin','Amoxicillin'],a:0,
    e:`Beta-blockers in breast milk may cause infant bradycardia, particularly with high-dose atenolol or nadolol which have higher milk-to-plasma ratios. The infant heart rate may drop and feeding may suffer.<br><br>Labetalol, propranolol and metoprolol have lower milk transfer and are considered compatible with breastfeeding at moderate doses. Atenolol is best avoided in lactation. Infant heart rate monitoring is reasonable when high-dose beta-blockers are essential.<br><br>A (Beta-blockers) is correct because of milk-mediated infant cardiovascular effects. B (Paracetamol) is wrong because it does not affect heart rate. C (Insulin) is wrong because insulin does not pass into milk in significant amounts. D (Amoxicillin) is wrong because it does not cause bradycardia.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Adrenoceptor Antagonist Drugs)</em>`},
    {q:'Which class of drugs is generally avoided in breastfeeding because of risk of immunosuppression in the infant?',o:['Paracetamol','Penicillins','Cephalosporins','Cytotoxic drugs'],a:3,
    e:`Cytotoxic drugs (methotrexate, cyclophosphamide, doxorubicin, cisplatin) are generally avoided in breastfeeding because they suppress the infant\'s rapidly dividing cells, including bone marrow, with risk of immunosuppression, neutropaenia and growth disturbance.<br><br>Most chemotherapy regimens require formula feeding for the duration of treatment and a washout period after. Some agents have very long terminal half-lives requiring extended cessation of breastfeeding even after a single dose.<br><br>D (Cytotoxic drugs) is correct because of infant bone marrow and immune suppression risk. A (Paracetamol) is wrong because it is safe in lactation. B (Penicillins) is wrong because they are compatible with breastfeeding. C (Cephalosporins) is wrong for the same reason.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Cancer Chemotherapy)</em>`},
    {q:'Which drug taken by breastfeeding mothers may cause hypotonia and sedation in the infant due to CNS depression?',o:['Benzodiazepines','Insulin','Paracetamol','Amoxicillin'],a:0,
    e:`Benzodiazepines passing into breast milk may cause infant hypotonia, sedation and poor feeding due to CNS depression. Long-acting agents (diazepam) and active metabolites accumulate in the infant due to immature drug metabolism.<br><br>Short-acting benzodiazepines (lorazepam, oxazepam) at low doses are better tolerated. Single doses are usually well tolerated; chronic use should generally be avoided.<br><br>A (Benzodiazepines) is correct because of CNS depression in the infant. B (Insulin) is wrong because it does not cause CNS depression. C (Paracetamol) is wrong because it does not cause sedation. D (Amoxicillin) is wrong for the same reason.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Sedative-Hypnotic Drugs)</em>`},
    {q:'Which drug used in maternal hyperthyroidism requires infant thyroid monitoring during breastfeeding?',o:['Insulin','Carbimazole','Paracetamol','Amoxicillin'],a:1,
    e:`Carbimazole (and its active metabolite methimazole) used by mothers with hyperthyroidism passes into breast milk and may suppress infant thyroid function. Infant thyroid monitoring (TSH at intervals) is therefore recommended during maternal antithyroid therapy.<br><br>At moderate doses (≤15 mg/day carbimazole or ≤10 mg/day methimazole), suppression is minimal and breastfeeding is generally compatible. Propylthiouracil has lower milk transfer. Radioiodine is absolutely contraindicated.<br><br>B (Carbimazole) is correct because milk transfer requires infant thyroid monitoring. A (Insulin) is wrong because it does not affect the infant thyroid. C (Paracetamol) is wrong for the same reason. D (Amoxicillin) is wrong for the same reason.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Thyroid and Antithyroid Drugs)</em>`},
    {q:'Which maternal drug exposure through breast milk may cause jaundice in the infant due to bilirubin displacement?',o:['Amoxicillin','Penicillin','Sulfonamides','Cephalosporins'],a:2,
    e:`Sulfonamides may cause neonatal jaundice through bilirubin displacement from albumin. Free unconjugated bilirubin can then deposit in the basal ganglia, with risk of kernicterus, especially in jaundiced or premature neonates.<br><br>Sulfonamides also cause haemolysis in G6PD-deficient infants through oxidative stress. They are therefore avoided in lactation when the infant is jaundiced, premature or G6PD-deficient. Penicillins and cephalosporins are safer.<br><br>C (Sulfonamides) is correct because albumin displacement of bilirubin causes neonatal jaundice. A (Amoxicillin) is wrong because penicillins do not displace bilirubin. B (Penicillin) is wrong for the same reason. D (Cephalosporins) is wrong for the same reason.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Sulfonamides, Trimethoprim, and Quinolones)</em>`},
    {q:'Which drug is considered compatible with breastfeeding for treatment of maternal infection?',o:['Chloramphenicol','Cephalosporins','Tetracycline prolonged therapy','Cytotoxic drugs'],a:1,
    e:`Cephalosporins are considered compatible with breastfeeding for treatment of maternal infection. Milk transfer is minimal and infant exposure is well below therapeutic doses, with rare mild gastrointestinal effects.<br><br>Penicillins and macrolides are similarly compatible. Tetracyclines (long-term), chloramphenicol and ciprofloxacin are best avoided. Cytotoxic drugs are absolutely contraindicated.<br><br>B (Cephalosporins) is correct because of low milk transfer and good infant tolerance. A (Chloramphenicol) is wrong because of gray baby and bone marrow risks. C (Tetracycline prolonged therapy) is wrong because of tooth staining. D (Cytotoxic drugs) is wrong because they are absolutely contraindicated.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Beta-Lactam and Other Cell Wall- and Membrane-Active Antibiotics)</em>`},
    {q:'Which maternal medication can suppress prolactin secretion and decrease breast milk production?',o:['Dopamine agonists','Paracetamol','Penicillin','Insulin'],a:0,
    e:`Dopamine agonists (bromocriptine, cabergoline) suppress prolactin secretion from the anterior pituitary, decreasing milk production. They are used to suppress lactation when breastfeeding is contraindicated or when stillbirth occurs.<br><br>Cabergoline is preferred (single-dose 1 mg) due to fewer side effects than bromocriptine. Pseudoephedrine, oestrogens and combined oral contraceptives can also reduce milk supply. Metoclopramide and domperidone are dopamine antagonists that increase prolactin.<br><br>A (Dopamine agonists) is correct because of prolactin suppression and reduced milk production. B (Paracetamol) is wrong because it does not affect lactation. C (Penicillin) is wrong for the same reason. D (Insulin) is wrong for the same reason.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Hypothalamic and Pituitary Hormones)</em>`},
    {q:'Which drug taken by the mother may cause restlessness and poor feeding in the breastfed infant?',o:['Amoxicillin','Paracetamol','Caffeine','Insulin'],a:2,
    e:`Caffeine in breast milk may cause infant restlessness and poor feeding due to CNS stimulation. The very long neonatal half-life (~80 hours) leads to cumulative effects with regular maternal intake.<br><br>Moderate maternal caffeine intake (under 300 mg/day) is generally compatible with breastfeeding. Premature infants are most susceptible due to immature hepatic metabolism. Other dietary sources include tea, cola and chocolate.<br><br>C (Caffeine) is correct because of CNS stimulation in the infant. A (Amoxicillin) is wrong because it does not cause restlessness. B (Paracetamol) is wrong for the same reason. D (Insulin) is wrong because it does not pass into milk in significant amounts.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Drugs of Abuse)</em>`},
    {q:'Which property of drugs facilitates easier passage into breast milk?',o:['High ionization','Large molecular weight','High protein binding','Low molecular weight'],a:3,
    e:`Low molecular weight (under 200 daltons) facilitates easier passage of drugs into breast milk because small molecules cross alveolar epithelial cell membranes more readily than larger molecules.<br><br>Other factors favouring transfer include high lipid solubility, weak base nature (ion-trapping in slightly acidic milk) and low maternal plasma protein binding. Conversely, large molecules (heparin, insulin) and highly protein-bound drugs transfer poorly.<br><br>D (Low molecular weight) is correct because small molecules cross alveolar membranes more easily. A (High ionization) is wrong because heavily ionised drugs cross poorly. B (Large molecular weight) is wrong because large molecules transfer poorly. C (High protein binding) is wrong because protein-bound drug stays in plasma.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Special Aspects of Perinatal Pharmacology)</em>`},
    {q:'Which drug used in migraine is contraindicated during breastfeeding because it suppresses prolactin and causes infant toxicity?',o:['Ergotamine','Paracetamol','Ibuprofen','Metoclopramide'],a:0,
    e:`Ergotamine for migraine is contraindicated during breastfeeding because it suppresses prolactin secretion (reducing milk production) and causes infant toxicity (vomiting, diarrhoea, convulsions) when transferred via milk.<br><br>Migraine in lactating women is managed with paracetamol, ibuprofen, sumatriptan or beta-blocker prophylaxis (propranolol). Triptans have generally favourable lactation data.<br><br>A (Ergotamine) is correct because of prolactin suppression and infant toxicity. B (Paracetamol) is wrong because it is the safest analgesic in lactation. C (Ibuprofen) is wrong because it is also safe. D (Metoclopramide) is wrong because while it raises prolactin, infant exposure is generally well tolerated.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Histamine, Serotonin, and the Ergot Alkaloids)</em>`},
    {q:'Which antibiotic exposure through breast milk may lead to alteration of infant gut flora and candidiasis?',o:['Paracetamol','Broad-spectrum antibiotics','Insulin','Metformin'],a:1,
    e:`Broad-spectrum antibiotics in breast milk may alter the infant\'s gut flora, leading to diarrhoea and oral or perianal candidiasis. The drug itself may also directly cause loose stools.<br><br>Effects are usually mild and resolve when antibiotics are stopped. Probiotics may help. Penicillins and cephalosporins are generally well tolerated. Tetracyclines (long-term), chloramphenicol and ciprofloxacin are best avoided.<br><br>B (Broad-spectrum antibiotics) is correct because of gut flora alteration causing diarrhoea and candidiasis. A (Paracetamol) is wrong because it does not affect gut flora. C (Insulin) is wrong because insulin does not pass into milk in significant amounts. D (Metformin) is wrong because it does not significantly alter infant gut flora.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Beta-Lactam and Other Cell Wall- and Membrane-Active Antibiotics)</em>`},
    {q:'Which drug used for diabetes is safe during breastfeeding because it does not significantly pass into breast milk?',o:['Cyclophosphamide','Chloramphenicol','Methotrexate','Insulin'],a:3,
    e:`Insulin is safe during breastfeeding because it is a large polypeptide molecule (5808 daltons) that does not pass into breast milk in significant amounts. Any small amount transferred is destroyed by infant gastrointestinal proteases.<br><br>Metformin is also generally compatible with breastfeeding (low milk transfer). Glyburide is acceptable. Pioglitazone is best avoided due to limited safety data. Insulin remains the gold standard for glycaemic control in pregnancy and lactation.<br><br>D (Insulin) is correct because of minimal milk transfer and gastric destruction. A (Cyclophosphamide) is wrong because it is a cytotoxic drug absolutely contraindicated. B (Chloramphenicol) is wrong because of gray baby and bone marrow risks. C (Methotrexate) is wrong because it is absolutely contraindicated.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Pancreatic Hormones and Antidiabetic Drugs)</em>`},
    {q:'Which maternal medication may cause infant hypotension if significantly transferred via breast milk?',o:['Insulin','Paracetamol','Propranolol','Penicillin'],a:2,
    e:`Propranolol is a beta-blocker that, when significantly transferred via breast milk, may cause infant hypotension and bradycardia. Milk transfer is moderate (M/P ratio ~0.5).<br><br>At standard maternal doses, propranolol is generally well tolerated by breastfed infants. Atenolol has higher milk transfer and is best avoided. Labetalol and metoprolol are alternatives. Infant heart rate and feeding monitoring is reasonable with high-dose beta-blockers.<br><br>C (Propranolol) is correct because of milk-mediated infant cardiovascular effects. A (Insulin) is wrong because insulin does not affect blood pressure. B (Paracetamol) is wrong because it does not affect blood pressure. D (Penicillin) is wrong for the same reason.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Adrenoceptor Antagonist Drugs)</em>`},
    {q:'Which drug used in psychiatric illness is generally considered compatible with breastfeeding in low doses?',o:['Clozapine','Sertraline','Lithium','Methotrexate'],a:1,
    e:`Sertraline is one of the SSRIs considered most compatible with breastfeeding in low doses. Milk transfer is low (M/P ratio under 1) and infant plasma levels are generally undetectable.<br><br>Paroxetine is also a good choice. Fluoxetine has higher milk transfer and a long-acting metabolite, with occasional reports of infant irritability or colic. SSRIs are generally preferred over tricyclic antidepressants. Lithium is contraindicated.<br><br>B (Sertraline) is correct because of low milk transfer and good infant safety. A (Clozapine) is wrong because it carries risk of infant agranulocytosis. C (Lithium) is wrong because it is contraindicated in lactation. D (Methotrexate) is wrong because it is absolutely contraindicated and not an antidepressant.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Antidepressant Agents)</em>`},
    {q:'Which drug taken by breastfeeding mothers may cause infant sedation and poor suckling reflex?',o:['Diazepam','Paracetamol','Penicillin','Insulin'],a:0,
    e:`Diazepam in breast milk may cause infant sedation and poor suckling reflex due to drug accumulation. Diazepam has a long half-life and active metabolites (desmethyldiazepam) that build up in the infant due to immature hepatic metabolism.<br><br>Short-acting benzodiazepines (lorazepam, oxazepam) at low doses are better tolerated. Single doses are usually well tolerated; chronic use should generally be avoided or alternative agents considered.<br><br>A (Diazepam) is correct because of CNS depression and poor feeding in the infant. B (Paracetamol) is wrong because it does not cause sedation. C (Penicillin) is wrong for the same reason. D (Insulin) is wrong because insulin does not pass into milk in significant amounts.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Sedative-Hypnotic Drugs)</em>`},
    {q:'Which drug exposure through breast milk may cause infant vomiting and diarrhea due to gastrointestinal irritation?',o:['Insulin','Paracetamol','Ergotamine','Amoxicillin'],a:2,
    e:`Ergotamine in breast milk may cause infant vomiting and diarrhoea due to direct gastrointestinal irritation. It also suppresses prolactin secretion and reduces milk production.<br><br>Migraine in lactating women is managed with paracetamol, ibuprofen, sumatriptan or beta-blocker prophylaxis (propranolol). Triptans have generally favourable lactation data.<br><br>C (Ergotamine) is correct because of GI irritation in the infant. A (Insulin) is wrong because it does not cause GI irritation. B (Paracetamol) is wrong for the same reason. D (Amoxicillin) is wrong because while it can cause mild diarrhoea via flora alteration, the GI irritation pattern fits ergotamine.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Histamine, Serotonin, and the Ergot Alkaloids)</em>`},
    {q:'Which infant group is most susceptible to adverse drug effects transmitted through breast milk?',o:['Toddlers','Infants older than 1 year','Healthy full-term infants','Premature infants'],a:3,
    e:`Premature infants are most susceptible to adverse drug effects from breast milk because they have immature hepatic metabolism, reduced renal clearance, lower plasma protein binding and immature blood-brain barrier.<br><br>These factors prolong drug half-life, increase free drug concentration and increase CNS drug exposure. Drug doses transferred via milk that are well tolerated by full-term infants may cause toxicity in preterm infants. Caution is required with all maternal medications.<br><br>D (Premature infants) is correct because immature elimination systems increase drug accumulation. A (Toddlers) is wrong because they have mature elimination. B (Infants older than 1 year) is wrong for the same reason. C (Healthy full-term infants) is wrong because full-term infants have more mature elimination than preterm infants.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Special Aspects of Perinatal Pharmacology)</em>`},
    {q:'Which local anesthetic is most commonly used for epidural analgesia during labor?',o:['Bupivacaine','Lidocaine','Procaine','Chloroprocaine'],a:0,
    e:`Bupivacaine is the most commonly used local anaesthetic for epidural analgesia during labour due to its long duration of action (about 2 to 3 hours) and good differential block (sensory more than motor at low concentrations).<br><br>Low-concentration bupivacaine (0.0625 to 0.125 percent) provides sensory block while preserving motor function for ambulation and pushing. Ropivacaine is an alternative with similar properties and lower cardiotoxicity. Lidocaine has shorter duration. Cardiotoxicity is a major risk with accidental intravascular injection.<br><br>A (Bupivacaine) is correct because of its long duration and differential sensory block. B (Lidocaine) is wrong because of shorter duration making it less suitable for prolonged labour analgesia. C (Procaine) is wrong because it is an older ester anaesthetic with limited use. D (Chloroprocaine) is wrong because it is short-acting and generally used for rapid-onset epidural top-ups.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Local Anesthetics)</em>`},
    {q:'The primary mechanism of action of local anesthetics is blockade of which ion channel in nerve fibers?',o:['Chloride channels','Potassium channels','Sodium channels','Calcium channels'],a:2,
    e:`Local anaesthetics block voltage-gated sodium channels in nerve fibres, preventing sodium influx and the propagation of action potentials. This produces reversible loss of sensation in the area of administration.<br><br>Local anaesthetics bind preferentially to inactivated sodium channels (use-dependent block), so rapidly firing fibres (small pain fibres) are blocked first. The amide group (lidocaine, bupivacaine) and ester group (procaine, chloroprocaine) differ mainly in metabolism (hepatic vs plasma cholinesterase).<br><br>C (Sodium channels) is correct because Na⁺ channel blockade prevents action potential propagation. A (Chloride channels) is wrong because they are targeted by GABA-A modulators (benzodiazepines, barbiturates). B (Potassium channels) is wrong because K⁺ channel modulation is a different mechanism. D (Calcium channels) is wrong because Ca²⁺ blockers are used as antihypertensives and tocolytics.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Local Anesthetics)</em>`},
    {q:'In obstetric anesthesia, which regional technique provides analgesia while allowing the mother to remain conscious during labor?',o:['Spinal cord transection','Deep sedation','General anesthesia','Epidural analgesia'],a:3,
    e:`Epidural analgesia provides effective pain relief during labour while allowing the mother to remain conscious and participate in delivery. A catheter is placed in the epidural space (lumbar L3-L4 or L4-L5) and local anaesthetic (typically dilute bupivacaine with fentanyl) is infused.<br><br>Advantages include effective analgesia, ability to convert to surgical anaesthesia for instrumental or caesarean delivery, and continuous titratable analgesia throughout labour. Complications include hypotension (sympathetic blockade), motor weakness and rare dural puncture.<br><br>D (Epidural analgesia) is correct because it provides analgesia with maternal consciousness preserved. A (Spinal cord transection) is wrong because it is not an anaesthetic technique but a pathological injury. B (Deep sedation) is wrong because deep sedation reduces consciousness. C (General anaesthesia) is wrong because it eliminates consciousness entirely.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics; Chapter: Obstetrical Anesthesia)</em>`},
    {q:'Which complication is most characteristic of accidental dural puncture during epidural anesthesia?',o:['Pulmonary embolism','Severe headache after delivery','Hematuria','Uterine rupture'],a:1,
    e:`Accidental dural puncture during epidural anaesthesia results in cerebrospinal fluid leak and post-dural puncture headache (PDPH), characteristically severe, postural (worse on standing, relieved by lying flat), frontal or occipital, and starting 24 to 72 hours after the procedure.<br><br>Treatment is initially conservative (bed rest, hydration, caffeine, analgesics). Refractory cases are treated with epidural blood patch (15 to 20 mL of autologous blood injected into the epidural space at the puncture site). Risk is approximately 1 to 2 percent with epidural placement.<br><br>B (Severe headache after delivery) is correct because PDPH is the classical complication of dural puncture. A (Pulmonary embolism) is wrong because it is unrelated to dural puncture. C (Hematuria) is wrong because dural puncture does not affect the urinary tract. D (Uterine rupture) is wrong because it is unrelated to anaesthetic technique.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics; Chapter: Obstetrical Anesthesia)</em>`},
    {q:'Which drug is commonly added to epidural local anesthetics to prolong analgesia and reduce dose requirement?',o:['Magnesium sulfate','Atropine','Calcium gluconate','Epinephrine'],a:3,
    e:`Epinephrine is commonly added to epidural local anaesthetics (typically 1:200,000) to prolong analgesia and reduce systemic absorption. Epinephrine causes local vasoconstriction at the injection site, slowing drug clearance and prolonging duration of action.<br><br>Epinephrine also serves as a marker for accidental intravascular injection (causing tachycardia and hypertension if injected IV). Fentanyl is also commonly added to enhance analgesia synergistically and allow lower local anaesthetic doses, reducing motor block.<br><br>D (Epinephrine) is correct because vasoconstriction prolongs local anaesthetic action. A (Magnesium sulfate) is wrong because it is used for eclampsia, not as an epidural adjunct. B (Atropine) is wrong because it is used for bradycardia, not local anaesthetic prolongation. C (Calcium gluconate) is wrong because it reverses magnesium toxicity.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Local Anesthetics)</em>`},
    {q:'Which inhalational anesthetic agent is commonly used to provide analgesia during labor in some obstetric units?',o:['Desflurane','Ether','Nitrous oxide','Halothane'],a:2,
    e:`Nitrous oxide (Entonox, 50 percent N₂O with 50 percent O₂) is commonly used in some obstetric units for inhalational labour analgesia. It provides mild to moderate analgesia, has rapid onset and offset (within breaths), and is self-administered by the mother through a demand valve.<br><br>Advantages include preserved consciousness, no significant maternal cardiovascular effects, no significant fetal effects (rapid clearance) and patient control. Limitations include partial efficacy (better as adjunct), nausea, dizziness and prolonged occupational exposure concerns for staff.<br><br>C (Nitrous oxide) is correct because of established use as Entonox for labour analgesia. A (Desflurane) is wrong because it is a volatile inhalational anaesthetic used in general anaesthesia, not for labour analgesia. B (Ether) is wrong because it is obsolete and toxic. D (Halothane) is wrong because it is associated with hepatotoxicity and uterine relaxation; not used for labour analgesia.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: General Anesthetics)</em>`},
    {q:'Which local anesthetic toxicity manifests with seizures and cardiac arrhythmias?',o:['Systemic local anesthetic toxicity','Amniotic fluid embolism','Placenta previa','Postpartum hemorrhage'],a:0,
    e:`Local anaesthetic systemic toxicity (LAST) results from accidental intravascular injection or excessive total dose. Early signs include circumoral numbness, metallic taste, tinnitus, dizziness and visual disturbance, progressing to convulsions and finally cardiac arrhythmias and arrest.<br><br>Bupivacaine is particularly cardiotoxic due to its long duration of binding to cardiac sodium channels. Treatment includes airway support, seizure control (benzodiazepines), and 20 percent lipid emulsion therapy (1.5 mL/kg bolus followed by infusion). Aspiration before injection and incremental dosing prevent toxicity.<br><br>A (Systemic local anesthetic toxicity) is correct because seizures and cardiac arrhythmias define this syndrome. B (Amniotic fluid embolism) is wrong because it presents with hypoxia, cardiovascular collapse and DIC, not initial seizures. C (Placenta previa) is wrong because it presents with painless vaginal bleeding. D (Postpartum hemorrhage) is wrong because it is a different complication.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Local Anesthetics)</em>`},
    {q:'Which regional anesthesia technique involves injection of anesthetic into the subarachnoid space?',o:['Pudendal block','Spinal anesthesia','Paracervical block','Epidural anesthesia'],a:1,
    e:`Spinal anaesthesia involves injection of local anaesthetic into the subarachnoid space (between the arachnoid and pia mater), where it directly bathes the spinal nerves and produces rapid, dense sensory and motor block.<br><br>The injection point is typically L3-L4 or L4-L5 below the conus medullaris (which ends at L1-L2 in adults). Onset is within 5 minutes; duration depends on the agent (bupivacaine 1.5 to 2 hours). Complications include hypotension, post-dural puncture headache and high spinal block.<br><br>B (Spinal anesthesia) is correct because subarachnoid injection is the defining feature. A (Pudendal block) is wrong because it injects local anaesthetic near the pudendal nerve. C (Paracervical block) is wrong because it injects into cervical tissues. D (Epidural anesthesia) is wrong because the epidural space is outside the dura, not in the subarachnoid space.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics; Chapter: Obstetrical Anesthesia)</em>`},
    {q:'Which nerve block is commonly used to provide analgesia during the second stage of labor and episiotomy repair?',o:['Pudendal nerve block','Femoral nerve block','Sciatic nerve block','Intercostal nerve block'],a:0,
    e:`Pudendal nerve block provides analgesia for the second stage of labour, episiotomy and outlet forceps delivery. Local anaesthetic (e.g. 1 percent lidocaine) is injected near the pudendal nerve as it crosses the ischial spine, accessed transvaginally.<br><br>The pudendal nerve (S2-S4) supplies the perineum, vulva, lower vagina and anal sphincter. Block is rapid, simple and avoids the systemic effects of general or regional anaesthesia. It does not provide upper vaginal or uterine analgesia.<br><br>A (Pudendal nerve block) is correct because it provides perineal analgesia for second-stage labour and episiotomy. B (Femoral nerve block) is wrong because it anaesthetises the anterior thigh, not the perineum. C (Sciatic nerve block) is wrong because it anaesthetises the posterior leg. D (Intercostal nerve block) is wrong because it anaesthetises the chest wall.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics; Chapter: Obstetrical Anesthesia)</em>`},
    {q:'Which complication may occur if local anesthetic is inadvertently injected intravascularly during regional anesthesia?',o:['Polyhydramnios','Convulsions','Hyperglycemia','Fetal bradycardia only'],a:1,
    e:`Inadvertent intravascular injection of local anaesthetic during regional anaesthesia produces local anaesthetic systemic toxicity (LAST), with early CNS signs progressing to convulsions and eventually cardiac arrhythmias and arrest.<br><br>Bupivacaine is particularly cardiotoxic. Prevention includes aspiration before injection, incremental dosing and use of a test dose with epinephrine. Treatment of LAST is airway support, seizure control with benzodiazepines and 20 percent lipid emulsion therapy.<br><br>B (Convulsions) is correct because CNS effects of intravascular local anaesthetic produce seizures before cardiac toxicity. A (Polyhydramnios) is wrong because it is unrelated to anaesthesia. C (Hyperglycemia) is wrong because local anaesthetics do not raise blood glucose. D (Fetal bradycardia only) is wrong because the maternal CNS effects (seizures) precede fetal effects.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Local Anesthetics)</em>`},
    {q:'Which anesthetic technique provides rapid and dense sensory and motor block for cesarean section?',o:['Local infiltration','Pudendal block','Nitrous oxide','Spinal anesthesia'],a:3,
    e:`Spinal anaesthesia provides rapid (within 5 minutes) and dense sensory and motor block suitable for caesarean section. Hyperbaric bupivacaine (typically 10 to 12 mg with fentanyl 10 to 25 μg and morphine 0.1 mg) is injected into the subarachnoid space.<br><br>The level required for caesarean is T4 (level of nipples). Onset is faster than epidural and total dose used is much smaller, reducing systemic toxicity risk. Limitations include limited duration (1.5 to 2 hours), inability to extend anaesthesia, and hypotension from sympathetic blockade.<br><br>D (Spinal anesthesia) is correct because of rapid dense block suitable for caesarean. A (Local infiltration) is wrong because it does not provide adequate caesarean anaesthesia. B (Pudendal block) is wrong because it only anaesthetises the perineum. C (Nitrous oxide) is wrong because it provides only mild analgesia, insufficient for surgery.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics; Chapter: Obstetrical Anesthesia)</em>`},
    {q:'Which drug is used as an antidote for severe systemic toxicity of local anesthetics?',o:['Sodium bicarbonate','Magnesium sulfate','Lipid emulsion therapy','Calcium gluconate'],a:2,
    e:`Lipid emulsion therapy (Intralipid 20 percent) is the antidote for severe local anaesthetic systemic toxicity, particularly cardiac arrest from bupivacaine. Initial bolus is 1.5 mL/kg over 1 minute, followed by infusion of 0.25 mL/kg/min, repeated as needed.<br><br>The proposed mechanism is a lipid sink that sequesters the highly lipophilic local anaesthetic from cardiac tissue, plus possible direct effects on cardiac metabolism. Standard ACLS resuscitation is also continued. Avoiding LAST is preferable: aspirate before injection, use incremental dosing and test doses.<br><br>C (Lipid emulsion therapy) is correct because it is the established antidote for LAST. A (Sodium bicarbonate) is wrong because it treats acidosis, not LAST directly. B (Magnesium sulfate) is wrong because it is for eclampsia. D (Calcium gluconate) is wrong because it reverses magnesium toxicity.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Local Anesthetics)</em>`},
    {q:'Which anesthetic complication is characterized by sudden hypotension after spinal anesthesia?',o:['Hypernatremia','Metabolic alkalosis','Hyperglycemia','Sympathetic blockade'],a:3,
    e:`Sudden hypotension following spinal anaesthesia results from sympathetic blockade. Local anaesthetic blocks sympathetic preganglionic fibres (T1 to L2), causing arteriolar and venous dilation with reduced systemic vascular resistance and venous return.<br><br>In pregnancy, aortocaval compression by the gravid uterus exacerbates hypotension. Prevention includes left lateral tilt (15 degrees), IV fluid co-loading and prophylactic vasopressors (phenylephrine, ephedrine). Treatment is the same plus oxygen and fluid administration.<br><br>D (Sympathetic blockade) is correct because spinal anaesthesia blocks sympathetic preganglionic fibres causing vasodilation and hypotension. A (Hypernatremia) is wrong because spinal anaesthesia does not affect sodium. B (Metabolic alkalosis) is wrong because it is unrelated to spinal anaesthesia. C (Hyperglycemia) is wrong because spinal anaesthesia does not raise blood glucose.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics; Chapter: Obstetrical Anesthesia)</em>`},
    {q:'Which factor increases the risk of hypotension during spinal anesthesia in obstetrics?',o:['Increased blood volume','Low estrogen levels','Sympathetic nerve blockade','High hemoglobin'],a:2,
    e:`Sympathetic nerve blockade is the principal mechanism of hypotension during spinal anaesthesia in obstetrics. Local anaesthetic blocks sympathetic preganglionic fibres (T1 to L2), causing arteriolar and venous dilation with reduced systemic vascular resistance and venous return.<br><br>Pregnant women are particularly susceptible because aortocaval compression by the gravid uterus reduces venous return when supine. Prevention includes left lateral tilt (15 degrees), IV fluid co-loading and prophylactic vasopressors (phenylephrine, ephedrine).<br><br>C (Sympathetic nerve blockade) is correct because vasodilation from sympathetic block causes the hypotension. A (Increased blood volume) is wrong because pregnancy increases blood volume but this would protect, not increase, hypotension risk. B (Low estrogen levels) is wrong because pregnancy is a high-oestrogen state. D (High hemoglobin) is wrong because pregnancy actually reduces haemoglobin (haemodilution).<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics; Chapter: Obstetrical Anesthesia)</em>`},
    {q:'Which anesthetic technique is preferred for elective cesarean section when no contraindication exists?',o:['Local infiltration only','Regional anesthesia','Deep sedation','General anesthesia'],a:1,
    e:`Regional anaesthesia (spinal, epidural or combined spinal-epidural) is preferred for elective caesarean section when no contraindication exists. Advantages include preserved maternal consciousness, reduced maternal mortality (vs general), avoidance of aspiration risk, reduced neonatal exposure to anaesthetic drugs and superior postoperative analgesia.<br><br>Contraindications to regional anaesthesia include patient refusal, coagulopathy, infection at the puncture site, raised intracranial pressure, severe hypovolaemia and severe aortic stenosis. General anaesthesia is reserved for emergencies, contraindications to regional, or failed regional.<br><br>B (Regional anesthesia) is correct because of established preference for elective caesarean. A (Local infiltration only) is wrong because it provides inadequate analgesia for caesarean. C (Deep sedation) is wrong because it does not provide surgical anaesthesia. D (General anesthesia) is wrong because it carries higher maternal and neonatal risks; reserved for emergencies.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics; Chapter: Obstetrical Anesthesia)</em>`},
    {q:'Which inhalational anesthetic has historically been used for obstetric analgesia but is now rarely used due to toxicity?',o:['Ether','Isoflurane','Nitrous oxide','Halothane'],a:0,
    e:`Diethyl ether was historically used for obstetric analgesia but is now obsolete due to its flammability, prolonged induction and recovery, severe nausea and vomiting and hepatotoxicity. It has been replaced by safer agents.<br><br>Modern obstetric anaesthesia uses regional techniques (epidural, spinal) for labour analgesia and surgery, supplemented by inhalational nitrous oxide where appropriate. Modern volatile anaesthetics (sevoflurane, desflurane, isoflurane) are used for general anaesthesia in caesarean section when needed.<br><br>A (Ether) is correct because it is the historical agent now obsolete. B (Isoflurane) is wrong because it is a modern volatile agent in current use. C (Nitrous oxide) is wrong because it is currently used (as Entonox) for labour analgesia. D (Halothane) is wrong because while it has been largely replaced, this is for hepatotoxicity, not the broader pattern of toxicity that defined ether.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: General Anesthetics)</em>`},
    {q:'Which complication of epidural anesthesia may result from injection of excessive anesthetic dose into the epidural space?',o:['Renal failure','Hypocalcemia','Hyperthyroidism','High spinal block'],a:3,
    e:`High spinal block (or total spinal) results from injection of an excessive epidural local anaesthetic dose into the subarachnoid space (e.g. through unrecognised dural puncture). The block ascends to high thoracic and cervical levels, causing severe hypotension, bradycardia, respiratory failure (paralysis of intercostal and phrenic nerves) and loss of consciousness.<br><br>Treatment is immediate: airway support and intubation, fluid resuscitation, vasopressors (phenylephrine, ephedrine) and atropine for bradycardia. Recovery occurs as the local anaesthetic wears off (typically 1 to 3 hours). Test dose with small volumes prevents this complication.<br><br>D (High spinal block) is correct because excessive intrathecal local anaesthetic causes ascending spinal block. A (Renal failure) is wrong because epidural overdose does not directly cause renal failure. B (Hypocalcemia) is wrong because it is unrelated to anaesthesia. C (Hyperthyroidism) is wrong for the same reason.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics; Chapter: Obstetrical Anesthesia)</em>`},
    {q:'Which nerve fibers are blocked first by local anesthetics?',o:['Skeletal muscle fibers','Large sensory fibers','Small myelinated pain fibers','Large motor fibers'],a:2,
    e:`Small myelinated pain fibres (Aδ fibres) and small unmyelinated C fibres are blocked first by local anaesthetics, due to their small diameter and high firing rate (use-dependent block). This explains the differential block where pain is lost before motor function.<br><br>The order of block typically progresses from pain (Aδ, C) to temperature, then touch and pressure, then motor (large myelinated Aα, Aβ fibres) last. Recovery occurs in reverse order.<br><br>A (Small myelinated pain fibers) is correct because small high-firing fibres are blocked first. B (Large motor fibers) is wrong because large myelinated motor fibres are blocked last. C (Sympathetic ganglion fibers) is wrong because while sympathetic preganglionic fibres are sensitive, they are not the first blocked overall. D (Autonomic postganglionic fibers) is wrong because these are not the primary differential block target.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Local Anesthetics)</em>`},
    {q:'Which anesthetic technique provides continuous analgesia throughout labor via catheter placement?',o:['Epidural analgesia','Spinal anesthesia','Pudendal block','Local infiltration'],a:0,
    e:`Epidural analgesia uses a continuous catheter system to provide titratable analgesia throughout labour. Dilute local anaesthetic (typically 0.0625 to 0.125 percent bupivacaine with fentanyl 2 μg/mL) is infused at 8 to 12 mL/hour, with patient-controlled boluses available.<br><br>Continuous infusion provides steady analgesia without the peaks and troughs of intermittent boluses, reducing motor block and improving maternal satisfaction. The catheter can also be used for surgical anaesthesia if instrumental delivery or caesarean becomes necessary.<br><br>B (Epidural analgesia) is correct because continuous catheter infusion is its defining feature. A (Spinal anesthesia) is wrong because it is a single-shot technique without a continuous catheter. C (Local infiltration) is wrong because it is a single perineal injection, not continuous. D (Pudendal block) is wrong because it is a single perineal injection.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics; Chapter: Obstetrical Anesthesia)</em>`},
    {q:'Which anesthetic complication may occur if epidural anesthesia spreads excessively into the thoracic region?',o:['Hyperglycemia','Respiratory depression','Polycythemia','Hyperkalemia'],a:1,
    e:`Excessive thoracic spread of local anaesthetic during epidural anaesthesia (especially with high doses or unrecognised intrathecal placement) can cause respiratory depression by paralysing the intercostal muscles and potentially the diaphragm (phrenic nerve, C3-C5).<br><br>Other complications of high blocks include severe hypotension, bradycardia and loss of consciousness. Treatment is immediate airway support, intubation if needed, fluid resuscitation and vasopressors. Test doses with small volumes detect intrathecal placement before full dose is given.<br><br>C (Respiratory depression) is correct because high thoracic block paralyses respiratory muscles. A (Acute renal failure) is wrong because thoracic block does not affect the kidneys. B (Polycythemia) is wrong because it is unrelated to anaesthetic spread. D (Hypocalcemia) is wrong because thoracic spread does not affect calcium.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics; Chapter: Obstetrical Anesthesia)</em>`},
    {q:'Which anesthetic drug used in general anesthesia may cause uterine relaxation and increase risk of postpartum hemorrhage?',o:['Halothane','Bupivacaine','Procaine','Lidocaine'],a:0,
    e:`Halothane is a volatile inhalational anaesthetic that produces dose-dependent uterine relaxation, useful when uterine relaxation is needed (e.g. internal podalic version, breech delivery, retained placenta). Modern volatile agents (sevoflurane, isoflurane, desflurane) share this effect.<br><br>However, halothane is now largely obsolete due to risk of halothane hepatitis and has been replaced by sevoflurane and isoflurane. Local anaesthetics (bupivacaine, lidocaine, procaine) do not directly relax the uterus.<br><br>A (Halothane) is correct because volatile anaesthetics produce uterine relaxation. B (Bupivacaine) is wrong because it is a local anaesthetic without direct uterine effects. C (Procaine) is wrong for the same reason. D (Lidocaine) is wrong for the same reason.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: General Anesthetics)</em>`},
    {q:'Which regional anesthesia technique is most suitable for repair of episiotomy after delivery?',o:['Epidural anesthesia','Spinal anesthesia','General anesthesia','Pudendal block'],a:3,
    e:`Pudendal block is the most suitable regional technique for episiotomy repair after delivery. Local anaesthetic injected near the pudendal nerve at the ischial spine provides perineal analgesia adequate for repair work.<br><br>It is rapid, simple and avoids the systemic effects of general or regional anaesthesia. The pudendal nerve (S2-S4) supplies the perineum, vulva, lower vagina and anal sphincter. Local infiltration of the wound edges with lidocaine is also commonly used.<br><br>D (Pudendal block) is correct because it provides perineal analgesia ideal for episiotomy repair. A (Epidural anesthesia) is wrong because it is unnecessarily extensive for episiotomy repair. B (Spinal anesthesia) is wrong for the same reason. C (General anesthesia) is wrong because it is excessive and carries higher risk.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics; Chapter: Obstetrical Anesthesia)</em>`},
    {q:'Which anesthetic complication is characterized by maternal hypotension leading to fetal bradycardia?',o:['Hypernatremia','Spinal anesthesia hypotension','Hyperglycemia','Hypocalcemia'],a:1,
    e:`Spinal anaesthesia commonly causes maternal hypotension through sympathetic blockade, which reduces venous return and uteroplacental perfusion. The resulting decrease in fetal oxygenation produces fetal bradycardia.<br><br>Prevention includes left lateral tilt (15 degrees) to relieve aortocaval compression, IV fluid co-loading and prophylactic vasopressors (phenylephrine, ephedrine). Treatment is the same plus oxygen and fluid administration.<br><br>B (Spinal anesthesia hypotension) is correct because the sympathetic blockade-induced maternal hypotension reduces uteroplacental perfusion. A (Hypernatremia) is wrong because it is unrelated to spinal anaesthesia. C (Hyperglycemia) is wrong for the same reason. D (Hypocalcemia) is wrong for the same reason.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics; Chapter: Obstetrical Anesthesia)</em>`},
    {q:'Which drug is commonly used for rapid sequence induction during cesarean section under general anesthesia?',o:['Metformin','Penicillin','Thiopental','Paracetamol'],a:2,
    e:`Thiopental (a barbiturate) is commonly used for rapid sequence induction in obstetric general anaesthesia at 4 to 5 mg/kg IV. It produces rapid loss of consciousness within 30 seconds and short duration of action (5 to 10 minutes).<br><br>Propofol is increasingly used as an alternative. Both agents are followed immediately by succinylcholine for rapid intubation. Maternal aspiration risk is high in pregnancy due to delayed gastric emptying and reduced lower oesophageal sphincter tone, making rapid sequence induction essential.<br><br>C (Thiopental) is correct because of its rapid onset for emergency airway control. A (Metformin) is wrong because it is an oral hypoglycaemic, not an anaesthetic. B (Penicillin) is wrong because it is an antibiotic. D (Paracetamol) is wrong because it is an analgesic.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: General Anesthetics)</em>`},
    {q:'Which muscle relaxant is commonly used in obstetric general anesthesia for rapid intubation?',o:['Diazepam','Morphine','Atropine','Succinylcholine'],a:3,
    e:`Succinylcholine is the muscle relaxant of choice for rapid intubation in obstetric general anaesthesia (1 to 1.5 mg/kg IV). It produces complete neuromuscular blockade within 60 seconds and short duration (5 to 10 minutes), allowing rapid intubation and recovery.<br><br>Succinylcholine is a depolarising neuromuscular blocker. Side effects include fasciculations, hyperkalaemia and rare malignant hyperthermia. Rocuronium (with sugammadex reversal) is an increasing alternative for rapid sequence induction.<br><br>D (Succinylcholine) is correct because of its rapid onset and offset. A (Diazepam) is wrong because it is a sedative-hypnotic, not a muscle relaxant. B (Morphine) is wrong because it is an opioid analgesic. C (Atropine) is wrong because it is an antimuscarinic, not a muscle relaxant.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Skeletal Muscle Relaxants)</em>`},
    {q:'Which anesthetic complication results from puncture of epidural veins during catheter insertion?',o:['Epidural hematoma','Hepatitis','Pulmonary embolism','Renal failure'],a:0,
    e:`Puncture of epidural veins during epidural catheter insertion can cause epidural haematoma, with risk of spinal cord compression and permanent neurological injury. Risk is increased in patients with coagulopathy or on anticoagulants.<br><br>Symptoms include severe back pain, motor weakness, sensory loss and bladder dysfunction. Diagnosis is by urgent MRI; treatment is emergency surgical decompression. Coagulopathy must be corrected and anticoagulants timed appropriately before regional anaesthesia.<br><br>A (Epidural hematoma) is correct because of vein puncture causing localised bleeding in the confined epidural space. B (Hepatitis) is wrong because it is unrelated to epidural placement. C (Pulmonary embolism) is wrong for the same reason. D (Renal failure) is wrong for the same reason.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics; Chapter: Obstetrical Anesthesia)</em>`},
    {q:'Which anesthetic drug is commonly used as a test dose during epidural placement?',o:['Atropine','Magnesium sulfate','Lidocaine with epinephrine','Morphine'],a:2,
    e:`Lidocaine with epinephrine (typically 3 mL of 1.5 percent lidocaine with 1:200,000 epinephrine) is used as the test dose during epidural placement to detect inadvertent intravascular or intrathecal placement.<br><br>Intravascular injection causes tachycardia and hypertension within 30 seconds (epinephrine effect). Intrathecal injection causes rapid sensory and motor block within 3 to 5 minutes (lidocaine effect). Negative test dose allows safe administration of the full epidural dose.<br><br>C (Lidocaine with epinephrine) is correct because it detects both intravascular and intrathecal misplacement. A (Atropine) is wrong because it is not a test dose agent. B (Magnesium sulfate) is wrong because it is for eclampsia. D (Morphine) is wrong because it is an analgesic, not a test agent.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Local Anesthetics)</em>`},
    {q:'Which local anesthetic has the longest duration of action among commonly used agents in obstetrics?',o:['Lidocaine','Bupivacaine','Procaine','Chloroprocaine'],a:1,
    e:`Bupivacaine has the longest duration of action among commonly used local anaesthetics in obstetrics, providing 2 to 3 hours of analgesia from a single dose. This makes it ideal for continuous epidural infusion during labour.<br><br>Lidocaine has shorter duration (1 to 1.5 hours). Procaine and chloroprocaine are very short-acting. Ropivacaine has similar duration to bupivacaine with lower cardiotoxicity. Bupivacaine cardiotoxicity is a major risk with accidental intravascular injection.<br><br>B (Bupivacaine) is correct because of its long duration of action. A (Lidocaine) is wrong because it has shorter duration. C (Procaine) is wrong because it is short-acting. D (Chloroprocaine) is wrong because it is also short-acting.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Local Anesthetics)</em>`},
    {q:'Which anesthetic technique blocks the pudendal nerve near the ischial spine?',o:['Spinal anesthesia','General anesthesia','Epidural anesthesia','Pudendal nerve block'],a:3,
    e:`Pudendal nerve block targets the pudendal nerve at the ischial spine, where the nerve passes around the spine to enter Alcock\'s canal. Local anaesthetic (e.g. 1 percent lidocaine) is injected transvaginally near the ischial spine.<br><br>The block provides analgesia for the perineum, vulva, lower vagina and anal sphincter (pudendal nerve S2-S4 distribution). It is useful for second-stage labour, episiotomy repair and outlet forceps delivery.<br><br>D (Pudendal nerve block) is correct because it targets the pudendal nerve at the ischial spine. A (Spinal anesthesia) is wrong because it injects into the subarachnoid space. B (General anesthesia) is wrong because it does not target peripheral nerves. C (Epidural anesthesia) is wrong because it injects into the epidural space.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics; Chapter: Obstetrical Anesthesia)</em>`},
    {q:'Which anesthetic complication may occur due to accidental injection of anesthetic into cerebrospinal fluid during epidural placement?',o:['Hyperglycemia','Total spinal anesthesia','Hypercalcemia','Hypothyroidism'],a:1,
    e:`Accidental injection of an epidural local anaesthetic dose into cerebrospinal fluid (through unrecognised dural puncture) results in total spinal anaesthesia. The block ascends to high cervical levels causing severe hypotension, bradycardia, respiratory failure and loss of consciousness.<br><br>Treatment is immediate airway support, intubation, fluid resuscitation, vasopressors and atropine for bradycardia. Recovery occurs as the local anaesthetic wears off (1 to 3 hours). Test dose with small volumes prevents this complication.<br><br>B (Total spinal anesthesia) is correct because intrathecal injection of an epidural dose causes ascending spinal block. A (Hyperglycemia) is wrong because epidural drugs do not affect blood glucose. C (Hypercalcemia) is wrong for the same reason. D (Hypothyroidism) is wrong for the same reason.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics; Chapter: Obstetrical Anesthesia)</em>`},
    {q:'Which anesthetic drug used in epidural analgesia may cause motor blockade at high doses?',o:['Bupivacaine','Insulin','Paracetamol','Penicillin'],a:0,
    e:`Bupivacaine at high concentrations (0.25 to 0.5 percent) produces motor blockade in addition to sensory analgesia during epidural anaesthesia. Lower concentrations (0.0625 to 0.125 percent) preserve motor function.<br><br>The differential block depends on concentration and lipophilicity. Adding fentanyl or sufentanil to bupivacaine allows lower local anaesthetic concentration with similar analgesia, reducing motor block (\'walking epidural\').<br><br>A (Bupivacaine) is correct because of dose-dependent motor block at higher concentrations. B (Insulin) is wrong because it is not an anaesthetic. C (Paracetamol) is wrong because it is an analgesic without motor effects. D (Penicillin) is wrong because it is an antibiotic.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Local Anesthetics)</em>`},
    {q:'Which anesthetic technique reduces maternal catecholamine levels and improves uteroplacental blood flow?',o:['Local infiltration','Sedation','Epidural analgesia','General anesthesia'],a:2,
    e:`Epidural analgesia reduces maternal catecholamine levels (norepinephrine, epinephrine) by abolishing pain stimulus. This reduction in sympathetic activity improves uteroplacental blood flow and reduces fetal acidosis.<br><br>Reduced catecholamines also reduce maternal cardiovascular stress. Epidural analgesia therefore has a positive effect on uteroplacental perfusion when hypotension is prevented (left lateral tilt, fluid co-loading, vasopressors).<br><br>C (Epidural analgesia) is correct because pain relief reduces maternal catecholamines and improves uteroplacental flow. A (Local infiltration) is wrong because it provides only minor analgesia. B (Sedation) is wrong because it does not reliably reduce pain-induced catecholamines. D (General anesthesia) is wrong because while it abolishes pain, it carries higher fetal drug exposure.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics; Chapter: Obstetrical Anesthesia)</em>`},
    {q:'Which anesthetic drug may cause neonatal respiratory depression if given close to delivery?',o:['Paracetamol','Penicillin','Insulin','Opioids'],a:3,
    e:`Opioids given to the mother close to delivery can cause neonatal respiratory depression as the drug crosses the placenta and affects the neonate\'s respiratory drive. Naloxone (0.1 mg/kg IV or IM) reverses opioid-induced neonatal respiratory depression.<br><br>Other opioid effects in the neonate include reduced Apgar scores and altered neurobehavioural responses. Limiting opioid doses near delivery and timing administration appropriately reduce risk. Pethidine (meperidine) is particularly known for prolonged neonatal effects.<br><br>D (Opioids) is correct because of placental transfer and fetal/neonatal CNS depression. A (Paracetamol) is wrong because it does not cause respiratory depression. B (Penicillin) is wrong for the same reason. C (Insulin) is wrong because it does not affect the respiratory system.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Opioid Analgesics and Antagonists)</em>`},
    {q:'Which anesthetic complication results from unintentional dural puncture during epidural insertion?',o:['Pulmonary embolism','Polyhydramnios','Post-dural puncture headache','Hyperglycemia'],a:2,
    e:`Unintentional dural puncture during epidural insertion (with the larger Tuohy needle) results in cerebrospinal fluid leak and post-dural puncture headache (PDPH), characteristically severe, postural and starting 24 to 72 hours after the procedure.<br><br>Treatment is initially conservative (bed rest, hydration, caffeine, analgesics). Refractory cases are treated with epidural blood patch. Risk is approximately 1 to 2 percent with epidural placement and is higher with larger gauge needles.<br><br>C (Post-dural puncture headache) is correct because PDPH is the classical complication of dural puncture. A (Pulmonary embolism) is wrong because it is unrelated. B (Polyhydramnios) is wrong for the same reason. D (Hyperglycemia) is wrong for the same reason.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics; Chapter: Obstetrical Anesthesia)</em>`},
    {q:'Which anesthetic drug is used for sedation during procedures in obstetric anesthesia?',o:['Midazolam','Penicillin','Insulin','Metformin'],a:0,
    e:`Midazolam is the most commonly used short-acting benzodiazepine for sedation during obstetric procedures. It has rapid onset (2 to 3 minutes IV) and short duration (1 to 2 hours), with anxiolysis and amnesia effects.<br><br>Midazolam is generally avoided during early pregnancy (small risk of cleft lip/palate) and near delivery (neonatal sedation). For brief postpartum procedures, it is well tolerated. Reversal is with flumazenil if needed.<br><br>A (Midazolam) is correct because it is the standard short-acting benzodiazepine for procedural sedation. B (Penicillin) is wrong because it is an antibiotic. C (Insulin) is wrong because it is for diabetes. D (Metformin) is wrong because it is an oral hypoglycaemic.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Sedative-Hypnotic Drugs)</em>`},
    {q:'Which anesthetic drug is often combined with epidural local anesthetics to enhance analgesia during labor?',o:['Insulin','Fentanyl','Paracetamol','Penicillin'],a:1,
    e:`Fentanyl is commonly added to epidural local anaesthetics (typically 2 μg/mL with bupivacaine) to enhance analgesia synergistically and allow lower local anaesthetic concentrations. This reduces motor block while maintaining good pain control.<br><br>Fentanyl acts on opioid receptors in the spinal cord (substantia gelatinosa). Other opioids used as epidural adjuncts include sufentanil and morphine. Side effects include pruritus, nausea and rarely respiratory depression. Sufentanil is more lipophilic with faster onset.<br><br>B (Fentanyl) is correct because it is the standard opioid adjunct for epidural analgesia. A (Insulin) is wrong because it is for diabetes. C (Paracetamol) is wrong because it is not used in epidurals. D (Penicillin) is wrong because it is an antibiotic.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Opioid Analgesics and Antagonists)</em>`},
    {q:'Which anesthetic complication can result from maternal hypotension during regional anesthesia?',o:['Polycythemia','Hyperglycemia','Fetal bradycardia','Hypernatremia'],a:2,
    e:`Maternal hypotension during regional anaesthesia reduces uteroplacental perfusion and fetal oxygen delivery, producing fetal bradycardia. The cardiotocographic pattern shows late decelerations or prolonged bradycardia.<br><br>Treatment is immediate: left lateral tilt to relieve aortocaval compression, IV fluid bolus, oxygen and vasopressors (phenylephrine 50 to 100 μg or ephedrine 5 to 10 mg). Prophylactic measures (fluid co-loading, prophylactic phenylephrine infusion) reduce hypotension incidence.<br><br>C (Fetal bradycardia) is correct because reduced uteroplacental perfusion causes fetal heart rate deceleration. A (Polycythemia) is wrong because it is unrelated to acute hypotension. B (Hyperglycemia) is wrong for the same reason. D (Hypernatremia) is wrong for the same reason.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics; Chapter: Obstetrical Anesthesia)</em>`},
    {q:'Which anesthetic drug is commonly used as an induction agent during obstetric general anesthesia?',o:['Penicillin','Propofol','Metformin','Insulin'],a:1,
    e:`Propofol is increasingly used as an induction agent for obstetric general anaesthesia (2 to 2.5 mg/kg IV). It produces rapid loss of consciousness within 30 seconds and short duration (5 to 10 minutes), with fewer side effects than thiopental.<br><br>Propofol acts at GABA-A receptors. Advantages over thiopental include cleaner recovery, less postoperative nausea and antiemetic effects. Disadvantages include hypotension and pain on injection. Both are followed immediately by succinylcholine for intubation.<br><br>B (Propofol) is correct because of its rapid onset and clean recovery profile. A (Penicillin) is wrong because it is an antibiotic. C (Metformin) is wrong because it is an oral hypoglycaemic. D (Insulin) is wrong because it is for diabetes.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: General Anesthetics)</em>`},
    {q:'Which anesthetic complication is characterized by difficulty breathing due to high spinal block?',o:['Respiratory paralysis','Hyperglycemia','Hyperthyroidism','Hypokalemia'],a:0,
    e:`High spinal block causes respiratory paralysis through ascending blockade of the intercostal muscles (T1 to T11) and potentially the diaphragm (phrenic nerve, C3 to C5). Maternal respiratory drive is lost, requiring immediate airway management and ventilation.<br><br>Other features include severe hypotension, bradycardia and loss of consciousness. Treatment is immediate intubation, fluid resuscitation, vasopressors and atropine. Test dose with small volumes prevents this complication during epidural placement.<br><br>A (Respiratory paralysis) is correct because high spinal block paralyses intercostal and phrenic respiratory muscles. B (Hyperglycemia) is wrong because it is unrelated to spinal block. C (Hyperthyroidism) is wrong for the same reason. D (Hypokalemia) is wrong for the same reason.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics; Chapter: Obstetrical Anesthesia)</em>`},
    {q:'Which anesthetic drug provides analgesia when added to spinal anesthesia during cesarean section?',o:['Paracetamol','Metformin','Penicillin','Morphine'],a:3,
    e:`Intrathecal morphine (typically 0.1 to 0.2 mg) added to spinal anaesthesia for caesarean section provides prolonged postoperative analgesia (12 to 24 hours). It acts on opioid receptors in the substantia gelatinosa of the spinal cord.<br><br>Side effects include pruritus (most common), nausea, urinary retention and rare delayed respiratory depression (4 to 12 hours after intrathecal injection). Postoperative monitoring is recommended. Fentanyl is more commonly added for intraoperative analgesia.<br><br>D (Morphine) is correct because intrathecal morphine provides prolonged postoperative analgesia. A (Paracetamol) is wrong because it is not given intrathecally. B (Metformin) is wrong because it is an oral hypoglycaemic. C (Penicillin) is wrong because it is an antibiotic.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Opioid Analgesics and Antagonists)</em>`},
    {q:'Which anesthetic complication may occur due to excessive sympathetic blockade during spinal anesthesia?',o:['Severe hypotension','Hyperglycemia','Hypercalcemia','Hypernatremia'],a:0,
    e:`Excessive sympathetic blockade during spinal anaesthesia causes severe hypotension. Local anaesthetic blocks sympathetic preganglionic fibres (T1 to L2), producing arteriolar and venous dilation, reduced systemic vascular resistance and reduced venous return.<br><br>Pregnant women are particularly susceptible because aortocaval compression by the gravid uterus reduces venous return when supine. Prevention includes left lateral tilt, IV fluid co-loading and prophylactic vasopressors.<br><br>A (Severe hypotension) is correct because vasodilation from sympathetic block causes the hypotension. B (Hyperglycemia) is wrong because spinal anaesthesia does not affect glucose. C (Hypercalcemia) is wrong for the same reason. D (Hypernatremia) is wrong for the same reason.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics; Chapter: Obstetrical Anesthesia)</em>`},
    {q:'Which anesthetic technique involves injection into the epidural space through a catheter allowing repeated dosing?',o:['Pudendal block','Epidural analgesia','Spinal anesthesia','Local infiltration'],a:1,
    e:`Epidural analgesia involves placement of a catheter into the epidural space (between the dura mater and ligamentum flavum) at L3-L4 or L4-L5, allowing repeated dosing or continuous infusion of local anaesthetic and opioid.<br><br>Continuous infusion or patient-controlled epidural analgesia (PCEA) provides titratable analgesia throughout labour. The catheter can also be used to convert to surgical anaesthesia for instrumental or caesarean delivery if needed.<br><br>B (Epidural analgesia) is correct because catheter placement in the epidural space allowing repeated dosing is its defining feature. A (Pudendal block) is wrong because it is a single-shot peripheral nerve block. C (Spinal anesthesia) is wrong because it is single-shot subarachnoid injection. D (Local infiltration) is wrong because it is single-shot subcutaneous injection.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics; Chapter: Obstetrical Anesthesia)</em>`},
    {q:'Which anesthetic drug may cause uterine relaxation during general anesthesia?',o:['Lidocaine','Procaine','Bupivacaine','Halothane'],a:3,
    e:`Halothane and other volatile anaesthetics produce dose-dependent uterine relaxation during general anaesthesia. This effect is useful when uterine relaxation is needed (e.g. internal podalic version, breech delivery, retained placenta) but undesirable in routine caesarean section due to increased postpartum haemorrhage risk.<br><br>Modern volatile agents (sevoflurane, isoflurane, desflurane) share this effect and are used at low concentrations (typically <1 MAC) during caesarean section to limit uterine relaxation. Halothane is now obsolete due to halothane hepatitis.<br><br>D (Halothane) is correct because volatile anaesthetics relax uterine smooth muscle. A (Lidocaine) is wrong because local anaesthetics do not directly relax the uterus. B (Procaine) is wrong for the same reason. C (Bupivacaine) is wrong for the same reason.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: General Anesthetics)</em>`},
    {q:'Which anesthetic block is useful for instrumental vaginal delivery?',o:['Femoral nerve block','Sciatic nerve block','Pudendal nerve block','Intercostal nerve block'],a:2,
    e:`Pudendal nerve block is useful for instrumental vaginal delivery (forceps or vacuum) by providing perineal analgesia adequate for the procedure. The pudendal nerve (S2-S4) supplies the perineum, vulva, lower vagina and anal sphincter.<br><br>Local anaesthetic (e.g. 1 percent lidocaine) is injected near the pudendal nerve at the ischial spine, accessed transvaginally. The block is rapid, simple and avoids the systemic effects of general or regional anaesthesia. Epidural top-up may also be used if catheter is in place.<br><br>C (Pudendal nerve block) is correct because it provides perineal analgesia for instrumental delivery. A (Femoral nerve block) is wrong because it anaesthetises the anterior thigh. B (Sciatic nerve block) is wrong because it anaesthetises the posterior leg. D (Intercostal nerve block) is wrong because it anaesthetises the chest wall.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics; Chapter: Obstetrical Anesthesia)</em>`},
    {q:'Which anesthetic complication may occur if epidural anesthesia spreads to cervical spinal segments?',o:['Hyperglycemia','Respiratory depression','Polycythemia','Hypernatremia'],a:1,
    e:`Excessive epidural local anaesthetic spread to cervical spinal segments (C3 to C5, the phrenic nerve roots) can cause respiratory depression by paralysing the diaphragm. Lower thoracic spread also paralyses intercostal muscles, further compromising ventilation.<br><br>Other features of high block include severe hypotension, bradycardia and loss of consciousness. Treatment is immediate airway support, intubation if needed, fluid resuscitation, vasopressors and atropine. Test doses prevent this complication.<br><br>B (Respiratory depression) is correct because cervical spread paralyses respiratory muscles via phrenic nerve block. A (Hyperglycemia) is wrong because epidural spread does not affect glucose. C (Polycythemia) is wrong for the same reason. D (Hypernatremia) is wrong for the same reason.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics; Chapter: Obstetrical Anesthesia)</em>`},
    {q:'Which anesthetic drug is commonly used for spinal anesthesia in cesarean section?',o:['Bupivacaine','Lidocaine','Penicillin','Insulin'],a:0,
    e:`Bupivacaine (typically hyperbaric 0.5 percent, 10 to 12 mg) is the most commonly used local anaesthetic for spinal anaesthesia in caesarean section. It produces dense sensory and motor block lasting 1.5 to 2 hours, sufficient for elective caesarean.<br><br>Hyperbaric bupivacaine (mixed with glucose) sinks in CSF, allowing predictable spread by patient positioning. Fentanyl (10 to 25 μg) and morphine (0.1 mg) are commonly added to enhance intra- and postoperative analgesia.<br><br>A (Bupivacaine) is correct because it is the standard spinal anaesthetic for caesarean section. B (Lidocaine) is wrong because it is shorter-acting and associated with transient neurological symptoms in spinal use. C (Penicillin) is wrong because it is an antibiotic. D (Insulin) is wrong because it is for diabetes.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Local Anesthetics)</em>`},
    {q:'Which anesthetic complication may result from inadequate hydration before spinal anesthesia?',o:['Hypernatremia','Hyperglycemia','Severe hypotension','Hypercalcemia'],a:2,
    e:`Inadequate hydration before spinal anaesthesia exacerbates the hypotension caused by sympathetic blockade. Reduced preload (already compromised by aortocaval compression in pregnancy) cannot compensate for the vasodilation, producing severe hypotension.<br><br>Prevention includes IV fluid co-loading (15 to 20 mL/kg crystalloid given immediately before or during spinal placement) and prophylactic phenylephrine infusion. Left lateral tilt (15 degrees) further protects venous return.<br><br>C (Severe hypotension) is correct because hypovolaemia plus sympathetic blockade produces severe hypotension. A (Hypernatremia) is wrong because spinal anaesthesia does not affect sodium. B (Hyperglycemia) is wrong because it is unrelated. D (Hypercalcemia) is wrong for the same reason.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics; Chapter: Obstetrical Anesthesia)</em>`},
    {q:'Which anesthetic drug is used to treat hypotension caused by spinal anesthesia?',o:['Insulin','Metformin','Penicillin','Ephedrine'],a:3,
    e:`Ephedrine (5 to 10 mg IV boluses) is a commonly used vasopressor to treat spinal-induced hypotension in obstetrics. It is an indirect sympathomimetic acting on alpha and beta receptors, increasing cardiac output and systemic vascular resistance.<br><br>Phenylephrine (50 to 100 μg IV boluses or infusion) is increasingly preferred as it produces less fetal acidosis than ephedrine. Both are effective for treating maternal hypotension. IV fluid co-loading and left lateral tilt are also essential.<br><br>D (Ephedrine) is correct because it is an established vasopressor for spinal hypotension. A (Insulin) is wrong because it is for diabetes. B (Metformin) is wrong because it is an oral hypoglycaemic. C (Penicillin) is wrong because it is an antibiotic.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Adrenoceptor Agonists and Sympathomimetic Drugs)</em>`},
    {q:'Which anesthetic technique provides segmental analgesia without complete motor blockade?',o:['General anesthesia','Spinal anesthesia','Epidural analgesia','Local infiltration'],a:2,
    e:`Epidural analgesia provides segmental analgesia (limited to specific spinal segments based on injection site and dose) without complete motor blockade when low-concentration local anaesthetic is used (0.0625 to 0.125 percent bupivacaine).<br><br>This \'walking epidural\' allows mobility, ambulation and effective pushing during second stage. Spinal anaesthesia produces dense motor block. General anaesthesia eliminates consciousness and motor function. Local infiltration provides only local field analgesia.<br><br>C (Epidural analgesia) is correct because of segmental analgesia with preserved motor function. A (General anesthesia) is wrong because it eliminates motor function. B (Spinal anesthesia) is wrong because it produces dense motor block. D (Local infiltration) is wrong because it is not segmental.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics; Chapter: Obstetrical Anesthesia)</em>`},
    {q:'Which anesthetic drug used in labor analgesia acts on opioid receptors in the spinal cord?',o:['Paracetamol','Insulin','Penicillin','Fentanyl'],a:3,
    e:`Fentanyl is an opioid that acts on opioid receptors in the spinal cord (substantia gelatinosa of the dorsal horn) when administered epidurally or intrathecally. This produces analgesia by inhibiting pain transmission at the spinal cord level.<br><br>Fentanyl is highly lipophilic, allowing rapid spinal cord penetration with limited rostral spread (lower risk of delayed respiratory depression than morphine). Side effects include pruritus, nausea and rarely respiratory depression.<br><br>D (Fentanyl) is correct because spinal opioid receptor binding produces its epidural/intrathecal analgesia. A (Paracetamol) is wrong because its analgesic mechanism is largely central (cortical) and not opioid receptor-mediated. B (Insulin) is wrong because it is for diabetes. C (Penicillin) is wrong because it is an antibiotic.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Opioid Analgesics and Antagonists)</em>`},
    {q:'Which anesthetic complication may occur if spinal anesthesia ascends excessively?',o:['Hypernatremia','Total spinal block','Hyperglycemia','Polycythemia'],a:1,
    e:`Total spinal block results when spinal anaesthesia ascends excessively, blocking sympathetic, sensory and motor function up to high cervical levels. This causes severe hypotension, bradycardia, respiratory paralysis and loss of consciousness.<br><br>Treatment is immediate: airway support and intubation, fluid resuscitation, vasopressors (phenylephrine, ephedrine) and atropine for bradycardia. Recovery occurs as the local anaesthetic wears off (1 to 3 hours). Excessive dose, hyperbaric solution with steep head-down tilt, or intrathecal injection of an epidural dose can cause this.<br><br>B (Total spinal block) is correct because excessive ascending block characterises this complication. A (Hypernatremia) is wrong because spinal block does not affect sodium. C (Hyperglycemia) is wrong for the same reason. D (Polycythemia) is wrong for the same reason.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics; Chapter: Obstetrical Anesthesia)</em>`},
    {q:'Which anesthetic drug used in epidural analgesia provides both sensory and motor block?',o:['Bupivacaine','Paracetamol','Insulin','Penicillin'],a:0,
    e:`Bupivacaine in epidural analgesia provides both sensory and motor block, the relative balance depending on concentration. High concentrations (0.25 to 0.5 percent) produce dense motor block; low concentrations (0.0625 to 0.125 percent) provide sensory block with preserved motor function.<br><br>The differential block depends on lipophilicity and concentration. Bupivacaine\'s long duration of action makes it ideal for continuous labour epidural infusion. Adding fentanyl allows lower bupivacaine concentration and reduced motor block.<br><br>A (Bupivacaine) is correct because it provides concentration-dependent sensory and motor block. B (Paracetamol) is wrong because it is a non-blocking analgesic. C (Insulin) is wrong because it is for diabetes. D (Penicillin) is wrong because it is an antibiotic.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Local Anesthetics)</em>`},
    {q:'Which anesthetic technique allows titration of analgesia throughout labor?',o:['Spinal injection only','General anesthesia','Pudendal block only','Epidural catheter technique'],a:3,
    e:`Epidural catheter technique allows titration of analgesia throughout labour by adjusting infusion rate, concentration or providing patient-controlled boluses. The continuous catheter system enables prolonged analgesia and conversion to surgical anaesthesia if needed.<br><br>Spinal anaesthesia is single-shot with fixed duration. Pudendal block is single-shot for second-stage perineal analgesia. General anaesthesia is reserved for emergencies or contraindications to regional. The flexibility of epidural makes it the modern standard.<br><br>D (Epidural catheter technique) is correct because catheter access allows titration. A (Spinal injection only) is wrong because it is single-shot. B (General anesthesia) is wrong because it is not titratable analgesia. C (Pudendal block only) is wrong because it provides only perineal block at second stage.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics; Chapter: Obstetrical Anesthesia)</em>`},
    {q:'Which anesthetic complication is most likely if epidural anesthesia spreads to high thoracic segments?',o:['Hyperglycemia','Respiratory depression','Polycythemia','Hypernatremia'],a:1,
    e:`Excessive epidural anaesthetic spread to high thoracic segments (T1 to T4) blocks intercostal muscles, compromising ventilation and producing respiratory depression. Further spread to cervical segments (C3 to C5) paralyses the diaphragm via phrenic nerve block.<br><br>Other features of high block include severe hypotension, bradycardia and loss of consciousness. Treatment is immediate airway support, intubation if needed, fluid resuscitation, vasopressors and atropine for bradycardia.<br><br>B (Respiratory depression) is correct because high thoracic spread paralyses intercostal respiratory muscles. A (Hyperglycemia) is wrong because epidural spread does not affect glucose. C (Polycythemia) is wrong for the same reason. D (Hypernatremia) is wrong for the same reason.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics; Chapter: Obstetrical Anesthesia)</em>`},
    {q:'Which anesthetic drug is used as a local anesthetic in pudendal nerve block?',o:['Metformin','Insulin','Lidocaine','Penicillin'],a:2,
    e:`Lidocaine (1 percent, 10 to 20 mL) is the most commonly used local anaesthetic for pudendal nerve block. It has rapid onset (3 to 5 minutes) and intermediate duration (1 to 1.5 hours), suitable for second-stage labour, episiotomy repair and outlet forceps delivery.<br><br>Bupivacaine can also be used for longer duration. Maximum safe dose of lidocaine is 4.5 mg/kg without adrenaline (300 mg) or 7 mg/kg with adrenaline (500 mg). Aspiration before injection prevents intravascular injection and systemic toxicity.<br><br>C (Lidocaine) is correct because it is the standard local anaesthetic for pudendal block. A (Metformin) is wrong because it is an oral hypoglycaemic. B (Insulin) is wrong because it is for diabetes. D (Penicillin) is wrong because it is an antibiotic.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Local Anesthetics)</em>`},
    {q:'Which anesthetic complication is most common with spinal anesthesia in obstetrics?',o:['Hypotension','Hyperglycemia','Hypercalcemia','Polycythemia'],a:0,
    e:`Hypotension is the most common complication of spinal anaesthesia in obstetrics, occurring in 50 to 80 percent of women without prophylaxis. It results from sympathetic blockade combined with aortocaval compression by the gravid uterus.<br><br>Prevention includes left lateral tilt (15 degrees), IV fluid co-loading and prophylactic vasopressors (phenylephrine infusion 25 to 50 μg/min or ephedrine boluses). Treatment is the same plus oxygen and additional fluid administration.<br><br>A (Hypotension) is correct because of its high incidence with spinal anaesthesia. B (Hyperglycemia) is wrong because spinal anaesthesia does not affect glucose. C (Hypercalcemia) is wrong for the same reason. D (Polycythemia) is wrong for the same reason.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics; Chapter: Obstetrical Anesthesia)</em>`},
    {q:'Which anesthetic technique is most commonly used for pain relief during normal labor in modern obstetrics?',o:['Deep sedation','General anesthesia','Epidural analgesia','Local infiltration only'],a:2,
    e:`Epidural analgesia is the most commonly used technique for pain relief during normal labour in modern obstetrics. It provides effective analgesia, allows maternal participation in delivery and can be titrated throughout labour.<br><br>Other options include nitrous oxide (Entonox) for partial relief, IV opioids (pethidine, fentanyl), pudendal block for second stage, and non-pharmacological methods (TENS, water birth, breathing techniques). General anaesthesia is reserved for emergency caesarean.<br><br>C (Epidural analgesia) is correct because it is the established gold standard for labour analgesia. A (Deep sedation) is wrong because it is rarely used and risks aspiration. B (General anesthesia) is wrong because it is reserved for emergencies. D (Local infiltration only) is wrong because it provides inadequate analgesia for labour.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics; Chapter: Obstetrical Anesthesia)</em>`},
    {q:'Which anesthetic drug may cause neonatal respiratory depression if administered to the mother close to delivery?',o:['Insulin','Paracetamol','Penicillin','Morphine'],a:3,
    e:`Morphine and other opioids given to the mother close to delivery can cause neonatal respiratory depression as the drug crosses the placenta and affects the neonate\'s respiratory drive. Naloxone (0.1 mg/kg IV or IM) reverses opioid-induced neonatal respiratory depression.<br><br>Pethidine (meperidine) is particularly known for prolonged neonatal effects (its active metabolite norpethidine has a long half-life). Limiting opioid doses near delivery and timing administration appropriately reduce risk.<br><br>D (Morphine) is correct because of placental transfer and fetal/neonatal CNS depression. A (Insulin) is wrong because it does not affect the respiratory system. B (Paracetamol) is wrong because it does not cause respiratory depression. C (Penicillin) is wrong for the same reason.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Opioid Analgesics and Antagonists)</em>`},
    {q:'Which anesthetic complication is associated with leakage of cerebrospinal fluid after dural puncture?',o:['Pulmonary embolism','Post-dural puncture headache','Hyperglycemia','Renal failure'],a:1,
    e:`Cerebrospinal fluid leak after dural puncture causes post-dural puncture headache (PDPH), characteristically severe, postural (worse on standing, relieved by lying flat), frontal or occipital, and starting 24 to 72 hours after the procedure.<br><br>Treatment is initially conservative (bed rest, hydration, caffeine, analgesics). Refractory cases are treated with epidural blood patch (15 to 20 mL of autologous blood injected into the epidural space at the puncture site). Risk is approximately 1 to 2 percent with epidural placement.<br><br>B (Post-dural puncture headache) is correct because CSF leak produces this characteristic postural headache. A (Pulmonary embolism) is wrong because it is unrelated to dural puncture. C (Hyperglycemia) is wrong for the same reason. D (Renal failure) is wrong for the same reason.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics; Chapter: Obstetrical Anesthesia)</em>`},
    {q:'Which anesthetic drug is commonly used to produce rapid induction in obstetric anesthesia due to its short onset time?',o:['Thiopental','Insulin','Paracetamol','Penicillin'],a:0,
    e:`Thiopental (a barbiturate, 4 to 5 mg/kg IV) produces rapid loss of consciousness within 30 seconds, making it ideal for rapid sequence induction in obstetric general anaesthesia. Short duration of action (5 to 10 minutes) allows rapid recovery.<br><br>Propofol is increasingly used as an alternative. Both agents are followed immediately by succinylcholine for rapid intubation. Maternal aspiration risk is high in pregnancy due to delayed gastric emptying and reduced lower oesophageal sphincter tone.<br><br>A (Thiopental) is correct because of its rapid onset suitable for emergency airway control. B (Insulin) is wrong because it is for diabetes. C (Paracetamol) is wrong because it is an analgesic. D (Penicillin) is wrong because it is an antibiotic.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: General Anesthetics)</em>`},
    {q:'Which drug is most commonly used for induction and augmentation of labor by stimulating uterine contractions?',o:['Progesterone','Oxytocin','Relaxin','Estrogen'],a:1,
    e:`Oxytocin is the drug of choice for induction and augmentation of labour. It directly stimulates uterine smooth muscle contractions through specific oxytocin receptors. Administered as IV infusion starting at 1 to 2 mU/min and titrated to adequate contractions (typically 8 to 12 mU/min).<br><br>Synthetic oxytocin is identical to endogenous nonapeptide. Side effects at high doses include hyperstimulation (causing fetal distress), water retention (antidiuretic effect, hyponatraemia) and uterine rupture in scarred uteri.<br><br>B (Oxytocin) is correct because it is the established drug for induction and augmentation. A (Progesterone) is wrong because it relaxes the uterus. C (Relaxin) is wrong because it relaxes pelvic ligaments and uterus. D (Estrogen) is wrong because it is not used to induce contractions.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Hypothalamic and Pituitary Hormones)</em>`},
    {q:'Oxytocin stimulates uterine contractions primarily by increasing intracellular levels of which ion in myometrial cells?',o:['Potassium','Sodium','Chloride','Calcium'],a:3,
    e:`Oxytocin stimulates uterine contractions by binding to oxytocin receptors on myometrial cells, activating Gq-coupled signalling and phospholipase C, which generates IP3. IP3 releases calcium from the sarcoplasmic reticulum, raising intracellular calcium.<br><br>Increased intracellular calcium activates calcium-calmodulin, which activates myosin light chain kinase (MLCK). MLCK phosphorylates myosin, enabling actin-myosin cross-bridging and uterine contraction. Oxytocin also stimulates prostaglandin synthesis, augmenting contractions.<br><br>D (Calcium) is correct because increased intracellular calcium drives uterine contraction via the actin-myosin system. A (Potassium) is wrong because potassium efflux causes membrane hyperpolarisation, opposing contraction. B (Sodium) is wrong because sodium influx is not the primary contractile signal. C (Chloride) is wrong because chloride is not the primary contractile signal.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Hypothalamic and Pituitary Hormones)</em>`},
    {q:'Which prostaglandin analogue is commonly used for cervical ripening before induction of labor?',o:['Latanoprost','Carboprost','Dinoprostone','Misoprostol'],a:2,
    e:`Dinoprostone (PGE2) is the prostaglandin analogue commonly used for cervical ripening before induction of labour. It is administered as a vaginal pessary (10 mg slow-release) or intracervical gel (0.5 mg) to soften and dilate the cervix.<br><br>Dinoprostone acts on prostaglandin EP receptors, causing collagen breakdown, increased proteoglycan synthesis and water content in cervical tissue. Side effects include uterine hyperstimulation, fetal distress, nausea and diarrhoea.<br><br>C (Dinoprostone) is correct because it is the licensed PGE2 analogue for cervical ripening. A (Latanoprost) is wrong because it is a topical PGF2α analogue used for glaucoma. B (Carboprost) is wrong because it is a PGF2α analogue used for postpartum haemorrhage. D (Misoprostol) is wrong because while it is also used for cervical ripening (off-label), it is a PGE1 analogue.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: The Eicosanoids)</em>`},
    {q:'Which prostaglandin E1 analogue is widely used for medical induction of labor and cervical ripening?',o:['Misoprostol','Oxytocin','Dinoprostone','Carboprost'],a:0,
    e:`Misoprostol is a prostaglandin E1 analogue widely used for medical induction of labour and cervical ripening. It is administered orally, sublingually or vaginally (typically 25 to 50 μg every 4 to 6 hours).<br><br>Misoprostol acts on prostaglandin EP receptors, causing cervical softening and uterine contractions. It is cheaper and more stable than dinoprostone but use in induction is off-label in many jurisdictions. Side effects include hyperstimulation, fetal distress, nausea and diarrhoea.<br><br>A (Misoprostol) is correct because it is the PGE1 analogue widely used for induction. B (Oxytocin) is wrong because it is a peptide hormone, not a prostaglandin. C (Dinoprostone) is wrong because it is the PGE2 (not PGE1) analogue. D (Carboprost) is wrong because it is the PGF2α analogue.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: The Eicosanoids)</em>`},
    {q:'Which hormone is naturally responsible for initiating uterine contractions during labor?',o:['Prolactin','Estrogen','Progesterone','Oxytocin'],a:3,
    e:`Oxytocin is the natural hormone responsible for initiating uterine contractions during labour. It is synthesised in the paraventricular and supraoptic nuclei of the hypothalamus and released from the posterior pituitary in response to cervical and uterine stretch (Ferguson reflex).<br><br>Oxytocin receptors increase markedly in the myometrium late in pregnancy, sensitising the uterus. The Ferguson reflex creates positive feedback during labour, with uterine stretch driving more oxytocin release. Synthetic oxytocin is used for induction and augmentation.<br><br>D (Oxytocin) is correct because endogenous oxytocin initiates and maintains labour contractions. A (Prolactin) is wrong because it stimulates milk synthesis, not uterine contractions. B (Estrogen) is wrong because while it sensitises the uterus, it does not directly cause contractions. C (Progesterone) is wrong because it relaxes the uterus during pregnancy.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Hypothalamic and Pituitary Hormones)</em>`},
    {q:'Which prostaglandin analogue is used mainly for treatment of postpartum hemorrhage but may also stimulate uterine contractions?',o:['Misoprostol','Dinoprostone','Carboprost','Latanoprost'],a:2,
    e:`Carboprost (15-methyl-PGF2α) is a prostaglandin analogue used mainly for treatment of postpartum haemorrhage refractory to oxytocin and ergometrine. It is given intramuscularly (250 μg every 15 to 90 minutes, max 2 mg) and stimulates strong uterine contractions.<br><br>Carboprost is contraindicated in asthma (bronchospasm risk). Side effects include diarrhoea, vomiting, fever, hypertension and bronchospasm. It is a second- or third-line uterotonic after oxytocin and ergometrine fail to control haemorrhage.<br><br>C (Carboprost) is correct because it is the PGF2α analogue used for postpartum haemorrhage. A (Misoprostol) is wrong because it is the PGE1 analogue used primarily for induction (although also used for PPH). B (Dinoprostone) is wrong because it is the PGE2 analogue used for cervical ripening. D (Latanoprost) is wrong because it is for glaucoma.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: The Eicosanoids)</em>`},
    {q:'Which receptor does oxytocin primarily act upon to stimulate uterine contractions?',o:['Beta-adrenergic receptors','Oxytocin receptors','Dopamine receptors','Alpha-adrenergic receptors'],a:1,
    e:`Oxytocin acts primarily on oxytocin receptors (specific G-protein coupled receptors of the rhodopsin family) on myometrial cells. Receptor activation triggers Gq-mediated phospholipase C, IP3 generation, intracellular calcium release and myometrial contraction.<br><br>Oxytocin receptor density increases up to 200-fold during late pregnancy due to oestrogen stimulation, sensitising the uterus to oxytocin. Oxytocin also activates oxytocin receptors on myoepithelial cells of the breast, causing milk ejection (let-down reflex).<br><br>B (Oxytocin receptors) is correct because oxytocin acts via specific oxytocin receptors. A (Beta-adrenergic receptors) is wrong because β2 receptors mediate uterine relaxation (used in tocolysis). C (Dopamine receptors) is wrong because they regulate prolactin secretion. D (Alpha-adrenergic receptors) is wrong because they are not the oxytocin target.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Hypothalamic and Pituitary Hormones)</em>`},
    {q:'Which route is commonly used for administration of dinoprostone gel for cervical ripening?',o:['Intracervical','Subcutaneous','Intramuscular','Intravenous'],a:0,
    e:`Dinoprostone gel is administered intracervically for cervical ripening before induction of labour. The 0.5 mg gel is placed in the cervical canal using a syringe applicator, with the woman remaining supine for 30 minutes after insertion.<br><br>Alternative formulations include vaginal pessary (10 mg slow-release in the posterior fornix) and vaginal gel. Patient should be monitored for uterine hyperstimulation and fetal distress. Repeat dosing is timed at 6-hour intervals if needed.<br><br>A (Intracervical) is correct because dinoprostone gel is administered into the cervical canal for ripening. B (Subcutaneous) is wrong because dinoprostone is not given subcutaneously. C (Intramuscular) is wrong because the IM route is for carboprost. D (Intravenous) is wrong because dinoprostone is not given IV.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics; Chapter: Induction and Augmentation of Labor)</em>`},
    {q:'Which complication may occur with excessive oxytocin infusion during labor induction?',o:['Placenta previa','Polyhydramnios','Uterine hyperstimulation','Fetal macrosomia'],a:2,
    e:`Excessive oxytocin infusion during labour induction can cause uterine hyperstimulation (tachysystole, defined as more than 5 contractions in 10 minutes averaged over 30 minutes). This compromises uteroplacental perfusion and causes fetal distress.<br><br>Management includes stopping or reducing oxytocin infusion, left lateral position, oxygen, IV fluids and tocolytic (terbutaline 0.25 mg SC) if hyperstimulation persists. Continuous fetal heart rate monitoring is essential during oxytocin induction.<br><br>C (Uterine hyperstimulation) is correct because excessive oxytocin overstimulates the myometrium. A (Placenta previa) is wrong because it is a placental implantation site abnormality unrelated to oxytocin. B (Polyhydramnios) is wrong because oxytocin does not cause polyhydramnios. D (Fetal macrosomia) is wrong because macrosomia is unrelated to oxytocin.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics; Chapter: Induction and Augmentation of Labor)</em>`},
    {q:'Which prostaglandin preparation is commonly inserted vaginally for cervical ripening before labor induction?',o:['Carboprost injection','Dinoprostone vaginal pessary','Progesterone tablet','Oxytocin infusion'],a:1,
    e:`Dinoprostone vaginal pessary (10 mg slow-release over 24 hours) is commonly inserted into the posterior vaginal fornix for cervical ripening before induction of labour. The pessary releases drug at a controlled rate and can be removed if hyperstimulation occurs.<br><br>Dinoprostone acts on prostaglandin EP receptors, causing cervical softening and uterine contractions. Vaginal pessary administration is convenient and allows easy removal if needed. Side effects include uterine hyperstimulation, fetal distress and gastrointestinal upset.<br><br>B (Dinoprostone vaginal pessary) is correct because it is the licensed sustained-release vaginal preparation for cervical ripening. A (Carboprost injection) is wrong because carboprost is for postpartum haemorrhage given IM, not vaginally. C (Progesterone tablet) is wrong because progesterone relaxes the uterus, opposite of induction. D (Oxytocin infusion) is wrong because oxytocin is given IV, not vaginally.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics; Chapter: Induction and Augmentation of Labor)</em>`},
    {q:'Which hormone level rises toward the end of pregnancy to promote uterine sensitivity to oxytocin?',o:['Cortisol','Prolactin','Progesterone','Estrogen'],a:3,
    e:`Oestrogen levels rise progressively during pregnancy, reaching peak at term. Rising oestrogen toward term sensitises the myometrium for labour by increasing oxytocin receptor density, gap junction formation between myocytes and prostaglandin synthesis.<br><br>Oestrogen also increases the uterine contractile protein content (actin, myosin). Together with declining progesterone effects, this oestrogen rise primes the uterus for labour. Cortisol from the maturing fetal adrenal also contributes to this transition.<br><br>D (Estrogen) is correct because rising oestrogen sensitises the uterus for labour. A (Insulin) is wrong because it does not affect uterine excitability. B (Progesterone) is wrong because progesterone relaxes the uterus and decreases functionally near term. C (Prolactin) is wrong because it stimulates milk synthesis, not uterine contractility.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics; Chapter: Parturition)</em>`},
    {q:'Which prostaglandin is classified as PGE2 and used for cervical ripening?',o:['Dinoprostone','Misoprostol','Oxytocin','Carboprost'],a:0,
    e:`Dinoprostone is prostaglandin E2 (PGE2), used for cervical ripening before induction of labour. It is administered as a vaginal pessary (10 mg slow-release) or intracervical gel (0.5 mg).<br><br>Dinoprostone acts on prostaglandin EP receptors, causing collagen breakdown, increased proteoglycan synthesis and water content in cervical tissue. Side effects include uterine hyperstimulation, fetal distress, nausea and diarrhoea.<br><br>A (Dinoprostone) is correct because it is the PGE2 analogue. B (Misoprostol) is wrong because it is a PGE1 analogue. C (Carboprost) is wrong because it is a PGF2α analogue. D (Latanoprost) is wrong because it is a PGF2α analogue used for glaucoma.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: The Eicosanoids)</em>`},
    {q:'Which complication may result from uterine hyperstimulation caused by prostaglandin induction?',o:['Polycythemia','Hyperemesis','Gestational diabetes','Fetal distress'],a:3,
    e:`Uterine hyperstimulation during labour induction (more than 5 contractions in 10 minutes) compromises uteroplacental perfusion because contractions reduce intervillous blood flow. Insufficient relaxation between contractions allows fetal hypoxia to develop, producing fetal distress.<br><br>Cardiotocographic features include late decelerations, prolonged decelerations or fetal bradycardia. Management includes stopping or reducing the inducing agent, left lateral position, oxygen, IV fluids and tocolytic (terbutaline 0.25 mg SC) if hyperstimulation persists.<br><br>D (Fetal distress) is correct because hyperstimulation reduces uteroplacental perfusion and fetal oxygenation. A (Hyperglycemia) is wrong because contraction frequency does not affect glucose. B (Hypernatremia) is wrong for the same reason. C (Polyhydramnios) is wrong because amniotic fluid volume is unrelated.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics; Chapter: Induction and Augmentation of Labor)</em>`},
    {q:'Which drug is administered intravenously with controlled infusion pump for labor augmentation?',o:['Misoprostol','Progesterone','Oxytocin','Carboprost'],a:2,
    e:`Oxytocin is administered as IV infusion with controlled rate for labour induction and augmentation. Starting dose is typically 1 to 2 mU/min, doubled every 30 minutes until adequate contractions (3 to 5 in 10 minutes) are achieved.<br><br>Maximum dose is typically 20 to 40 mU/min. Continuous fetal heart rate and uterine activity monitoring are essential. The infusion can be reduced or stopped if hyperstimulation or fetal distress develops. Synthetic oxytocin is identical to endogenous nonapeptide.<br><br>C (Oxytocin) is correct because it is the standard IV agent for controlled-rate induction. A (Misoprostol) is wrong because it is given vaginally, orally or sublingually. B (Dinoprostone) is wrong because it is given vaginally or intracervically. D (Carboprost) is wrong because it is given IM for postpartum haemorrhage.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Hypothalamic and Pituitary Hormones)</em>`},
    {q:'Which effect of oxytocin contributes to postpartum hemostasis?',o:['Uterine contraction and compression of uterine vessels','Platelet aggregation','Reduced uterine blood flow via vasospasm','Increased fibrin synthesis'],a:0,
    e:`Oxytocin contributes to control of postpartum haemorrhage by causing uterine contraction, which compresses the uterine vessels at the placental implantation site (\'living ligature\') and reduces bleeding. Strong sustained myometrial contraction is essential for placental separation and haemostasis.<br><br>Active management of the third stage with prophylactic oxytocin (10 IU IM after delivery of the anterior shoulder) reduces postpartum haemorrhage risk. If bleeding continues, additional uterotonics (ergometrine, carboprost, misoprostol) and uterine massage are added.<br><br>A (Uterine contraction and compression of uterine vessels) is correct because myometrial contraction compresses bleeding vessels. B (Vasoconstriction of placental vessels only) is wrong because the mechanism is myometrial compression, not placental vessel vasoconstriction. C (Increased clotting factors) is wrong because oxytocin does not directly affect clotting. D (Direct platelet activation) is wrong because oxytocin does not activate platelets.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics; Chapter: Obstetrical Hemorrhage)</em>`},
    {q:'Which prostaglandin analogue is most commonly used for medical termination of pregnancy in combination with mifepristone?',o:['Carboprost','Misoprostol','Oxytocin','Dinoprostone'],a:1,
    e:`Misoprostol is the most commonly used prostaglandin analogue for medical management of incomplete abortion and missed miscarriage. Typical dose is 600 to 800 μg vaginally or sublingually, repeated as needed. It is also used for medical termination of pregnancy combined with mifepristone.<br><br>Misoprostol acts on prostaglandin EP receptors causing cervical softening and uterine contractions to expel retained products. Side effects include uterine cramping, bleeding, nausea, diarrhoea, fever and chills.<br><br>B (Misoprostol) is correct because it is the established PGE1 analogue for evacuation of retained products. A (Latanoprost) is wrong because it is for glaucoma. C (Carboprost) is wrong because it is for postpartum haemorrhage given IM. D (Oxytocin) is wrong because it is less effective than prostaglandins for retained products.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: The Eicosanoids)</em>`},
    {q:'Which complication is associated with rapid high-dose oxytocin infusion?',o:['Hyperglycemia','Polycythemia','Water intoxication','Hypernatremia'],a:2,
    e:`Rapid high-dose oxytocin infusion can cause water intoxication (hyponatraemic encephalopathy) due to oxytocin\'s antidiuretic effect at high doses. Oxytocin is structurally similar to vasopressin (ADH) and cross-reacts with vasopressin V2 receptors at high concentrations.<br><br>Symptoms include headache, nausea, vomiting, lethargy, confusion, seizures and coma. Risk is highest with prolonged infusion in dilute electrolyte-free solutions (5 percent dextrose in water). Prevention is with concentrated oxytocin in normal saline or balanced electrolyte solutions.<br><br>C (Water intoxication) is correct because oxytocin\'s antidiuretic effect at high doses causes hyponatraemic encephalopathy. A (Hypernatremia) is wrong because oxytocin causes water retention and hyponatraemia, not hypernatraemia. B (Hyperglycemia) is wrong because oxytocin does not raise glucose. D (Hypothyroidism) is wrong because oxytocin does not affect thyroid function.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics; Chapter: Induction and Augmentation of Labor)</em>`},
    {q:'Which hormone decreases before the onset of labor allowing uterine contractions to occur?',o:['Estrogen','Progesterone','Relaxin','Prolactin'],a:1,
    e:`Progesterone levels decrease functionally before labour onset, removing its uterine-relaxing effect and allowing labour to begin. \'Functional progesterone withdrawal\' is mediated by changes in progesterone receptor isoform expression in late pregnancy.<br><br>Although total progesterone levels in plasma do not drop sharply before labour in humans, the myometrium becomes less responsive to progesterone\'s relaxing effects through receptor isoform changes. Concurrent oestrogen rise sensitises the uterus.<br><br>B (Progesterone) is correct because functional progesterone withdrawal precedes labour onset. A (Estrogen) is wrong because oestrogen rises (not falls) before labour. C (Insulin) is wrong because insulin does not regulate parturition. D (Prolactin) is wrong because prolactin is for lactation, not labour onset.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics; Chapter: Parturition)</em>`},
    {q:'Which drug used for induction of labor acts by increasing prostaglandin synthesis in the uterus?',o:['Misoprostol','Progesterone','Estrogen','Oxytocin'],a:0,
    e:`Misoprostol increases intracellular calcium in myometrial cells by acting on prostaglandin EP receptors. EP1 and EP3 receptors are coupled to Gq proteins and phospholipase C, generating IP3 and releasing calcium from the sarcoplasmic reticulum.<br><br>The increased intracellular calcium activates calcium-calmodulin and myosin light chain kinase, producing actin-myosin cross-bridging and uterine contraction. Misoprostol also softens the cervix through collagen breakdown.<br><br>A (Misoprostol) is correct because EP receptor activation raises intracellular calcium and triggers contraction. B (Insulin) is wrong because it does not raise myometrial calcium. C (Paracetamol) is wrong because it is an analgesic, not a uterotonic. D (Penicillin) is wrong because it is an antibiotic.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: The Eicosanoids)</em>`},
    {q:'Which fetal complication may result from excessive uterine contractions during labor induction?',o:['Congenital malformations','Polycythemia','Fetal macrosomia','Fetal hypoxia'],a:3,
    e:`Excessive uterine activity (hyperstimulation, tachysystole) compromises uteroplacental perfusion because contractions reduce intervillous blood flow. Insufficient relaxation between contractions allows fetal hypoxia to develop.<br><br>Cardiotocographic features include late decelerations, prolonged decelerations or fetal bradycardia. Management includes stopping or reducing the inducing agent, left lateral position, oxygen, IV fluids and tocolytic (terbutaline 0.25 mg SC) if hyperstimulation persists.<br><br>D (Fetal hypoxia) is correct because excessive contractions reduce uteroplacental perfusion. A (Hyperglycemia) is wrong because contraction frequency does not affect glucose. B (Hypernatremia) is wrong for the same reason. C (Polyhydramnios) is wrong because amniotic fluid volume is unrelated.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics; Chapter: Induction and Augmentation of Labor)</em>`},
    {q:'Which prostaglandin analogue is contraindicated in women with bronchial asthma?',o:['Dinoprostone','Carboprost','Misoprostol','Oxytocin'],a:1,
    e:`Carboprost (15-methyl-PGF2α) is contraindicated in women with asthma because it can cause severe bronchospasm. PGF2α stimulates bronchial smooth muscle contraction in addition to its uterine effects.<br><br>Carboprost is also contraindicated in cardiac, pulmonary, renal or hepatic disease. Side effects include diarrhoea, vomiting, fever, hypertension and bronchospasm. It is used for postpartum haemorrhage refractory to oxytocin and ergometrine. Misoprostol is preferred when carboprost is contraindicated.<br><br>B (Carboprost) is correct because PGF2α causes bronchospasm. A (Oxytocin) is wrong because it does not cause significant bronchospasm. C (Misoprostol) is wrong because PGE1 has milder bronchial effects than PGF2α. D (Dinoprostone) is wrong because PGE2 is bronchodilator, not bronchoconstrictor.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: The Eicosanoids)</em>`},
    {q:'Which drug increases uterine contractility by stimulating G-protein coupled receptors on myometrial cells?',o:['Oxytocin','Estrogen','Progesterone','Prolactin'],a:0,
    e:`Oxytocin increases uterine contractility by stimulating specific oxytocin receptors on myometrial cells. Receptor activation triggers Gq-mediated phospholipase C, IP3 generation and intracellular calcium release, producing actin-myosin cross-bridging and contraction.<br><br>Oxytocin receptor density increases up to 200-fold during late pregnancy due to oestrogen stimulation, sensitising the uterus to oxytocin. Synthetic oxytocin is identical to endogenous nonapeptide. Side effects at high doses include hyperstimulation and water intoxication.<br><br>A (Oxytocin) is correct because it acts on specific oxytocin receptors to drive contraction. B (Insulin) is wrong because it does not affect uterine contractility. C (Paracetamol) is wrong because it is an analgesic. D (Penicillin) is wrong because it is an antibiotic.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Hypothalamic and Pituitary Hormones)</em>`},
    {q:'Which route of administration is commonly used for misoprostol during labor induction?',o:['Intramuscular','Subcutaneous','Vaginal','Intravenous'],a:2,
    e:`Vaginal administration is commonly used for misoprostol in obstetric and gynaecological indications, including cervical ripening, labour induction, medical abortion and management of incomplete abortion. Typical dose is 25 to 50 μg every 4 hours for induction.<br><br>Vaginal administration produces sustained drug levels and lower peak plasma concentrations than oral administration. Sublingual and oral routes are also used. Pre-moistening tablets in saline can enhance absorption. Side effects include uterine cramping, nausea, diarrhoea and fever.<br><br>C (Vaginal) is correct because vaginal administration is established for obstetric misoprostol use. A (Intracervical) is wrong because it is the route for dinoprostone gel, not misoprostol. B (Subcutaneous) is wrong because misoprostol is not given subcutaneously. D (Intravenous) is wrong because misoprostol is not given IV.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics; Chapter: Induction and Augmentation of Labor)</em>`},
    {q:'Which complication may occur if prostaglandins are used in excessive doses during labor induction?',o:['Placenta accreta','Polyhydramnios','Fetal macrosomia','Uterine rupture'],a:3,
    e:`Prostaglandins (especially misoprostol) used for induction of labour in women with previous caesarean section carry an increased risk of uterine rupture. The scarred uterus has weakened tissue prone to dehiscence under strong contractions.<br><br>Misoprostol is contraindicated in women with previous caesarean section due to higher rupture rates compared with mechanical methods or oxytocin. Dinoprostone is used cautiously. Mechanical methods (Foley catheter, osmotic dilators) are preferred for cervical ripening in VBAC candidates.<br><br>D (Uterine rupture) is correct because prostaglandin-induced strong contractions risk dehiscence of the caesarean scar. A (Polyhydramnios) is wrong because amniotic fluid is unrelated. B (Hypernatremia) is wrong because prostaglandins do not affect sodium. C (Hyperglycemia) is wrong because they do not raise glucose.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics; Chapter: Induction and Augmentation of Labor)</em>`},
    {q:'Which physiologic effect of prostaglandins helps facilitate cervical ripening?',o:['Increased progesterone levels','Increased fetal growth','Collagen breakdown in cervical tissue','Reduced uterine blood flow'],a:2,
    e:`Prostaglandins facilitate cervical ripening primarily through collagen breakdown in cervical tissue. They activate matrix metalloproteinases that degrade collagen and increase proteoglycan synthesis and water content, transforming the firm cervix into a soft, dilatable structure.<br><br>Prostaglandins also enhance gap junction formation and uterine contractility. Cervical changes include effacement (shortening), softening and dilatation. The Bishop score (cervical assessment) improves after prostaglandin use, indicating better induction success.<br><br>C (Collagen breakdown in cervical tissue) is correct because matrix metalloproteinase-mediated collagen breakdown softens the cervix. A (Hyperglycemia) is wrong because cervical ripening does not involve glucose. B (Calcium release in muscle cells only) is wrong because while prostaglandins do raise myometrial calcium, the cervical ripening effect is via collagen breakdown. D (Vasoconstriction of cervical vessels) is wrong because prostaglandins cause vasodilation.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics; Chapter: Parturition)</em>`},
    {q:'Which hormone increases oxytocin receptor density in the uterus near term?',o:['Cortisol','Estrogen','Insulin','Progesterone'],a:1,
    e:`Oestrogen increases oxytocin receptor density in the myometrium during late pregnancy. Receptor density rises up to 200-fold near term, sensitising the uterus to circulating and synthetic oxytocin and contributing to onset of labour.<br><br>Oestrogen also increases gap junction (connexin 43) formation between myocytes, allowing synchronised contractions across the myometrium. Concurrently, functional progesterone withdrawal removes uterine relaxation. These changes prepare the uterus for labour.<br><br>B (Estrogen) is correct because rising oestrogen drives oxytocin receptor upregulation. A (Insulin) is wrong because it does not affect oxytocin receptors. C (Progesterone) is wrong because progesterone opposes contractility, not enhances oxytocin receptors. D (Cortisol) is wrong because while fetal cortisol contributes to labour onset, oestrogen drives oxytocin receptor upregulation.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics; Chapter: Parturition)</em>`},
    {q:'Which drug is used to augment labor when uterine contractions are inadequate?',o:['Relaxin injection','Estrogen tablets','Progesterone injection','Oxytocin infusion'],a:3,
    e:`Oxytocin infusion is the standard method to augment labour when uterine contractions are inadequate (hypotonic uterine activity, prolonged labour). Starting dose is 1 to 2 mU/min, titrated up to achieve adequate contractions (3 to 5 in 10 minutes).<br><br>Augmentation is indicated when active labour has not progressed adequately and contractions are insufficient. Continuous fetal heart rate and uterine activity monitoring are essential. The infusion can be reduced or stopped if hyperstimulation or fetal distress develops.<br><br>D (Oxytocin infusion) is correct because oxytocin is the standard augmentation agent. A (Misoprostol) is wrong because it is for cervical ripening and induction, not augmentation. B (Magnesium sulfate) is wrong because it is for eclampsia prophylaxis. C (Terbutaline) is wrong because it is a tocolytic that inhibits contractions.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics; Chapter: Induction and Augmentation of Labor)</em>`},
    {q:'Which complication is monitored during oxytocin infusion using cardiotocography?',o:['Fetal distress','Placenta previa','Polyhydramnios','Fetal macrosomia'],a:0,
    e:`Fetal distress is the most important complication monitored during oxytocin infusion. Excessive contractions reduce uteroplacental perfusion, causing fetal hypoxia evident on cardiotocograph as late decelerations, prolonged decelerations or fetal bradycardia.<br><br>Continuous CTG monitoring is mandatory during oxytocin infusion. If fetal distress develops, oxytocin is reduced or stopped, the woman is positioned in left lateral, oxygen is given, IV fluids are administered, and tocolytic (terbutaline) is given for hyperstimulation. Persistent distress may require expedited delivery.<br><br>A (Fetal distress) is correct because hyperstimulation-induced fetal hypoxia is the main risk. B (Hyperglycemia) is wrong because oxytocin does not raise glucose. C (Hypernatremia) is wrong because oxytocin causes hyponatraemia (water intoxication). D (Hypothyroidism) is wrong because oxytocin does not affect thyroid function.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics; Chapter: Induction and Augmentation of Labor)</em>`},
    {q:'Which prostaglandin analogue is commonly used orally or vaginally for induction of labor?',o:['Oxytocin','Misoprostol','Carboprost','Dinoprostone'],a:1,
    e:`Misoprostol is commonly administered orally or sublingually for cervical ripening and induction of labour, in addition to vaginal use. Sublingual route provides faster onset and higher peak levels than oral; oral is convenient but has lower bioavailability.<br><br>Typical doses for induction are 25 to 50 μg orally every 2 to 4 hours or 25 μg vaginally every 4 to 6 hours. Side effects include uterine cramping, hyperstimulation, fetal distress, nausea, diarrhoea and fever. It is contraindicated in women with previous caesarean section.<br><br>B (Misoprostol) is correct because oral and sublingual routes are widely used. A (Oxytocin) is wrong because it is given IV, not orally. C (Carboprost) is wrong because it is given IM. D (Dinoprostone) is wrong because it is given vaginally or intracervically, not orally.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: The Eicosanoids)</em>`},
    {q:'Which drug acts synergistically with prostaglandins to enhance uterine contractions during labor induction?',o:['Oxytocin','Insulin','Progesterone','Relaxin'],a:0,
    e:`Oxytocin and prostaglandins act synergistically to enhance uterine contractions during labour. Oxytocin stimulates myometrial prostaglandin synthesis (PGE2 and PGF2α) by activating phospholipase A2, augmenting the contractile signal.<br><br>This synergy means that combined oxytocin and prostaglandins (or sequential use after cervical ripening with prostaglandins) is more effective than either alone. Caution is needed because the combination also increases the risk of uterine hyperstimulation and rupture.<br><br>A (Oxytocin) is correct because it stimulates myometrial prostaglandin synthesis, augmenting contractions. B (Insulin) is wrong because it does not affect contractility. C (Paracetamol) is wrong because it is an analgesic. D (Penicillin) is wrong because it is an antibiotic.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics; Chapter: Parturition)</em>`},
    {q:'A primigravida at 41 weeks gestation with an unfavorable Bishop score is planned for induction of labor. Which drug is most appropriate for cervical ripening before starting oxytocin?',o:['Ergometrine','Oxytocin','Carboprost','Dinoprostone'],a:3,
    e:`A primigravida at 41 weeks with an unfavourable cervix (low Bishop score under 6) requires cervical ripening before labour induction with oxytocin. Dinoprostone (PGE2) vaginal pessary or gel is the licensed first-line agent for cervical ripening.<br><br>Mechanical methods (Foley catheter) are alternatives. Once the cervix is favourable (Bishop score 6 or above), labour can be induced with oxytocin or amniotomy. Misoprostol is also effective but not licensed for induction in many jurisdictions.<br><br>D (Dinoprostone) is correct because it is the licensed PGE2 analogue for cervical ripening. A (Oxytocin) is wrong because it is used after cervical ripening for induction, not for ripening itself. B (Magnesium sulfate) is wrong because it is for eclampsia. C (Carboprost) is wrong because it is for postpartum haemorrhage.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics; Chapter: Induction and Augmentation of Labor)</em>`},
    {q:'Which prostaglandin analogue used for induction of labor is a synthetic PGE1 derivative?',o:['Carboprost','Dinoprostone','Misoprostol','Oxytocin'],a:2,
    e:`Misoprostol, a prostaglandin E1 analogue, is widely used for induction of labour. Dose is typically 25 to 50 μg orally every 2 to 4 hours or 25 μg vaginally every 4 to 6 hours.<br><br>Misoprostol acts on prostaglandin EP receptors causing cervical softening and uterine contractions. It is cheap and stable but use in induction is off-label in many jurisdictions. Side effects include hyperstimulation, fetal distress, nausea, diarrhoea and fever. Contraindicated in women with previous caesarean section.<br><br>C (Misoprostol) is correct because it is the PGE1 analogue used for induction. A (Oxytocin) is wrong because it is a peptide hormone, not a prostaglandin. B (Dinoprostone) is wrong because it is the PGE2 (not PGE1) analogue. D (Carboprost) is wrong because it is the PGF2α analogue used for postpartum haemorrhage.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: The Eicosanoids)</em>`},
    {q:'A woman receiving oxytocin infusion develops uterine contractions every minute with fetal heart rate decelerations. What is the most likely diagnosis?',o:['Fetal macrosomia','Placental abruption','Uterine inertia','Uterine tachysystole'],a:3,
    e:`Uterine tachysystole (more than 5 contractions in 10 minutes averaged over 30 minutes) develops with excessive oxytocin infusion. This compromises uteroplacental perfusion and may cause fetal distress.<br><br>Management includes stopping or reducing oxytocin infusion, left lateral position, oxygen, IV fluids and tocolytic (terbutaline 0.25 mg SC) if tachysystole persists. Continuous fetal heart rate monitoring is essential. The aim is to restore adequate (3 to 5 in 10 minutes) contractions with normal fetal heart rate pattern.<br><br>D (Uterine tachysystole) is correct because excessive contractions defines this complication. A (Hyperglycemia) is wrong because oxytocin does not raise glucose. B (Hypernatremia) is wrong because oxytocin causes hyponatraemia. C (Polycythemia) is wrong because contractions do not affect haematocrit.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics; Chapter: Induction and Augmentation of Labor)</em>`},
    {q:'Which prostaglandin preparation is most commonly used as a controlled-release vaginal insert for cervical ripening?',o:['Carboprost','Misoprostol','Dinoprostone','Oxytocin'],a:2,
    e:`Dinoprostone (PGE2) vaginal pessary (10 mg slow-release over 24 hours) is most commonly used as a slow-release vaginal preparation for cervical ripening. The pessary is placed in the posterior vaginal fornix and can be removed if hyperstimulation occurs.<br><br>Dinoprostone acts on prostaglandin EP receptors, causing cervical softening and uterine contractions. The slow-release formulation provides sustained drug delivery without need for repeat dosing. Side effects include uterine hyperstimulation, fetal distress and gastrointestinal upset.<br><br>C (Dinoprostone) is correct because the slow-release vaginal pessary is its established formulation. A (Misoprostol) is wrong because it is used as smaller doses every 4 hours, not as slow-release. B (Carboprost) is wrong because it is given IM. D (Latanoprost) is wrong because it is for glaucoma.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics; Chapter: Induction and Augmentation of Labor)</em>`},
    {q:'Oxytocin produces uterine contraction mainly by increasing intracellular levels of which ion in myometrial cells?',o:['Calcium','Potassium','Chloride','Sodium'],a:0,
    e:`Oxytocin produces uterine contraction primarily by increasing intracellular calcium in myometrial cells. Receptor activation triggers Gq-mediated phospholipase C, IP3 generation and calcium release from the sarcoplasmic reticulum.<br><br>Increased intracellular calcium activates calcium-calmodulin and myosin light chain kinase, producing actin-myosin cross-bridging and uterine contraction. Oxytocin also stimulates myometrial prostaglandin synthesis, augmenting contractions further.<br><br>A (Calcium) is correct because raised intracellular calcium drives myometrial contraction. B (Potassium) is wrong because potassium efflux causes hyperpolarisation, opposing contraction. C (Magnesium) is wrong because magnesium opposes calcium and inhibits contraction. D (Sodium) is wrong because sodium influx is not the primary contractile signal.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Hypothalamic and Pituitary Hormones)</em>`},
    {q:'A patient undergoing labor induction develops confusion, seizures, and hyponatremia during prolonged oxytocin infusion. What is the most likely complication?',o:['Hyperglycemia','Water intoxication','Pulmonary embolism','Metabolic alkalosis'],a:1,
    e:`A patient developing confusion, seizures and hyponatraemia during labour induction has water intoxication from oxytocin\'s antidiuretic effect at high doses. Oxytocin is structurally similar to vasopressin (ADH) and cross-reacts with vasopressin V2 receptors at high concentrations.<br><br>Symptoms include headache, nausea, vomiting, lethargy, confusion, seizures and coma. Risk is highest with prolonged infusion in dilute electrolyte-free solutions. Prevention is with concentrated oxytocin in normal saline. Treatment is fluid restriction and hypertonic saline if severe.<br><br>B (Water intoxication) is correct because oxytocin\'s antidiuretic effect causes hyponatraemic encephalopathy. A (Hypernatremia) is wrong because oxytocin causes hyponatraemia, not hypernatraemia. C (Hyperglycemia) is wrong because oxytocin does not raise glucose. D (Hypocalcemia) is wrong because oxytocin does not lower calcium.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics; Chapter: Induction and Augmentation of Labor)</em>`},
    {q:'Which prostaglandin analogue is classified as PGF₂α and is mainly used for postpartum hemorrhage but may induce uterine contractions?',o:['Oxytocin','Dinoprostone','Misoprostol','Carboprost'],a:3,
    e:`Carboprost (15-methyl-PGF2α) is the prostaglandin analogue classified as PGF2α and used mainly for postpartum haemorrhage refractory to oxytocin and ergometrine. It is given IM (250 μg every 15 to 90 minutes, max 2 mg) and stimulates strong uterine contractions.<br><br>Carboprost is contraindicated in asthma (bronchospasm risk), cardiac, pulmonary, renal or hepatic disease. Side effects include diarrhoea, vomiting, fever, hypertension and bronchospasm.<br><br>D (Carboprost) is correct because it is the PGF2α analogue used for postpartum haemorrhage. A (Misoprostol) is wrong because it is the PGE1 analogue. B (Dinoprostone) is wrong because it is the PGE2 analogue. C (Latanoprost) is wrong because it is for glaucoma.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: The Eicosanoids)</em>`},
    {q:'Which hormone increases the number of oxytocin receptors in the uterus near term?',o:['Estrogen','Progesterone','Prolactin','Cortisol'],a:0,
    e:`Oestrogen increases the number of oxytocin receptors in the myometrium during late pregnancy. Receptor density rises up to 200-fold near term, sensitising the uterus to circulating and synthetic oxytocin and contributing to onset of labour.<br><br>Oestrogen also increases gap junction (connexin 43) formation between myocytes, allowing synchronised contractions across the myometrium. Concurrent functional progesterone withdrawal removes uterine relaxation. These changes prepare the uterus for labour.<br><br>A (Estrogen) is correct because rising oestrogen drives oxytocin receptor upregulation. B (Insulin) is wrong because it does not affect oxytocin receptors. C (Progesterone) is wrong because progesterone opposes contractility. D (Cortisol) is wrong because while fetal cortisol contributes to labour onset, oestrogen drives receptor upregulation.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics; Chapter: Parturition)</em>`},
    {q:'A woman with bronchial asthma requires induction of labor. Which drug should be avoided because it may cause bronchospasm?',o:['Misoprostol','Dinoprostone','Carboprost','Oxytocin'],a:2,
    e:`Carboprost (PGF2α analogue) is contraindicated in women with bronchial asthma because it can cause severe bronchospasm. PGF2α stimulates bronchial smooth muscle contraction in addition to its uterine effects.<br><br>For induction in asthmatic women, dinoprostone (PGE2, mild bronchodilator) and misoprostol (PGE1, milder bronchial effects) are preferred. Mechanical methods (Foley catheter) are also options. Carboprost is reserved for postpartum haemorrhage refractory to other uterotonics, but contraindicated in asthma.<br><br>C (Carboprost) is correct because PGF2α causes bronchospasm. A (Oxytocin) is wrong because it does not cause significant bronchospasm. B (Dinoprostone) is wrong because PGE2 is mildly bronchodilatory. D (Misoprostol) is wrong because PGE1 has milder bronchial effects than PGF2α.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: The Eicosanoids)</em>`},
    {q:'Which route is most commonly used for administration of oxytocin during induction of labor?',o:['Intramuscular','Intravenous infusion','Oral','Vaginal'],a:1,
    e:`Intravenous infusion is the most common route for oxytocin administration in labour induction and augmentation. Starting dose is typically 1 to 2 mU/min, titrated up every 30 minutes until adequate contractions (3 to 5 in 10 minutes) are achieved.<br><br>Oxytocin can also be given as IM injection (10 IU after delivery for active management of third stage). IV infusion allows precise titration and rapid stoppage if hyperstimulation or fetal distress develops. Continuous fetal heart rate monitoring is essential.<br><br>B (Intravenous infusion) is correct because IV infusion allows controlled-rate titration. A (Oral) is wrong because oxytocin is a peptide destroyed by gut proteases. C (Subcutaneous) is wrong because it is not the standard route for induction. D (Vaginal) is wrong because oxytocin is not given vaginally.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Hypothalamic and Pituitary Hormones)</em>`},
    {q:'A drug used for labor induction acts by promoting collagen degradation and increasing cervical water content. Which drug is responsible for this effect?',o:['Progesterone','Oxytocin','Relaxin','Misoprostol'],a:3,
    e:`Misoprostol (PGE1 analogue) acts on the cervix by promoting collagen breakdown via matrix metalloproteinase activation, increasing proteoglycan synthesis and water content. This softens, effaces and dilates the cervix, transforming it into a dilatable structure suitable for labour.<br><br>Misoprostol also acts on myometrial cells via prostaglandin EP receptors, raising intracellular calcium and stimulating uterine contractions. The combined cervical and uterine effects make it effective for both ripening and induction.<br><br>D (Misoprostol) is correct because PGE1 promotes collagen breakdown in the cervix. A (Oxytocin) is wrong because oxytocin acts mainly on myometrium, not cervix. B (Insulin) is wrong because it does not affect cervical tissue. C (Magnesium sulfate) is wrong because it inhibits, not promotes, contractions.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: The Eicosanoids)</em>`},
    {q:'Which mechanism explains uterine contractions caused by oxytocin?',o:['Activation of oxytocin receptors linked to phospholipase-C pathway','Inhibition of prostaglandin synthesis','Blockade of calcium channels','Stimulation of beta-adrenergic receptors'],a:0,
    e:`Oxytocin causes uterine contractions by activating oxytocin receptors linked to phospholipase C via Gq proteins. Phospholipase C cleaves PIP2 into IP3 and DAG. IP3 releases calcium from the sarcoplasmic reticulum, raising intracellular calcium.<br><br>Calcium-calmodulin activates myosin light chain kinase (MLCK), which phosphorylates myosin and enables actin-myosin cross-bridging and contraction. Oxytocin also stimulates myometrial prostaglandin synthesis via phospholipase A2, augmenting contractions.<br><br>A (Activation of oxytocin receptors linked to phospholipase C) is correct because this Gq-PLC-IP3-Ca²⁺ pathway drives contraction. B (Direct activation of cardiac receptors) is wrong because oxytocin acts on uterine, not cardiac, receptors primarily. C (Inhibition of voltage-gated calcium channels) is wrong because oxytocin raises intracellular calcium, not blocks it. D (Beta-adrenergic stimulation) is wrong because that mediates uterine relaxation.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Hypothalamic and Pituitary Hormones)</em>`},
    {q:'A patient induced with prostaglandins develops fetal bradycardia due to excessive uterine contractions. What is the underlying mechanism?',o:['Increased fetal cortisol secretion','Increased amniotic fluid pressure','Reduced uteroplacental perfusion','Increased fetal insulin secretion'],a:2,
    e:`A patient developing fetal bradycardia after prostaglandin induction has reduced uteroplacental perfusion from uterine hyperstimulation. Excessive contractions reduce intervillous blood flow and inadequate relaxation between contractions allows fetal hypoxia.<br><br>Cardiotocographic features include late decelerations, prolonged decelerations or fetal bradycardia. Management includes stopping or removing the inducing agent (e.g. removing dinoprostone pessary), left lateral position, oxygen, IV fluids and tocolytic (terbutaline 0.25 mg SC) if hyperstimulation persists.<br><br>C (Reduced uteroplacental perfusion) is correct because hyperstimulation reduces fetal oxygenation. A (Hyperglycemia) is wrong because prostaglandins do not raise glucose. B (Hypernatremia) is wrong because prostaglandins do not affect sodium. D (Polyhydramnios) is wrong because amniotic fluid is unrelated.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics; Chapter: Induction and Augmentation of Labor)</em>`},
    {q:'Which drug combination is commonly used for medical termination of early pregnancy?',o:['Oxytocin and estrogen','Mifepristone and misoprostol','Progesterone and oxytocin','Carboprost and estrogen'],a:1,
    e:`Mifepristone (RU-486) plus misoprostol is the standard drug combination for medical termination of pregnancy in early gestation. Mifepristone (200 mg PO) is a progesterone receptor antagonist that destabilises the pregnancy.<br><br>Misoprostol (800 μg vaginally or sublingually) is given 24 to 48 hours after mifepristone to induce uterine contractions and expel the products. Effectiveness is up to 95 to 99 percent in early pregnancy. Methotrexate plus misoprostol is an alternative regimen.<br><br>B (Mifepristone and misoprostol) is correct because this is the standard medical abortion regimen. A (Oxytocin and dinoprostone) is wrong because they are used for labour induction at term, not first-trimester abortion. C (Carboprost and oxytocin) is wrong because they are for postpartum haemorrhage. D (Insulin and metformin) is wrong because these are for diabetes.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics; Chapter: First-Trimester Pregnancy Loss)</em>`},
    {q:'A patient undergoing induction develops uterine contractions lasting more than 90 seconds with minimal relaxation between them. What is the most likely complication?',o:['Amniotic fluid embolism','Placenta previa','Uterine tachysystole','Polyhydramnios'],a:2,
    e:`Uterine contractions occurring more than 5 in 10 minutes during induction is uterine tachysystole (hyperstimulation). This compromises uteroplacental perfusion and may cause fetal distress.<br><br>Management includes stopping or reducing the inducing agent, left lateral position, oxygen, IV fluids and tocolytic (terbutaline 0.25 mg SC) if hyperstimulation persists. Continuous fetal heart rate monitoring is essential. The aim is to restore adequate (3 to 5 in 10 minutes) contractions with normal fetal heart rate pattern.<br><br>C (Uterine tachysystole) is correct because excessive contractions defines this complication. A (Hyperglycemia) is wrong because contractions do not affect glucose. B (Hypernatremia) is wrong for the same reason. D (Polycythemia) is wrong because contractions do not affect haematocrit.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics; Chapter: Induction and Augmentation of Labor)</em>`},
    {q:'Which prostaglandin analogue used in induction is inexpensive and stable at room temperature?',o:['Dinoprostone','Oxytocin','Carboprost','Misoprostol'],a:3,
    e:`Misoprostol is the prostaglandin analogue that is inexpensive, stable at room temperature and widely used in low-resource settings for labour induction, postpartum haemorrhage, missed miscarriage and incomplete abortion.<br><br>Compared to dinoprostone (which requires refrigeration and is expensive), misoprostol\'s stability, oral availability and low cost make it the WHO-recommended choice in many settings. Use in induction is off-label in many jurisdictions but widespread.<br><br>D (Misoprostol) is correct because it is cheap, stable and widely available. A (Oxytocin) is wrong because it is a peptide requiring refrigeration. B (Dinoprostone) is wrong because it is expensive and requires cold chain. C (Carboprost) is wrong because it is also expensive.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: The Eicosanoids)</em>`},
    {q:'Which physiologic hormone normally suppresses uterine contractions during pregnancy and falls near term?',o:['Estrogen','Progesterone','Oxytocin','Prostaglandin'],a:1,
    e:`Progesterone is the physiological hormone that normally suppresses uterine contractions during pregnancy. It maintains pregnancy by relaxing the myometrium and reducing oxytocin receptor expression and gap junction formation.<br><br>Functional progesterone withdrawal (changes in receptor isoform expression) precedes labour onset, removing this inhibition. Concurrent oestrogen rise sensitises the uterus. The progesterone receptor antagonist mifepristone is used in medical abortion.<br><br>B (Progesterone) is correct because it relaxes the uterus during pregnancy. A (Oxytocin) is wrong because it stimulates contractions. C (Estrogen) is wrong because it sensitises the uterus for contractions, opposing progesterone. D (Prolactin) is wrong because it stimulates milk synthesis, not uterine relaxation.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics; Chapter: Parturition)</em>`},
    {q:'A patient undergoing induction develops severe abdominal pain and fetal distress. Excessive prostaglandin use is suspected. What serious complication must be considered?',o:['Uterine rupture','Placenta previa','Polyhydramnios','Macrosomia'],a:0,
    e:`A patient developing severe abdominal pain, fetal bradycardia and loss of contractions during induction has uterine rupture. Risk is increased with previous caesarean section, grand multiparity, oxytocin or misoprostol use and obstructed labour.<br><br>Clinical features include sudden severe abdominal pain, vaginal bleeding, recession of the presenting part, fetal distress and maternal shock. Management is immediate caesarean section with repair or hysterectomy. Misoprostol is contraindicated in women with previous caesarean section due to higher rupture rates.<br><br>A (Uterine rupture) is correct because the clinical features match this catastrophic complication. B (Polyhydramnios) is wrong because it is unrelated to the acute presentation. C (Hyperglycemia) is wrong because rupture does not affect glucose. D (Hypernatremia) is wrong because rupture does not affect sodium.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics; Chapter: Induction and Augmentation of Labor)</em>`},
    {q:'Which drug is commonly used to augment labor when contractions are inadequate after membrane rupture?',o:['Misoprostol','Oxytocin','Carboprost','Dinoprostone'],a:1,
    e:`Oxytocin is the standard drug for augmenting labour when uterine contractions are inadequate (hypotonic uterine activity, prolonged labour). It is given as IV infusion starting at 1 to 2 mU/min, titrated up to achieve adequate contractions.<br><br>Augmentation is indicated when active labour has not progressed adequately. Continuous fetal heart rate and uterine activity monitoring are essential. The infusion can be reduced or stopped if hyperstimulation or fetal distress develops.<br><br>B (Oxytocin) is correct because it is the standard augmentation agent. A (Misoprostol) is wrong because it is for cervical ripening and induction. C (Magnesium sulfate) is wrong because it is for eclampsia prophylaxis. D (Terbutaline) is wrong because it is a tocolytic that inhibits contractions.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Hypothalamic and Pituitary Hormones)</em>`},
    {q:'Which prostaglandin analogue acts mainly as PGE₂ for cervical ripening?',o:['Misoprostol','Oxytocin','Carboprost','Dinoprostone'],a:3,
    e:`Dinoprostone is the prostaglandin analogue acting mainly as PGE2 for cervical ripening. It is administered as a vaginal pessary (10 mg slow-release over 24 hours) or intracervical gel (0.5 mg).<br><br>Dinoprostone acts on prostaglandin EP receptors causing cervical softening (collagen breakdown, increased water content) and uterine contractions. Side effects include uterine hyperstimulation, fetal distress, nausea and diarrhoea.<br><br>D (Dinoprostone) is correct because it is the PGE2 analogue. A (Misoprostol) is wrong because it is the PGE1 analogue. B (Carboprost) is wrong because it is the PGF2α analogue. C (Latanoprost) is wrong because it is for glaucoma.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: The Eicosanoids)</em>`},
    {q:'A woman induced with oxytocin requires continuous cardiotocography monitoring mainly to detect which complication?',o:['Fetal distress','Fetal macrosomia','Polyhydramnios','Congenital anomalies'],a:0,
    e:`A woman induced with oxytocin requires continuous cardiotocograph (CTG) monitoring primarily to detect fetal distress. Excessive contractions reduce uteroplacental perfusion, causing fetal hypoxia evident on CTG as late decelerations, prolonged decelerations or fetal bradycardia.<br><br>If fetal distress develops, oxytocin is reduced or stopped, the woman is positioned in left lateral, oxygen is given, IV fluids are administered, and tocolytic is given for hyperstimulation. Persistent distress may require expedited delivery (instrumental or caesarean).<br><br>A (Fetal distress) is correct because hyperstimulation-induced fetal hypoxia is the main monitoring concern. B (Hyperglycemia) is wrong because oxytocin does not raise glucose. C (Hypernatremia) is wrong because oxytocin causes hyponatraemia. D (Polycythemia) is wrong because contractions do not affect haematocrit.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics; Chapter: Induction and Augmentation of Labor)</em>`},
    {q:'Which drug used for induction may cause fever, shivering, and diarrhea as common side effects?',o:['Dinoprostone','Carboprost','Misoprostol','Oxytocin'],a:2,
    e:`Misoprostol may cause fever, shivering, nausea, vomiting and diarrhoea due to its prostaglandin effects on thermoregulation, smooth muscle and gastrointestinal tract. These side effects are dose-related.<br><br>Other prostaglandins (dinoprostone, carboprost) cause similar side effects. Maternal fever during prostaglandin use should be distinguished from chorioamnionitis. Diarrhoea and vomiting may require fluid replacement. Antiemetics and antipyretics provide symptomatic relief.<br><br>C (Misoprostol) is correct because PGE1 commonly causes fever and GI side effects. A (Insulin) is wrong because it does not cause fever or shivering. B (Penicillin) is wrong because antibiotics rarely cause this pattern of side effects. D (Paracetamol) is wrong because it is an antipyretic, not a cause of fever.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: The Eicosanoids)</em>`},
    {q:'Oxytocin-induced uterine contraction occurs through activation of which receptor type?',o:['Beta-adrenergic receptor','Oxytocin G-protein receptor','Dopamine receptor','Muscarinic receptor'],a:1,
    e:`Oxytocin-induced uterine contraction occurs through activation of the oxytocin G-protein receptor (a Gq-coupled receptor) on myometrial cells. Receptor activation triggers phospholipase C, IP3 generation and intracellular calcium release.<br><br>Increased intracellular calcium activates calcium-calmodulin and myosin light chain kinase, producing actin-myosin cross-bridging and contraction. Oxytocin receptor density increases up to 200-fold during late pregnancy due to oestrogen stimulation.<br><br>B (Oxytocin G-protein receptor) is correct because oxytocin acts via specific Gq-coupled receptors. A (Beta-adrenergic receptor) is wrong because β2 receptors mediate uterine relaxation. C (Dopamine receptor) is wrong because dopamine receptors regulate prolactin secretion. D (Alpha-adrenergic receptor) is wrong because alpha receptors are not the oxytocin target.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Hypothalamic and Pituitary Hormones)</em>`},
    {q:'Which complication may occur if oxytocin infusion is continued at high dose for prolonged periods?',o:['Hypokalemia','Hyperglycemia','Hypercalcemia','Water intoxication'],a:3,
    e:`Continuous oxytocin infusion in dilute electrolyte-free fluids (e.g. 5 percent dextrose in water) for prolonged periods can cause water intoxication due to oxytocin\'s antidiuretic effect at high doses. Oxytocin is structurally similar to vasopressin and cross-reacts with vasopressin V2 receptors.<br><br>Symptoms include headache, nausea, vomiting, lethargy, confusion, seizures and coma due to hyponatraemic encephalopathy. Prevention is with concentrated oxytocin in normal saline. Treatment is fluid restriction and hypertonic saline if severe.<br><br>D (Water intoxication) is correct because oxytocin\'s antidiuretic effect causes hyponatraemic encephalopathy. A (Hyperglycemia) is wrong because oxytocin does not raise glucose. B (Hypernatremia) is wrong because oxytocin causes hyponatraemia. C (Hypocalcemia) is wrong because oxytocin does not affect calcium.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics; Chapter: Induction and Augmentation of Labor)</em>`},
    {q:'Which prostaglandin analogue is administered vaginally or orally for induction of labor?',o:['Misoprostol','Carboprost','Oxytocin','Dinoprostone'],a:0,
    e:`Misoprostol is administered vaginally or orally (also sublingually) for labour induction and other obstetric indications. Vaginal route (25 μg every 4 to 6 hours) provides sustained drug levels. Oral route (25 to 50 μg every 2 to 4 hours) is convenient.<br><br>Misoprostol acts on prostaglandin EP receptors causing cervical softening and uterine contractions. It is contraindicated in women with previous caesarean section due to increased rupture risk. Side effects include hyperstimulation, fetal distress, nausea, diarrhoea and fever.<br><br>A (Misoprostol) is correct because vaginal and oral routes are widely used. B (Oxytocin) is wrong because it is given IV, not orally or vaginally. C (Carboprost) is wrong because it is given IM. D (Dinoprostone) is wrong because it is given vaginally or intracervically, not orally.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: The Eicosanoids)</em>`},
    {q:'A woman receiving prostaglandin induction develops uterine contractions every 1 minute. What is the most appropriate first step?',o:['Increase oxytocin dose','Give progesterone','Stop prostaglandin administration','Continue observation'],a:2,
    e:`A woman receiving prostaglandin induction who develops uterine hyperstimulation requires immediate stopping of prostaglandin administration as the first step. For dinoprostone vaginal pessary, removal of the pessary is essential.<br><br>Additional management includes left lateral position, oxygen, IV fluids and tocolytic (terbutaline 0.25 mg SC) if hyperstimulation persists. Continuous fetal heart rate monitoring is essential. The aim is to restore adequate (3 to 5 in 10 minutes) contractions with normal fetal heart rate pattern.<br><br>C (Stop prostaglandin administration) is correct because removing the cause is the first priority. A (Continue prostaglandins and add oxytocin) is wrong because adding oxytocin would worsen hyperstimulation. B (Increase prostaglandin dose) is wrong for the same reason. D (Give magnesium sulfate) is wrong because while it can be used, terbutaline is the standard tocolytic for hyperstimulation.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics; Chapter: Induction and Augmentation of Labor)</em>`},
    {q:'Which hormone directly stimulates rhythmic uterine contractions during normal labor?',o:['Estrogen','Oxytocin','Progesterone','Relaxin'],a:1,
    e:`Oxytocin is the hormone directly stimulating rhythmic uterine contractions during labour. It is synthesised in the hypothalamus and released from the posterior pituitary in response to cervical and uterine stretch (Ferguson reflex).<br><br>Oxytocin acts on specific oxytocin receptors on myometrial cells, raising intracellular calcium via the Gq-PLC-IP3 pathway and producing contraction. Oxytocin receptor density increases up to 200-fold during late pregnancy due to oestrogen stimulation, sensitising the uterus.<br><br>B (Oxytocin) is correct because it directly drives uterine contractions. A (Estrogen) is wrong because while it sensitises the uterus, it does not directly cause contractions. C (Progesterone) is wrong because progesterone relaxes the uterus. D (Prolactin) is wrong because prolactin is for milk synthesis.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Hypothalamic and Pituitary Hormones)</em>`},
    {q:'Which drug used for labor induction also promotes cervical dilation by softening connective tissue?',o:['Progesterone','Oxytocin','Misoprostol','Relaxin'],a:2,
    e:`Misoprostol promotes both cervical dilatation and uterine contractions, making it effective for both ripening and induction. It softens the cervix through collagen breakdown and stimulates myometrial contractions through EP receptor activation.<br><br>Compared to oxytocin (which acts mainly on the myometrium), misoprostol\'s dual cervical and uterine actions make it useful when the cervix is unfavourable (low Bishop score). Side effects include hyperstimulation, fetal distress, nausea, diarrhoea and fever.<br><br>C (Misoprostol) is correct because PGE1 promotes cervical dilatation and uterine contractions. A (Oxytocin) is wrong because oxytocin acts mainly on the myometrium, not the cervix. B (Insulin) is wrong because it does not affect uterus or cervix. D (Magnesium sulfate) is wrong because it inhibits, not promotes, contractions.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: The Eicosanoids)</em>`},
    {q:'A primigravida undergoing induction receives a vaginal insert that slowly releases prostaglandin for cervical ripening. Which drug is most likely used?',o:['Carboprost','Oxytocin','Progesterone','Dinoprostone'],a:3,
    e:`A primigravida undergoing induction receives a vaginal insert containing dinoprostone (PGE2) 10 mg slow-release over 24 hours. The insert is placed in the posterior vaginal fornix and can be removed if hyperstimulation occurs.<br><br>Dinoprostone acts on prostaglandin EP receptors, causing cervical softening (collagen breakdown, increased water content) and uterine contractions. Side effects include uterine hyperstimulation, fetal distress, nausea and diarrhoea.<br><br>D (Dinoprostone) is correct because it is the licensed PGE2 vaginal insert for cervical ripening. A (Misoprostol) is wrong because while it can be given vaginally, the licensed slow-release vaginal insert is dinoprostone. B (Carboprost) is wrong because it is given IM. C (Oxytocin) is wrong because it is given IV.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics; Chapter: Induction and Augmentation of Labor)</em>`},
    {q:'Which drug acts synergistically with prostaglandins to enhance uterine contractions during labor induction?',o:['Oxytocin','Relaxin','Progesterone','Insulin'],a:0,
    e:`Oxytocin acts synergistically with prostaglandins to enhance uterine contractions during labour. Oxytocin stimulates myometrial prostaglandin synthesis (PGE2 and PGF2α) by activating phospholipase A2, augmenting the contractile signal.<br><br>This synergy means that combined or sequential use of oxytocin after prostaglandin cervical ripening is more effective than either alone. Caution is needed because the combination also increases the risk of uterine hyperstimulation. Sequential use (typically 6 hours after prostaglandin) reduces this risk.<br><br>A (Oxytocin) is correct because it stimulates myometrial prostaglandin synthesis, augmenting contractions. B (Insulin) is wrong because it does not affect contractility. C (Paracetamol) is wrong because it is an analgesic. D (Penicillin) is wrong because it is an antibiotic.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics; Chapter: Parturition)</em>`},
    {q:'A 19-year-old woman presents with irregular heavy menstrual bleeding due to anovulatory cycles. Which hormonal therapy is most commonly used to regulate cycles and reduce bleeding?',o:['Oxytocin','Carboprost','Combined oral contraceptive pills','Prostaglandin E2'],a:2,
    e:`A 19-year-old with irregular heavy menstrual bleeding is treated with combined oral contraceptive pills (COCPs) as first-line hormonal therapy. COCPs regulate cycles, reduce menstrual blood loss by 40 to 50 percent and provide contraception.<br><br>Mechanism includes ovulation suppression (negative feedback on hypothalamic GnRH and pituitary FSH/LH), endometrial stabilisation and reduced prostaglandin synthesis. Side effects include nausea, breast tenderness, breakthrough bleeding and rare thromboembolism.<br><br>C (Combined oral contraceptive pills) is correct because COCPs are first-line for irregular heavy menstrual bleeding in young women. A (Insulin) is wrong because it is for diabetes. B (Levothyroxine) is wrong because it is for hypothyroidism. D (GnRH agonist) is wrong because it is reserved for severe cases (endometriosis, fibroids), not first-line.<br><br><em>(Shaw\'s Textbook of Gynaecology; Chapter: Disorders of Menstruation)</em>`},
    {q:'Which hormone is primarily responsible for stabilizing the endometrium during the secretory phase of the menstrual cycle?',o:['Prolactin','Progesterone','Oxytocin','Estrogen'],a:1,
    e:`Progesterone is primarily responsible for stabilising the endometrium during the luteal phase. After ovulation, the corpus luteum produces progesterone, which transforms the proliferative endometrium into a secretory endometrium prepared for implantation.<br><br>If pregnancy does not occur, progesterone falls (corpus luteum regresses around day 24 to 26), causing endometrial breakdown and menstruation. Progesterone also reduces endometrial proliferation, opposes oestrogen and decreases uterine contractility.<br><br>B (Progesterone) is correct because luteal-phase progesterone stabilises the endometrium. A (Estrogen) is wrong because oestrogen drives proliferation, not stabilisation. C (Prolactin) is wrong because it is for milk synthesis. D (FSH) is wrong because FSH stimulates follicle growth, not endometrial stabilisation.<br><br><em>(Shaw\'s Textbook of Gynaecology; Chapter: Menstrual Cycle)</em>`},
    {q:'A woman with dysmenorrhea is treated with combined oral contraceptive pills. What is the main mechanism by which they reduce menstrual pain?',o:['Increased luteinizing hormone secretion','Increased uterine prostaglandin production','Increased endometrial thickness','Suppression of ovulation'],a:3,
    e:`Combined oral contraceptive pills treat dysmenorrhoea by suppressing ovulation. Without ovulation, there is no luteal phase, no progesterone-prostaglandin production by the secretory endometrium, and no painful contractions of menstruation.<br><br>COCPs also reduce menstrual blood loss and produce a thinner, more stable endometrium. Continuous (no-pill week) regimens further reduce dysmenorrhoea by eliminating menstruation. NSAIDs are also effective for dysmenorrhoea by inhibiting prostaglandin synthesis.<br><br>D (Suppression of ovulation) is correct because anovulation eliminates the luteal-phase prostaglandin surge driving dysmenorrhoea. A (Inhibition of clotting) is wrong because COCPs do not reduce dysmenorrhoea via clotting effects. B (Direct uterine relaxation) is wrong because COCPs do not directly relax the uterus. C (Increased oxytocin secretion) is wrong because oxytocin would worsen, not relieve, dysmenorrhoea.<br><br><em>(Shaw\'s Textbook of Gynaecology; Chapter: Disorders of Menstruation)</em>`},
    {q:'Which hormone withdrawal is primarily responsible for the onset of menstruation?',o:['Progesterone withdrawal','Estrogen withdrawal','Oxytocin withdrawal','Prolactin withdrawal'],a:0,
    e:`Progesterone withdrawal at the end of the luteal phase is primarily responsible for menstruation onset. As the corpus luteum regresses (around days 24 to 26), progesterone levels fall, withdrawing the endometrial stabilisation effect.<br><br>Progesterone withdrawal triggers endometrial vasoconstriction (via prostaglandins), tissue ischaemia, breakdown and shedding. Concurrent oestrogen fall also contributes. The progesterone withdrawal bleed is the basis of cyclic combined hormone therapy.<br><br>A (Progesterone withdrawal) is correct because falling progesterone triggers endometrial breakdown. B (Estrogen surge) is wrong because oestrogen surge triggers ovulation, not menstruation. C (FSH rise) is wrong because FSH rises in early follicular phase. D (LH surge) is wrong because LH surge triggers ovulation.<br><br><em>(Shaw\'s Textbook of Gynaecology; Chapter: Menstrual Cycle)</em>`},
    {q:'A patient with dysfunctional uterine bleeding is treated with cyclic progesterone therapy. What is the main purpose of this treatment?',o:['Induce ovulation','Increase prolactin secretion','Stabilize and organize endometrium','Stimulate prostaglandin production'],a:2,
    e:`A patient with dysfunctional uterine bleeding (DUB) treated with cyclic progesterone has the endometrium stabilised and organised by progesterone\'s secretory transformation effect. This converts disorganised, oestrogen-stimulated proliferative endometrium into stable secretory endometrium.<br><br>Cyclic progesterone (e.g. medroxyprogesterone acetate 10 mg daily for days 16 to 25 of the cycle) produces a controlled withdrawal bleed at the end of the cycle. This is particularly useful in anovulatory DUB where unopposed oestrogen has caused endometrial overgrowth.<br><br>C (Stabilize and organize endometrium) is correct because progesterone\'s secretory transformation organises proliferative endometrium. A (Increase uterine contractility) is wrong because progesterone reduces, not increases, contractility. B (Stimulate endometrial proliferation) is wrong because oestrogen, not progesterone, causes proliferation. D (Suppress prolactin) is wrong because progesterone does not regulate prolactin in this context.<br><br><em>(Shaw\'s Textbook of Gynaecology; Chapter: Disorders of Menstruation)</em>`},
    {q:'Which hormonal therapy is commonly used for treatment of endometriosis by inducing a hypoestrogenic state?',o:['GnRH agonists','Estrogen therapy','Oxytocin','Prolactin'],a:0,
    e:`GnRH agonists (leuprolide, goserelin) are commonly used for endometriosis treatment. Continuous GnRH receptor stimulation initially causes a brief flare-up of FSH/LH (1 to 2 weeks), followed by receptor downregulation and pituitary desensitisation, producing hypogonadotropic hypogonadism.<br><br>The resulting low oestrogen state causes regression of endometriotic implants and improves pain. Treatment is limited to 6 months due to bone loss; \'add-back\' therapy with low-dose oestrogen-progestogen mitigates side effects. COCPs and progestins are also options for milder disease.<br><br>A (GnRH agonists) is correct because they produce a hypoestrogenic state that suppresses endometriotic implants. B (Insulin) is wrong because it is for diabetes. C (Levothyroxine) is wrong because it is for hypothyroidism. D (Calcium supplements) is wrong because they do not treat endometriosis directly.<br><br><em>(Shaw\'s Textbook of Gynaecology; Chapter: Endometriosis)</em>`},
    {q:'A patient with polycystic ovarian syndrome (PCOS) presents with irregular menses. Which hormonal treatment is commonly used to regulate menstrual cycles?',o:['Dinoprostone','Carboprost','Oxytocin','Combined oral contraceptive pills'],a:3,
    e:`A patient with PCOS presenting with menstrual irregularities is commonly treated with combined oral contraceptive pills. COCPs regulate cycles, reduce androgen levels (oestrogen increases SHBG, lowering free testosterone), treat hirsutism and acne, and prevent endometrial hyperplasia from unopposed oestrogen.<br><br>COCPs containing progestogens with anti-androgenic activity (cyproterone acetate, drospirenone) are particularly useful for hirsutism and acne. Metformin is added for insulin resistance and ovulation induction in fertility cases.<br><br>D (Combined oral contraceptive pills) is correct because COCPs regulate cycles and treat androgenic features in PCOS. A (Levothyroxine) is wrong because it is for hypothyroidism. B (Insulin) is wrong because while metformin is used for insulin resistance, insulin itself is not first-line for PCOS menstrual irregularities. C (GnRH agonist) is wrong because it is reserved for severe cases.<br><br><em>(Shaw\'s Textbook of Gynaecology; Chapter: Polycystic Ovarian Syndrome)</em>`},
    {q:'Which hormone therapy is used to treat secondary amenorrhea due to hypothalamic suppression?',o:['Oxytocin therapy','Estrogen-progesterone cyclic therapy','Ergometrine','Carboprost injection'],a:1,
    e:`Secondary amenorrhoea due to hypothalamic-pituitary axis dysfunction may be treated with cyclic oestrogen-progesterone therapy to restore menstrual cycles, protect against endometrial hyperplasia and provide hormonal replacement for bone and other tissues.<br><br>Underlying causes (stress, weight loss, exercise, hyperprolactinaemia, premature ovarian insufficiency) should be addressed. Combined hormonal contraceptives are an alternative if contraception is also desired. The aim is to restore physiological hormonal exposure.<br><br>B (Estrogen-progesterone cyclic therapy) is correct because cyclic combined hormone therapy restores cycles and protects the endometrium. A (Insulin) is wrong because it is for diabetes. C (Levothyroxine) is wrong because it is for hypothyroidism. D (GnRH agonist) is wrong because it would worsen, not treat, amenorrhoea.<br><br><em>(Shaw\'s Textbook of Gynaecology; Chapter: Amenorrhoea)</em>`},
    {q:'A patient with heavy menstrual bleeding is prescribed levonorgestrel intrauterine system (LNG-IUS). What is its main mechanism?',o:['Endometrial suppression','Suppression of ovulation only','Increased estrogen production','Increased prostaglandin synthesis'],a:0,
    e:`Levonorgestrel intrauterine system (Mirena, 52 mg LNG releasing 20 μg/day for 5 to 8 years) reduces heavy menstrual bleeding by endometrial suppression. Continuous local progestogen exposure produces atrophic endometrium with reduced bleeding.<br><br>Menstrual blood loss is reduced by 80 to 90 percent and 20 to 50 percent of women become amenorrhoeic. The LNG-IUS is also a highly effective contraceptive (failure rate <0.2 percent/year) and is used in PCOS, fibroids and endometriosis.<br><br>A (Endometrial suppression) is correct because local progestogen produces atrophic endometrium and reduced bleeding. B (Increased uterine contractility) is wrong because LNG-IUS does not increase contractility. C (Vasoconstriction of placental vessels) is wrong because there is no placenta in non-pregnant women. D (Increased clotting factors) is wrong because LNG-IUS does not affect clotting.<br><br><em>(Shaw\'s Textbook of Gynaecology; Chapter: Disorders of Menstruation)</em>`},
    {q:'Which hormone increases endometrial proliferation during the menstrual cycle?',o:['Relaxin','Progesterone','Oxytocin','Estrogen'],a:3,
    e:`Oestrogen increases endometrial proliferation during the follicular (proliferative) phase of the menstrual cycle. Rising oestrogen from developing follicles stimulates endometrial epithelial and stromal proliferation, glandular development and blood vessel growth.<br><br>After ovulation, progesterone from the corpus luteum transforms the proliferative endometrium into a secretory endometrium prepared for implantation. Unopposed oestrogen (e.g. anovulatory cycles, oestrogen-only HRT) causes endometrial hyperplasia and increases endometrial cancer risk.<br><br>D (Estrogen) is correct because oestrogen drives endometrial proliferation in the follicular phase. A (Progesterone) is wrong because progesterone causes secretory transformation, not proliferation. B (Prolactin) is wrong because it is for milk synthesis. C (FSH) is wrong because FSH acts on ovarian follicles, not directly on the endometrium.<br><br><em>(Shaw\'s Textbook of Gynaecology; Chapter: Menstrual Cycle)</em>`},
    {q:'A woman with severe dysmenorrhea is treated with hormonal contraceptives. What is the main therapeutic effect?',o:['Increased LH secretion','Suppression of ovulation and prostaglandin production','Increased uterine contractions','Increased estrogen levels'],a:1,
    e:`Hormonal contraceptives (combined oral pills, progestin-only pills) treat severe dysmenorrhoea through suppression of ovulation and prostaglandin production. Without ovulation, no luteal phase prostaglandin surge occurs to drive dysmenorrhoea.<br><br>Hormonal contraceptives also produce a thinner, more stable endometrium with less prostaglandin synthesis. Continuous (no-pill week) regimens further reduce dysmenorrhoea by eliminating menstruation. NSAIDs are also effective by inhibiting prostaglandin synthesis directly.<br><br>B (Suppression of ovulation and prostaglandin production) is correct because both effects together relieve dysmenorrhoea. A (Inhibition of clotting only) is wrong because clotting effects are not the analgesic mechanism. C (Direct uterine relaxation only) is wrong because hormonal contraceptives do not directly relax the uterus. D (Increased oxytocin) is wrong because oxytocin would worsen dysmenorrhoea.<br><br><em>(Shaw\'s Textbook of Gynaecology; Chapter: Disorders of Menstruation)</em>`},
    {q:'Which hormonal therapy is commonly used for treatment of premenstrual syndrome (PMS)?',o:['Prolactin therapy','Carboprost','Combined oral contraceptives','Oxytocin therapy'],a:2,
    e:`Premenstrual syndrome (PMS) is commonly treated with combined oral contraceptives, particularly those containing drospirenone (which has anti-mineralocorticoid and anti-androgenic activity). Continuous (no-pill-free interval) regimens are particularly effective.<br><br>COCPs reduce PMS symptoms by suppressing ovulation and stabilising hormone levels. SSRIs (fluoxetine, sertraline) are also first-line for severe PMS/premenstrual dysphoric disorder. GnRH agonists are reserved for severe refractory cases.<br><br>C (Combined oral contraceptives) is correct because they suppress ovulation and reduce hormonal fluctuations. A (Insulin) is wrong because it is for diabetes. B (Levothyroxine) is wrong because it is for hypothyroidism. D (Metformin) is wrong because it is for insulin resistance/PCOS, not PMS.<br><br><em>(Shaw\'s Textbook of Gynaecology; Chapter: Premenstrual Syndrome)</em>`},
    {q:'A patient with anovulatory dysfunctional uterine bleeding is treated with progesterone. What is the expected effect?',o:['Increased follicular growth','Endometrial secretory transformation','Increased estrogen secretion','Increased LH secretion'],a:1,
    e:`A patient with anovulatory dysfunctional uterine bleeding treated with cyclic progesterone has the endometrium converted to secretory transformation. Anovulatory cycles lack luteal-phase progesterone, leaving the endometrium under unopposed oestrogen with disorganised proliferation.<br><br>Cyclic progesterone (medroxyprogesterone acetate 10 mg daily for days 16 to 25) reverses this by inducing secretory transformation, stabilising the endometrium and producing a controlled withdrawal bleed. This treats both bleeding and the underlying endometrial overgrowth.<br><br>B (Endometrial secretory transformation) is correct because progesterone converts proliferative endometrium to secretory. A (Increased endometrial proliferation) is wrong because progesterone opposes proliferation. C (Vasoconstriction of uterine arteries) is wrong because progesterone does not act primarily by vasoconstriction. D (Increased oxytocin secretion) is wrong because progesterone does not increase oxytocin.<br><br><em>(Shaw\'s Textbook of Gynaecology; Chapter: Disorders of Menstruation)</em>`},
    {q:'Which contraceptive hormone mainly suppresses the LH surge and prevents ovulation?',o:['Prolactin','Estrogen','Oxytocin','Progesterone'],a:3,
    e:`Progesterone is the contraceptive hormone primarily responsible for suppressing the LH surge and inhibiting ovulation. Progesterone exerts negative feedback on hypothalamic GnRH pulse frequency and pituitary LH release, preventing the mid-cycle LH surge needed for ovulation.<br><br>Combined oral contraceptives use both oestrogen (suppresses FSH, inhibits follicular development) and progestogen (suppresses LH surge, prevents ovulation; thickens cervical mucus; thins endometrium). Progestogen-only methods rely mainly on cervical mucus thickening and endometrial thinning, with variable ovulation suppression.<br><br>D (Progesterone) is correct because progestogens suppress the LH surge needed for ovulation. A (Estrogen) is wrong because while oestrogen suppresses FSH, the LH-surge suppression is mainly progestogenic. B (Insulin) is wrong because it does not affect ovulation. C (Prolactin) is wrong because while high prolactin can suppress ovulation pathologically, it is not a contraceptive hormone.<br><br><em>(Shaw\'s Textbook of Gynaecology; Chapter: Contraception)</em>`},
    {q:'A patient with menorrhagia is treated with combined oral contraceptives. What is the major benefit?',o:['Increased estrogen production','Increased uterine blood flow','Reduced endometrial proliferation','Increased prostaglandin levels'],a:2,
    e:`A patient with menorrhagia treated with combined oral contraceptives has reduced menstrual blood loss through reduced endometrial proliferation. COCPs produce a thin, stable endometrium with reduced glandular development.<br><br>COCPs reduce menstrual blood loss by 40 to 50 percent. Mechanisms include ovulation suppression, endometrial atrophy and reduced prostaglandin synthesis. Tranexamic acid and the levonorgestrel intrauterine system are also effective for menorrhagia.<br><br>C (Reduced endometrial proliferation) is correct because COCPs suppress endometrial growth, reducing bleeding. A (Increased platelet count) is wrong because COCPs do not increase platelets. B (Direct uterine vasoconstriction) is wrong because the mechanism is endometrial thinning. D (Increased oxytocin secretion) is wrong because COCPs do not affect oxytocin.<br><br><em>(Shaw\'s Textbook of Gynaecology; Chapter: Disorders of Menstruation)</em>`},
    {q:'Which hormone therapy may be used to treat delayed puberty in females?',o:['Estrogen therapy','Oxytocin therapy','Prostaglandin therapy','Carboprost'],a:0,
    e:`Delayed puberty in girls (no breast development by age 13 or no menarche by age 16) due to hypoestrogenism may be treated with low-dose oestrogen therapy to induce secondary sexual characteristics.<br><br>Treatment typically starts with low-dose oestrogen (ethinylestradiol 2 to 5 μg daily) and is gradually increased over 2 years to mimic normal puberty. After 2 to 3 years (or after breakthrough bleeding), cyclic progestogen is added. Underlying causes (Turner syndrome, hypothalamic-pituitary disease) should be identified.<br><br>A (Estrogen therapy) is correct because oestrogen induces secondary sexual characteristics. B (Insulin) is wrong because it is for diabetes. C (Levothyroxine) is wrong unless hypothyroidism is the cause. D (GnRH agonist) is wrong because it would suppress, not induce, puberty.<br><br><em>(Shaw\'s Textbook of Gynaecology; Chapter: Puberty and its Disorders)</em>`},
    {q:'A woman with endometriosis receives GnRH agonist therapy. What is the primary mechanism?',o:['Increased progesterone production','Increased ovulation','Suppression of ovarian estrogen production','Increased prolactin secretion'],a:2,
    e:`GnRH agonists treat endometriosis by suppression of ovarian oestrogen production. Continuous GnRH receptor stimulation initially causes a brief flare-up of FSH/LH (1 to 2 weeks), followed by receptor downregulation and pituitary desensitisation, producing hypogonadotropic hypogonadism.<br><br>The resulting low oestrogen state causes regression of endometriotic implants and improves pain. Treatment is limited to 6 months due to bone loss; \'add-back\' therapy with low-dose oestrogen-progestogen mitigates side effects. After stopping, ovarian function returns within weeks.<br><br>C (Suppression of ovarian estrogen production) is correct because GnRH agonists produce hypogonadotropic hypogonadism. A (Direct uterine vasoconstriction) is wrong because it is not the mechanism. B (Increased oxytocin) is wrong because GnRH agonists do not increase oxytocin. D (Endometrial proliferation) is wrong because GnRH agonists cause endometrial atrophy.<br><br><em>(Shaw\'s Textbook of Gynaecology; Chapter: Endometriosis)</em>`},
    {q:'Which hormonal contraceptive method provides continuous progesterone release from an intrauterine device?',o:['Oxytocin implant','Copper IUD','Barrier contraception','Levonorgestrel intrauterine system'],a:3,
    e:`Levonorgestrel intrauterine system (Mirena) provides continuous progestogen release locally to the uterus. The device releases 20 μg/day of levonorgestrel for 5 to 8 years, providing highly effective contraception (failure rate <0.2 percent/year).<br><br>Mechanism includes endometrial atrophy (thin, hostile endometrium), thickened cervical mucus and partial ovulation suppression. Other progestogen-only methods include progestogen-only pills, depot medroxyprogesterone (every 12 weeks) and etonogestrel implant (3 years).<br><br>D (Levonorgestrel intrauterine system) is correct because it releases continuous local progestogen for years. A (Combined oral contraceptive) is wrong because it contains both oestrogen and progestogen, not progestogen-only. B (Copper IUD) is wrong because it has no hormones. C (Vaginal ring) is wrong because it releases both oestrogen and progestogen.<br><br><em>(Shaw\'s Textbook of Gynaecology; Chapter: Contraception)</em>`},
    {q:'A patient with secondary amenorrhea receives a progesterone challenge test. What does withdrawal bleeding indicate?',o:['Adequate estrogen levels','Ovarian failure','Pituitary failure','Low estrogen levels'],a:0,
    e:`A patient with secondary amenorrhoea who has a positive progesterone challenge test (withdrawal bleed after progesterone administration) demonstrates adequate oestrogen levels priming the endometrium. The progesterone caused withdrawal bleeding because the endometrium was already proliferated.<br><br>Positive progesterone challenge indicates anovulation with adequate oestrogen (e.g. PCOS, hypothalamic dysfunction with preserved oestrogen). Negative challenge suggests inadequate oestrogen or outflow tract obstruction; combined oestrogen-progesterone challenge differentiates these.<br><br>A (Adequate estrogen levels) is correct because the withdrawal bleed proves the endometrium was oestrogen-primed. B (Hypothyroidism) is wrong because thyroid status is assessed separately. C (Adrenal insufficiency) is wrong because adrenal function is not directly tested. D (Outflow tract obstruction) is wrong because withdrawal bleeding excludes obstruction.<br><br><em>(Shaw\'s Textbook of Gynaecology; Chapter: Amenorrhoea)</em>`},
    {q:'Which hormone therapy suppresses ovulation by inhibiting FSH and LH secretion?',o:['Oxytocin therapy','Combined oral contraceptives','Carboprost','Dinoprostone'],a:1,
    e:`Combined oral contraceptives suppress ovulation by inhibiting FSH and LH release from the anterior pituitary. The oestrogen component suppresses FSH (inhibiting follicular development) and the progestogen component suppresses the LH surge (preventing ovulation).<br><br>COCPs also thicken cervical mucus, thin the endometrium and reduce tubal motility, providing multiple contraceptive mechanisms. Failure rate is 0.3 percent with perfect use and 7 to 9 percent with typical use.<br><br>B (Combined oral contraceptives) is correct because they suppress both FSH and LH. A (Insulin) is wrong because it does not affect FSH/LH. C (Levothyroxine) is wrong because it does not affect ovulation directly. D (Metformin) is wrong because while it improves ovulation in PCOS, it does not suppress FSH/LH.<br><br><em>(Shaw\'s Textbook of Gynaecology; Chapter: Contraception)</em>`},
    {q:'A woman with heavy menstrual bleeding receives hormonal therapy along with tranexamic acid. What is the primary role of hormonal therapy?',o:['Endometrial stabilization','Increased uterine contractions','Increased prostaglandin release','Increased ovulation frequency'],a:0,
    e:`A woman with heavy menstrual bleeding receiving hormonal therapy benefits primarily from endometrial stabilisation. Combined oral contraceptives, progestogens and the levonorgestrel intrauterine system all stabilise and thin the endometrium, reducing bleeding.<br><br>The LNG-IUS is most effective (80 to 90 percent reduction). COCPs reduce bleeding by 40 to 50 percent. Cyclic or continuous progestogens stabilise the endometrium with cyclic withdrawal bleeds. Tranexamic acid (antifibrinolytic) is non-hormonal alternative.<br><br>A (Endometrial stabilization) is correct because hormonal therapy stabilises and thins the endometrium. B (Increased uterine contractility) is wrong because the mechanism is endometrial thinning, not contractility. C (Vasoconstriction of placental vessels) is wrong because there is no placenta in non-pregnant women. D (Increased clotting factors) is wrong because hormonal therapy does not increase clotting.<br><br><em>(Shaw\'s Textbook of Gynaecology; Chapter: Disorders of Menstruation)</em>`},
    {q:'Which hormone is primarily responsible for the proliferative phase of the menstrual cycle?',o:['Progesterone','Estrogen','Prolactin','Oxytocin'],a:1,
    e:`Oestrogen is primarily responsible for the proliferative phase of the menstrual cycle. Rising oestrogen from developing follicles stimulates endometrial epithelial and stromal proliferation, glandular development and blood vessel growth from days 5 to 14 of the cycle.<br><br>After ovulation (day 14), progesterone from the corpus luteum transforms the proliferative endometrium into a secretory endometrium. Unopposed oestrogen causes endometrial hyperplasia and increases endometrial cancer risk.<br><br>B (Estrogen) is correct because oestrogen drives endometrial proliferation. A (Progesterone) is wrong because progesterone causes secretory transformation. C (Prolactin) is wrong because it is for milk synthesis. D (FSH) is wrong because FSH acts on ovarian follicles, not directly on the endometrium.<br><br><em>(Shaw\'s Textbook of Gynaecology; Chapter: Menstrual Cycle)</em>`},
    {q:'A patient using progesterone-only pills mainly prevents pregnancy by which mechanism?',o:['Increasing endometrial proliferation','Increasing ovulation','Increasing LH surge','Thickening cervical mucus'],a:3,
    e:`Progesterone-only pills (POPs, mini-pills) prevent pregnancy primarily by thickening cervical mucus, making it impenetrable to sperm. Other mechanisms include partial ovulation suppression (in about 50 percent of cycles) and endometrial thinning.<br><br>POPs must be taken at the same time daily (within a 3-hour window for traditional POPs; 12-hour window for desogestrel POPs) to maintain cervical mucus effect. Failure rate is 0.3 percent with perfect use and 7 percent with typical use. Useful when oestrogen is contraindicated.<br><br>D (Thickening cervical mucus) is correct because cervical mucus thickening is the primary contraceptive mechanism of POPs. A (Endometrial proliferation) is wrong because POPs cause endometrial thinning, not proliferation. B (Direct ovarian destruction) is wrong because POPs do not destroy ovaries. C (Increased uterine contractility) is wrong because POPs do not increase contractility.<br><br><em>(Shaw\'s Textbook of Gynaecology; Chapter: Contraception)</em>`},
    {q:'Which hormonal therapy is used to treat hypoestrogenism in premature ovarian failure?',o:['Oxytocin therapy','Carboprost therapy','Estrogen replacement therapy','Prostaglandin therapy'],a:2,
    e:`Postmenopausal hypoestrogenism is treated with oestrogen replacement therapy (HRT) to relieve vasomotor symptoms (hot flushes, night sweats), urogenital atrophy and prevent osteoporosis. Oestrogen-only therapy is used in hysterectomised women.<br><br>Combined oestrogen-progestogen therapy is used in women with intact uterus to prevent endometrial hyperplasia and cancer from unopposed oestrogen. HRT is started at the lowest effective dose for the shortest duration. Risks include venous thromboembolism, breast cancer and stroke.<br><br>C (Estrogen replacement therapy) is correct because oestrogen treats postmenopausal hypoestrogenism. A (Insulin) is wrong because it is for diabetes. B (Levothyroxine) is wrong because it is for hypothyroidism. D (GnRH agonist) is wrong because it would worsen, not treat, hypoestrogenism.<br><br><em>(Shaw\'s Textbook of Gynaecology; Chapter: Menopause and Hormone Replacement)</em>`},
    {q:'A patient with PCOS receives cyclic progesterone therapy. What is the main purpose?',o:['Prevent endometrial hyperplasia','Increase LH levels','Increase estrogen secretion','Increase ovulation frequency'],a:0,
    e:`A PCOS patient receives cyclic progesterone therapy primarily to prevent endometrial hyperplasia and endometrial cancer from unopposed oestrogen exposure due to anovulation.<br><br>Anovulatory cycles in PCOS lack luteal-phase progesterone, leaving the endometrium under unopposed oestrogen with disorganised proliferation and increased hyperplasia/cancer risk. Cyclic medroxyprogesterone acetate 10 mg daily for 10 to 14 days every 1 to 3 months induces withdrawal bleeding and protects the endometrium.<br><br>A (Prevent endometrial hyperplasia) is correct because cyclic progesterone protects against unopposed oestrogen effects. B (Increase ovulation) is wrong because cyclic progesterone does not induce ovulation; clomiphene or letrozole are used for ovulation induction. C (Reduce androgen levels) is wrong because COCPs (not progesterone alone) reduce androgens. D (Treat hirsutism) is wrong because hirsutism requires anti-androgens or COCPs.<br><br><em>(Shaw\'s Textbook of Gynaecology; Chapter: Polycystic Ovarian Syndrome)</em>`},
    {q:'Which hormonal contraceptive method inhibits ovulation primarily through continuous progestin exposure?',o:['Spermicides','Copper IUD','Barrier methods','Progesterone-only pills'],a:3,
    e:`Progesterone-only pills (POPs, mini-pills) inhibit ovulation primarily through cervical mucus thickening and partial ovulation suppression. Traditional POPs (levonorgestrel, norethisterone) suppress ovulation in about 50 percent of cycles; desogestrel POPs suppress ovulation in over 95 percent.<br><br>POPs must be taken at the same time daily (within a 3-hour window for traditional POPs; 12-hour window for desogestrel POPs). Failure rate is 0.3 percent with perfect use and 7 percent with typical use. Useful when oestrogen is contraindicated.<br><br>D (Progesterone-only pills) is correct because POPs use progestogen-mediated effects on cervical mucus and ovulation. A (Combined oral contraceptive) is wrong because COCPs use oestrogen-progestogen combination. B (Copper IUD) is wrong because it has no hormones. C (Vaginal ring) is wrong because it releases both oestrogen and progestogen.<br><br><em>(Shaw\'s Textbook of Gynaecology; Chapter: Contraception)</em>`},
    {q:'A patient with endometriosis is treated with continuous combined oral contraceptives. What is the therapeutic goal?',o:['Increase estrogen production','Increase uterine blood flow','Suppress menstruation and ovarian activity','Increase ovulation frequency'],a:2,
    e:`A patient with endometriosis treated with continuous combined oral contraceptives has menstruation and ovarian activity suppressed. Continuous (no-pill-free interval) regimens eliminate withdrawal bleeding, suppress ovulation and produce a hypoestrogenic state at the endometriotic implants.<br><br>This reduces pain and slows progression of disease. Continuous regimens are particularly useful for severe dysmenorrhoea and dyspareunia. GnRH agonists are reserved for refractory cases due to bone loss with prolonged use.<br><br>C (Suppress menstruation and ovarian activity) is correct because continuous COCPs eliminate menstruation and suppress ovaries. A (Increase uterine contractility) is wrong because COCPs do not increase contractility. B (Direct uterine vasoconstriction) is wrong because the mechanism is hormonal suppression. D (Increased oxytocin secretion) is wrong because COCPs do not affect oxytocin.<br><br><em>(Shaw\'s Textbook of Gynaecology; Chapter: Endometriosis)</em>`},
    {q:'Which hormone therapy reduces menstrual bleeding by causing endometrial atrophy when delivered intrauterinely?',o:['Estrogen','Levonorgestrel','Oxytocin','Relaxin'],a:1,
    e:`Levonorgestrel intrauterine system (LNG-IUS, Mirena) reduces menstrual bleeding by causing endometrial atrophy from continuous local progestogen exposure. Menstrual blood loss is reduced by 80 to 90 percent and 20 to 50 percent of women become amenorrhoeic.<br><br>The LNG-IUS releases 20 μg/day of levonorgestrel locally to the uterus for 5 to 8 years. It is also a highly effective contraceptive (failure rate <0.2 percent/year) and is used in PCOS, fibroids and endometriosis.<br><br>B (Levonorgestrel) is correct because the LNG-IUS produces endometrial atrophy through local progestogen exposure. A (Estrogen) is wrong because oestrogen causes proliferation, not atrophy. C (FSH) is wrong because FSH stimulates follicle growth. D (Insulin) is wrong because it does not affect endometrium.<br><br><em>(Shaw\'s Textbook of Gynaecology; Chapter: Disorders of Menstruation)</em>`},
    {q:'A patient with dysmenorrhea receives hormonal therapy that suppresses ovulation and reduces prostaglandin levels. Which therapy is most likely used?',o:['Oxytocin injection','Carboprost','Dinoprostone','Combined oral contraceptive pills'],a:3,
    e:`A patient with dysmenorrhoea receiving hormonal therapy that suppresses ovulation is using combined oral contraceptive pills. Without ovulation, no luteal phase prostaglandin surge occurs to drive dysmenorrhoea.<br><br>COCPs also produce a thinner, more stable endometrium with less prostaglandin synthesis. Continuous (no-pill week) regimens further reduce dysmenorrhoea by eliminating menstruation. Failure rate is 0.3 percent with perfect use and 7 to 9 percent with typical use.<br><br>D (Combined oral contraceptive pills) is correct because COCPs suppress ovulation and reduce dysmenorrhoea. A (Insulin) is wrong because it does not affect ovulation. B (Levothyroxine) is wrong because it is for hypothyroidism. C (Metformin) is wrong because while it improves ovulation in PCOS, it does not suppress ovulation.<br><br><em>(Shaw\'s Textbook of Gynaecology; Chapter: Disorders of Menstruation)</em>`},
    {q:'Which hormonal therapy is commonly used to induce withdrawal bleeding in women with secondary amenorrhea?',o:['Oxytocin therapy','Carboprost therapy','Cyclic progesterone therapy','Prostaglandin therapy'],a:2,
    e:`Cyclic progesterone therapy is commonly used to induce withdrawal bleeding in women with secondary amenorrhoea or anovulatory dysfunctional uterine bleeding. Medroxyprogesterone acetate 10 mg daily for 10 days induces a withdrawal bleed at the end of the course.<br><br>The progesterone-induced secretory transformation of the endometrium followed by progesterone withdrawal mimics the natural luteal-phase events. Cyclic progesterone protects the endometrium against unopposed oestrogen and is useful in PCOS, anovulation and oestrogen-replete amenorrhoea.<br><br>C (Cyclic progesterone therapy) is correct because progesterone withdrawal induces controlled bleeding. A (Insulin) is wrong because it does not induce withdrawal bleeding. B (Levothyroxine) is wrong unless hypothyroidism is the cause. D (GnRH agonist) is wrong because GnRH agonists suppress, not induce, menstruation.<br><br><em>(Shaw\'s Textbook of Gynaecology; Chapter: Amenorrhoea)</em>`},
    {q:'A 24-year-old woman with polycystic ovarian syndrome presents with irregular menses and acne. Which hormonal therapy is most appropriate to regulate cycles and reduce androgenic symptoms?',o:['Oxytocin','Combined oral contraceptive pills','Carboprost','Dinoprostone'],a:1,
    e:`A 24-year-old with PCOS presenting with menstrual irregularity and androgen excess is best treated with combined oral contraceptive pills. COCPs regulate cycles, reduce androgen levels (oestrogen increases SHBG, lowering free testosterone), treat hirsutism and acne, and prevent endometrial hyperplasia.<br><br>COCPs containing progestogens with anti-androgenic activity (cyproterone acetate, drospirenone) are particularly useful. Metformin is added for insulin resistance and ovulation induction in fertility cases. Spironolactone can be added for severe hirsutism.<br><br>B (Combined oral contraceptive pills) is correct because COCPs treat menstrual irregularity and androgenic features in PCOS. A (Insulin) is wrong because while metformin treats insulin resistance, insulin itself is not first-line. C (Levothyroxine) is wrong because it is for hypothyroidism. D (GnRH agonist) is wrong because it is reserved for severe cases.<br><br><em>(Shaw\'s Textbook of Gynaecology; Chapter: Polycystic Ovarian Syndrome)</em>`},
    {q:'Which hormone primarily converts proliferative endometrium into secretory endometrium during the menstrual cycle?',o:['Progesterone','Estrogen','Prolactin','Oxytocin'],a:0,
    e:`Progesterone primarily converts proliferative endometrium into secretory endometrium during the luteal phase. After ovulation, the corpus luteum produces progesterone, which transforms the proliferated endometrium into a secretory state prepared for implantation.<br><br>Secretory transformation includes glandular enlargement with serpentine appearance, glycogen accumulation, stromal oedema and predecidual changes. If pregnancy does not occur, progesterone falls and menstruation occurs. Cyclic progesterone treats anovulatory bleeding by inducing this transformation.<br><br>A (Progesterone) is correct because progesterone causes secretory transformation. B (Estrogen) is wrong because oestrogen causes proliferation, not secretory transformation. C (Prolactin) is wrong because it is for milk synthesis. D (FSH) is wrong because FSH acts on ovaries, not directly on endometrium.<br><br><em>(Shaw\'s Textbook of Gynaecology; Chapter: Menstrual Cycle)</em>`},
    {q:'A woman using combined oral contraceptive pills mainly prevents ovulation through suppression of which pituitary hormones?',o:['ACTH and prolactin','TSH and prolactin','FSH and LH','GH and ACTH'],a:2,
    e:`Combined oral contraceptive pills mainly prevent pregnancy by suppressing FSH and LH from the anterior pituitary. The oestrogen component suppresses FSH (inhibiting follicular development) and the progestogen component suppresses the LH surge (preventing ovulation).<br><br>COCPs also thicken cervical mucus, thin the endometrium and reduce tubal motility, providing multiple contraceptive mechanisms. Failure rate is 0.3 percent with perfect use and 7 to 9 percent with typical use.<br><br>C (FSH and LH) is correct because COCPs suppress both gonadotropins to prevent ovulation. A (Insulin) is wrong because it is for diabetes. B (Cortisol) is wrong because it is unrelated to ovulation. D (TSH) is wrong because it regulates thyroid, not ovulation.<br><br><em>(Shaw\'s Textbook of Gynaecology; Chapter: Contraception)</em>`},
    {q:'A patient with severe dysmenorrhea is started on hormonal therapy that suppresses ovulation. Which drug class is most commonly used?',o:['Combined oral contraceptives','Prostaglandin analogues','Oxytocin agonists','Ergot derivatives'],a:0,
    e:`A patient with severe dysmenorrhoea started on hormonal therapy is most commonly given combined oral contraceptives. COCPs suppress ovulation, eliminating the luteal-phase prostaglandin surge that drives dysmenorrhoea.<br><br>COCPs also produce a thinner, more stable endometrium with less prostaglandin synthesis. Continuous regimens further reduce dysmenorrhoea by eliminating menstruation. NSAIDs are also first-line by inhibiting prostaglandin synthesis directly. The LNG-IUS is also effective.<br><br>A (Combined oral contraceptives) is correct because COCPs are first-line hormonal therapy for dysmenorrhoea. B (Insulin) is wrong because it does not affect dysmenorrhoea. C (Levothyroxine) is wrong because it is for hypothyroidism. D (GnRH agonist) is wrong because it is reserved for refractory cases.<br><br><em>(Shaw\'s Textbook of Gynaecology; Chapter: Disorders of Menstruation)</em>`},
    {q:'Which hormone is responsible for proliferative changes in the endometrium during the follicular phase?',o:['Progesterone','Oxytocin','Prolactin','Estrogen'],a:3,
    e:`Oestrogen is responsible for proliferative changes in the endometrium during the follicular (proliferative) phase of the menstrual cycle. Rising oestrogen from developing follicles stimulates endometrial epithelial and stromal proliferation, glandular development and blood vessel growth.<br><br>Proliferation occurs from days 5 to 14 of the cycle. After ovulation, progesterone from the corpus luteum transforms the proliferative endometrium into a secretory state. Unopposed oestrogen causes endometrial hyperplasia.<br><br>D (Estrogen) is correct because oestrogen drives endometrial proliferation. A (Progesterone) is wrong because progesterone causes secretory transformation. B (Prolactin) is wrong because it is for milk synthesis. C (FSH) is wrong because FSH acts on ovaries, not directly on endometrium.<br><br><em>(Shaw\'s Textbook of Gynaecology; Chapter: Menstrual Cycle)</em>`},
    {q:'A patient with dysfunctional uterine bleeding due to anovulatory cycles is treated with cyclic progesterone. What is the main benefit?',o:['Increase estrogen secretion','Prevent endometrial hyperplasia','Stimulate uterine contractions','Increase ovulation frequency'],a:1,
    e:`A patient with dysfunctional uterine bleeding due to anovulation receives cyclic progesterone primarily to prevent endometrial hyperplasia and endometrial cancer from unopposed oestrogen exposure.<br><br>Anovulatory cycles lack luteal-phase progesterone, leaving the endometrium under unopposed oestrogen with disorganised proliferation and increased hyperplasia/cancer risk. Cyclic medroxyprogesterone acetate 10 mg daily for 10 to 14 days induces secretory transformation, controlled withdrawal bleed and protects the endometrium.<br><br>B (Prevent endometrial hyperplasia) is correct because cyclic progesterone protects against unopposed oestrogen effects. A (Increase ovulation) is wrong because cyclic progesterone does not induce ovulation. C (Reduce androgen levels) is wrong because COCPs (not progesterone alone) reduce androgens. D (Treat hirsutism) is wrong because hirsutism requires anti-androgens or COCPs.<br><br><em>(Shaw\'s Textbook of Gynaecology; Chapter: Disorders of Menstruation)</em>`},
    {q:'A woman with secondary amenorrhea undergoes a progesterone challenge test and develops withdrawal bleeding. What does this result indicate?',o:['Pituitary failure','Complete hypothalamic suppression','Ovarian failure','Adequate estrogen priming of the endometrium'],a:3,
    e:`A woman with secondary amenorrhoea who has a positive progesterone challenge test (withdrawal bleed after progesterone administration) demonstrates adequate oestrogen priming of the endometrium. The progesterone caused withdrawal bleeding because the endometrium was already proliferated by oestrogen.<br><br>Positive progesterone challenge indicates anovulation with adequate oestrogen (e.g. PCOS, hypothalamic dysfunction with preserved oestrogen). Negative challenge suggests inadequate oestrogen or outflow tract obstruction; combined oestrogen-progesterone challenge differentiates these.<br><br>D (Adequate estrogen priming of the endometrium) is correct because the withdrawal bleed proves the endometrium was oestrogen-primed. A (Hypothyroidism) is wrong because thyroid status is assessed separately. B (Adrenal insufficiency) is wrong because adrenal function is not directly tested. C (Outflow tract obstruction) is wrong because withdrawal bleeding excludes obstruction.<br><br><em>(Shaw\'s Textbook of Gynaecology; Chapter: Amenorrhoea)</em>`},
    {q:'Which hormonal therapy suppresses ovarian estrogen production and is commonly used in the management of endometriosis?',o:['GnRH agonists','Oxytocin therapy','Estrogen therapy','Prolactin therapy'],a:0,
    e:`GnRH agonists (leuprolide, goserelin) suppress ovarian oestrogen production by producing pituitary desensitisation and downregulation. Continuous GnRH receptor stimulation initially causes a brief flare-up (1 to 2 weeks), followed by suppression of FSH/LH and ovarian oestrogen.<br><br>The resulting hypogonadotropic hypogonadism is used to treat endometriosis, fibroids and as part of IVF protocols. Treatment is limited to 6 months due to bone loss; \'add-back\' therapy with low-dose oestrogen-progestogen mitigates side effects.<br><br>A (GnRH agonists) is correct because they cause hypogonadotropic hypogonadism after pituitary desensitisation. B (Insulin) is wrong because it does not affect ovarian oestrogen. C (Levothyroxine) is wrong because it is for hypothyroidism. D (Metformin) is wrong because it does not suppress ovarian oestrogen.<br><br><em>(Shaw\'s Textbook of Gynaecology; Chapter: Endometriosis)</em>`},
    {q:'A woman with menorrhagia is treated with levonorgestrel-releasing intrauterine system. What is the main mechanism of reducing bleeding?',o:['Increased uterine contractions','Endometrial atrophy','Increased estrogen production','Increased LH secretion'],a:1,
    e:`A woman with menorrhagia treated with levonorgestrel-releasing intrauterine system (Mirena) has reduced menstrual bleeding through endometrial atrophy. Continuous local progestogen exposure produces atrophic endometrium with reduced bleeding.<br><br>Menstrual blood loss is reduced by 80 to 90 percent and 20 to 50 percent of women become amenorrhoeic. The LNG-IUS is also a highly effective contraceptive (failure rate <0.2 percent/year) and lasts 5 to 8 years. It is first-line therapy for menorrhagia in many guidelines.<br><br>B (Endometrial atrophy) is correct because local progestogen produces atrophic endometrium. A (Endometrial proliferation) is wrong because LNG-IUS thins, not thickens, the endometrium. C (Vasoconstriction of uterine arteries) is wrong because the mechanism is endometrial atrophy. D (Increased clotting factors) is wrong because LNG-IUS does not increase clotting.<br><br><em>(Shaw\'s Textbook of Gynaecology; Chapter: Disorders of Menstruation)</em>`},
    {q:'Which hormonal contraceptive mainly prevents pregnancy by thickening cervical mucus and suppressing ovulation?',o:['Copper IUD','Barrier contraception','Progesterone-only pills','Spermicides'],a:2,
    e:`Progesterone-only pills (POPs, mini-pills) mainly prevent pregnancy by thickening cervical mucus, making it impenetrable to sperm. Other mechanisms include partial ovulation suppression and endometrial thinning.<br><br>POPs must be taken at the same time daily to maintain cervical mucus effect. Traditional POPs allow a 3-hour window; desogestrel POPs allow 12 hours. Failure rate is 0.3 percent with perfect use and 7 percent with typical use. Useful when oestrogen is contraindicated.<br><br>C (Progesterone-only pills) is correct because POPs use cervical mucus thickening as primary mechanism. A (Combined oral contraceptive) is wrong because COCPs primarily suppress ovulation via FSH/LH. B (Copper IUD) is wrong because it has no hormones; it acts via copper toxicity to sperm. D (Vaginal ring) is wrong because it primarily suppresses ovulation.<br><br><em>(Shaw\'s Textbook of Gynaecology; Chapter: Contraception)</em>`},
    {q:'A patient using combined oral contraceptives has lighter menstrual bleeding. What is the primary mechanism?',o:['Increased prostaglandin synthesis','Suppression of endometrial proliferation','Increased ovarian follicular growth','Increased uterine contractions'],a:1,
    e:`A patient using combined oral contraceptives has lighter menstrual bleeding due to suppression of endometrial proliferation. COCPs produce a thin, stable endometrium with reduced glandular development.<br><br>COCPs reduce menstrual blood loss by 40 to 50 percent. Mechanisms include ovulation suppression, endometrial atrophy and reduced prostaglandin synthesis. The LNG-IUS is more effective (80 to 90 percent reduction). Tranexamic acid is a non-hormonal alternative for menorrhagia.<br><br>B (Suppression of endometrial proliferation) is correct because COCPs suppress endometrial growth, reducing bleeding. A (Increased platelet count) is wrong because COCPs do not increase platelets. C (Direct uterine vasoconstriction) is wrong because the mechanism is endometrial thinning. D (Increased oxytocin secretion) is wrong because COCPs do not affect oxytocin.<br><br><em>(Shaw\'s Textbook of Gynaecology; Chapter: Disorders of Menstruation)</em>`},
    {q:'Which hormonal therapy is used for treatment of hypoestrogenism in premature ovarian failure?',o:['Prostaglandin therapy','Carboprost therapy','Oxytocin therapy','Estrogen replacement therapy'],a:3,
    e:`Hypoestrogenism in postmenopausal women is treated with oestrogen replacement therapy (HRT) to relieve vasomotor symptoms (hot flushes, night sweats), urogenital atrophy and prevent osteoporosis. Oestrogen-only therapy is used in hysterectomised women.<br><br>Combined oestrogen-progestogen therapy is used in women with intact uterus to prevent endometrial hyperplasia and cancer from unopposed oestrogen. HRT is started at the lowest effective dose for the shortest duration. Risks include venous thromboembolism, breast cancer and stroke.<br><br>D (Estrogen replacement therapy) is correct because oestrogen treats postmenopausal hypoestrogenism. A (Insulin) is wrong because it is for diabetes. B (Levothyroxine) is wrong because it is for hypothyroidism. C (GnRH agonist) is wrong because it would worsen, not treat, hypoestrogenism.<br><br><em>(Shaw\'s Textbook of Gynaecology; Chapter: Menopause and Hormone Replacement)</em>`},
    {q:'A patient with endometriosis is treated with continuous combined oral contraceptives. What is the therapeutic objective?',o:['Increase LH secretion','Increase estrogen production','Suppress ovulation and menstruation','Increase follicular development'],a:2,
    e:`A patient with endometriosis treated with continuous combined oral contraceptives has ovulation and menstruation suppressed. Continuous (no-pill-free interval) regimens eliminate withdrawal bleeding, suppress ovulation and produce a hypoestrogenic state at the endometriotic implants.<br><br>This reduces pain and slows progression of disease. Continuous regimens are particularly useful for severe dysmenorrhoea and dyspareunia. GnRH agonists are reserved for refractory cases due to bone loss with prolonged use.<br><br>C (Suppress ovulation and menstruation) is correct because continuous COCPs eliminate menstruation and suppress ovulation. A (Increase uterine contractility) is wrong because COCPs do not increase contractility. B (Direct uterine vasoconstriction) is wrong because the mechanism is hormonal suppression. D (Increased oxytocin secretion) is wrong because COCPs do not affect oxytocin.<br><br><em>(Shaw\'s Textbook of Gynaecology; Chapter: Endometriosis)</em>`},
    {q:'Which contraceptive hormone inhibits the LH surge most directly?',o:['Progesterone','Estrogen','Oxytocin','Relaxin'],a:0,
    e:`Progesterone is the contraceptive hormone that inhibits the LH surge most directly. Progesterone exerts negative feedback on hypothalamic GnRH pulse frequency and pituitary LH release, preventing the mid-cycle LH surge needed for ovulation.<br><br>Combined oral contraceptives use both oestrogen (suppresses FSH, inhibits follicular development) and progestogen (suppresses LH surge, prevents ovulation; thickens cervical mucus; thins endometrium). Progestogen-only methods rely mainly on cervical mucus thickening, with variable ovulation suppression.<br><br>A (Progesterone) is correct because progestogens suppress the LH surge. B (Estrogen) is wrong because while oestrogen suppresses FSH, the LH-surge suppression is mainly progestogenic. C (Prolactin) is wrong because pathologic prolactin can suppress ovulation but is not a contraceptive hormone. D (FSH) is wrong because FSH stimulates follicles.<br><br><em>(Shaw\'s Textbook of Gynaecology; Chapter: Contraception)</em>`},
    {q:'A woman presents with premenstrual syndrome and is started on hormonal therapy to suppress ovulation. Which therapy is most appropriate?',o:['Carboprost','Dinoprostone','Combined oral contraceptives','Oxytocin injections'],a:2,
    e:`Premenstrual syndrome (PMS) is commonly treated with combined oral contraceptives, particularly those containing drospirenone (which has anti-mineralocorticoid and anti-androgenic activity). Continuous (no-pill-free interval) regimens are particularly effective.<br><br>COCPs reduce PMS symptoms by suppressing ovulation and stabilising hormone levels. SSRIs (fluoxetine, sertraline) are also first-line for severe PMS/premenstrual dysphoric disorder. GnRH agonists are reserved for severe refractory cases.<br><br>C (Combined oral contraceptives) is correct because they suppress ovulation and reduce hormonal fluctuations. A (Insulin) is wrong because it is for diabetes. B (Levothyroxine) is wrong because it is for hypothyroidism. D (Metformin) is wrong because it is for insulin resistance/PCOS, not PMS.<br><br><em>(Shaw\'s Textbook of Gynaecology; Chapter: Premenstrual Syndrome)</em>`},
    {q:'Which hormone therapy reduces menstrual bleeding by suppressing endometrial growth when administered continuously?',o:['Prolactin','Estrogen','Oxytocin','Levonorgestrel'],a:3,
    e:`Levonorgestrel intrauterine system reduces menstrual bleeding by suppressing endometrial growth from continuous local progestogen exposure. Atrophic endometrium reduces bleeding by 80 to 90 percent.<br><br>The LNG-IUS releases 20 μg/day of levonorgestrel locally to the uterus for 5 to 8 years. It is also a highly effective contraceptive (failure rate <0.2 percent/year). Used in PCOS, fibroids, endometriosis and hormone replacement therapy. Local action minimises systemic effects.<br><br>D (Levonorgestrel) is correct because LNG-IUS produces endometrial atrophy through local progestogen. A (Estrogen) is wrong because oestrogen causes proliferation, not atrophy. B (FSH) is wrong because FSH stimulates follicle growth. C (Insulin) is wrong because it does not affect endometrium.<br><br><em>(Shaw\'s Textbook of Gynaecology; Chapter: Disorders of Menstruation)</em>`},
    {q:'A patient with PCOS is prescribed cyclic progesterone therapy. What is the major clinical purpose of this therapy?',o:['Increase LH secretion','Prevent endometrial hyperplasia','Increase ovulation frequency','Increase estrogen secretion'],a:1,
    e:`A patient with PCOS prescribed cyclic progesterone therapy has the goal of preventing endometrial hyperplasia and endometrial cancer from unopposed oestrogen exposure due to anovulation.<br><br>Anovulatory cycles in PCOS lack luteal-phase progesterone, leaving the endometrium under unopposed oestrogen with disorganised proliferation and increased hyperplasia/cancer risk. Cyclic medroxyprogesterone acetate 10 mg daily for 10 to 14 days every 1 to 3 months induces withdrawal bleeding and protects the endometrium.<br><br>B (Prevent endometrial hyperplasia) is correct because cyclic progesterone protects against unopposed oestrogen effects. A (Increase ovulation) is wrong because cyclic progesterone does not induce ovulation. C (Reduce androgen levels) is wrong because COCPs (not progesterone alone) reduce androgens. D (Treat hirsutism) is wrong because hirsutism requires anti-androgens or COCPs.<br><br><em>(Shaw\'s Textbook of Gynaecology; Chapter: Polycystic Ovarian Syndrome)</em>`},
    {q:'Which hormonal therapy is used to induce withdrawal bleeding in women with anovulatory amenorrhea?',o:['Cyclic progesterone therapy','Prostaglandin therapy','Oxytocin therapy','Carboprost therapy'],a:0,
    e:`Cyclic progesterone therapy is used to induce withdrawal bleeding in women with secondary amenorrhoea or anovulatory dysfunctional uterine bleeding. Medroxyprogesterone acetate 10 mg daily for 10 days induces a withdrawal bleed at the end of the course.<br><br>The progesterone-induced secretory transformation of the endometrium followed by progesterone withdrawal mimics natural luteal-phase events. Cyclic progesterone protects the endometrium against unopposed oestrogen and is useful in PCOS, anovulation and oestrogen-replete amenorrhoea.<br><br>A (Cyclic progesterone therapy) is correct because progesterone withdrawal induces controlled bleeding. B (Insulin) is wrong because it does not induce withdrawal bleeding. C (Levothyroxine) is wrong unless hypothyroidism is the cause. D (GnRH agonist) is wrong because GnRH agonists suppress, not induce, menstruation.<br><br><em>(Shaw\'s Textbook of Gynaecology; Chapter: Amenorrhoea)</em>`},
    {q:'Which contraceptive method releases a progestin continuously from an intrauterine device?',o:['Copper IUD','Barrier methods','Spermicides','Levonorgestrel intrauterine system'],a:3,
    e:`Levonorgestrel intrauterine system releases progestin continuously to the uterus for 5 to 8 years (depending on device). The Mirena releases 20 μg/day of levonorgestrel locally.<br><br>Mechanism includes endometrial atrophy (thin, hostile endometrium), thickened cervical mucus and partial ovulation suppression. It provides highly effective contraception (failure rate <0.2 percent/year) and reduces menstrual bleeding by 80 to 90 percent. Used in PCOS, fibroids, endometriosis and HRT.<br><br>D (Levonorgestrel intrauterine system) is correct because it releases continuous local progestogen for years. A (Combined oral contraceptive) is wrong because it contains both oestrogen and progestogen taken daily. B (Copper IUD) is wrong because it has no hormones. C (Vaginal ring) is wrong because it contains both oestrogen and progestogen and is replaced monthly.<br><br><em>(Shaw\'s Textbook of Gynaecology; Chapter: Contraception)</em>`},
    {q:'Which hormone is mainly responsible for negative feedback on the hypothalamus and pituitary in hormonal contraceptives?',o:['Progesterone','Relaxin','Oxytocin','Prolactin'],a:0,
    e:`Progesterone is the hormone mainly responsible for negative feedback on LH secretion during the luteal phase. Luteal-phase progesterone exerts negative feedback on hypothalamic GnRH pulse frequency and pituitary LH release.<br><br>If pregnancy does not occur, the corpus luteum regresses (around days 24 to 26), progesterone falls and the negative feedback is removed. FSH then begins to rise to recruit the next cohort of follicles. Progesterone\'s LH-suppressive effect is the basis of progestogen contraception.<br><br>A (Progesterone) is correct because progesterone provides negative feedback on LH during the luteal phase. B (Estrogen) is wrong because oestrogen has both negative and positive feedback effects depending on phase, and the luteal-phase LH suppression is mainly progestogenic. C (Prolactin) is wrong because while pathologic prolactin can suppress GnRH, it is not the physiological luteal-phase regulator. D (FSH) is wrong because FSH does not regulate LH directly.<br><br><em>(Shaw\'s Textbook of Gynaecology; Chapter: Menstrual Cycle)</em>`},
    {q:'A patient with heavy menstrual bleeding receives hormonal therapy to stabilize the endometrium. Which hormone is primarily responsible for this stabilization?',o:['Estrogen','Progesterone','Oxytocin','Prolactin'],a:1,
    e:`A patient with heavy menstrual bleeding receiving hormonal therapy benefits from progesterone. Cyclic or continuous progestogens (medroxyprogesterone acetate, norethisterone) and the levonorgestrel intrauterine system stabilise and thin the endometrium.<br><br>Cyclic progestogens (e.g. norethisterone 5 mg three times daily during heavy bleeding) reduce menstrual loss by inducing secretory transformation. The LNG-IUS reduces bleeding by 80 to 90 percent. COCPs reduce bleeding by 40 to 50 percent. Tranexamic acid is a non-hormonal alternative.<br><br>B (Progesterone) is correct because progestogens stabilise and thin the endometrium, reducing bleeding. A (Estrogen) is wrong because oestrogen alone would worsen bleeding by causing proliferation. C (Insulin) is wrong because it does not affect endometrium. D (Cortisol) is wrong because it does not affect bleeding.<br><br><em>(Shaw\'s Textbook of Gynaecology; Chapter: Disorders of Menstruation)</em>`},
    {q:'Which hormonal therapy is most useful for regulating menstrual cycles in adolescents with anovulatory bleeding?',o:['Carboprost','Oxytocin','Combined oral contraceptives','Dinoprostone'],a:2,
    e:`Combined oral contraceptives are most useful for regulating menstrual cycles in young women with anovulation, irregular cycles or oligomenorrhoea. COCPs override the endogenous cycle with predictable monthly withdrawal bleeds.<br><br>COCPs also provide contraception, treat dysmenorrhoea, reduce menstrual loss, treat acne and PCOS-related androgen excess, and protect the endometrium from unopposed oestrogen. Failure rate is 0.3 percent with perfect use and 7 to 9 percent with typical use.<br><br>C (Combined oral contraceptives) is correct because COCPs are first-line for regulating menstrual cycles. A (Insulin) is wrong because it is for diabetes. B (Levothyroxine) is wrong because it is for hypothyroidism. D (GnRH agonist) is wrong because it suppresses, not regulates, cycles.<br><br><em>(Shaw\'s Textbook of Gynaecology; Chapter: Contraception)</em>`},
    {q:'A woman with endometriosis receives GnRH agonist therapy. What hormonal change occurs after prolonged administration?',o:['Decreased estrogen production','Increased progesterone production','Increased oxytocin secretion','Increased prolactin secretion'],a:0,
    e:`A woman with endometriosis receiving GnRH agonist therapy has decreased oestrogen production from the ovaries. Continuous GnRH receptor stimulation produces pituitary desensitisation, suppressing FSH/LH and ovarian oestrogen.<br><br>The resulting hypogonadotropic hypogonadism causes regression of endometriotic implants and improves pain. Treatment is limited to 6 months due to bone loss; \'add-back\' therapy with low-dose oestrogen-progestogen mitigates side effects. After stopping, ovarian function returns within weeks.<br><br>A (Decreased estrogen production) is correct because GnRH agonists produce hypogonadotropic hypogonadism. B (Increased estrogen production) is wrong because GnRH agonists suppress, not increase, oestrogen. C (Increased ovulation) is wrong because GnRH agonists suppress ovulation. D (Increased prolactin) is wrong because GnRH agonists do not raise prolactin.<br><br><em>(Shaw\'s Textbook of Gynaecology; Chapter: Endometriosis)</em>`},
    {q:'Which hormone primarily causes endometrial proliferation during the menstrual cycle?',o:['Oxytocin','Progesterone','Estrogen','Prolactin'],a:2,
    e:`Oestrogen primarily causes endometrial proliferation during the follicular phase of the menstrual cycle. Rising oestrogen from developing follicles stimulates endometrial epithelial and stromal proliferation, glandular development and blood vessel growth.<br><br>Proliferation occurs from days 5 to 14 of the cycle. After ovulation, progesterone from the corpus luteum transforms the proliferative endometrium into a secretory state. Unopposed oestrogen causes endometrial hyperplasia and increases endometrial cancer risk.<br><br>C (Estrogen) is correct because oestrogen drives endometrial proliferation. A (Progesterone) is wrong because progesterone causes secretory transformation. B (Prolactin) is wrong because it is for milk synthesis. D (FSH) is wrong because FSH acts on ovaries, not directly on endometrium.<br><br><em>(Shaw\'s Textbook of Gynaecology; Chapter: Menstrual Cycle)</em>`},
    {q:'Which hormonal contraceptive reduces menstrual blood loss by causing thinning of the endometrium?',o:['Copper IUD','Levonorgestrel intrauterine system','Barrier contraception','Spermicides'],a:1,
    e:`Levonorgestrel intrauterine system reduces menstrual blood loss by 80 to 90 percent through endometrial atrophy from continuous local progestogen exposure. Many women become amenorrhoeic (20 to 50 percent at 1 year).<br><br>The Mirena releases 20 μg/day of levonorgestrel locally to the uterus for 5 to 8 years. It is also a highly effective contraceptive (failure rate <0.2 percent/year). It is first-line therapy for menorrhagia in many guidelines.<br><br>B (Levonorgestrel intrauterine system) is correct because LNG-IUS produces dramatic reduction in menstrual blood loss. A (Combined oral contraceptive) is wrong because COCPs reduce bleeding by 40 to 50 percent, less than LNG-IUS. C (Copper IUD) is wrong because it has no hormones and may increase bleeding. D (Vaginal ring) is wrong because it reduces bleeding similarly to COCPs, less than LNG-IUS.<br><br><em>(Shaw\'s Textbook of Gynaecology; Chapter: Disorders of Menstruation)</em>`},
    {q:'A patient with dysmenorrhea is treated with combined oral contraceptives. Which physiologic effect contributes to pain relief?',o:['Increased prostaglandin synthesis','Increased estrogen production','Increased uterine contractions','Suppression of ovulation'],a:3,
    e:`A patient with dysmenorrhoea treated with combined oral contraceptives has dysmenorrhoea relieved primarily through suppression of ovulation. Without ovulation, no luteal phase prostaglandin surge occurs to drive painful contractions of menstruation.<br><br>COCPs also produce a thinner, more stable endometrium with less prostaglandin synthesis. Continuous (no-pill week) regimens further reduce dysmenorrhoea by eliminating menstruation. NSAIDs are also effective by inhibiting prostaglandin synthesis directly.<br><br>D (Suppression of ovulation) is correct because anovulation eliminates luteal-phase prostaglandins driving dysmenorrhoea. A (Inhibition of clotting) is wrong because clotting effects do not relieve pain. B (Direct uterine relaxation) is wrong because COCPs do not directly relax the uterus. C (Increased oxytocin secretion) is wrong because oxytocin would worsen dysmenorrhoea.<br><br><em>(Shaw\'s Textbook of Gynaecology; Chapter: Disorders of Menstruation)</em>`},
    {q:'Which hormonal therapy is used to treat delayed puberty in females due to ovarian insufficiency?',o:['Carboprost therapy','Prostaglandin therapy','Estrogen therapy','Oxytocin therapy'],a:2,
    e:`Delayed puberty in girls due to hypoestrogenism is treated with low-dose oestrogen therapy to induce secondary sexual characteristics. Treatment typically starts with low-dose oestrogen (ethinylestradiol 2 to 5 μg daily) and is gradually increased over 2 years to mimic normal puberty.<br><br>After 2 to 3 years (or after breakthrough bleeding), cyclic progestogen is added to protect the endometrium. Underlying causes (Turner syndrome, hypothalamic-pituitary disease, premature ovarian insufficiency) should be identified.<br><br>C (Estrogen therapy) is correct because oestrogen induces secondary sexual characteristics in delayed puberty. A (Insulin) is wrong because it is for diabetes. B (Levothyroxine) is wrong unless hypothyroidism is the cause. D (GnRH agonist) is wrong because it would suppress, not induce, puberty.<br><br><em>(Shaw\'s Textbook of Gynaecology; Chapter: Puberty and its Disorders)</em>`},
    {q:'A patient with secondary amenorrhea receives estrogen followed by progesterone. What is the purpose of this regimen?',o:['Increase LH secretion','Stimulate ovulation','Increase prolactin secretion','Evaluate endometrial responsiveness'],a:3,
    e:`A patient with secondary amenorrhoea receiving oestrogen followed by progesterone (combined hormone challenge test) has the test performed to evaluate endometrial responsiveness when initial progesterone challenge alone failed to produce withdrawal bleed.<br><br>The combined challenge primes the endometrium with oestrogen for 21 to 25 days, then adds progesterone for 5 to 10 days. Withdrawal bleed indicates a responsive endometrium and intact outflow tract; absence suggests endometrial damage (Asherman syndrome) or outflow obstruction.<br><br>D (Evaluate endometrial responsiveness) is correct because the combined challenge tests the endometrium and outflow tract. A (Stimulate ovulation) is wrong because the test does not stimulate ovulation. B (Increase prolactin) is wrong because the test does not affect prolactin. C (Treat hirsutism) is wrong because it is unrelated.<br><br><em>(Shaw\'s Textbook of Gynaecology; Chapter: Amenorrhoea)</em>`},
    {q:'Which hormone suppresses gonadotropin secretion in progesterone-only contraceptive methods?',o:['Oxytocin','Progesterone','Estrogen','Prolactin'],a:1,
    e:`Progesterone-only contraceptives (POPs, depot, implant, LNG-IUS) suppress gonadotropin secretion through progesterone\'s negative feedback on hypothalamic GnRH and pituitary LH/FSH release. Suppression is variable: traditional POPs suppress ovulation in 50 percent; desogestrel POPs in over 95 percent.<br><br>Combined oral contraceptives use both oestrogen (suppresses FSH) and progestogen (suppresses LH surge). Progesterone-only methods primarily rely on cervical mucus thickening and endometrial thinning, with variable ovulation suppression.<br><br>B (Progesterone) is correct because progestogens suppress gonadotropins (especially LH surge). A (Estrogen) is wrong because while oestrogen suppresses FSH, the question specifies progestogen-only therapy. C (Prolactin) is wrong because pathologic prolactin can suppress GnRH but is not contraceptive. D (FSH) is wrong because FSH does not regulate gonadotropin secretion.<br><br><em>(Shaw\'s Textbook of Gynaecology; Chapter: Contraception)</em>`},
    {q:'A patient with severe menorrhagia receives hormonal therapy aimed at reducing endometrial growth and menstrual blood loss. Which treatment is most effective long-term?',o:['Levonorgestrel intrauterine system','Carboprost therapy','Dinoprostone','Oxytocin injection'],a:0,
    e:`A patient with severe menorrhagia receiving hormonal therapy is most effectively treated with the levonorgestrel intrauterine system. Menstrual blood loss is reduced by 80 to 90 percent and 20 to 50 percent of women become amenorrhoeic.<br><br>The LNG-IUS releases 20 μg/day of levonorgestrel locally for 5 to 8 years, producing endometrial atrophy. It is first-line therapy for menorrhagia in many guidelines, also providing highly effective contraception (failure rate <0.2 percent/year). Used in PCOS, fibroids, endometriosis and HRT.<br><br>A (Levonorgestrel intrauterine system) is correct because LNG-IUS is the most effective hormonal therapy for menorrhagia. B (Combined oral contraceptive) is wrong because COCPs reduce bleeding less effectively. C (Copper IUD) is wrong because it has no hormones and may increase bleeding. D (Vaginal ring) is wrong because it is similar to COCPs in efficacy.<br><br><em>(Shaw\'s Textbook of Gynaecology; Chapter: Disorders of Menstruation)</em>`},
    {q:'A 29-year-old woman at 30 weeks gestation presents with preterm uterine contractions. A drug is given that relaxes uterine smooth muscle by increasing intracellular cAMP through β₂-adrenergic receptor stimulation. Which drug is most likely used?',o:['Nifedipine','Indomethacin','Terbutaline','Magnesium sulphate'],a:2,
    e:`A 29-year-old at 30 weeks gestation in preterm labour is treated with terbutaline, a β₂-adrenergic agonist that activates myometrial β₂ receptors, increasing intracellular cAMP and reducing intracellular calcium, producing uterine relaxation.<br><br>Terbutaline is given as 0.25 mg SC every 20 to 30 minutes (max 4 doses) for acute tocolysis. Side effects include maternal tachycardia, palpitations, hyperglycaemia, hypokalaemia, pulmonary oedema and rare cardiac arrhythmias. Long-term use is avoided due to maternal cardiovascular events.<br><br>C (Terbutaline) is correct because it is the established β₂-agonist tocolytic. A (Oxytocin) is wrong because it is a uterotonic, not a tocolytic. B (Misoprostol) is wrong because it stimulates contractions. D (Carboprost) is wrong because it is a uterotonic for postpartum haemorrhage.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Adrenoceptor Agonists and Sympathomimetic Drugs)</em>`},
    {q:'Which class of tocolytic drugs acts by blocking L-type calcium channels in myometrial cells, thereby reducing uterine contractions?',o:['Calcium channel blockers','Beta-agonists','NSAIDs','Magnesium salts'],a:0,
    e:`Calcium channel blockers (nifedipine) are tocolytics that block L-type calcium channels in myometrial cells, reducing intracellular calcium, myosin light chain phosphorylation and uterine contraction.<br><br>Nifedipine 20 mg orally followed by 10 to 20 mg every 4 to 6 hours is widely used as first-line tocolytic. Advantages include oral administration, low cost and good efficacy. Side effects include maternal hypotension, headache, flushing and tachycardia. Avoid concurrent use with magnesium sulfate (synergistic neuromuscular block).<br><br>A (Calcium channel blockers) is correct because L-type Ca²⁺ channel blockade reduces myometrial contraction. B (Beta-blockers) is wrong because beta-blockers do not relax the uterus. C (ACE inhibitors) is wrong because they are antihypertensives without uterine effects. D (Diuretics) is wrong because they are not tocolytics.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Vasodilators and the Treatment of Angina Pectoris)</em>`},
    {q:'A patient in preterm labor is treated with a drug that inhibits cyclooxygenase and reduces prostaglandin synthesis, thereby decreasing uterine contractions. Which drug is most likely used?',o:['Ritodrine','Magnesium sulphate','Nifedipine','Indomethacin'],a:3,
    e:`A patient in preterm labour treated with a drug that inhibits prostaglandin synthesis is receiving indomethacin (NSAID, COX inhibitor). Indomethacin reduces prostaglandin synthesis (PGE2 and PGF2α) which mediate uterine contractions.<br><br>Dose is typically 50 to 100 mg loading followed by 25 to 50 mg every 4 to 6 hours. Use is limited to under 32 weeks gestation and for less than 48 hours due to risks of premature ductus arteriosus closure, oligohydramnios and necrotising enterocolitis. Monitoring of amniotic fluid index and ductal flow is needed.<br><br>D (Indomethacin) is correct because COX inhibition reduces prostaglandin-mediated contractions. A (Oxytocin) is wrong because it stimulates, not inhibits, contractions. B (Carboprost) is wrong because it is a prostaglandin agonist (uterotonic). C (Misoprostol) is wrong because it stimulates contractions.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Nonsteroidal Anti-Inflammatory Drugs)</em>`},
    {q:'Which tocolytic drug reduces uterine contractility primarily by competing with calcium at cellular entry sites and reducing acetylcholine release?',o:['Terbutaline','Magnesium sulphate','Indomethacin','Nifedipine'],a:1,
    e:`Magnesium sulfate reduces uterine contractility primarily by competing with calcium at L-type calcium channels and reducing intracellular calcium availability for contractile machinery. Magnesium also stabilises cell membranes.<br><br>Loading dose is typically 4 to 6 g IV over 20 minutes, followed by 1 to 2 g/hour infusion. Magnesium also has fetal neuroprotective effects in preterm labour, reducing cerebral palsy risk. Toxicity (loss of deep tendon reflexes, respiratory depression) is reversed with calcium gluconate.<br><br>B (Magnesium sulphate) is correct because magnesium competes with calcium at myometrial channels. A (Oxytocin) is wrong because it stimulates contractions. C (Misoprostol) is wrong because it stimulates contractions. D (Carboprost) is wrong because it is a uterotonic.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Antiseizure Drugs)</em>`},
    {q:'A pregnant woman receiving a beta-agonist tocolytic develops tachycardia and tremors. Which drug is the most likely cause?',o:['Indomethacin','Magnesium sulphate','Nifedipine','Ritodrine'],a:3,
    e:`A pregnant woman receiving a beta-agonist tocolytic developing maternal tachycardia and hyperglycaemia is on ritodrine (β₂-agonist). Ritodrine activates β₂ receptors, causing myometrial relaxation but also β₁-mediated cardiac stimulation (tachycardia) and metabolic effects (hyperglycaemia, hypokalaemia).<br><br>Other side effects include palpitations, tremor, anxiety, pulmonary oedema and rare cardiac arrhythmias. Ritodrine is largely replaced by terbutaline and other tocolytics due to side effects. Calcium channel blockers (nifedipine) and oxytocin antagonists (atosiban) are now preferred.<br><br>D (Ritodrine) is correct because it causes the classic β-agonist side effects of tachycardia and hyperglycaemia. A (Magnesium sulphate) is wrong because magnesium does not cause tachycardia or hyperglycaemia. B (Indomethacin) is wrong because it does not cause tachycardia. C (Nifedipine) is wrong because while it can cause tachycardia, hyperglycaemia is not characteristic.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Adrenoceptor Agonists and Sympathomimetic Drugs)</em>`},
    {q:'Which tocolytic drug class decreases uterine contractions by reducing prostaglandin production from arachidonic acid?',o:['Calcium channel blockers','Beta agonists','NSAIDs','Magnesium salts'],a:2,
    e:`NSAIDs (indomethacin) decrease uterine contractions by inhibiting cyclooxygenase (COX), reducing prostaglandin synthesis (PGE2 and PGF2α) which mediate uterine contractions.<br><br>Indomethacin 50 to 100 mg loading followed by 25 to 50 mg every 4 to 6 hours is commonly used. Use is limited to under 32 weeks gestation and for less than 48 hours due to risks of premature ductus arteriosus closure, oligohydramnios and necrotising enterocolitis. Monitoring of amniotic fluid index and ductal flow is needed.<br><br>C (NSAIDs) is correct because COX inhibition reduces prostaglandin-mediated contractions. A (Oxytocin agonists) is wrong because oxytocin stimulates, not reduces, contractions. B (Beta-agonists) is wrong because while they are tocolytics, they act through cAMP-Ca²⁺ pathway, not prostaglandins. D (Vasopressin) is wrong because it does not affect uterine contractions therapeutically.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Nonsteroidal Anti-Inflammatory Drugs)</em>`},
    {q:'A patient at 31 weeks gestation is given nifedipine for preterm labor. What is the primary mechanism of uterine relaxation?',o:['Inhibition of calcium influx in myometrial cells','Increased intracellular cAMP','Inhibition of prostaglandin synthesis','Decreased acetylcholine release'],a:0,
    e:`A patient at 31 weeks given nifedipine for preterm labour has uterine relaxation through inhibition of calcium influx in myometrial cells. Nifedipine blocks L-type calcium channels, reducing intracellular calcium, myosin light chain phosphorylation and contraction.<br><br>Nifedipine 20 mg orally followed by 10 to 20 mg every 4 to 6 hours is widely used as first-line tocolytic. Advantages include oral administration, low cost and good efficacy. Side effects include maternal hypotension, headache, flushing and tachycardia. Avoid with magnesium sulfate.<br><br>A (Inhibition of calcium influx in myometrial cells) is correct because nifedipine blocks L-type Ca²⁺ channels. B (Stimulation of beta-receptors) is wrong because that is the β-agonist mechanism. C (Inhibition of cyclooxygenase) is wrong because that is the NSAID mechanism. D (Activation of oxytocin receptors) is wrong because that would stimulate, not relax, contractions.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Vasodilators and the Treatment of Angina Pectoris)</em>`},
    {q:'Which fetal complication is most strongly associated with prolonged use of indomethacin as a tocolytic?',o:['Patent ductus arteriosus','Premature closure of ductus arteriosus','Neural tube defect','Ventricular septal defect'],a:1,
    e:`Premature closure of the fetal ductus arteriosus is the most strongly associated fetal complication of prolonged indomethacin tocolysis. Indomethacin inhibits prostaglandin synthesis (especially PGE2 maintaining ductal patency), causing premature closure with right ventricular hypertrophy and pulmonary hypertension.<br><br>Risk increases with use beyond 32 weeks gestation and for more than 48 to 72 hours. Other indomethacin-related fetal effects include oligohydramnios (reduced fetal renal perfusion) and necrotising enterocolitis in preterm infants. Use is therefore limited to <32 weeks for <48 hours.<br><br>B (Premature closure of ductus arteriosus) is correct because COX inhibition removes prostaglandin maintenance of ductal patency. A (Patent ductus arteriosus) is wrong because indomethacin closes, not opens, the ductus. C (Ventricular septal defect) is wrong because it is unrelated. D (Coarctation of aorta) is wrong because it is unrelated to NSAIDs.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics; Chapter: Preterm Labor)</em>`},
    {q:'A drug used for tocolysis acts by stimulating β₂-adrenergic receptors on uterine smooth muscle. Which intracellular pathway mediates this effect?',o:['Decreased cAMP','Increased intracellular calcium','Activation of cyclooxygenase','Increased cAMP production'],a:3,
    e:`A drug used for tocolysis acting by stimulating β₂-adrenergic receptors increases cAMP production through Gs-coupled receptor activation. Increased cAMP activates protein kinase A, which inhibits myosin light chain kinase and reduces intracellular calcium, producing uterine relaxation.<br><br>Examples include terbutaline and ritodrine. Side effects from β₂ receptor activation include maternal tachycardia (β₁ cross-activation), palpitations, hyperglycaemia, hypokalaemia and rare pulmonary oedema. Ritodrine is largely replaced due to side effects.<br><br>D (Increased cAMP production) is correct because β₂ activation raises cAMP, producing uterine relaxation. A (Increased calcium influx) is wrong because β₂ agonists reduce, not increase, intracellular calcium. B (Increased prostaglandin synthesis) is wrong because that would stimulate contractions. C (Increased oxytocin release) is wrong because that would stimulate contractions.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Adrenoceptor Agonists and Sympathomimetic Drugs)</em>`},
    {q:'A woman treated with nifedipine for preterm labor develops hypotension and flushing. Which mechanism explains this side effect?',o:['Increased prostaglandin synthesis','Peripheral vasodilation due to calcium channel blockade','β₂-receptor stimulation','Increased acetylcholine release'],a:1,
    e:`A woman treated with nifedipine for preterm labour developing maternal hypotension has peripheral vasodilation due to calcium channel blockade. Nifedipine blocks L-type calcium channels in vascular smooth muscle, causing vasodilation and reduced systemic vascular resistance.<br><br>Maternal blood pressure should be monitored during nifedipine tocolysis. Hypotension may be treated with IV fluids and positioning. Reflex tachycardia is also common. Avoid concurrent use with magnesium sulfate due to synergistic neuromuscular block and severe hypotension.<br><br>B (Peripheral vasodilation due to calcium channel blockade) is correct because nifedipine reduces vascular resistance. A (Increased preload) is wrong because nifedipine reduces, not increases, preload. C (Direct cardiac stimulation) is wrong because nifedipine does not directly stimulate the heart. D (Increased oxytocin release) is wrong because oxytocin does not lower blood pressure.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Vasodilators and the Treatment of Angina Pectoris)</em>`},
    {q:'Which tocolytic drug is also used for fetal neuroprotection in very preterm deliveries?',o:['Ritodrine','Nifedipine','Magnesium sulphate','Indomethacin'],a:2,
    e:`Magnesium sulfate is the tocolytic also used for fetal neuroprotection in preterm labour. Magnesium given to women at risk of imminent preterm delivery before 32 weeks reduces cerebral palsy risk in surviving infants.<br><br>Loading dose for neuroprotection is 4 g IV over 20 minutes, followed by 1 g/hour infusion until delivery or 12 to 24 hours. Magnesium also has tocolytic and eclampsia-preventive effects. Toxicity (loss of deep tendon reflexes, respiratory depression) is reversed with calcium gluconate.<br><br>C (Magnesium sulphate) is correct because magnesium has both tocolytic and neuroprotective effects. A (Indomethacin) is wrong because while it is a tocolytic, it has no neuroprotective benefit. B (Terbutaline) is wrong because beta-agonists are not neuroprotective. D (Nifedipine) is wrong because calcium channel blockers are not neuroprotective.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics; Chapter: Preterm Labor)</em>`},
    {q:'A woman at 29 weeks gestation receives indomethacin for preterm labor. What is the primary pharmacologic action responsible for uterine relaxation?',o:['Inhibition of cyclooxygenase','Increased prostaglandin synthesis','β-receptor blockade','Calcium channel activation'],a:0,
    e:`A woman at 29 weeks receiving indomethacin for preterm labour has uterine relaxation through inhibition of cyclooxygenase. Indomethacin (a non-selective COX inhibitor) reduces prostaglandin synthesis (PGE2 and PGF2α) which mediate uterine contractions.<br><br>Dose is typically 50 to 100 mg loading followed by 25 to 50 mg every 4 to 6 hours. Use is limited to under 32 weeks gestation and for less than 48 hours due to risks of premature ductus arteriosus closure, oligohydramnios and necrotising enterocolitis.<br><br>A (Inhibition of cyclooxygenase) is correct because COX inhibition reduces prostaglandin-mediated contractions. B (Calcium channel blockade) is wrong because that is the nifedipine mechanism. C (Beta-receptor activation) is wrong because that is the β-agonist mechanism. D (Oxytocin receptor antagonism) is wrong because that is the atosiban mechanism.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Nonsteroidal Anti-Inflammatory Drugs)</em>`},
    {q:'Which tocolytic drug is most likely to cause maternal hyperglycemia and hypokalemia?',o:['Indomethacin','Terbutaline','Nifedipine','Magnesium sulphate'],a:1,
    e:`Terbutaline (β₂-agonist tocolytic) is the most likely to cause maternal hyperglycaemia. β₂ receptor activation in liver and pancreas increases glycogenolysis, gluconeogenesis and reduces insulin sensitivity, raising blood glucose.<br><br>Other terbutaline side effects from β receptor activation include tachycardia, palpitations, hypokalaemia, pulmonary oedema and rare cardiac arrhythmias. Special caution is needed in diabetic women, who may need increased insulin during terbutaline therapy. Long-term use is avoided.<br><br>B (Terbutaline) is correct because β₂ activation raises blood glucose. A (Magnesium sulphate) is wrong because magnesium does not raise glucose. C (Nifedipine) is wrong because calcium channel blockers do not raise glucose significantly. D (Indomethacin) is wrong because NSAIDs do not raise glucose.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Adrenoceptor Agonists and Sympathomimetic Drugs)</em>`},
    {q:'A woman with preterm labor is treated with magnesium sulphate. Which physiologic effect contributes to uterine relaxation?',o:['Increased prostaglandin synthesis','Increased intracellular sodium','Increased oxytocin receptor activity','Inhibition of calcium entry into smooth muscle cells'],a:3,
    e:`A woman with preterm labour treated with magnesium sulfate has uterine relaxation through inhibition of calcium entry into smooth muscle cells. Magnesium competes with calcium at L-type calcium channels and reduces intracellular calcium availability for contractile machinery.<br><br>Loading dose is typically 4 to 6 g IV over 20 minutes, followed by 1 to 2 g/hour infusion. Toxicity (loss of deep tendon reflexes, respiratory depression) is reversed with calcium gluconate. Magnesium also has fetal neuroprotective effects, reducing cerebral palsy risk in preterm infants.<br><br>D (Inhibition of calcium entry into smooth muscle cells) is correct because magnesium competes with calcium at myometrial channels. A (Activation of beta-receptors) is wrong because that is the β-agonist mechanism. B (Inhibition of cyclooxygenase) is wrong because that is the NSAID mechanism. C (Stimulation of oxytocin receptors) is wrong because that would stimulate contractions.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Antiseizure Drugs)</em>`},
    {q:'Which drug used as a tocolytic may cause oligohydramnios due to reduced fetal urine production?',o:['Indomethacin','Nifedipine','Ritodrine','Magnesium sulphate'],a:0,
    e:`Indomethacin used as a tocolytic may cause oligohydramnios due to reduced fetal renal perfusion and decreased fetal urine production. Prostaglandins maintain fetal renal blood flow; their inhibition reduces glomerular filtration and urine output, depleting amniotic fluid.<br><br>Indomethacin tocolysis is therefore limited to under 32 weeks gestation and for less than 48 hours. Other indomethacin-related fetal effects include premature ductus arteriosus closure (right heart failure) and necrotising enterocolitis in preterm infants. Amniotic fluid index monitoring is needed.<br><br>A (Indomethacin) is correct because COX inhibition reduces fetal renal perfusion and urine output. B (Magnesium sulphate) is wrong because magnesium does not significantly affect fetal renal function. C (Nifedipine) is wrong because calcium channel blockers do not cause oligohydramnios. D (Terbutaline) is wrong because β₂-agonists do not cause oligohydramnios.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics; Chapter: Preterm Labor)</em>`},
    {q:'A drug used in preterm labor inhibits L-type calcium channels and reduces myometrial contractility. Which drug fits this description?',o:['Indomethacin','Terbutaline','Nifedipine','Magnesium sulphate'],a:2,
    e:`A drug used in preterm labour that inhibits L-type calcium channels in myometrial cells is nifedipine. By blocking voltage-gated calcium channels, nifedipine reduces intracellular calcium, myosin light chain phosphorylation and uterine contraction.<br><br>Nifedipine 20 mg orally followed by 10 to 20 mg every 4 to 6 hours is widely used as first-line tocolytic. Side effects include maternal hypotension, headache, flushing and tachycardia. Avoid concurrent use with magnesium sulfate due to synergistic neuromuscular block.<br><br>C (Nifedipine) is correct because it is the L-type Ca²⁺ channel blocker tocolytic. A (Magnesium sulphate) is wrong because magnesium competes with calcium but does not block channels directly. B (Indomethacin) is wrong because it inhibits cyclooxygenase. D (Terbutaline) is wrong because it acts via β₂-adrenergic receptors.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Vasodilators and the Treatment of Angina Pectoris)</em>`},
    {q:'Which adverse maternal effect is most commonly associated with beta-agonist tocolytics?',o:['Maternal tachycardia','Severe bradycardia','Hypothermia','Hypocalcemia'],a:0,
    e:`Maternal tachycardia is the most commonly associated adverse effect of β₂-agonist tocolytics (terbutaline, ritodrine). β₁ receptor cross-activation in the heart causes increased heart rate, palpitations and rare arrhythmias.<br><br>Other β-agonist side effects include hyperglycaemia, hypokalaemia, tremor, anxiety, pulmonary oedema and rare cardiac arrhythmias. Long-term use is avoided due to maternal cardiovascular events. Monitoring of pulse, blood pressure and signs of pulmonary oedema is needed.<br><br>A (Maternal tachycardia) is correct because β receptor activation increases heart rate. B (Bradycardia) is wrong because β-agonists increase, not decrease, heart rate. C (Hypotension) is wrong because while it can occur, tachycardia is more characteristic. D (Hypothermia) is wrong because β-agonists do not lower temperature.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Adrenoceptor Agonists and Sympathomimetic Drugs)</em>`},
    {q:'Which mechanism best explains uterine relaxation produced by β₂-agonist tocolytics?',o:['Decreased cAMP levels','Increased cAMP leading to reduced intracellular calcium','Direct inhibition of prostaglandin synthesis','Activation of calcium channels'],a:1,
    e:`β₂-agonists produce uterine relaxation through increased cAMP leading to reduced intracellular calcium. β₂ receptor activation couples to Gs proteins and adenylyl cyclase, raising cAMP. Increased cAMP activates protein kinase A, which phosphorylates myosin light chain kinase (inactivating it) and reduces intracellular calcium availability.<br><br>Reduced calcium and inactive MLCK prevent actin-myosin cross-bridging, producing relaxation. Examples include terbutaline and ritodrine. Side effects include maternal tachycardia, hyperglycaemia, hypokalaemia and rare pulmonary oedema.<br><br>B (Increased cAMP leading to reduced intracellular calcium) is correct because β₂ activation raises cAMP and lowers calcium. A (Increased calcium influx) is wrong because β₂-agonists reduce, not increase, calcium. C (Direct uterine receptor blockade) is wrong because β-agonists activate, not block, receptors. D (Inhibition of cyclooxygenase) is wrong because that is the NSAID mechanism.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Adrenoceptor Agonists and Sympathomimetic Drugs)</em>`},
    {q:'A patient treated with indomethacin for preterm labor should be monitored for which fetal complication?',o:['Polyhydramnios','Fetal tachycardia','Neural tube defects','Premature closure of ductus arteriosus'],a:3,
    e:`A patient treated with indomethacin for preterm labour should be monitored for premature closure of fetal ductus arteriosus, the most strongly associated fetal complication. Indomethacin inhibits prostaglandin synthesis (especially PGE2 maintaining ductal patency), causing premature closure with right ventricular hypertrophy and pulmonary hypertension.<br><br>Risk increases with use beyond 32 weeks gestation and for more than 48 to 72 hours. Other indomethacin-related fetal effects include oligohydramnios (reduced fetal renal perfusion) and necrotising enterocolitis in preterm infants. Use is therefore limited to under 32 weeks for under 48 hours, with fetal echocardiography monitoring.<br><br>D (Premature closure of ductus arteriosus) is correct because COX inhibition removes prostaglandin maintenance of ductal patency. A (Patent ductus arteriosus) is wrong because indomethacin closes, not opens, the ductus. B (Ventricular septal defect) is wrong because it is unrelated. C (Coarctation of aorta) is wrong because it is unrelated to NSAIDs.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics; Chapter: Preterm Labor)</em>`},
    {q:'Which tocolytic agent acts mainly by inhibiting voltage-gated calcium channels in uterine smooth muscle?',o:['Magnesium sulphate','Indomethacin','Nifedipine','Terbutaline'],a:2,
    e:`Nifedipine acts mainly by inhibiting voltage-gated L-type calcium channels in myometrial cells, reducing intracellular calcium, myosin light chain phosphorylation and uterine contraction.<br><br>Nifedipine 20 mg orally followed by 10 to 20 mg every 4 to 6 hours is widely used as first-line tocolytic. Advantages include oral administration, low cost and good efficacy. Side effects include maternal hypotension, headache, flushing and tachycardia. Avoid with magnesium sulfate.<br><br>C (Nifedipine) is correct because it is the voltage-gated calcium channel blocker. A (Magnesium sulphate) is wrong because magnesium competes with calcium but does not directly block channels. B (Indomethacin) is wrong because it acts on cyclooxygenase. D (Ritodrine) is wrong because it acts on β₂-adrenergic receptors.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Vasodilators and the Treatment of Angina Pectoris)</em>`},
    {q:'Which drug relaxes uterine smooth muscle by stimulating β₂-adrenergic receptors and increasing adenylate cyclase activity?',o:['Magnesium sulphate','Indomethacin','Nifedipine','Ritodrine'],a:3,
    e:`Ritodrine relaxes uterine smooth muscle by stimulating β₂-adrenergic receptors. β₂ receptor activation couples to Gs proteins and adenylyl cyclase, raising cAMP, activating protein kinase A and reducing intracellular calcium for myometrial contraction.<br><br>Ritodrine is largely replaced by terbutaline and other tocolytics due to side effects (tachycardia, palpitations, hyperglycaemia, hypokalaemia, pulmonary oedema). Calcium channel blockers (nifedipine) and oxytocin antagonists (atosiban) are now preferred.<br><br>D (Ritodrine) is correct because it is a β₂-agonist tocolytic. A (Magnesium sulphate) is wrong because magnesium acts via calcium competition. B (Indomethacin) is wrong because it acts on cyclooxygenase. C (Nifedipine) is wrong because it acts on calcium channels.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Adrenoceptor Agonists and Sympathomimetic Drugs)</em>`},
    {q:'Which tocolytic drug should be avoided after 32 weeks gestation due to risk of fetal ductus arteriosus constriction?',o:['Terbutaline','Nifedipine','Indomethacin','Magnesium sulphate'],a:2,
    e:`Indomethacin should be avoided after 32 weeks gestation due to risk of premature closure of fetal ductus arteriosus, oligohydramnios and necrotising enterocolitis in preterm infants. The fetal ductus is more sensitive to prostaglandin inhibition after 32 weeks.<br><br>Indomethacin tocolysis is therefore limited to under 32 weeks gestation and for less than 48 hours. Monitoring includes fetal echocardiography for ductal flow and amniotic fluid index. Other tocolytics (nifedipine, magnesium, terbutaline) are preferred after 32 weeks.<br><br>C (Indomethacin) is correct because COX inhibition risks ductal closure after 32 weeks. A (Magnesium sulphate) is wrong because magnesium can be used through to delivery. B (Nifedipine) is wrong because it is used until 34 weeks. D (Terbutaline) is wrong because it can be used until 34 weeks.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics; Chapter: Preterm Labor)</em>`},
    {q:'Which drug used for tocolysis also has anticonvulsant properties in obstetrics?',o:['Magnesium sulphate','Nifedipine','Terbutaline','Indomethacin'],a:0,
    e:`Magnesium sulfate is the tocolytic drug that also has anticonvulsant properties. It is the drug of choice for seizure prophylaxis in severe pre-eclampsia and treatment of eclampsia, in addition to its tocolytic and fetal neuroprotective effects.<br><br>Mechanism involves NMDA receptor antagonism, calcium channel modulation and cerebral vasodilation. Loading dose is typically 4 to 6 g IV over 20 minutes, followed by 1 to 2 g/hour infusion. Toxicity (loss of deep tendon reflexes, respiratory depression) is reversed with calcium gluconate.<br><br>A (Magnesium sulphate) is correct because magnesium has both tocolytic and anticonvulsant properties. B (Indomethacin) is wrong because it does not have anticonvulsant effects. C (Nifedipine) is wrong because it does not have anticonvulsant effects. D (Terbutaline) is wrong because it does not have anticonvulsant effects.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Antiseizure Drugs)</em>`},
    {q:'Which class of drugs reduces uterine contractions by decreasing intracellular calcium concentration through β-receptor stimulation?',o:['NSAIDs','Beta agonists','Calcium channel blockers','Magnesium salts'],a:1,
    e:`Beta-agonists (terbutaline, ritodrine) reduce uterine contractions by decreasing intracellular calcium in myometrial cells. β₂ receptor activation raises cAMP, which activates protein kinase A and reduces calcium availability for the contractile machinery.<br><br>Examples include terbutaline (0.25 mg SC every 20 to 30 minutes for acute tocolysis) and ritodrine. Side effects from β receptor activation include tachycardia, hyperglycaemia, hypokalaemia and rare pulmonary oedema. Long-term use is avoided due to maternal cardiovascular events.<br><br>B (Beta agonists) is correct because β₂-agonists reduce intracellular calcium via cAMP elevation. A (Calcium channel blockers) is wrong because while they reduce calcium, the question specifies decreased calcium without specifying mechanism class. C (NSAIDs) is wrong because they act via prostaglandin inhibition. D (Magnesium sulphate) is wrong because magnesium acts via calcium competition.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Adrenoceptor Agonists and Sympathomimetic Drugs)</em>`},
    {q:'A woman receiving nifedipine for tocolysis develops headache and flushing. What pharmacologic property explains these symptoms?',o:['Increased calcium entry','Increased prostaglandin synthesis','Increased catecholamine release','Peripheral vasodilation'],a:3,
    e:`A woman receiving nifedipine for tocolysis developing headache and flushing has peripheral vasodilation from calcium channel blockade in vascular smooth muscle. Nifedipine reduces systemic vascular resistance, lowering blood pressure and producing reflex tachycardia.<br><br>Maternal blood pressure should be monitored during nifedipine tocolysis. Hypotension may be treated with IV fluids and positioning. Reflex tachycardia is also common. Avoid concurrent use with magnesium sulfate due to synergistic neuromuscular block and severe hypotension.<br><br>D (Peripheral vasodilation) is correct because nifedipine reduces vascular resistance. A (Increased preload) is wrong because nifedipine reduces preload. B (Direct cardiac stimulation) is wrong because nifedipine does not directly stimulate the heart. C (Increased oxytocin release) is wrong because oxytocin does not cause headache and flushing.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Vasodilators and the Treatment of Angina Pectoris)</em>`},
    {q:'Which tocolytic drug is most associated with pulmonary edema as a rare maternal complication?',o:['Ritodrine','Indomethacin','Nifedipine','Magnesium sulphate'],a:0,
    e:`Ritodrine (β₂-agonist tocolytic) is most associated with pulmonary oedema, particularly with concurrent corticosteroids, multiple gestation, fluid overload or prolonged infusion. β-agonists increase capillary permeability and intravascular volume retention, predisposing to pulmonary oedema.<br><br>Other β-agonist side effects include tachycardia, palpitations, hyperglycaemia, hypokalaemia and rare cardiac arrhythmias. Ritodrine is largely replaced by safer tocolytics. Monitoring of fluid balance, oxygen saturation and chest examination is essential during β-agonist tocolysis.<br><br>A (Ritodrine) is correct because β₂-agonists are most associated with pulmonary oedema. B (Magnesium sulphate) is wrong because while magnesium can rarely cause pulmonary oedema, ritodrine is more characteristic. C (Nifedipine) is wrong because pulmonary oedema is not a typical effect. D (Indomethacin) is wrong because it does not cause pulmonary oedema.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics; Chapter: Preterm Labor)</em>`},
    {q:'Which mechanism explains the reduction of uterine contractions by indomethacin?',o:['Activation of β₂ receptors','Cyclooxygenase inhibition reducing prostaglandins','Calcium channel blockade','Magnesium-mediated neuromuscular blockade'],a:1,
    e:`Indomethacin reduces uterine contractions through cyclooxygenase inhibition reducing prostaglandins. Both COX-1 and COX-2 are inhibited (non-selective), reducing PGE2 and PGF2α synthesis which mediate uterine contractions.<br><br>Dose is typically 50 to 100 mg loading followed by 25 to 50 mg every 4 to 6 hours. Use is limited to under 32 weeks gestation and for less than 48 hours due to risks of premature ductus arteriosus closure, oligohydramnios and necrotising enterocolitis.<br><br>B (Cyclooxygenase inhibition reducing prostaglandins) is correct because COX inhibition is the indomethacin mechanism. A (Calcium channel blockade) is wrong because that is the nifedipine mechanism. C (Beta-receptor activation) is wrong because that is the β-agonist mechanism. D (Oxytocin receptor antagonism) is wrong because that is the atosiban mechanism.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Nonsteroidal Anti-Inflammatory Drugs)</em>`},
    {q:'A patient receiving magnesium sulphate for tocolysis develops loss of deep tendon reflexes. What is the likely cause?',o:['Hypokalemia','Hypocalcemia','Magnesium toxicity','Hyperglycemia'],a:2,
    e:`A patient receiving magnesium sulfate for tocolysis developing loss of deep tendon reflexes, respiratory depression and bradycardia has magnesium toxicity. Toxic effects appear at serum magnesium levels above 4 mmol/L.<br><br>Loss of deep tendon reflexes (5 to 10 mg/dL) is the earliest sign and an indication to stop or reduce the infusion. Respiratory depression occurs above 12 mg/dL, cardiac arrest above 25 mg/dL. Treatment is immediate stop of magnesium, IV calcium gluconate (1 g over 5 to 10 minutes) and respiratory support.<br><br>C (Magnesium toxicity) is correct because the clinical features are characteristic. A (Hyperkalemia) is wrong because magnesium does not raise potassium. B (Hyperglycemia) is wrong because magnesium does not raise glucose. D (Anaphylaxis) is wrong because the features are not anaphylactic (no urticaria, no hypotension as primary feature).<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics; Chapter: Preterm Labor)</em>`},
    {q:'Which tocolytic drug works by blocking calcium entry into smooth muscle and is also commonly used as an antihypertensive?',o:['Nifedipine','Indomethacin','Magnesium sulphate','Terbutaline'],a:0,
    e:`Nifedipine works by blocking calcium entry into smooth muscle cells. It blocks voltage-gated L-type calcium channels in myometrial cells, reducing intracellular calcium, myosin light chain phosphorylation and uterine contraction.<br><br>Nifedipine 20 mg orally followed by 10 to 20 mg every 4 to 6 hours is widely used as first-line tocolytic. Advantages include oral administration, low cost and good efficacy. Side effects include maternal hypotension, headache, flushing and tachycardia. Avoid with magnesium sulfate.<br><br>A (Nifedipine) is correct because it blocks L-type calcium channels in myometrial cells. B (Magnesium sulphate) is wrong because magnesium competes with calcium but does not directly block channels. C (Indomethacin) is wrong because it acts via cyclooxygenase. D (Terbutaline) is wrong because it acts via β₂-adrenergic receptors.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Vasodilators and the Treatment of Angina Pectoris)</em>`},
    {q:'A woman at 30 weeks gestation receives a β₂-agonist tocolytic. Which intracellular change directly leads to uterine relaxation?',o:['Decreased cAMP levels','Increased cAMP leading to reduced myometrial contractility','Increased intracellular sodium','Increased prostaglandin synthesis'],a:1,
    e:`A woman at 30 weeks receiving a β₂-agonist tocolytic has uterine relaxation through increased cAMP leading to reduced myometrial contractility. β₂ receptor activation couples to Gs proteins and adenylyl cyclase, raising cAMP.<br><br>Increased cAMP activates protein kinase A, which phosphorylates myosin light chain kinase (inactivating it) and reduces intracellular calcium availability. Reduced calcium and inactive MLCK prevent actin-myosin cross-bridging. Side effects include tachycardia, hyperglycaemia, hypokalaemia and rare pulmonary oedema.<br><br>B (Increased cAMP leading to reduced myometrial contractility) is correct because β₂ activation raises cAMP and reduces contraction. A (Increased calcium influx) is wrong because β₂-agonists reduce calcium. C (Inhibition of cyclooxygenase) is wrong because that is the NSAID mechanism. D (Activation of oxytocin receptors) is wrong because that would stimulate contractions.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Adrenoceptor Agonists and Sympathomimetic Drugs)</em>`},
    {q:'A 28-year-old woman at 29 weeks gestation presents with regular uterine contractions. A tocolytic is administered that increases cAMP in uterine smooth muscle leading to relaxation. Which drug class is responsible for this effect?',o:['Calcium channel blockers','Magnesium salts','NSAIDs','Beta-adrenergic agonists'],a:3,
    e:`A 28-year-old at 29 weeks with regular preterm contractions may be treated with beta-adrenergic agonists (terbutaline, ritodrine) for tocolysis. β₂ receptor activation raises cAMP, reducing intracellular calcium and producing uterine relaxation.<br><br>Terbutaline 0.25 mg SC every 20 to 30 minutes (max 4 doses) is given for acute tocolysis. Side effects include maternal tachycardia, hyperglycaemia, hypokalaemia and rare pulmonary oedema. Calcium channel blockers (nifedipine) and magnesium sulfate are preferred first-line tocolytics in many guidelines.<br><br>D (Beta-adrenergic agonists) is correct because β₂-agonists are an established tocolytic class. A (Oxytocin) is wrong because it is a uterotonic, not a tocolytic. B (Misoprostol) is wrong because it stimulates contractions. C (Carboprost) is wrong because it is a uterotonic for postpartum haemorrhage.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Adrenoceptor Agonists and Sympathomimetic Drugs)</em>`},
    {q:'Which tocolytic drug inhibits prostaglandin synthesis by blocking cyclooxygenase activity in the decidua and fetal membranes?',o:['Nifedipine','Terbutaline','Indomethacin','Magnesium sulphate'],a:2,
    e:`Indomethacin inhibits prostaglandin synthesis by blocking cyclooxygenase (COX-1 and COX-2). Reduced prostaglandin (PGE2 and PGF2α) synthesis decreases uterine contractions, providing tocolytic effect.<br><br>Dose is typically 50 to 100 mg loading followed by 25 to 50 mg every 4 to 6 hours. Use is limited to under 32 weeks gestation and for less than 48 hours due to risks of premature ductus arteriosus closure, oligohydramnios and necrotising enterocolitis.<br><br>C (Indomethacin) is correct because it is the COX-inhibiting tocolytic. A (Nifedipine) is wrong because it blocks calcium channels. B (Magnesium sulphate) is wrong because magnesium competes with calcium. D (Terbutaline) is wrong because it acts on β₂-adrenergic receptors.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Nonsteroidal Anti-Inflammatory Drugs)</em>`},
    {q:'A woman treated with magnesium sulphate for preterm labor develops respiratory depression. Which mechanism explains this complication?',o:['Increased prostaglandin synthesis','Increased intracellular calcium','Beta-adrenergic stimulation','Neuromuscular blockade due to elevated magnesium levels'],a:3,
    e:`A woman treated with magnesium sulfate for preterm labour developing muscle weakness and hyporeflexia has neuromuscular blockade due to elevated magnesium levels. Magnesium competes with calcium at neuromuscular junctions, reducing acetylcholine release and blocking neuromuscular transmission.<br><br>Loss of deep tendon reflexes (serum Mg 5 to 10 mg/dL) is the earliest sign and an indication to stop or reduce the infusion. Respiratory depression occurs above 12 mg/dL, cardiac arrest above 25 mg/dL. Treatment is immediate stop of magnesium, IV calcium gluconate (1 g over 5 to 10 minutes) and respiratory support.<br><br>D (Neuromuscular blockade due to elevated magnesium levels) is correct because magnesium reduces acetylcholine release at the neuromuscular junction. A (Hyperkalemia) is wrong because magnesium does not raise potassium. B (Hyperglycemia) is wrong because magnesium does not raise glucose. C (Anaphylaxis) is wrong because the features are not anaphylactic.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics; Chapter: Preterm Labor)</em>`},
    {q:'Which tocolytic drug reduces uterine contractions by inhibiting L-type calcium channels in smooth muscle cells?',o:['Nifedipine','Ritodrine','Indomethacin','Magnesium sulphate'],a:0,
    e:`Nifedipine reduces uterine contractions by inhibiting calcium entry into myometrial cells via blockade of voltage-gated L-type calcium channels. Reduced intracellular calcium decreases myosin light chain phosphorylation and prevents actin-myosin cross-bridging.<br><br>Nifedipine 20 mg orally followed by 10 to 20 mg every 4 to 6 hours is widely used as first-line tocolytic. Side effects include maternal hypotension, headache, flushing and tachycardia. Avoid concurrent use with magnesium sulfate due to synergistic neuromuscular block.<br><br>A (Nifedipine) is correct because it blocks L-type calcium channels in myometrial cells. B (Magnesium sulphate) is wrong because magnesium competes with calcium but does not directly block channels. C (Indomethacin) is wrong because it acts via cyclooxygenase. D (Terbutaline) is wrong because it acts via β₂-adrenergic receptors.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Vasodilators and the Treatment of Angina Pectoris)</em>`},
    {q:'A patient treated with indomethacin for preterm labor is monitored by ultrasound for decreased amniotic fluid volume. What is the mechanism behind this complication?',o:['Increased fetal renal blood flow','Increased uteroplacental blood flow','Reduced fetal urine production due to prostaglandin inhibition','Increased fetal cardiac output'],a:2,
    e:`A patient treated with indomethacin for preterm labour is monitored for oligohydramnios from reduced fetal urine production due to prostaglandin inhibition. Prostaglandins maintain fetal renal blood flow; their inhibition reduces glomerular filtration and urine output, depleting amniotic fluid.<br><br>Other indomethacin-related fetal effects include premature ductus arteriosus closure (right heart failure) and necrotising enterocolitis in preterm infants. Use is limited to under 32 weeks gestation and for less than 48 hours. Amniotic fluid index and fetal echocardiography monitoring are essential.<br><br>C (Reduced fetal urine production due to prostaglandin inhibition) is correct because COX inhibition reduces fetal renal perfusion. A (Increased fetal swallowing) is wrong because indomethacin does not affect fetal swallowing. B (Decreased fetal cardiac output) is wrong because the primary mechanism is renal not cardiac. D (Increased amniotic fluid production) is wrong because indomethacin reduces, not increases, amniotic fluid.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics; Chapter: Preterm Labor)</em>`},
    {q:'Which maternal adverse effect is most commonly associated with beta-agonist tocolytic therapy?',o:['Hypotension','Tachycardia','Bradycardia','Hypocalcemia'],a:1,
    e:`Tachycardia is the most commonly associated maternal adverse effect of β₂-agonist tocolytics (terbutaline, ritodrine). β₁ receptor cross-activation in the heart causes increased heart rate, palpitations and rare arrhythmias.<br><br>Other β-agonist side effects include hyperglycaemia, hypokalaemia, tremor, anxiety, pulmonary oedema and rare cardiac arrhythmias. Long-term use is avoided due to maternal cardiovascular events. Monitoring of pulse, blood pressure and signs of pulmonary oedema is needed.<br><br>B (Tachycardia) is correct because β receptor activation increases heart rate. A (Bradycardia) is wrong because β-agonists increase, not decrease, heart rate. C (Hypothermia) is wrong because β-agonists do not lower temperature. D (Hyperkalemia) is wrong because β-agonists cause hypokalaemia, not hyperkalaemia.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Adrenoceptor Agonists and Sympathomimetic Drugs)</em>`},
    {q:'A drug used for tocolysis works by reducing acetylcholine release at neuromuscular junctions and decreasing calcium entry into smooth muscle cells. Which drug fits this description?',o:['Terbutaline','Nifedipine','Indomethacin','Magnesium sulphate'],a:3,
    e:`A drug used for tocolysis that reduces acetylcholine release at the neuromuscular junction is magnesium sulfate. Magnesium competes with calcium at neuromuscular junctions, reducing presynaptic calcium influx and acetylcholine release.<br><br>This neuromuscular blockade explains the loss of deep tendon reflexes and respiratory depression of magnesium toxicity. Loading dose for tocolysis is typically 4 to 6 g IV over 20 minutes, followed by 1 to 2 g/hour infusion. Toxicity is reversed with calcium gluconate.<br><br>D (Magnesium sulphate) is correct because magnesium reduces acetylcholine release at the neuromuscular junction. A (Nifedipine) is wrong because it blocks myometrial calcium channels, not neuromuscular junction. B (Indomethacin) is wrong because it acts on cyclooxygenase. C (Terbutaline) is wrong because it acts on β₂-adrenergic receptors.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Antiseizure Drugs)</em>`},
    {q:'Which tocolytic drug is most appropriate in a patient with preterm labor and coexisting hypertension due to its antihypertensive effect?',o:['Terbutaline','Nifedipine','Indomethacin','Ritodrine'],a:1,
    e:`Nifedipine is the most appropriate tocolytic in a patient with preterm labour and asthma because beta-agonists (terbutaline, ritodrine) are relatively contraindicated in asthma, indomethacin should be avoided after 32 weeks, and magnesium sulfate may be problematic with concurrent asthma medications.<br><br>Nifedipine has no contraindication in asthma and is widely used as first-line tocolytic. Dose is 20 mg orally followed by 10 to 20 mg every 4 to 6 hours. Side effects include maternal hypotension, headache, flushing and tachycardia.<br><br>B (Nifedipine) is correct because it has no contraindication in asthma. A (Terbutaline) is wrong because while it is also a bronchodilator, β-agonists generally are avoided as tocolytics in asthma. C (Indomethacin) is wrong because NSAIDs may worsen asthma. D (Magnesium sulphate) is wrong because while it can be used, nifedipine is preferred in asthma.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics; Chapter: Preterm Labor)</em>`},
    {q:'A woman treated with β₂-agonist tocolytics develops hyperglycemia and hypokalemia. Which drug is most likely responsible?',o:['Indomethacin','Magnesium sulphate','Terbutaline','Nifedipine'],a:2,
    e:`A woman treated with β₂-agonist tocolytics (terbutaline, ritodrine) develops hyperglycaemia. β₂ receptor activation in liver and pancreas increases glycogenolysis, gluconeogenesis and reduces insulin sensitivity, raising blood glucose.<br><br>Other β-agonist side effects include tachycardia, palpitations, hypokalaemia, pulmonary oedema and rare cardiac arrhythmias. Special caution is needed in diabetic women, who may need increased insulin during β-agonist therapy. Long-term use is avoided due to maternal cardiovascular events.<br><br>C (Terbutaline) is correct because β₂ activation raises blood glucose. A (Magnesium sulphate) is wrong because magnesium does not raise glucose. B (Indomethacin) is wrong because NSAIDs do not raise glucose. D (Nifedipine) is wrong because calcium channel blockers do not raise glucose significantly.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Adrenoceptor Agonists and Sympathomimetic Drugs)</em>`},
    {q:'Which mechanism best explains the uterine relaxation effect of calcium channel blockers used as tocolytics?',o:['Reduction of intracellular calcium in myometrial cells','Inhibition of prostaglandin synthesis','Activation of adenylate cyclase','Increased acetylcholine release'],a:0,
    e:`The uterine relaxation effect of nifedipine is best explained by reduction of intracellular calcium in myometrial cells. Nifedipine blocks voltage-gated L-type calcium channels, reducing calcium influx, myosin light chain phosphorylation and actin-myosin cross-bridging.<br><br>Nifedipine 20 mg orally followed by 10 to 20 mg every 4 to 6 hours is widely used as first-line tocolytic. Side effects include maternal hypotension, headache, flushing and tachycardia. Avoid concurrent use with magnesium sulfate due to synergistic neuromuscular block.<br><br>A (Reduction of intracellular calcium in myometrial cells) is correct because L-type Ca²⁺ blockade reduces myometrial calcium. B (Increased prostaglandin synthesis) is wrong because prostaglandins stimulate contractions. C (Stimulation of beta-receptors) is wrong because that would relax via cAMP, not directly via calcium. D (Oxytocin receptor activation) is wrong because that would stimulate contractions.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Vasodilators and the Treatment of Angina Pectoris)</em>`},
    {q:'A 30-year-old pregnant woman at 34 weeks gestation presents with blood pressure of 170/110 mmHg. Which antihypertensive drug is most commonly used intravenously for rapid control of severe hypertension in pregnancy?',o:['Methyldopa','Atenolol','Hydralazine','Losartan'],a:2,
    e:`A 30-year-old at 34 weeks with severe hypertension may be treated with hydralazine, a direct arteriolar vasodilator given as 5 to 10 mg IV boluses every 20 to 30 minutes. It lowers systemic vascular resistance and is widely used for severe hypertensive emergencies in pregnancy.<br><br>Hydralazine causes reflex tachycardia and may cause maternal headache, nausea, palpitations and a lupus-like syndrome on chronic use. IV labetalol and oral nifedipine are also first-line for severe hypertension in pregnancy.<br><br>C (Hydralazine) is correct because it is an established IV first-line agent for severe hypertension. A (Captopril) is wrong because ACE inhibitors are contraindicated. B (Losartan) is wrong because angiotensin receptor blockers are contraindicated. D (Enalapril) is wrong because it is also an ACE inhibitor.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics; Chapter: Hypertensive Disorders)</em>`},
    {q:'Which antihypertensive drug acts as a centrally acting α₂-adrenergic agonist and is commonly used for chronic hypertension in pregnancy?',o:['Hydralazine','Methyldopa','Nifedipine','Lisinopril'],a:1,
    e:`Methyldopa is the centrally acting α₂-adrenergic agonist used for chronic hypertension in pregnancy. It is converted to α-methylnorepinephrine which acts on central α₂ receptors, decreasing sympathetic outflow from the CNS.<br><br>Methyldopa has the longest safety record in pregnancy. Side effects include sedation, depression and rarely positive Coombs test or haemolytic anaemia. Labetalol and nifedipine are also widely used as first-line options. ACE inhibitors and angiotensin receptor blockers are contraindicated.<br><br>B (Methyldopa) is correct because it is the centrally acting α₂-agonist used in pregnancy. A (Hydralazine) is wrong because it is a direct arteriolar vasodilator. C (Nifedipine) is wrong because it is a calcium channel blocker. D (Labetalol) is wrong because it is a combined α and β blocker.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Antihypertensive Agents)</em>`},
    {q:'A pregnant woman with hypertension is treated with nifedipine. What is the primary mechanism of action of this drug?',o:['Calcium channel blockade','β₁-receptor blockade','ACE inhibition','Angiotensin receptor blockade'],a:0,
    e:`A pregnant woman with hypertension treated with nifedipine has blood pressure lowered through calcium channel blockade in vascular smooth muscle. Nifedipine blocks L-type calcium channels, reducing intracellular calcium and producing vasodilation.<br><br>Nifedipine 10 to 20 mg PO every 6 to 8 hours is widely used for chronic and severe hypertension in pregnancy. Side effects include headache, flushing, peripheral oedema and reflex tachycardia. Avoid concurrent use with magnesium sulfate due to synergistic neuromuscular block.<br><br>A (Calcium channel blockade) is correct because nifedipine blocks L-type calcium channels. B (Beta-receptor blockade) is wrong because that is the beta-blocker mechanism. C (ACE inhibition) is wrong because that is the ACE inhibitor mechanism. D (Direct vasodilation independent of calcium channels) is wrong because nifedipine\'s vasodilation is calcium-channel-mediated.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Vasodilators and the Treatment of Angina Pectoris)</em>`},
    {q:'Which antihypertensive drug is contraindicated during pregnancy because of risk of fetal renal dysgenesis?',o:['Methyldopa','Labetalol','Hydralazine','Enalapril'],a:3,
    e:`Enalapril (an ACE inhibitor) is contraindicated during pregnancy because it causes fetal renal dysgenesis and the ACE inhibitor fetopathy: oligohydramnios, pulmonary hypoplasia, calvarial hypoplasia and limb contractures. Risk is greatest in the second and third trimesters.<br><br>Angiotensin receptor blockers cause similar effects and are also contraindicated. Methyldopa, labetalol and nifedipine are first-line antihypertensives in pregnancy. Hydralazine is used IV for hypertensive emergencies.<br><br>D (Enalapril) is correct because ACE inhibitors are contraindicated in pregnancy. A (Methyldopa) is wrong because it is the most established safe first-line agent. B (Labetalol) is wrong because it is widely used in pregnancy. C (Hydralazine) is wrong because it is used for severe hypertension.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics; Chapter: Hypertensive Disorders)</em>`},
    {q:'A pregnant woman with severe preeclampsia requires rapid blood pressure control. Which drug acts by direct relaxation of arteriolar smooth muscle?',o:['Methyldopa','Atenolol','Hydralazine','Propranolol'],a:2,
    e:`A pregnant woman with severe pre-eclampsia requiring rapid blood pressure control is treated with hydralazine 5 to 10 mg IV bolus, repeated every 20 to 30 minutes as needed. Hydralazine is a direct arteriolar vasodilator that rapidly lowers systemic vascular resistance.<br><br>IV labetalol and oral nifedipine are also first-line for severe hypertension in pregnancy. Hydralazine causes reflex tachycardia and may cause maternal headache, nausea, palpitations and a lupus-like syndrome on chronic use. The aim is to lower blood pressure to <160/110 mmHg without compromising uteroplacental perfusion.<br><br>C (Hydralazine) is correct because it is an established IV first-line agent for severe hypertension. A (Captopril) is wrong because ACE inhibitors are contraindicated. B (Losartan) is wrong because ARBs are contraindicated. D (Enalapril) is wrong because it is an ACE inhibitor.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics; Chapter: Hypertensive Disorders)</em>`},
    {q:'Which antihypertensive drug blocks both α₁ and β-adrenergic receptors and is commonly used in pregnancy?',o:['Propranolol','Atenolol','Metoprolol','Labetalol'],a:3,
    e:`Labetalol blocks both α₁ and β-adrenergic receptors. The α₁ blockade causes vasodilation and reduces systemic vascular resistance. The β-blockade reduces heart rate and cardiac output, preventing reflex tachycardia.<br><br>Labetalol is widely used for chronic and severe hypertension in pregnancy. Oral dose is 100 to 400 mg twice or three times daily; IV dose is 20 mg over 2 minutes, doubled every 10 minutes (max 220 mg). Side effects include orthostatic hypotension, fatigue, bronchospasm in asthmatics and rare hepatotoxicity.<br><br>D (Labetalol) is correct because it is a combined α₁ and β-blocker. A (Methyldopa) is wrong because it is a centrally acting α₂-agonist. B (Hydralazine) is wrong because it is a direct arteriolar vasodilator. C (Nifedipine) is wrong because it is a calcium channel blocker.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Adrenoceptor Antagonist Drugs)</em>`},
    {q:'A woman with pregnancy-induced hypertension is started on methyldopa. What is the primary pharmacologic effect of this drug?',o:['Peripheral vasodilation via calcium channel blockade','Reduction of sympathetic outflow from the CNS','ACE inhibition','Increased renin release'],a:1,
    e:`A woman with pregnancy-induced hypertension started on methyldopa has blood pressure lowered through reduction of sympathetic outflow from the CNS. Methyldopa is converted to α-methylnorepinephrine which acts on central α₂ receptors in the brainstem, reducing sympathetic outflow.<br><br>Methyldopa has the longest safety record in pregnancy. Side effects include sedation, depression and rarely positive Coombs test or haemolytic anaemia. It does not affect uteroplacental perfusion. Other antihypertensives (labetalol, nifedipine) are also widely used.<br><br>B (Reduction of sympathetic outflow from the CNS) is correct because methyldopa\'s central α₂-agonism reduces sympathetic outflow. A (Direct arteriolar vasodilation) is wrong because that is the hydralazine mechanism. C (Calcium channel blockade) is wrong because that is the nifedipine mechanism. D (ACE inhibition) is wrong because that is the ACE inhibitor mechanism.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Antihypertensive Agents)</em>`},
    {q:'Which antihypertensive drug is associated with a risk of fetal growth restriction when used during pregnancy?',o:['Atenolol','Methyldopa','Hydralazine','Labetalol'],a:0,
    e:`Atenolol is associated with a risk of fetal growth restriction in pregnancy when used long-term, particularly when started in the first trimester. The mechanism may involve reduced uteroplacental perfusion from beta-blockade.<br><br>Labetalol (combined α₁ and β blockade) is preferred over atenolol because it has less effect on uteroplacental perfusion and lower fetal growth restriction risk. Methyldopa, nifedipine and hydralazine are also first-line options. ACE inhibitors and ARBs are contraindicated.<br><br>A (Atenolol) is correct because of its association with fetal growth restriction. B (Methyldopa) is wrong because it does not cause growth restriction. C (Nifedipine) is wrong because it is not associated with growth restriction. D (Hydralazine) is wrong because it does not cause growth restriction.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics; Chapter: Hypertensive Disorders)</em>`},
    {q:'A patient with preeclampsia receives nifedipine. Which physiologic effect contributes to its antihypertensive action?',o:['Increased sodium excretion','Increased sympathetic tone','Peripheral arterial vasodilation','Increased renin secretion'],a:2,
    e:`A patient with pre-eclampsia receiving nifedipine has blood pressure lowered through peripheral arterial vasodilation. Nifedipine blocks L-type calcium channels in vascular smooth muscle, reducing intracellular calcium and producing vasodilation.<br><br>Nifedipine 10 to 20 mg PO every 6 to 8 hours is widely used for chronic and severe hypertension in pregnancy. Side effects include headache, flushing, peripheral oedema and reflex tachycardia. Avoid concurrent use with magnesium sulfate due to synergistic neuromuscular block.<br><br>C (Peripheral arterial vasodilation) is correct because nifedipine causes calcium-channel-mediated vasodilation. A (Increased cardiac output) is wrong because nifedipine reduces, not increases, cardiac output. B (Increased venous return) is wrong because nifedipine reduces preload. D (Direct cardiac stimulation) is wrong because nifedipine does not directly stimulate the heart.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Vasodilators and the Treatment of Angina Pectoris)</em>`},
    {q:'Which antihypertensive drug used in pregnancy works by reducing systemic vascular resistance through direct arteriolar dilation?',o:['Methyldopa','Hydralazine','Atenolol','Propranolol'],a:1,
    e:`Hydralazine works by reducing peripheral arterial resistance through direct arteriolar vasodilation. The exact mechanism involves activation of guanylyl cyclase, increased cGMP and smooth muscle relaxation in arterioles.<br><br>Hydralazine 5 to 10 mg IV boluses every 20 to 30 minutes is used for severe hypertension in pregnancy. Side effects include reflex tachycardia, headache, nausea, palpitations and a lupus-like syndrome on chronic use. IV labetalol and oral nifedipine are also first-line for severe hypertension.<br><br>B (Hydralazine) is correct because it is the direct arteriolar vasodilator. A (Methyldopa) is wrong because it acts centrally on α₂ receptors. C (Atenolol) is wrong because it blocks β receptors. D (Captopril) is wrong because it is an ACE inhibitor and contraindicated.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Vasodilators and the Treatment of Angina Pectoris)</em>`},
    {q:'A pregnant woman with chronic hypertension is treated with labetalol. Which receptors are primarily blocked by this drug?',o:['Dopamine receptors','Muscarinic receptors','β₁ receptors only','α₁ and β receptors'],a:3,
    e:`A pregnant woman with chronic hypertension treated with labetalol has both α₁ and β receptors blocked. The α₁ blockade causes vasodilation; the β-blockade reduces heart rate and prevents reflex tachycardia.<br><br>Labetalol is widely used for chronic and severe hypertension in pregnancy due to safety, lack of fetal effects and minimal effect on uteroplacental perfusion. Oral dose is 100 to 400 mg twice or three times daily; IV dose is 20 mg over 2 minutes, doubled every 10 minutes (max 220 mg).<br><br>D (α₁ and β receptors) is correct because labetalol is a combined α₁ and β-blocker. A (Calcium channels only) is wrong because that is the nifedipine mechanism. B (ACE only) is wrong because that is the ACE inhibitor mechanism. C (α₂ receptors only) is wrong because that is the methyldopa target.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Adrenoceptor Antagonist Drugs)</em>`},
    {q:'Which antihypertensive drug lowers blood pressure by reducing central sympathetic outflow through α₂ receptor stimulation?',o:['Methyldopa','Nifedipine','Hydralazine','Propranolol'],a:0,
    e:`Methyldopa lowers blood pressure by reducing sympathetic outflow from the CNS. Methyldopa is converted to α-methylnorepinephrine which acts on central α₂ receptors in the brainstem, reducing sympathetic outflow to peripheral vasculature and heart.<br><br>Methyldopa has the longest safety record in pregnancy. Side effects include sedation, depression and rarely positive Coombs test or haemolytic anaemia. It does not affect uteroplacental perfusion. Labetalol and nifedipine are also widely used as first-line options.<br><br>A (Methyldopa) is correct because central α₂-agonism reduces sympathetic outflow. B (Hydralazine) is wrong because it is a direct arteriolar vasodilator. C (Nifedipine) is wrong because it is a calcium channel blocker. D (Labetalol) is wrong because it is a combined α and β-blocker.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Antihypertensive Agents)</em>`},
    {q:'A patient treated with hydralazine develops reflex tachycardia. What is the primary cause of this effect?',o:['Increased renin inhibition','Direct stimulation of β receptors','Increased sympathetic activity due to vasodilation','Reduced cardiac output'],a:2,
    e:`A patient treated with hydralazine developing reflex tachycardia has increased sympathetic activity due to vasodilation. Direct arteriolar vasodilation reduces blood pressure, triggering baroreceptor-mediated sympathetic activation and increasing heart rate.<br><br>Reflex tachycardia is a common hydralazine side effect, particularly with rapid or large doses. Combination with a beta-blocker (atenolol, metoprolol) or labetalol blunts the reflex response. Hydralazine also causes headache, nausea, palpitations and a lupus-like syndrome on chronic use.<br><br>C (Increased sympathetic activity due to vasodilation) is correct because baroreceptor reflex causes tachycardia after vasodilation. A (Decreased cardiac output) is wrong because cardiac output increases (not decreases) with reflex tachycardia. B (Direct cardiac stimulation by hydralazine) is wrong because hydralazine does not directly stimulate the heart. D (Increased oxytocin release) is wrong because hydralazine does not affect oxytocin.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Vasodilators and the Treatment of Angina Pectoris)</em>`},
    {q:'Which antihypertensive drug class is contraindicated in pregnancy due to risk of fetal skull hypoplasia and renal failure?',o:['ACE inhibitors','Beta blockers','Central α₂ agonists','Calcium channel blockers'],a:0,
    e:`ACE inhibitors are contraindicated in pregnancy because they cause fetal renal dysgenesis and the ACE inhibitor fetopathy: oligohydramnios, pulmonary hypoplasia, calvarial hypoplasia and limb contractures. Risk is greatest in the second and third trimesters.<br><br>Angiotensin receptor blockers cause similar effects and are also contraindicated. Methyldopa, labetalol and nifedipine are first-line antihypertensives in pregnancy. Hydralazine is used IV for hypertensive emergencies.<br><br>A (ACE inhibitors) is correct because of the established fetal renal failure risk. B (Calcium channel blockers) is wrong because they are widely used in pregnancy. C (Beta-blockers) is wrong because labetalol and other beta-blockers are widely used. D (Centrally acting α₂-agonists) is wrong because methyldopa is the gold standard.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics; Chapter: Hypertensive Disorders)</em>`},
    {q:'A pregnant patient with hypertension is prescribed labetalol. What is the main advantage of labetalol in pregnancy?',o:['Strong diuretic effect','Combined α and β blockade with minimal effect on uteroplacental blood flow','Potent ACE inhibition','Prostaglandin inhibition'],a:1,
    e:`A pregnant patient with hypertension prescribed labetalol benefits from combined α and β blockade with minimal effect on uteroplacental perfusion. The α₁ blockade vasodilates while the β-blockade reduces heart rate, providing balanced blood pressure control.<br><br>Labetalol is widely used for chronic and severe hypertension in pregnancy due to safety, lack of fetal effects and minimal effect on uteroplacental perfusion (unlike pure beta-blockers like atenolol which are associated with fetal growth restriction). Side effects include orthostatic hypotension, fatigue and bronchospasm in asthmatics.<br><br>B (Combined α and β blockade with minimal effect on uteroplacental perfusion) is correct because labetalol\'s combined action preserves uteroplacental flow. A (Pure beta-blockade reducing cardiac output) is wrong because labetalol has alpha activity too. C (ACE inhibition) is wrong because labetalol is not an ACE inhibitor. D (Calcium channel blockade) is wrong because labetalol is not a calcium channel blocker.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Adrenoceptor Antagonist Drugs)</em>`},
    {q:'Which antihypertensive drug used in pregnancy is a dihydropyridine calcium channel blocker?',o:['Hydralazine','Methyldopa','Labetalol','Nifedipine'],a:3,
    e:`Nifedipine is the dihydropyridine calcium channel blocker used in pregnancy. It selectively blocks vascular L-type calcium channels (with greater vascular than cardiac selectivity), producing arterial vasodilation with less direct cardiac depression.<br><br>Nifedipine 10 to 20 mg PO every 6 to 8 hours is widely used for chronic and severe hypertension in pregnancy. Side effects include headache, flushing, peripheral oedema and reflex tachycardia. Avoid concurrent use with magnesium sulfate due to synergistic neuromuscular block.<br><br>D (Nifedipine) is correct because it is the dihydropyridine CCB used in pregnancy. A (Methyldopa) is wrong because it is a centrally acting α₂-agonist. B (Hydralazine) is wrong because it is a direct arteriolar vasodilator. C (Atenolol) is wrong because it is a β-blocker.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Vasodilators and the Treatment of Angina Pectoris)</em>`},
    {q:'A woman with severe hypertension in pregnancy is treated with intravenous labetalol. What is the primary pharmacologic effect leading to reduced blood pressure?',o:['Increased cardiac contractility','Increased renin secretion','Decreased systemic vascular resistance','Increased sodium retention'],a:2,
    e:`A woman with severe hypertension in pregnancy treated with hydralazine has decreased systemic vascular resistance through direct arteriolar vasodilation. Reduced afterload lowers blood pressure rapidly.<br><br>Hydralazine 5 to 10 mg IV boluses every 20 to 30 minutes is used for severe hypertension in pregnancy. The mechanism involves activation of guanylyl cyclase, increased cGMP and arteriolar smooth muscle relaxation. Side effects include reflex tachycardia, headache, nausea, palpitations and lupus-like syndrome on chronic use.<br><br>C (Decreased systemic vascular resistance) is correct because arteriolar vasodilation reduces SVR. A (Increased cardiac output) is wrong because while there is reflex tachycardia, the primary effect is reduced SVR. B (Increased preload) is wrong because hydralazine reduces, not increases, preload (mainly afterload reduction). D (Direct myocardial depression) is wrong because hydralazine does not directly depress the heart.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Vasodilators and the Treatment of Angina Pectoris)</em>`},
    {q:'Which drug used for hypertension in pregnancy may cause sedation and depression as side effects?',o:['Labetalol','Hydralazine','Nifedipine','Methyldopa'],a:3,
    e:`Methyldopa is the antihypertensive used for hypertension in pregnancy that may cause sedation. Methyldopa\'s central α₂-agonist activity in the brainstem reduces sympathetic outflow but also produces sedation, fatigue and depression as common side effects.<br><br>Other side effects include rarely positive Coombs test, autoimmune haemolytic anaemia and hepatotoxicity. Despite these effects, methyldopa has the longest safety record in pregnancy and remains a first-line option. Sedation often improves with continued use or dose reduction.<br><br>D (Methyldopa) is correct because central α₂-agonism causes sedation. A (Hydralazine) is wrong because it does not cause sedation. B (Nifedipine) is wrong because it does not cause sedation. C (Labetalol) is wrong because while it may cause fatigue, sedation is more characteristic of methyldopa.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Antihypertensive Agents)</em>`},
    {q:'A patient receiving nifedipine therapy develops flushing and headache. What is the most likely mechanism?',o:['Peripheral vasodilation','Increased sympathetic tone','Reduced renin release','Increased prostaglandin synthesis'],a:0,
    e:`A patient receiving nifedipine therapy who develops flushing and headache has peripheral vasodilation from calcium channel blockade in vascular smooth muscle. Cutaneous vasodilation causes flushing; cerebral vasodilation contributes to headache.<br><br>Nifedipine blocks L-type calcium channels, reducing intracellular calcium and producing vasodilation. Side effects include headache, flushing, peripheral oedema and reflex tachycardia. Avoid concurrent use with magnesium sulfate due to synergistic neuromuscular block. Hypotension may be treated with IV fluids and positioning.<br><br>A (Peripheral vasodilation) is correct because nifedipine reduces vascular resistance. B (Increased preload) is wrong because nifedipine reduces preload. C (Direct cardiac stimulation) is wrong because nifedipine does not directly stimulate the heart. D (Increased oxytocin release) is wrong because nifedipine does not affect oxytocin.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Vasodilators and the Treatment of Angina Pectoris)</em>`},
    {q:'Which antihypertensive drug used in pregnancy primarily lowers blood pressure by decreasing systemic vascular resistance without significant reduction in cardiac output?',o:['Methyldopa','Hydralazine','Atenolol','Propranolol'],a:1,
    e:`Hydralazine primarily lowers blood pressure by direct arteriolar vasodilation, reducing systemic vascular resistance. The mechanism involves activation of guanylyl cyclase, increased cGMP and arteriolar smooth muscle relaxation.<br><br>Hydralazine 5 to 10 mg IV boluses every 20 to 30 minutes is used for severe hypertension in pregnancy. Side effects include reflex tachycardia, headache, nausea, palpitations and a lupus-like syndrome on chronic use. IV labetalol and oral nifedipine are also first-line for severe hypertension.<br><br>B (Hydralazine) is correct because it is the direct arteriolar vasodilator. A (Methyldopa) is wrong because it acts centrally on α₂ receptors. C (Nifedipine) is wrong because it acts via L-type calcium channels. D (Atenolol) is wrong because it blocks β receptors.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Vasodilators and the Treatment of Angina Pectoris)</em>`},
    {q:'A woman with preeclampsia is treated with labetalol. Which pharmacologic property contributes to its antihypertensive action?',o:['Combined α₁ and β blockade','ACE inhibition','Prostaglandin inhibition','Calcium channel activation'],a:0,
    e:`A woman with pre-eclampsia treated with labetalol has blood pressure lowered through combined α₁ and β blockade. The α₁ blockade causes vasodilation; the β-blockade reduces heart rate and prevents reflex tachycardia.<br><br>Labetalol is widely used for chronic and severe hypertension in pregnancy. Oral dose is 100 to 400 mg twice or three times daily; IV dose is 20 mg over 2 minutes, doubled every 10 minutes (max 220 mg). Side effects include orthostatic hypotension, fatigue, bronchospasm in asthmatics and rare hepatotoxicity.<br><br>A (Combined α₁ and β blockade) is correct because labetalol blocks both α₁ and β receptors. B (Calcium channel blockade) is wrong because that is the nifedipine mechanism. C (ACE inhibition) is wrong because labetalol is not an ACE inhibitor. D (Direct vasodilation) is wrong because that is the hydralazine mechanism.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Adrenoceptor Antagonist Drugs)</em>`},
    {q:'Which antihypertensive drug used in pregnancy acts mainly by blocking L-type calcium channels in vascular smooth muscle?',o:['Methyldopa','Labetalol','Nifedipine','Hydralazine'],a:2,
    e:`Nifedipine acts mainly by blocking L-type calcium channels in vascular smooth muscle. This reduces intracellular calcium, decreases vascular smooth muscle contraction and causes peripheral vasodilation, lowering blood pressure.<br><br>Nifedipine 10 to 20 mg PO every 6 to 8 hours is widely used for chronic and severe hypertension in pregnancy. Side effects include headache, flushing, peripheral oedema and reflex tachycardia. Avoid concurrent use with magnesium sulfate due to synergistic neuromuscular block.<br><br>C (Nifedipine) is correct because it blocks L-type calcium channels. A (Methyldopa) is wrong because it is a centrally acting α₂-agonist. B (Hydralazine) is wrong because it is a direct arteriolar vasodilator. D (Atenolol) is wrong because it is a β-blocker.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Vasodilators and the Treatment of Angina Pectoris)</em>`},
    {q:'A patient with severe hypertension during pregnancy requires immediate blood pressure control. Which drug is commonly given intravenously in emergency situations?',o:['Methyldopa','Atenolol','Enalapril','Hydralazine'],a:3,
    e:`A patient with severe hypertension during pregnancy requiring rapid blood pressure control may receive hydralazine 5 to 10 mg IV boluses every 20 to 30 minutes. Hydralazine is a direct arteriolar vasodilator that rapidly lowers systemic vascular resistance.<br><br>IV labetalol (20 mg over 2 minutes, doubled every 10 minutes) and oral nifedipine (10 to 20 mg) are also first-line for severe hypertension. The aim is to lower blood pressure to <160/110 mmHg without compromising uteroplacental perfusion.<br><br>D (Hydralazine) is correct because it is an established IV first-line agent for severe hypertension. A (Captopril) is wrong because ACE inhibitors are contraindicated. B (Losartan) is wrong because ARBs are contraindicated. C (Enalapril) is wrong because it is an ACE inhibitor.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics; Chapter: Hypertensive Disorders)</em>`},
    {q:'Which antihypertensive drug reduces blood pressure by decreasing central sympathetic outflow?',o:['Nifedipine','Methyldopa','Hydralazine','Labetalol'],a:1,
    e:`Methyldopa reduces blood pressure by decreasing sympathetic outflow from the CNS. Methyldopa is converted to α-methylnorepinephrine which acts on central α₂ receptors in the brainstem, reducing sympathetic outflow to peripheral vasculature and heart.<br><br>Methyldopa has the longest safety record in pregnancy. Side effects include sedation, depression and rarely positive Coombs test or haemolytic anaemia. It does not affect uteroplacental perfusion. Labetalol and nifedipine are also widely used as first-line options.<br><br>B (Methyldopa) is correct because central α₂-agonism reduces sympathetic outflow. A (Hydralazine) is wrong because it is a direct arteriolar vasodilator. C (Nifedipine) is wrong because it is a calcium channel blocker. D (Labetalol) is wrong because it is a combined α and β-blocker.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Antihypertensive Agents)</em>`},
    {q:'A pregnant patient receiving beta-blocker therapy develops fetal growth restriction. Which drug is most commonly associated with this effect?',o:['Atenolol','Methyldopa','Nifedipine','Hydralazine'],a:0,
    e:`A pregnant patient receiving beta-blocker therapy who develops fetal growth restriction is most likely on atenolol. Atenolol is associated with reduced fetal growth, particularly when started in the first trimester. The mechanism may involve reduced uteroplacental perfusion from beta-blockade.<br><br>Labetalol (combined α₁ and β blockade) is preferred over atenolol because it has less effect on uteroplacental perfusion. Methyldopa, nifedipine and hydralazine are also first-line options. ACE inhibitors and ARBs are contraindicated.<br><br>A (Atenolol) is correct because of its association with fetal growth restriction. B (Labetalol) is wrong because it has less impact on growth. C (Nifedipine) is wrong because it is not associated with growth restriction. D (Methyldopa) is wrong because it does not cause growth restriction.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics; Chapter: Hypertensive Disorders)</em>`},
    {q:'Which antihypertensive drug used in pregnancy primarily causes arteriolar dilation without significant venous dilation?',o:['Propranolol','Methyldopa','Hydralazine','Atenolol'],a:2,
    e:`Hydralazine, used in pregnancy for severe hypertension, primarily causes peripheral arteriolar vasodilation through direct smooth muscle relaxation. The mechanism involves activation of guanylyl cyclase, increased cGMP and arteriolar smooth muscle relaxation.<br><br>Hydralazine 5 to 10 mg IV boluses every 20 to 30 minutes is used for severe hypertension. Side effects include reflex tachycardia, headache, nausea, palpitations and lupus-like syndrome on chronic use. IV labetalol and oral nifedipine are also first-line.<br><br>C (Hydralazine) is correct because it is the direct arteriolar vasodilator. A (Methyldopa) is wrong because it acts centrally on α₂ receptors. B (Atenolol) is wrong because it blocks β receptors. D (Captopril) is wrong because it is an ACE inhibitor and contraindicated.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Vasodilators and the Treatment of Angina Pectoris)</em>`},
    {q:'Which antihypertensive drug used during pregnancy is both an α₁ blocker and a nonselective β-blocker?',o:['Atenolol','Labetalol','Metoprolol','Propranolol'],a:1,
    e:`Labetalol is the antihypertensive used during pregnancy that is both an α and β-adrenergic blocker. The α₁ blockade produces vasodilation; the β-blockade reduces heart rate and prevents reflex tachycardia.<br><br>Labetalol is widely used for chronic and severe hypertension in pregnancy due to safety, lack of fetal effects and minimal effect on uteroplacental perfusion. Oral dose is 100 to 400 mg twice or three times daily; IV dose is 20 mg over 2 minutes, doubled every 10 minutes (max 220 mg).<br><br>B (Labetalol) is correct because it is the combined α and β-blocker. A (Methyldopa) is wrong because it is a centrally acting α₂-agonist. C (Atenolol) is wrong because it is a selective β-blocker without alpha activity. D (Nifedipine) is wrong because it is a calcium channel blocker.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Adrenoceptor Antagonist Drugs)</em>`},
    {q:'A pregnant patient treated with nifedipine experiences dizziness and flushing. What pharmacologic action explains these symptoms?',o:['Increased sodium retention','Increased sympathetic stimulation','Increased prostaglandin synthesis','Vasodilation from calcium channel blockade'],a:3,
    e:`A pregnant patient treated with nifedipine experiencing dizziness has hypotension from vasodilation due to calcium channel blockade. Nifedipine blocks L-type calcium channels in vascular smooth muscle, reducing intracellular calcium and producing vasodilation.<br><br>Maternal blood pressure should be monitored during nifedipine therapy. Hypotension may be treated with IV fluids and positioning. Reflex tachycardia is also common. Avoid concurrent use with magnesium sulfate due to synergistic neuromuscular block.<br><br>D (Vasodilation from calcium channel blockade) is correct because nifedipine reduces vascular resistance. A (Increased preload) is wrong because nifedipine reduces preload. B (Direct cardiac stimulation) is wrong because nifedipine does not directly stimulate the heart. C (Increased oxytocin release) is wrong because nifedipine does not affect oxytocin.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Vasodilators and the Treatment of Angina Pectoris)</em>`},
    {q:'Which antihypertensive drug used in pregnancy acts centrally by stimulating α₂ receptors in the brain?',o:['Hydralazine','Methyldopa','Nifedipine','Labetalol'],a:1,
    e:`Methyldopa is the antihypertensive used in pregnancy that acts centrally as an α₂-adrenergic agonist. Methyldopa is converted to α-methylnorepinephrine which acts on central α₂ receptors in the brainstem, reducing sympathetic outflow.<br><br>Methyldopa has the longest safety record in pregnancy. Side effects include sedation, depression and rarely positive Coombs test or haemolytic anaemia. It does not affect uteroplacental perfusion. Labetalol and nifedipine are also widely used as first-line options.<br><br>B (Methyldopa) is correct because central α₂-agonism is its mechanism. A (Hydralazine) is wrong because it is a direct arteriolar vasodilator. C (Nifedipine) is wrong because it is a calcium channel blocker. D (Labetalol) is wrong because it is a combined α and β-blocker.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Antihypertensive Agents)</em>`},
    {q:'Which drug is considered one of the first-line antihypertensive agents for chronic hypertension during pregnancy?',o:['Methyldopa','Losartan','Enalapril','Captopril'],a:0,
    e:`Methyldopa is considered one of the first-line antihypertensives in pregnancy due to its long safety record. It is a centrally acting α₂-adrenergic agonist that reduces sympathetic outflow.<br><br>Side effects include sedation, depression and rarely positive Coombs test or haemolytic anaemia. Labetalol and nifedipine are also widely used as first-line options. ACE inhibitors and angiotensin receptor blockers are contraindicated. Hydralazine is used IV for hypertensive emergencies.<br><br>A (Methyldopa) is correct because of its long safety record. B (Captopril) is wrong because ACE inhibitors are contraindicated. C (Losartan) is wrong because ARBs are contraindicated. D (Enalapril) is wrong because it is an ACE inhibitor.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics; Chapter: Hypertensive Disorders)</em>`},
    {q:'A 32-year-old pregnant woman with severe hypertension (BP 180/110 mmHg) requires rapid control of blood pressure. Which antihypertensive drug is commonly used intravenously in obstetric emergencies?',o:['Losartan','Methyldopa','Enalapril','Hydralazine'],a:3,
    e:`A 32-year-old pregnant woman with severe hypertension (BP 180/120) requires rapid blood pressure control with hydralazine 5 to 10 mg IV bolus, repeated every 20 to 30 minutes as needed. Hydralazine is a direct arteriolar vasodilator.<br><br>IV labetalol (20 mg over 2 minutes, doubled every 10 minutes) and oral nifedipine (10 to 20 mg) are also first-line for severe hypertension. The aim is to lower blood pressure to <160/110 mmHg without compromising uteroplacental perfusion.<br><br>D (Hydralazine) is correct because it is an established IV first-line agent for severe hypertension. A (Captopril) is wrong because ACE inhibitors are contraindicated. B (Losartan) is wrong because ARBs are contraindicated. C (Enalapril) is wrong because it is an ACE inhibitor.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics; Chapter: Hypertensive Disorders)</em>`},
    {q:'Which antihypertensive drug used in pregnancy acts by blocking L-type calcium channels in vascular smooth muscle leading to vasodilation?',o:['Labetalol','Methyldopa','Nifedipine','Propranolol'],a:2,
    e:`Nifedipine acts by blocking L-type voltage-gated calcium channels in vascular smooth muscle. This reduces intracellular calcium, decreases vascular smooth muscle contraction and produces peripheral vasodilation, lowering blood pressure.<br><br>Nifedipine 10 to 20 mg PO every 6 to 8 hours is widely used for chronic and severe hypertension in pregnancy. Side effects include headache, flushing, peripheral oedema and reflex tachycardia. Avoid concurrent use with magnesium sulfate due to synergistic neuromuscular block.<br><br>C (Nifedipine) is correct because it blocks L-type calcium channels. A (Methyldopa) is wrong because it is a centrally acting α₂-agonist. B (Hydralazine) is wrong because it is a direct arteriolar vasodilator. D (Atenolol) is wrong because it is a β-blocker.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Vasodilators and the Treatment of Angina Pectoris)</em>`},
    {q:'A pregnant woman with chronic hypertension is started on labetalol. What is the primary pharmacologic action responsible for its antihypertensive effect?',o:['Combined α₁ and β-adrenergic blockade','ACE inhibition','Direct renin inhibition','Cyclooxygenase inhibition'],a:0,
    e:`A pregnant woman with chronic hypertension started on labetalol benefits from combined α₁ and β-adrenergic blockade. The α₁ blockade produces vasodilation; the β-blockade reduces heart rate and prevents reflex tachycardia.<br><br>Labetalol is widely used for chronic and severe hypertension in pregnancy due to safety, lack of fetal effects and minimal effect on uteroplacental perfusion. Oral dose is 100 to 400 mg twice or three times daily.<br><br>A (Combined α₁ and β-adrenergic blockade) is correct because labetalol blocks both α₁ and β receptors. B (Calcium channel blockade) is wrong because that is the nifedipine mechanism. C (ACE inhibition) is wrong because labetalol is not an ACE inhibitor. D (Direct vasodilation) is wrong because that is the hydralazine mechanism.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Adrenoceptor Antagonist Drugs)</em>`},
    {q:'Which antihypertensive drug used in pregnancy primarily decreases blood pressure by stimulating central α₂ receptors and reducing sympathetic outflow?',o:['Hydralazine','Nifedipine','Labetalol','Methyldopa'],a:3,
    e:`Methyldopa primarily decreases blood pressure by reducing central sympathetic activity. Methyldopa is converted to α-methylnorepinephrine which acts on central α₂ receptors in the brainstem, reducing sympathetic outflow to peripheral vasculature and heart.<br><br>Methyldopa has the longest safety record in pregnancy. Side effects include sedation, depression and rarely positive Coombs test or haemolytic anaemia. It does not affect uteroplacental perfusion. Labetalol and nifedipine are also widely used as first-line options.<br><br>D (Methyldopa) is correct because central α₂-agonism reduces sympathetic outflow. A (Hydralazine) is wrong because it is a direct arteriolar vasodilator. B (Nifedipine) is wrong because it is a calcium channel blocker. C (Labetalol) is wrong because it is a combined α and β-blocker.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Antihypertensive Agents)</em>`},
    {q:'A pregnant patient treated with nifedipine develops headache and flushing. These symptoms are mainly due to which pharmacologic effect?',o:['Increased prostaglandin synthesis','Peripheral vasodilation','Increased sympathetic activity','Reduced cardiac output'],a:1,
    e:`A pregnant patient treated with nifedipine developing headache and flushing has peripheral vasodilation from calcium channel blockade. Cutaneous vasodilation causes flushing; cerebral vasodilation contributes to headache.<br><br>Nifedipine blocks L-type calcium channels, reducing intracellular calcium and producing vasodilation. Side effects include headache, flushing, peripheral oedema and reflex tachycardia. Avoid concurrent use with magnesium sulfate. Hypotension may be treated with IV fluids and positioning.<br><br>B (Peripheral vasodilation) is correct because nifedipine reduces vascular resistance. A (Increased preload) is wrong because nifedipine reduces preload. C (Direct cardiac stimulation) is wrong because nifedipine does not directly stimulate the heart. D (Increased oxytocin release) is wrong because nifedipine does not affect oxytocin.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Vasodilators and the Treatment of Angina Pectoris)</em>`},
    {q:'Which antihypertensive drug class is contraindicated during pregnancy because it may cause fetal renal failure and oligohydramnios?',o:['Calcium channel blockers','Central α₂ agonists','ACE inhibitors','Beta blockers'],a:2,
    e:`ACE inhibitors are contraindicated during pregnancy due to fetal renal dysgenesis, oligohydramnios, pulmonary hypoplasia, calvarial hypoplasia and limb contractures. Risk is greatest in the second and third trimesters.<br><br>Angiotensin receptor blockers cause similar effects and are also contraindicated. Methyldopa, labetalol and nifedipine are first-line antihypertensives in pregnancy. Hydralazine is used IV for hypertensive emergencies.<br><br>C (ACE inhibitors) is correct because of the established fetal renal failure risk. A (Calcium channel blockers) is wrong because they are widely used in pregnancy. B (Beta-blockers) is wrong because labetalol and other beta-blockers are widely used. D (Centrally acting α₂-agonists) is wrong because methyldopa is the gold standard.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics; Chapter: Hypertensive Disorders)</em>`},
    {q:'A pregnant woman receiving methyldopa therapy complains of excessive fatigue and sedation. What is the mechanism responsible for these side effects?',o:['Reduced central sympathetic activity','Peripheral vasodilation','Increased renin secretion','Increased prostaglandin production'],a:0,
    e:`A pregnant woman receiving methyldopa therapy complaining of excessive sedation has reduced central sympathetic activity. Methyldopa\'s central α₂-agonist activity in the brainstem reduces sympathetic outflow but also produces sedation, fatigue and depression as common side effects.<br><br>Other side effects include rarely positive Coombs test, autoimmune haemolytic anaemia and hepatotoxicity. Despite these effects, methyldopa has the longest safety record in pregnancy and remains a first-line option. Sedation often improves with continued use or dose reduction.<br><br>A (Reduced central sympathetic activity) is correct because methyldopa\'s mechanism produces sedation. B (Direct arteriolar vasodilation) is wrong because that is the hydralazine mechanism. C (Calcium channel blockade) is wrong because that is the nifedipine mechanism. D (ACE inhibition) is wrong because that is the ACE inhibitor mechanism.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Antihypertensive Agents)</em>`},
    {q:'Which antihypertensive drug used in pregnancy primarily reduces systemic vascular resistance through direct arteriolar relaxation?',o:['Methyldopa','Labetalol','Hydralazine','Atenolol'],a:2,
    e:`Hydralazine primarily reduces blood pressure by direct arteriolar vasodilation, lowering systemic vascular resistance and afterload. The mechanism involves activation of guanylyl cyclase, increased cGMP and arteriolar smooth muscle relaxation.<br><br>Hydralazine 5 to 10 mg IV boluses every 20 to 30 minutes is used for severe hypertension in pregnancy. Side effects include reflex tachycardia, headache, nausea, palpitations and a lupus-like syndrome on chronic use. IV labetalol and oral nifedipine are also first-line for severe hypertension.<br><br>C (Hydralazine) is correct because it is the direct arteriolar vasodilator. A (Methyldopa) is wrong because it acts centrally. B (Labetalol) is wrong because it acts via combined α and β blockade. D (Nifedipine) is wrong because it acts via calcium channel blockade.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Vasodilators and the Treatment of Angina Pectoris)</em>`},
    {q:'A pregnant patient treated with a beta-blocker develops fetal growth restriction. Which drug is most commonly associated with this complication?',o:['Methyldopa','Hydralazine','Nifedipine','Atenolol'],a:3,
    e:`A pregnant patient treated with a beta-blocker who develops fetal growth restriction is most likely on atenolol. Atenolol is associated with reduced fetal growth, particularly when started in the first trimester. The mechanism may involve reduced uteroplacental perfusion from beta-blockade.<br><br>Labetalol (combined α₁ and β blockade) is preferred over atenolol because it has less effect on uteroplacental perfusion. Methyldopa, nifedipine and hydralazine are also first-line options.<br><br>D (Atenolol) is correct because of its association with fetal growth restriction. A (Methyldopa) is wrong because it does not cause growth restriction. B (Nifedipine) is wrong because it is not associated with growth restriction. C (Hydralazine) is wrong because it does not cause growth restriction.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics; Chapter: Hypertensive Disorders)</em>`},
    {q:'Which antihypertensive drug commonly used in pregnancy blocks both α₁ and β receptors and helps maintain uteroplacental blood flow?',o:['Propranolol','Labetalol','Atenolol','Metoprolol'],a:1,
    e:`Labetalol commonly used in pregnancy blocks both α₁ and β-adrenergic receptors. The α₁ blockade causes vasodilation; the β-blockade reduces heart rate and prevents reflex tachycardia.<br><br>Labetalol is widely used for chronic and severe hypertension in pregnancy due to safety, lack of fetal effects and minimal effect on uteroplacental perfusion. Oral dose is 100 to 400 mg twice or three times daily; IV dose is 20 mg over 2 minutes, doubled every 10 minutes (max 220 mg). Side effects include orthostatic hypotension, fatigue, bronchospasm in asthmatics and rare hepatotoxicity.<br><br>B (Labetalol) is correct because it is the combined α and β-blocker. A (Methyldopa) is wrong because it is a centrally acting α₂-agonist. C (Atenolol) is wrong because it is a selective β-blocker without alpha activity. D (Nifedipine) is wrong because it is a calcium channel blocker.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Adrenoceptor Antagonist Drugs)</em>`},
    {q:'A 30-year-old pregnant woman with gestational diabetes mellitus (GDM) is started on an oral drug that decreases hepatic gluconeogenesis and improves peripheral insulin sensitivity. Which drug is most likely prescribed?',o:['Sitagliptin','Glibenclamide','Metformin','Acarbose'],a:2,
    e:`A 30-year-old pregnant woman with gestational diabetes inadequately controlled by diet and exercise may be prescribed metformin as an alternative to insulin. Metformin reduces hepatic glucose production (decreased gluconeogenesis), increases peripheral insulin sensitivity and reduces intestinal glucose absorption.<br><br>Metformin crosses the placenta but is generally considered safe in pregnancy. Insulin remains the gold standard. Glyburide is also used in some centres. Pioglitazone is avoided due to limited safety data. Metformin offers practical advantages: oral administration and no risk of severe hypoglycaemia.<br><br>C (Metformin) is correct because it is widely used as an alternative to insulin in gestational diabetes. A (Glipizide) is wrong because sulfonylureas are not first-line in gestational diabetes. B (Pioglitazone) is wrong because thiazolidinediones are avoided. D (Acarbose) is wrong because it has limited efficacy and GI side effects.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Pancreatic Hormones and Antidiabetic Drugs)</em>`},
    {q:'Which oral hypoglycemic drug stimulates insulin secretion by closing ATP-sensitive potassium channels in pancreatic β-cells and is sometimes used in gestational diabetes?',o:['Alpha-glucosidase inhibitors','Sulfonylureas','Biguanides','Thiazolidinediones'],a:1,
    e:`Sulfonylureas (glibenclamide/glyburide, glipizide, gliclazide) stimulate insulin secretion by binding to SUR1 (sulfonylurea receptor 1) on pancreatic β-cell ATP-sensitive potassium channels. This closes the K+ channels, depolarises the cell, opens voltage-gated calcium channels and triggers insulin secretion.<br><br>Sulfonylureas require functioning β-cells. Side effects include hypoglycaemia (most common) and weight gain. They are not first-line in gestational diabetes (insulin and metformin preferred), though glyburide is used in some centres. Long-acting sulfonylureas can cause prolonged neonatal hypoglycaemia if used near delivery.<br><br>B (Sulfonylureas) is correct because they stimulate insulin secretion via SUR1/K+ channel closure. A (Biguanides) is wrong because metformin reduces hepatic glucose production, not insulin secretion. C (Thiazolidinediones) is wrong because pioglitazone improves insulin sensitivity, not secretion. D (Alpha-glucosidase inhibitors) is wrong because acarbose delays carbohydrate absorption.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Pancreatic Hormones and Antidiabetic Drugs)</em>`},
    {q:'A pregnant patient with diabetes develops lactic acidosis while on an oral hypoglycemic drug. Which drug is most likely responsible?',o:['Acarbose','Pioglitazone','Glibenclamide','Metformin'],a:3,
    e:`A pregnant patient with diabetes developing lactic acidosis is on metformin. Metformin can cause lactic acidosis, especially in patients with renal insufficiency, hypoxia, sepsis, dehydration or after radiocontrast media. Symptoms include nausea, vomiting, abdominal pain, hyperventilation and altered consciousness.<br><br>Metformin reduces hepatic glucose production by inhibiting gluconeogenesis (which uses lactate as substrate), leading to lactate accumulation in susceptible patients. Risk is low if eGFR is above 30 mL/min and the drug is held during acute illness. Treatment of lactic acidosis is supportive with fluid resuscitation and possibly haemodialysis.<br><br>D (Metformin) is correct because metformin causes lactic acidosis. A (Glipizide) is wrong because sulfonylureas cause hypoglycaemia, not lactic acidosis. B (Pioglitazone) is wrong because thiazolidinediones cause fluid retention, not lactic acidosis. C (Acarbose) is wrong because alpha-glucosidase inhibitors cause GI side effects.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Pancreatic Hormones and Antidiabetic Drugs)</em>`},
    {q:'A pregnant woman with mild gestational diabetes is given a drug that delays carbohydrate digestion in the intestine. Which drug has this mechanism?',o:['Acarbose','Sitagliptin','Pioglitazone','Metformin'],a:0,
    e:`A pregnant woman with mild gestational diabetes given a drug that delays carbohydrate absorption is on acarbose. Acarbose is an alpha-glucosidase inhibitor that competitively inhibits intestinal alpha-glucosidase enzymes (sucrase, maltase, glucoamylase), delaying complex carbohydrate breakdown to glucose.<br><br>This blunts postprandial glucose rises. Acarbose has minimal systemic absorption (under 2 percent), making it relatively safe in pregnancy though data are limited. Side effects are predominantly GI: flatulence, bloating, diarrhoea (from undigested carbohydrate fermentation by colonic bacteria). It is rarely used as monotherapy due to limited efficacy.<br><br>A (Acarbose) is correct because alpha-glucosidase inhibition delays carbohydrate absorption. B (Glipizide) is wrong because sulfonylureas stimulate insulin secretion. C (Metformin) is wrong because metformin reduces hepatic glucose production. D (Pioglitazone) is wrong because thiazolidinediones improve insulin sensitivity.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Pancreatic Hormones and Antidiabetic Drugs)</em>`},
    {q:'Which oral hypoglycemic drug improves insulin sensitivity by activating PPAR-γ receptors but is generally avoided in pregnancy due to safety concerns?',o:['Acarbose','Pioglitazone','Metformin','Glibenclamide'],a:1,
    e:`Pioglitazone (a thiazolidinedione, TZD) improves insulin sensitivity by activating peroxisome proliferator-activated receptor gamma (PPAR-γ). PPAR-γ activation alters transcription of genes involved in glucose and lipid metabolism, increasing glucose uptake in muscle and adipose tissue.<br><br>Side effects include fluid retention, weight gain, increased risk of heart failure, bone fractures (especially in postmenopausal women) and bladder cancer (controversial). Pioglitazone is avoided in pregnancy due to limited safety data. Insulin and metformin are preferred for gestational diabetes.<br><br>B (Pioglitazone) is correct because TZDs improve insulin sensitivity via PPAR-γ. A (Glipizide) is wrong because sulfonylureas stimulate insulin secretion. C (Metformin) is wrong because metformin works through AMPK activation, not PPAR-γ. D (Acarbose) is wrong because it inhibits alpha-glucosidase.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Pancreatic Hormones and Antidiabetic Drugs)</em>`},
    {q:'A patient with gestational diabetes taking acarbose complains of abdominal bloating and flatulence. What is the most likely explanation?',o:['Increased insulin secretion','Increased hepatic glucose production','Fermentation of undigested carbohydrates in the colon','Renal glucose excretion'],a:2,
    e:`A patient with gestational diabetes taking acarbose complains of flatulence and abdominal discomfort. The mechanism is fermentation of undigested carbohydrates in the colon by gut bacteria, producing gas and short-chain fatty acids that irritate the colon.<br><br>Acarbose competitively inhibits intestinal alpha-glucosidase, delaying complex carbohydrate breakdown. Undigested carbohydrates pass to the colon where they are fermented. Side effects (flatulence, bloating, diarrhoea) are dose-dependent and often improve with continued use. Starting at low dose and gradually increasing helps tolerability.<br><br>C (Fermentation of undigested carbohydrates in the colon) is correct because this is the well-established mechanism of GI side effects with acarbose. A (Direct toxicity to the gut) is wrong because acarbose has minimal systemic absorption and is not toxic. B (Increased pancreatic secretion) is wrong because acarbose does not affect pancreatic secretion. D (Direct gut motility increase) is wrong because acarbose does not directly affect motility.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Pancreatic Hormones and Antidiabetic Drugs)</em>`},
    {q:'A woman with type 2 diabetes planning pregnancy is switched to a drug that improves insulin sensitivity without causing hypoglycemia. Which drug is preferred?',o:['Repaglinide','Pioglitazone','Glibenclamide','Metformin'],a:3,
    e:`A woman with type 2 diabetes planning pregnancy is switched to a safer agent. Metformin is generally considered safe in pregnancy and may be continued or used as alternative to insulin. Insulin is the gold standard for glycaemic control in pregnancy due to no placental transfer.<br><br>Sulfonylureas (other than glyburide in some centres) are generally avoided. Pioglitazone is avoided due to limited safety data. Glyburide is used in some centres for gestational diabetes but has mixed safety data. Pre-pregnancy counselling and optimisation of glycaemic control are essential.<br><br>D (Metformin) is correct because it is generally considered safe in pregnancy and may continue. A (Glipizide) is wrong because sulfonylureas are not first-line. B (Pioglitazone) is wrong because thiazolidinediones are avoided. C (Acarbose) is wrong because it has limited efficacy and is not preferred.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics; Chapter: Diabetes Mellitus)</em>`},
    {q:'A pregnant patient treated with glibenclamide develops symptomatic hypoglycemia. What is the main mechanism of this drug?',o:['Increased pancreatic insulin secretion','Inhibition of carbohydrate absorption','Increased urinary glucose excretion','Activation of incretin hormones'],a:0,
    e:`A pregnant patient treated with glibenclamide (glyburide) developing symptoms of hypoglycaemia (sweating, tremor, dizziness) has hypoglycaemia from increased pancreatic insulin secretion. Sulfonylureas stimulate insulin secretion regardless of glucose level, risking hypoglycaemia.<br><br>Sulfonylureas bind to SUR1 on pancreatic β-cell ATP-sensitive potassium channels, closing them, depolarising the cell, opening voltage-gated calcium channels and triggering insulin secretion. Long-acting sulfonylureas can cause prolonged neonatal hypoglycaemia if used near delivery. Treatment of severe hypoglycaemia is IV dextrose or oral glucose.<br><br>A (Increased pancreatic insulin secretion) is correct because sulfonylureas stimulate insulin secretion. B (Direct gluconeogenesis suppression) is wrong because glyburide does not directly suppress hepatic gluconeogenesis. C (Increased glucose uptake in muscle) is wrong because that is the action of insulin (downstream effect), not the primary glyburide mechanism. D (Decreased intestinal glucose absorption) is wrong because that is the acarbose mechanism.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Pancreatic Hormones and Antidiabetic Drugs)</em>`},
    {q:'Which oral hypoglycemic drug used in some patients with gestational diabetes reduces hepatic glucose production without stimulating insulin secretion?',o:['Acarbose','Metformin','Repaglinide','Glibenclamide'],a:1,
    e:`Metformin is the oral hypoglycaemic used in some patients with gestational diabetes when diet and exercise fail and as an alternative to insulin. It reduces hepatic glucose production (decreased gluconeogenesis), increases peripheral insulin sensitivity and reduces intestinal glucose absorption.<br><br>Metformin crosses the placenta but is generally considered safe. Insulin remains the gold standard. Glyburide is also used in some centres. Pioglitazone is avoided due to limited safety data. Metformin offers practical advantages: oral administration and no risk of severe hypoglycaemia.<br><br>B (Metformin) is correct because it is widely used in gestational diabetes. A (Pioglitazone) is wrong because thiazolidinediones are avoided. C (Acarbose) is wrong because it has limited efficacy. D (Glipizide) is wrong because long-acting sulfonylureas are not first-line.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics; Chapter: Diabetes Mellitus)</em>`},
    {q:'Which class of oral hypoglycemic drugs lowers blood glucose by inhibiting intestinal α-glucosidase enzymes?',o:['Sulfonylureas','Biguanides','Alpha-glucosidase inhibitors','Meglitinides'],a:2,
    e:`Alpha-glucosidase inhibitors (acarbose, miglitol) lower blood glucose by competitively inhibiting intestinal alpha-glucosidase enzymes (sucrase, maltase, glucoamylase). This delays complex carbohydrate breakdown to monosaccharides, blunting postprandial glucose rises.<br><br>Alpha-glucosidase inhibitors have minimal systemic absorption (under 2 percent). Side effects are predominantly GI: flatulence, bloating, diarrhoea (from undigested carbohydrate fermentation by colonic bacteria). They are rarely used as monotherapy due to limited efficacy and tolerability issues. Hypoglycaemia from acarbose alone is uncommon (treated with glucose, not sucrose).<br><br>C (Alpha-glucosidase inhibitors) is correct because they delay carbohydrate digestion and absorption. A (Sulfonylureas) is wrong because they stimulate insulin secretion. B (Biguanides) is wrong because they reduce hepatic glucose production. D (Thiazolidinediones) is wrong because they improve insulin sensitivity.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Pancreatic Hormones and Antidiabetic Drugs)</em>`},
    {q:'A pregnant patient with GDM is started on metformin. Which physiologic effect contributes most to glucose lowering?',o:['Decreased hepatic gluconeogenesis','Increased insulin secretion','Increased glucagon secretion','Increased intestinal glucose absorption'],a:0,
    e:`A pregnant patient with GDM started on metformin has glycaemic control through decreased hepatic gluconeogenesis as the primary mechanism. Metformin activates AMP-activated protein kinase (AMPK) in hepatocytes, suppressing gluconeogenesis and reducing hepatic glucose output.<br><br>Metformin also increases peripheral insulin sensitivity (in muscle and adipose tissue) and reduces intestinal glucose absorption. It does not directly stimulate insulin secretion. Metformin crosses the placenta but is generally considered safe in pregnancy.<br><br>A (Decreased hepatic gluconeogenesis) is correct because reducing hepatic glucose production is metformin\'s primary action. B (Increased insulin secretion) is wrong because that is the sulfonylurea mechanism. C (Delayed intestinal carbohydrate absorption) is wrong because that is the acarbose mechanism. D (PPAR-γ activation) is wrong because that is the thiazolidinedione mechanism.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Pancreatic Hormones and Antidiabetic Drugs)</em>`},
    {q:'Which oral hypoglycemic drug class increases insulin secretion from pancreatic β-cells and may cause hypoglycemia if meals are skipped?',o:['Alpha-glucosidase inhibitors','Thiazolidinediones','Biguanides','Sulfonylureas'],a:3,
    e:`Sulfonylureas (glibenclamide, glipizide, gliclazide) increase insulin secretion by binding to SUR1 (sulfonylurea receptor 1) on pancreatic β-cell ATP-sensitive potassium channels. Channel closure depolarises the cell, opens voltage-gated calcium channels and triggers insulin secretion.<br><br>Sulfonylureas require functioning β-cells. Side effects include hypoglycaemia (most common) and weight gain. They are not first-line in gestational diabetes (insulin and metformin preferred), though glyburide is used in some centres. Long-acting sulfonylureas can cause prolonged neonatal hypoglycaemia if used near delivery.<br><br>D (Sulfonylureas) is correct because they stimulate insulin secretion via SUR1/K+ channel closure. A (Biguanides) is wrong because metformin reduces hepatic glucose production, not insulin secretion. B (Thiazolidinediones) is wrong because they improve insulin sensitivity. C (Alpha-glucosidase inhibitors) is wrong because acarbose delays carbohydrate absorption.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Pancreatic Hormones and Antidiabetic Drugs)</em>`},
    {q:'A woman with gestational diabetes treated with metformin develops nausea and diarrhea. Which side effect of metformin explains this?',o:['Increased insulin secretion','Gastrointestinal irritation','Renal glucose excretion','Increased glucagon release'],a:1,
    e:`A woman with gestational diabetes treated with metformin develops nausea and abdominal pain due to gastrointestinal irritation. GI side effects (nausea, vomiting, abdominal cramps, diarrhoea, metallic taste) are the most common metformin adverse effects, occurring in 20 to 30 percent of users.<br><br>Side effects are dose-related and often improve with continued use. Starting at low dose (500 mg once daily) and titrating up, taking with meals, and using extended-release formulations improve tolerability. Lactic acidosis is a rare but serious complication, especially with renal impairment, hypoxia or sepsis.<br><br>B (Gastrointestinal irritation) is correct because GI side effects are the most common metformin adverse effects. A (Hypoglycemia) is wrong because metformin alone rarely causes hypoglycaemia. C (Liver failure) is wrong because metformin is not hepatotoxic. D (Weight gain) is wrong because metformin tends to be weight-neutral or cause weight loss, not gain.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Pancreatic Hormones and Antidiabetic Drugs)</em>`},
    {q:'Which oral hypoglycemic drug reduces postprandial hyperglycemia by delaying carbohydrate digestion in the intestine?',o:['Acarbose','Pioglitazone','Metformin','Sitagliptin'],a:0,
    e:`Acarbose reduces postprandial hyperglycaemia by competitively inhibiting intestinal alpha-glucosidase enzymes (sucrase, maltase, glucoamylase), delaying complex carbohydrate breakdown to glucose. This blunts postprandial glucose rises.<br><br>Acarbose has minimal systemic absorption (under 2 percent), making it relatively safe in pregnancy though data are limited. Side effects are predominantly GI: flatulence, bloating, diarrhoea (from undigested carbohydrate fermentation by colonic bacteria). It is rarely used as monotherapy due to limited efficacy.<br><br>A (Acarbose) is correct because alpha-glucosidase inhibition delays carbohydrate absorption and blunts postprandial glucose. B (Glipizide) is wrong because sulfonylureas stimulate insulin secretion. C (Metformin) is wrong because metformin primarily reduces hepatic glucose production. D (Pioglitazone) is wrong because thiazolidinediones improve insulin sensitivity.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Pancreatic Hormones and Antidiabetic Drugs)</em>`},
    {q:'A pregnant patient with GDM receives an oral drug that stimulates insulin secretion from pancreatic β-cells. Which drug is most likely used?',o:['Metformin','Pioglitazone','Glibenclamide','Acarbose'],a:2,
    e:`A pregnant patient with GDM receiving an oral drug that stimulates pancreatic insulin secretion is on glibenclamide (glyburide). Glibenclamide is the sulfonylurea most commonly used in gestational diabetes (in some centres) when oral therapy is preferred over insulin.<br><br>Glibenclamide binds to SUR1 on pancreatic β-cell ATP-sensitive potassium channels, closing them, depolarising the cell, opening voltage-gated calcium channels and triggering insulin secretion. Side effects include hypoglycaemia and weight gain. Long-acting sulfonylureas can cause prolonged neonatal hypoglycaemia if used near delivery.<br><br>C (Glibenclamide) is correct because it stimulates pancreatic insulin secretion via SUR1. A (Metformin) is wrong because metformin does not stimulate insulin secretion. B (Pioglitazone) is wrong because thiazolidinediones improve insulin sensitivity. D (Acarbose) is wrong because acarbose delays carbohydrate absorption.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics; Chapter: Diabetes Mellitus)</em>`},
    {q:'Which oral hypoglycemic drug improves insulin sensitivity and reduces hepatic glucose production without causing weight gain?',o:['Pioglitazone','Repaglinide','Glibenclamide','Metformin'],a:3,
    e:`Metformin improves insulin sensitivity and reduces hepatic glucose production. It activates AMP-activated protein kinase (AMPK) in hepatocytes, suppressing gluconeogenesis and reducing hepatic glucose output, while improving peripheral insulin sensitivity in muscle and adipose tissue.<br><br>Metformin also reduces intestinal glucose absorption. It does not directly stimulate insulin secretion. Metformin crosses the placenta but is generally considered safe in pregnancy. Insulin remains the gold standard for glycaemic control in pregnancy.<br><br>D (Metformin) is correct because it improves insulin sensitivity and reduces hepatic glucose production. A (Glipizide) is wrong because sulfonylureas stimulate insulin secretion. B (Acarbose) is wrong because acarbose delays carbohydrate absorption. C (Pioglitazone) is wrong because while it improves insulin sensitivity, it does not primarily reduce hepatic glucose production and is avoided in pregnancy.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Pancreatic Hormones and Antidiabetic Drugs)</em>`},
    {q:'Which oral hypoglycemic drug is most likely to cause flatulence due to fermentation of undigested carbohydrates?',o:['Sitagliptin','Metformin','Acarbose','Pioglitazone'],a:2,
    e:`Acarbose is the oral hypoglycaemic most likely to cause flatulence and bloating. Side effects are predominantly GI: flatulence, bloating, diarrhoea, abdominal pain. The mechanism is fermentation of undigested carbohydrates in the colon by gut bacteria, producing gas and short-chain fatty acids.<br><br>Acarbose competitively inhibits intestinal alpha-glucosidase, delaying complex carbohydrate breakdown. Undigested carbohydrates pass to the colon where they are fermented. Side effects are dose-dependent and often improve with continued use. Starting at low dose and gradually increasing helps tolerability.<br><br>C (Acarbose) is correct because GI fermentation causes flatulence and bloating. A (Metformin) is wrong because while metformin causes GI side effects, the flatulence/bloating pattern from fermentation is more characteristic of acarbose. B (Glipizide) is wrong because sulfonylureas cause hypoglycaemia, not flatulence. D (Pioglitazone) is wrong because thiazolidinediones cause fluid retention and weight gain, not flatulence.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Pancreatic Hormones and Antidiabetic Drugs)</em>`},
    {q:'A patient with type 2 diabetes planning pregnancy is advised to avoid thiazolidinediones. What is the main pharmacologic action of this class?',o:['Stimulation of insulin release','Activation of PPAR-γ receptors increasing insulin sensitivity','Inhibition of carbohydrate digestion','Increased renal glucose excretion'],a:1,
    e:`Pioglitazone improves insulin sensitivity through activation of PPAR-γ (peroxisome proliferator-activated receptor gamma) receptors. PPAR-γ activation alters transcription of genes involved in glucose and lipid metabolism, increasing glucose uptake in muscle and adipose tissue.<br><br>Side effects include fluid retention, weight gain, increased risk of heart failure, bone fractures (especially in postmenopausal women) and bladder cancer (controversial). Pioglitazone is avoided in pregnancy due to limited safety data. Insulin and metformin are preferred for gestational diabetes.<br><br>B (Activation of PPAR-γ receptors increasing insulin sensitivity) is correct because pioglitazone\'s mechanism is PPAR-γ activation. A (Increased insulin secretion) is wrong because that is the sulfonylurea mechanism. C (Delayed intestinal carbohydrate absorption) is wrong because that is the acarbose mechanism. D (Decreased hepatic gluconeogenesis primarily) is wrong because that is the metformin mechanism.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Pancreatic Hormones and Antidiabetic Drugs)</em>`},
    {q:'Which oral hypoglycemic drug may cause hypoglycemia due to excessive insulin release from β-cells?',o:['Glibenclamide','Metformin','Acarbose','Sitagliptin'],a:0,
    e:`Glibenclamide may cause hypoglycaemia due to excessive insulin secretion. Sulfonylureas stimulate insulin secretion regardless of glucose level (unlike GLP-1 receptor agonists which are glucose-dependent), risking hypoglycaemia.<br><br>Long-acting sulfonylureas (glibenclamide, glimepiride) cause more prolonged hypoglycaemia than short-acting ones (gliclazide, glipizide). Risk is increased in elderly, renal/hepatic impairment, missed meals, alcohol and drug interactions. Long-acting sulfonylureas can cause prolonged neonatal hypoglycaemia if used near delivery.<br><br>A (Glibenclamide) is correct because it is a long-acting sulfonylurea most associated with prolonged hypoglycaemia. B (Acarbose) is wrong because acarbose alone rarely causes hypoglycaemia. C (Pioglitazone) is wrong because thiazolidinediones do not directly cause hypoglycaemia. D (Metformin) is wrong because metformin alone rarely causes hypoglycaemia.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Pancreatic Hormones and Antidiabetic Drugs)</em>`},
    {q:'Which oral hypoglycemic drug improves glycemic control mainly by decreasing hepatic glucose production?',o:['Pioglitazone','Repaglinide','Acarbose','Metformin'],a:3,
    e:`Metformin improves glycaemic control mainly through reduced hepatic glucose production. Metformin activates AMP-activated protein kinase (AMPK) in hepatocytes, suppressing gluconeogenesis and reducing hepatic glucose output (especially fasting glucose).<br><br>Metformin also improves peripheral insulin sensitivity and reduces intestinal glucose absorption. It does not directly stimulate insulin secretion, so does not cause hypoglycaemia as monotherapy. Metformin crosses the placenta but is generally considered safe in pregnancy.<br><br>D (Metformin) is correct because reduced hepatic glucose production is its main mechanism. A (Glipizide) is wrong because sulfonylureas stimulate insulin secretion. B (Acarbose) is wrong because acarbose delays carbohydrate absorption. C (Pioglitazone) is wrong because thiazolidinediones primarily improve insulin sensitivity.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Pancreatic Hormones and Antidiabetic Drugs)</em>`},
    {q:'Which drug is commonly used as first-line pharmacologic therapy for type 2 diabetes and sometimes for gestational diabetes when insulin is not required?',o:['Metformin','Glibenclamide','Pioglitazone','Repaglinide'],a:0,
    e:`Metformin is commonly used as first-line pharmacologic therapy for gestational diabetes when diet and exercise are inadequate, as an alternative to insulin. It reduces hepatic glucose production, improves peripheral insulin sensitivity and reduces intestinal glucose absorption.<br><br>Insulin remains the gold standard. Glyburide is also used in some centres. Pioglitazone is avoided due to limited safety data. Metformin offers practical advantages: oral administration, no risk of severe hypoglycaemia and good safety profile in pregnancy. Insulin is added if metformin alone is inadequate.<br><br>A (Metformin) is correct because it is first-line oral therapy for gestational diabetes. B (Pioglitazone) is wrong because thiazolidinediones are avoided. C (Acarbose) is wrong because it has limited efficacy. D (Glipizide) is wrong because it is not first-line.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics; Chapter: Diabetes Mellitus)</em>`},
    {q:'A patient treated with sulfonylureas develops hypoglycemia. Which mechanism explains this effect?',o:['Reduced carbohydrate absorption','Increased insulin secretion','Increased insulin sensitivity','Increased renal glucose excretion'],a:1,
    e:`A patient treated with sulfonylureas developing hypoglycaemia has hypoglycaemia from increased insulin secretion. Sulfonylureas stimulate insulin secretion regardless of glucose level (unlike GLP-1 receptor agonists which are glucose-dependent), risking hypoglycaemia.<br><br>Sulfonylureas bind to SUR1 on pancreatic β-cell ATP-sensitive potassium channels, closing them, depolarising the cell, opening voltage-gated calcium channels and triggering insulin secretion. Long-acting sulfonylureas (glibenclamide, glimepiride) cause more prolonged hypoglycaemia. Treatment of severe hypoglycaemia is IV dextrose or oral glucose.<br><br>B (Increased insulin secretion) is correct because sulfonylureas stimulate insulin secretion. A (Decreased hepatic gluconeogenesis) is wrong because that is the metformin mechanism. C (Increased glucose uptake) is wrong because that is the action of insulin (downstream effect). D (Delayed intestinal absorption) is wrong because that is the acarbose mechanism.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Pancreatic Hormones and Antidiabetic Drugs)</em>`},
    {q:'Which oral hypoglycemic drug delays intestinal glucose absorption by inhibiting brush-border enzymes?',o:['Metformin','Glibenclamide','Acarbose','Pioglitazone'],a:2,
    e:`Acarbose delays intestinal glucose absorption by competitively inhibiting intestinal alpha-glucosidase enzymes (sucrase, maltase, glucoamylase). This delays complex carbohydrate breakdown to monosaccharides, blunting postprandial glucose rises.<br><br>Acarbose has minimal systemic absorption (under 2 percent). Side effects are predominantly GI: flatulence, bloating, diarrhoea (from undigested carbohydrate fermentation by colonic bacteria). It is rarely used as monotherapy due to limited efficacy. Hypoglycaemia from acarbose alone is uncommon.<br><br>C (Acarbose) is correct because alpha-glucosidase inhibition delays carbohydrate absorption. A (Glipizide) is wrong because sulfonylureas stimulate insulin secretion. B (Metformin) is wrong because metformin reduces hepatic glucose production. D (Pioglitazone) is wrong because thiazolidinediones improve insulin sensitivity.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Pancreatic Hormones and Antidiabetic Drugs)</em>`},
    {q:'Which drug improves insulin sensitivity through activation of nuclear receptors involved in glucose metabolism?',o:['Metformin','Sitagliptin','Acarbose','Pioglitazone'],a:3,
    e:`Pioglitazone improves insulin sensitivity through activation of nuclear PPAR-γ (peroxisome proliferator-activated receptor gamma) receptors. PPAR-γ activation alters transcription of genes involved in glucose and lipid metabolism, increasing glucose uptake in muscle and adipose tissue.<br><br>Side effects include fluid retention, weight gain, increased risk of heart failure, bone fractures (especially in postmenopausal women) and bladder cancer (controversial). Pioglitazone is avoided in pregnancy due to limited safety data. Insulin and metformin are preferred for gestational diabetes.<br><br>D (Pioglitazone) is correct because it activates nuclear PPAR-γ receptors. A (Glipizide) is wrong because sulfonylureas stimulate insulin secretion via membrane K+ channels. B (Metformin) is wrong because metformin works through AMPK activation. C (Acarbose) is wrong because acarbose inhibits intestinal alpha-glucosidase.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Pancreatic Hormones and Antidiabetic Drugs)</em>`},
    {q:'A pregnant woman with diabetes develops symptomatic hypoglycemia after taking a sulfonylurea. Which drug is most likely responsible?',o:['Glibenclamide','Metformin','Acarbose','Pioglitazone'],a:0,
    e:`A pregnant woman with diabetes developing symptomatic hypoglycaemia after starting an oral hypoglycaemic is most likely on glibenclamide (glyburide). Sulfonylureas stimulate insulin secretion regardless of glucose level, risking hypoglycaemia.<br><br>Long-acting sulfonylureas (glibenclamide, glimepiride) cause more prolonged hypoglycaemia than short-acting ones. Risk is increased in elderly, renal/hepatic impairment, missed meals, alcohol and drug interactions. Long-acting sulfonylureas can cause prolonged neonatal hypoglycaemia if used near delivery.<br><br>A (Glibenclamide) is correct because it is most associated with hypoglycaemia. B (Acarbose) is wrong because acarbose alone rarely causes hypoglycaemia. C (Pioglitazone) is wrong because thiazolidinediones do not directly cause hypoglycaemia. D (Metformin) is wrong because metformin alone rarely causes hypoglycaemia.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics; Chapter: Diabetes Mellitus)</em>`},
    {q:'Which oral hypoglycemic drug decreases hepatic glucose output and improves peripheral glucose utilization?',o:['Repaglinide','Acarbose','Pioglitazone','Metformin'],a:3,
    e:`Metformin decreases hepatic glucose output through AMP-activated protein kinase (AMPK) activation in hepatocytes. AMPK suppresses gluconeogenic gene expression and inhibits gluconeogenesis directly, reducing hepatic glucose output (especially fasting glucose).<br><br>Metformin also improves peripheral insulin sensitivity and reduces intestinal glucose absorption. It does not directly stimulate insulin secretion. The drug is excreted unchanged in urine, requiring dose adjustment with renal impairment. Lactic acidosis is a rare but serious complication.<br><br>D (Metformin) is correct because reducing hepatic glucose output via AMPK is its main mechanism. A (Glipizide) is wrong because sulfonylureas stimulate insulin secretion. B (Acarbose) is wrong because acarbose delays carbohydrate absorption. C (Pioglitazone) is wrong because thiazolidinediones primarily improve insulin sensitivity.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Pancreatic Hormones and Antidiabetic Drugs)</em>`},
    {q:'Which drug reduces postprandial hyperglycemia by inhibiting intestinal alpha-glucosidase enzymes?',o:['Metformin','Acarbose','Glibenclamide','Pioglitazone'],a:1,
    e:`Acarbose reduces postprandial hyperglycaemia by inhibiting intestinal alpha-glucosidase enzymes (sucrase, maltase, glucoamylase). This delays complex carbohydrate breakdown to monosaccharides, blunting postprandial glucose rises.<br><br>Acarbose has minimal systemic absorption (under 2 percent). Side effects are predominantly GI: flatulence, bloating, diarrhoea (from undigested carbohydrate fermentation by colonic bacteria). It is rarely used as monotherapy due to limited efficacy. Hypoglycaemia from acarbose alone is uncommon (treated with glucose, not sucrose, since acarbose blocks sucrose breakdown).<br><br>B (Acarbose) is correct because alpha-glucosidase inhibition reduces postprandial hyperglycaemia. A (Glipizide) is wrong because sulfonylureas stimulate insulin secretion. C (Pioglitazone) is wrong because thiazolidinediones improve insulin sensitivity. D (Metformin) is wrong because metformin reduces hepatic glucose production.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Pancreatic Hormones and Antidiabetic Drugs)</em>`},
    {q:'Which oral hypoglycemic drug stimulates pancreatic insulin secretion by acting on sulfonylurea receptors?',o:['Metformin','Acarbose','Glibenclamide','Sitagliptin'],a:2,
    e:`Glibenclamide (glyburide) stimulates pancreatic insulin secretion by binding to SUR1 (sulfonylurea receptor 1) on pancreatic β-cell ATP-sensitive potassium channels. This closes the K+ channels, depolarises the cell, opens voltage-gated calcium channels and triggers insulin secretion.<br><br>Side effects include hypoglycaemia (most common) and weight gain. Long-acting sulfonylureas (glibenclamide, glimepiride) cause more prolonged hypoglycaemia. Glibenclamide is used in gestational diabetes in some centres but has mixed safety data; insulin and metformin remain preferred.<br><br>C (Glibenclamide) is correct because it stimulates pancreatic insulin secretion via SUR1. A (Metformin) is wrong because metformin does not stimulate insulin secretion. B (Acarbose) is wrong because acarbose delays carbohydrate absorption. D (Pioglitazone) is wrong because thiazolidinediones improve insulin sensitivity.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Pancreatic Hormones and Antidiabetic Drugs)</em>`},
    {q:'Which oral hypoglycemic drug improves insulin sensitivity without directly stimulating insulin release?',o:['Chlorpropamide','Glibenclamide','Repaglinide','Metformin'],a:3,
    e:`Metformin improves insulin sensitivity without stimulating insulin secretion. It activates AMP-activated protein kinase (AMPK) in hepatocytes, suppressing gluconeogenesis and reducing hepatic glucose output, while improving peripheral insulin sensitivity in muscle and adipose tissue.<br><br>Because metformin does not stimulate insulin secretion, it does not cause hypoglycaemia as monotherapy. This is a major advantage over sulfonylureas in pregnancy and elderly patients. Metformin crosses the placenta but is generally considered safe in pregnancy.<br><br>D (Metformin) is correct because it improves insulin sensitivity without stimulating insulin secretion. A (Glipizide) is wrong because sulfonylureas stimulate insulin secretion. B (Acarbose) is wrong because acarbose delays carbohydrate absorption. C (Pioglitazone) is wrong because while it improves insulin sensitivity, it acts via PPAR-γ and is avoided in pregnancy.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Pancreatic Hormones and Antidiabetic Drugs)</em>`},
    {q:'Which oral hypoglycemic drug primarily delays digestion of complex carbohydrates in the small intestine?',o:['Metformin','Acarbose','Pioglitazone','Sitagliptin'],a:1,
    e:`Acarbose primarily delays digestion of complex carbohydrates by competitively inhibiting intestinal alpha-glucosidase enzymes (sucrase, maltase, glucoamylase). This delays breakdown of disaccharides and oligosaccharides to monosaccharides, blunting postprandial glucose rises.<br><br>Acarbose has minimal systemic absorption (under 2 percent). Side effects are predominantly GI: flatulence, bloating, diarrhoea (from undigested carbohydrate fermentation by colonic bacteria). It is rarely used as monotherapy due to limited efficacy. Hypoglycaemia from acarbose alone is uncommon.<br><br>B (Acarbose) is correct because alpha-glucosidase inhibition delays carbohydrate digestion. A (Glipizide) is wrong because sulfonylureas stimulate insulin secretion. C (Metformin) is wrong because metformin reduces hepatic glucose production. D (Pioglitazone) is wrong because thiazolidinediones improve insulin sensitivity.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Pancreatic Hormones and Antidiabetic Drugs)</em>`},
    {q:'Which oral hypoglycemic drug class improves insulin sensitivity through PPAR-γ receptor activation?',o:['Thiazolidinediones','Biguanides','Alpha-glucosidase inhibitors','Sulfonylureas'],a:0,
    e:`Thiazolidinediones (TZDs: pioglitazone, rosiglitazone) improve insulin sensitivity by activating peroxisome proliferator-activated receptor gamma (PPAR-γ). PPAR-γ activation alters transcription of genes involved in glucose and lipid metabolism, increasing glucose uptake in muscle and adipose tissue.<br><br>Side effects include fluid retention, weight gain, increased risk of heart failure, bone fractures (especially in postmenopausal women) and bladder cancer (controversial). TZDs are avoided in pregnancy due to limited safety data. Insulin and metformin are preferred for gestational diabetes.<br><br>A (Thiazolidinediones) is correct because they improve insulin sensitivity via PPAR-γ. B (Sulfonylureas) is wrong because they stimulate insulin secretion. C (Biguanides) is wrong because metformin acts through AMPK, not PPAR-γ. D (Alpha-glucosidase inhibitors) is wrong because acarbose delays carbohydrate absorption.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Pancreatic Hormones and Antidiabetic Drugs)</em>`},
    {q:'Which drug is commonly used for type 2 diabetes and may also be used for gestational diabetes when insulin is not feasible?',o:['Repaglinide','Pioglitazone','Metformin','Acarbose'],a:2,
    e:`Metformin is commonly used for type 2 diabetes and may also be used in some pregnant women with gestational diabetes. It reduces hepatic glucose production, improves peripheral insulin sensitivity and reduces intestinal glucose absorption.<br><br>In type 2 diabetes, metformin is first-line oral therapy due to weight neutrality, low hypoglycaemia risk and cardiovascular benefits. In gestational diabetes, it is an alternative to insulin when diet and exercise fail. Metformin crosses the placenta but is generally considered safe in pregnancy.<br><br>C (Metformin) is correct because it is widely used in both type 2 and gestational diabetes. A (Glipizide) is wrong because sulfonylureas are not first-line in either context. B (Acarbose) is wrong because it has limited efficacy. D (Pioglitazone) is wrong because thiazolidinediones are avoided in pregnancy.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics; Chapter: Diabetes Mellitus)</em>`},
    {q:'Which oral hypoglycemic drug primarily reduces fasting plasma glucose levels?',o:['Acarbose','Metformin','Repaglinide','Nateglinide'],a:1,
    e:`Metformin primarily reduces fasting plasma glucose by inhibiting hepatic gluconeogenesis. Metformin activates AMP-activated protein kinase (AMPK) in hepatocytes, suppressing gluconeogenic gene expression and reducing hepatic glucose output, particularly during the fasting state.<br><br>Metformin also improves peripheral insulin sensitivity and reduces intestinal glucose absorption. It does not directly stimulate insulin secretion, so does not cause hypoglycaemia as monotherapy. The drug is excreted unchanged in urine, requiring dose adjustment with renal impairment.<br><br>B (Metformin) is correct because reducing fasting glucose via hepatic gluconeogenesis inhibition is its primary action. A (Glipizide) is wrong because sulfonylureas stimulate insulin secretion. C (Acarbose) is wrong because acarbose primarily affects postprandial glucose. D (Pioglitazone) is wrong because thiazolidinediones primarily improve insulin sensitivity.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Pancreatic Hormones and Antidiabetic Drugs)</em>`},
    {q:'Which drug increases insulin release through closure of ATP-sensitive potassium channels in β-cells?',o:['Biguanides','Alpha-glucosidase inhibitors','Sulfonylureas','DPP-4 inhibitors'],a:2,
    e:`Sulfonylureas increase insulin release through closure of ATP-sensitive potassium channels on pancreatic β-cells. Sulfonylureas bind to SUR1 (sulfonylurea receptor 1) on these K+ channels, closing them, depolarising the cell, opening voltage-gated calcium channels and triggering insulin secretion.<br><br>This is the same final pathway used physiologically by glucose-stimulated insulin secretion (where intracellular ATP rises and closes K+ channels). Side effects include hypoglycaemia and weight gain. Sulfonylureas require functioning β-cells.<br><br>C (Sulfonylureas) is correct because they close ATP-sensitive K+ channels via SUR1 binding. A (Biguanides) is wrong because metformin reduces hepatic glucose production. B (Thiazolidinediones) is wrong because TZDs improve insulin sensitivity via PPAR-γ. D (Alpha-glucosidase inhibitors) is wrong because acarbose delays carbohydrate absorption.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Pancreatic Hormones and Antidiabetic Drugs)</em>`},
    {q:'Which oral hypoglycemic drug delays glucose absorption in the intestine and mainly affects postprandial glucose levels?',o:['Metformin','Pioglitazone','Repaglinide','Acarbose'],a:3,
    e:`Acarbose delays glucose absorption in the intestine by competitively inhibiting intestinal alpha-glucosidase enzymes (sucrase, maltase, glucoamylase). This delays complex carbohydrate breakdown to monosaccharides, blunting postprandial glucose rises.<br><br>Acarbose has minimal systemic absorption (under 2 percent). Side effects are predominantly GI: flatulence, bloating, diarrhoea (from undigested carbohydrate fermentation by colonic bacteria). It is rarely used as monotherapy due to limited efficacy. Hypoglycaemia from acarbose alone is uncommon.<br><br>D (Acarbose) is correct because alpha-glucosidase inhibition delays intestinal glucose absorption. A (Glipizide) is wrong because sulfonylureas stimulate insulin secretion. B (Metformin) is wrong because metformin reduces hepatic glucose production. C (Pioglitazone) is wrong because thiazolidinediones improve insulin sensitivity.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Pancreatic Hormones and Antidiabetic Drugs)</em>`},
    {q:'Which oral hypoglycemic drug may cause gastrointestinal side effects but rarely causes hypoglycemia?',o:['Metformin','Glibenclamide','Repaglinide','Chlorpropamide'],a:0,
    e:`Metformin causes gastrointestinal side effects (nausea, vomiting, abdominal cramps, diarrhoea, metallic taste) in 20 to 30 percent of users. Side effects are dose-related and often improve with continued use.<br><br>Starting at low dose (500 mg once daily) and titrating up, taking with meals, and using extended-release formulations improve tolerability. Lactic acidosis is a rare but serious complication, especially with renal impairment, hypoxia or sepsis. Hypoglycaemia is uncommon with metformin monotherapy.<br><br>A (Metformin) is correct because GI side effects are most common with metformin. B (Glipizide) is wrong because sulfonylureas cause hypoglycaemia, not GI symptoms. C (Pioglitazone) is wrong because thiazolidinediones cause fluid retention and weight gain. D (Insulin) is wrong because insulin does not cause GI side effects.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Pancreatic Hormones and Antidiabetic Drugs)</em>`},
    {q:'Which oral hypoglycemic drug improves insulin sensitivity in skeletal muscle and adipose tissue?',o:['Glibenclamide','Pioglitazone','Repaglinide','Acarbose'],a:1,
    e:`Pioglitazone improves insulin sensitivity in muscle and adipose tissue by activating peroxisome proliferator-activated receptor gamma (PPAR-γ). PPAR-γ activation alters transcription of genes involved in glucose and lipid metabolism, increasing glucose uptake in muscle and adipose tissue.<br><br>Side effects include fluid retention, weight gain, increased risk of heart failure, bone fractures (especially in postmenopausal women) and bladder cancer (controversial). Pioglitazone is avoided in pregnancy due to limited safety data.<br><br>B (Pioglitazone) is correct because TZDs improve insulin sensitivity in peripheral tissues via PPAR-γ. A (Glipizide) is wrong because sulfonylureas stimulate insulin secretion. C (Acarbose) is wrong because acarbose delays carbohydrate absorption. D (Metformin) is wrong because while it improves insulin sensitivity, the primary effect is on hepatic glucose production rather than peripheral tissues.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Pancreatic Hormones and Antidiabetic Drugs)</em>`},
    {q:'Which oral hypoglycemic drug works primarily by decreasing hepatic gluconeogenesis?',o:['Sitagliptin','Glibenclamide','Acarbose','Metformin'],a:3,
    e:`Metformin works primarily by decreasing hepatic glucose production. Metformin activates AMP-activated protein kinase (AMPK) in hepatocytes, suppressing gluconeogenesis and reducing hepatic glucose output (especially fasting glucose).<br><br>Metformin also improves peripheral insulin sensitivity and reduces intestinal glucose absorption. It does not directly stimulate insulin secretion. The drug is excreted unchanged in urine, requiring dose adjustment with renal impairment. Lactic acidosis is a rare but serious complication.<br><br>D (Metformin) is correct because reducing hepatic glucose production is its primary mechanism. A (Glipizide) is wrong because sulfonylureas stimulate insulin secretion. B (Acarbose) is wrong because acarbose delays carbohydrate absorption. C (Pioglitazone) is wrong because thiazolidinediones primarily improve peripheral insulin sensitivity.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Pancreatic Hormones and Antidiabetic Drugs)</em>`},
    {q:'Which oral hypoglycemic drug stimulates insulin release and may cause hypoglycemia if meals are skipped?',o:['Metformin','Pioglitazone','Glibenclamide','Acarbose'],a:2,
    e:`Glibenclamide stimulates insulin release and may cause hypoglycaemia. Glibenclamide binds to SUR1 on pancreatic β-cell ATP-sensitive potassium channels, closing them, depolarising the cell, opening voltage-gated calcium channels and triggering insulin secretion.<br><br>Long-acting sulfonylureas (glibenclamide, glimepiride) cause more prolonged hypoglycaemia than short-acting ones. Risk is increased in elderly, renal/hepatic impairment, missed meals, alcohol and drug interactions. Long-acting sulfonylureas can cause prolonged neonatal hypoglycaemia if used near delivery.<br><br>C (Glibenclamide) is correct because sulfonylureas stimulate insulin release and risk hypoglycaemia. A (Metformin) is wrong because metformin alone rarely causes hypoglycaemia. B (Acarbose) is wrong because acarbose alone rarely causes hypoglycaemia. D (Pioglitazone) is wrong because thiazolidinediones do not directly cause hypoglycaemia.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Pancreatic Hormones and Antidiabetic Drugs)</em>`},
    {q:'Which oral hypoglycemic drug mainly reduces postprandial glucose spikes by delaying carbohydrate digestion?',o:['Acarbose','Pioglitazone','Repaglinide','Metformin'],a:0,
    e:`Acarbose mainly reduces postprandial glucose by competitively inhibiting intestinal alpha-glucosidase enzymes (sucrase, maltase, glucoamylase). This delays complex carbohydrate breakdown to monosaccharides, blunting postprandial glucose rises.<br><br>Acarbose has minimal systemic absorption (under 2 percent). Side effects are predominantly GI: flatulence, bloating, diarrhoea (from undigested carbohydrate fermentation by colonic bacteria). It is rarely used as monotherapy due to limited efficacy. Hypoglycaemia from acarbose alone is uncommon (treated with glucose, not sucrose).<br><br>A (Acarbose) is correct because alpha-glucosidase inhibition primarily targets postprandial glucose. B (Glipizide) is wrong because sulfonylureas have broad glucose-lowering effects. C (Metformin) is wrong because metformin primarily reduces fasting glucose. D (Pioglitazone) is wrong because thiazolidinediones improve insulin sensitivity broadly.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Pancreatic Hormones and Antidiabetic Drugs)</em>`},
    {q:'Which oral hypoglycemic drug increases insulin secretion from pancreatic β-cells via sulfonylurea receptor activation?',o:['Metformin','Glibenclamide','Pioglitazone','Acarbose'],a:1,
    e:`Glibenclamide increases insulin secretion from pancreatic β-cells. It binds to SUR1 on pancreatic β-cell ATP-sensitive potassium channels, closing them, depolarising the cell, opening voltage-gated calcium channels and triggering insulin secretion.<br><br>Side effects include hypoglycaemia (most common) and weight gain. Glibenclamide is used in gestational diabetes in some centres but has mixed safety data; insulin and metformin remain preferred. Long-acting sulfonylureas can cause prolonged neonatal hypoglycaemia if used near delivery.<br><br>B (Glibenclamide) is correct because sulfonylureas increase insulin secretion via SUR1. A (Metformin) is wrong because metformin does not stimulate insulin secretion. C (Acarbose) is wrong because acarbose delays carbohydrate absorption. D (Pioglitazone) is wrong because thiazolidinediones improve insulin sensitivity.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Pancreatic Hormones and Antidiabetic Drugs)</em>`},
    {q:'Which oral hypoglycemic drug decreases hepatic glucose production and improves insulin sensitivity?',o:['Metformin','Pioglitazone','Repaglinide','Acarbose'],a:0,
    e:`Metformin decreases hepatic glucose production through AMP-activated protein kinase (AMPK) activation in hepatocytes. AMPK suppresses gluconeogenic gene expression and inhibits gluconeogenesis directly, reducing hepatic glucose output (especially fasting glucose).<br><br>Metformin also improves peripheral insulin sensitivity and reduces intestinal glucose absorption. It does not directly stimulate insulin secretion. The drug is excreted unchanged in urine, requiring dose adjustment with renal impairment.<br><br>A (Metformin) is correct because reducing hepatic glucose production via AMPK is its main mechanism. B (Glipizide) is wrong because sulfonylureas stimulate insulin secretion. C (Acarbose) is wrong because acarbose delays carbohydrate absorption. D (Pioglitazone) is wrong because thiazolidinediones primarily improve peripheral insulin sensitivity.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Pancreatic Hormones and Antidiabetic Drugs)</em>`},
    {q:'Which oral hypoglycemic drug delays digestion of carbohydrates in the small intestine?',o:['Metformin','Pioglitazone','Acarbose','Sitagliptin'],a:2,
    e:`Acarbose delays digestion of carbohydrates by competitively inhibiting intestinal alpha-glucosidase enzymes (sucrase, maltase, glucoamylase). This delays complex carbohydrate breakdown to monosaccharides, blunting postprandial glucose rises.<br><br>Acarbose has minimal systemic absorption (under 2 percent). Side effects are predominantly GI: flatulence, bloating, diarrhoea (from undigested carbohydrate fermentation by colonic bacteria). It is rarely used as monotherapy due to limited efficacy. Hypoglycaemia from acarbose alone is uncommon (treated with glucose, not sucrose).<br><br>C (Acarbose) is correct because alpha-glucosidase inhibition delays carbohydrate digestion. A (Glipizide) is wrong because sulfonylureas stimulate insulin secretion. B (Metformin) is wrong because metformin reduces hepatic glucose production. D (Pioglitazone) is wrong because thiazolidinediones improve insulin sensitivity.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Pancreatic Hormones and Antidiabetic Drugs)</em>`},
    {q:'Which drug improves insulin sensitivity by activating PPAR-γ receptors?',o:['Metformin','Acarbose','Sitagliptin','Pioglitazone'],a:3,
    e:`Pioglitazone improves insulin sensitivity by activating PPAR-γ (peroxisome proliferator-activated receptor gamma) in nuclear receptor signalling. PPAR-γ activation alters transcription of genes involved in glucose and lipid metabolism, increasing glucose uptake in muscle and adipose tissue.<br><br>Side effects include fluid retention, weight gain, increased risk of heart failure, bone fractures (especially in postmenopausal women) and bladder cancer (controversial). Pioglitazone is avoided in pregnancy due to limited safety data. Insulin and metformin are preferred for gestational diabetes.<br><br>D (Pioglitazone) is correct because TZDs activate PPAR-γ. A (Glipizide) is wrong because sulfonylureas stimulate insulin secretion via SUR1/K+ channels. B (Metformin) is wrong because metformin works through AMPK activation. C (Acarbose) is wrong because acarbose inhibits intestinal alpha-glucosidase.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Pancreatic Hormones and Antidiabetic Drugs)</em>`},
    {q:'Which oral hypoglycemic drug may cause hypoglycemia due to increased insulin secretion?',o:['Acarbose','Metformin','Glibenclamide','Pioglitazone'],a:2,
    e:`Glibenclamide may cause hypoglycaemia due to increased insulin secretion regardless of glucose level. Sulfonylureas stimulate insulin secretion via SUR1/K+ channel closure, depolarising β-cells and triggering calcium-mediated insulin release.<br><br>Long-acting sulfonylureas (glibenclamide, glimepiride) cause more prolonged hypoglycaemia than short-acting ones. Risk is increased in elderly, renal/hepatic impairment, missed meals, alcohol and drug interactions. Long-acting sulfonylureas can cause prolonged neonatal hypoglycaemia if used near delivery.<br><br>C (Glibenclamide) is correct because sulfonylureas cause hypoglycaemia from excessive insulin secretion. A (Metformin) is wrong because metformin alone rarely causes hypoglycaemia. B (Acarbose) is wrong because acarbose alone rarely causes hypoglycaemia. D (Pioglitazone) is wrong because thiazolidinediones do not directly cause hypoglycaemia.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Pancreatic Hormones and Antidiabetic Drugs)</em>`},
    {q:'Which oral hypoglycemic drug is considered first-line therapy for type 2 diabetes mellitus?',o:['Metformin','Repaglinide','Pioglitazone','Acarbose'],a:0,
    e:`Metformin is considered first-line therapy for type 2 diabetes due to weight neutrality, low hypoglycaemia risk, cardiovascular benefits, low cost and good tolerability. It reduces hepatic glucose production, improves peripheral insulin sensitivity and reduces intestinal glucose absorption.<br><br>Side effects include GI upset (most common) and rare lactic acidosis. Contraindications include severe renal impairment (eGFR <30), severe hepatic disease, hypoxia and acute illness. Metformin is also used in some pregnant women with gestational diabetes.<br><br>A (Metformin) is correct because metformin is established first-line for type 2 diabetes. B (Pioglitazone) is wrong because thiazolidinediones are not first-line. C (Glipizide) is wrong because sulfonylureas are not first-line. D (Acarbose) is wrong because acarbose has limited efficacy.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Pancreatic Hormones and Antidiabetic Drugs)</em>`},
    {q:'Which oral hypoglycemic drug inhibits intestinal alpha-glucosidase enzymes?',o:['Metformin','Acarbose','Pioglitazone','Glibenclamide'],a:1,
    e:`Acarbose inhibits intestinal alpha-glucosidase enzymes (sucrase, maltase, glucoamylase). This delays complex carbohydrate breakdown to monosaccharides, blunting postprandial glucose rises.<br><br>Acarbose has minimal systemic absorption (under 2 percent). Side effects are predominantly GI: flatulence, bloating, diarrhoea (from undigested carbohydrate fermentation by colonic bacteria). It is rarely used as monotherapy due to limited efficacy. Hypoglycaemia from acarbose alone is uncommon (treated with glucose, not sucrose, since acarbose blocks sucrose breakdown).<br><br>B (Acarbose) is correct because it is the alpha-glucosidase inhibitor. A (Glipizide) is wrong because sulfonylureas stimulate insulin secretion. C (Metformin) is wrong because metformin reduces hepatic glucose production. D (Pioglitazone) is wrong because thiazolidinediones improve insulin sensitivity.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Pancreatic Hormones and Antidiabetic Drugs)</em>`},
    {q:'Which oral hypoglycemic drug improves insulin sensitivity in peripheral tissues via nuclear receptor activation?',o:['Metformin','Sitagliptin','Acarbose','Pioglitazone'],a:3,
    e:`Pioglitazone improves insulin sensitivity in peripheral tissues by activating PPAR-γ (peroxisome proliferator-activated receptor gamma). PPAR-γ activation alters transcription of genes involved in glucose and lipid metabolism, increasing glucose uptake in muscle and adipose tissue.<br><br>Side effects include fluid retention, weight gain, increased risk of heart failure, bone fractures (especially in postmenopausal women) and bladder cancer (controversial). Pioglitazone is avoided in pregnancy due to limited safety data.<br><br>D (Pioglitazone) is correct because TZDs improve insulin sensitivity in peripheral tissues. A (Glipizide) is wrong because sulfonylureas stimulate insulin secretion. B (Metformin) is wrong because metformin\'s primary effect is on hepatic glucose production. C (Acarbose) is wrong because acarbose delays carbohydrate absorption.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Pancreatic Hormones and Antidiabetic Drugs)</em>`},
    {q:'Which oral hypoglycemic drug stimulates pancreatic insulin secretion and may cause hypoglycemia?',o:['Metformin','Acarbose','Glibenclamide','Pioglitazone'],a:2,
    e:`Glibenclamide stimulates pancreatic insulin secretion by binding to SUR1 (sulfonylurea receptor 1) on pancreatic β-cell ATP-sensitive potassium channels. This closes the K+ channels, depolarises the cell, opens voltage-gated calcium channels and triggers insulin secretion.<br><br>Side effects include hypoglycaemia (most common) and weight gain. Glibenclamide is used in gestational diabetes in some centres but has mixed safety data; insulin and metformin remain preferred. Long-acting sulfonylureas can cause prolonged neonatal hypoglycaemia if used near delivery.<br><br>C (Glibenclamide) is correct because it stimulates pancreatic insulin secretion. A (Metformin) is wrong because metformin does not stimulate insulin secretion. B (Acarbose) is wrong because acarbose delays carbohydrate absorption. D (Pioglitazone) is wrong because thiazolidinediones improve insulin sensitivity.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Pancreatic Hormones and Antidiabetic Drugs)</em>`},
    {q:'Which oral hypoglycemic drug reduces fasting blood glucose mainly by decreasing hepatic glucose output?',o:['Acarbose','Glibenclamide','Pioglitazone','Metformin'],a:3,
    e:`Metformin reduces fasting blood glucose mainly by suppressing hepatic gluconeogenesis. Metformin activates AMP-activated protein kinase (AMPK) in hepatocytes, suppressing gluconeogenic gene expression and reducing hepatic glucose output, particularly during the fasting state.<br><br>Metformin also improves peripheral insulin sensitivity and reduces intestinal glucose absorption. It does not directly stimulate insulin secretion, so does not cause hypoglycaemia as monotherapy. The drug is excreted unchanged in urine, requiring dose adjustment with renal impairment.<br><br>D (Metformin) is correct because reducing fasting glucose via gluconeogenesis suppression is its main effect. A (Glipizide) is wrong because sulfonylureas stimulate insulin secretion. B (Acarbose) is wrong because acarbose primarily affects postprandial glucose. C (Pioglitazone) is wrong because thiazolidinediones primarily improve insulin sensitivity.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Pancreatic Hormones and Antidiabetic Drugs)</em>`},
    {q:'A pregnant woman with type 1 diabetes presents for routine antenatal care at 10 weeks. Due to placental hormone effects, insulin requirement during the first trimester is typically:',o:['Markedly increased','Slightly decreased or unchanged','Increased two-fold','Completely stopped'],a:1,
    e:`A pregnant woman with type 1 diabetes in the first trimester typically has insulin requirements that are slightly decreased or unchanged compared to pre-pregnancy. Reduced insulin requirements occur due to nausea, vomiting, reduced caloric intake and increased insulin sensitivity in early pregnancy.<br><br>Insulin requirements increase substantially in the second and third trimesters as placental hormones (human placental lactogen, cortisol, oestrogen, progesterone, prolactin) cause progressive insulin resistance. Requirements typically double or triple by term, then drop sharply after delivery.<br><br>B (Slightly decreased or unchanged) is correct because first-trimester insulin requirements are typically reduced or stable. A (Markedly increased) is wrong because marked increase occurs later, not in first trimester. C (Triple of pre-pregnancy levels) is wrong because that is the third-trimester pattern. D (Decreased to half of pre-pregnancy levels) is wrong because reductions are mild, not by half.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics; Chapter: Diabetes Mellitus)</em>`},
    {q:'Which insulin preparation has the fastest onset of action and is most suitable for controlling post-prandial glucose in gestational diabetes?',o:['Insulin lispro','Insulin glargine','NPH insulin','Insulin detemir'],a:0,
    e:`Insulin lispro has the fastest onset of action (within 5 to 15 minutes) and shortest duration (3 to 4 hours) among insulin preparations. It is a rapid-acting insulin analog used for prandial (mealtime) glucose control.<br><br>Other rapid-acting analogs include insulin aspart and insulin glulisine. Regular (soluble) insulin has slower onset (30 minutes) and longer duration (6 to 8 hours). Rapid-acting analogs are preferred in pregnancy for postprandial glucose control because they better mimic physiological insulin secretion and reduce hypoglycaemia risk.<br><br>A (Insulin lispro) is correct because it is the rapid-acting prandial insulin. B (Regular insulin) is wrong because it has slower onset and longer duration. C (NPH insulin) is wrong because it is intermediate-acting. D (Insulin glargine) is wrong because it is long-acting basal insulin.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Pancreatic Hormones and Antidiabetic Drugs)</em>`},
    {q:'A pregnant woman with poorly controlled diabetes develops severe hypoglycemia after missing a meal following insulin injection. The most appropriate immediate treatment is:',o:['Intravenous regular insulin','Intravenous sodium bicarbonate','Oral metformin','Intramuscular glucagon'],a:3,
    e:`A pregnant woman with poorly controlled diabetes developing severe hypoglycaemia and unconsciousness is treated with intramuscular glucagon 1 mg IM (or IV/SC). Glucagon stimulates hepatic glycogenolysis and gluconeogenesis, raising blood glucose within 10 to 15 minutes.<br><br>If IV access is available, IV dextrose (50 mL of 50 percent dextrose) is preferred and faster. Oral glucose is used if the patient is conscious and able to swallow. After recovery, food should be given to prevent recurrence (glucagon\'s effect is short-lived). Family members of insulin-using diabetics should be trained in glucagon administration.<br><br>D (Intramuscular glucagon) is correct because IM glucagon is the standard emergency treatment when IV is unavailable. A (Oral glucose) is wrong because the patient is unconscious and cannot swallow. B (Subcutaneous insulin) is wrong because insulin would worsen hypoglycaemia. C (Intravenous saline) is wrong because saline does not raise blood glucose.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Pancreatic Hormones and Antidiabetic Drugs)</em>`},
    {q:'Which insulin preparation is classified as an intermediate-acting insulin commonly used in pregnancy?',o:['Insulin glulisine','NPH insulin','Regular insulin','Insulin lispro'],a:1,
    e:`NPH (Neutral Protamine Hagedorn) insulin is classified as an intermediate-acting insulin with onset of 1 to 2 hours, peak at 4 to 8 hours and duration of 12 to 18 hours. It contains regular insulin combined with protamine, which delays absorption.<br><br>NPH is used as basal insulin (typically twice daily) in many regimens. It has been largely replaced by long-acting analogs (glargine, detemir, degludec) which provide more even 24-hour coverage with less hypoglycaemia. NPH remains useful in pregnancy due to extensive safety data.<br><br>B (NPH insulin) is correct because it is the intermediate-acting insulin. A (Insulin lispro) is wrong because it is rapid-acting. C (Insulin glargine) is wrong because it is long-acting. D (Regular insulin) is wrong because it is short-acting.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Pancreatic Hormones and Antidiabetic Drugs)</em>`},
    {q:'Placental hormones responsible for increased insulin resistance in the second and third trimesters include all EXCEPT:',o:['Human placental lactogen','Progesterone','Oxytocin','Cortisol'],a:2,
    e:`Placental hormones responsible for increased insulin resistance in pregnancy include human placental lactogen (hPL), cortisol, oestrogen, progesterone and prolactin. These hormones progressively rise in the second and third trimesters, causing insulin resistance and increasing insulin requirements.<br><br>Oxytocin is NOT a placental hormone responsible for insulin resistance. Oxytocin is released from the posterior pituitary for labour and lactation. The other listed hormones (insulin, glucagon and growth hormone) are not the primary placental drivers of pregnancy insulin resistance, though growth hormone has some indirect role.<br><br>C (Oxytocin) is correct because oxytocin is NOT among the placental hormones causing insulin resistance. A (Human placental lactogen) is wrong because hPL is a major cause of pregnancy insulin resistance. B (Cortisol) is wrong because cortisol contributes to insulin resistance. D (Progesterone) is wrong because progesterone contributes to insulin resistance.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics; Chapter: Diabetes Mellitus)</em>`},
    {q:'A 28-year-old pregnant woman at 30 weeks gestation with gestational diabetes requires insulin therapy. Which insulin regimen most closely mimics physiological insulin secretion?',o:['Basal-bolus regimen','Single daily NPH dose','Premixed insulin only','Weekly insulin injection'],a:0,
    e:`A 28-year-old at 30 weeks with gestational diabetes inadequately controlled on diet is best managed with a basal-bolus insulin regimen (long-acting basal insulin once daily plus rapid-acting insulin before each meal). This mimics physiological insulin secretion and provides best glycaemic control.<br><br>Insulin remains the gold standard for glycaemic control in pregnancy due to no placental transfer. Metformin is also widely used as alternative. Targets are fasting glucose <95 mg/dL, 1-hour postprandial <140 mg/dL or 2-hour postprandial <120 mg/dL.<br><br>A (Basal-bolus regimen) is correct because it provides physiological glycaemic control in pregnancy. B (Single dose of NPH at bedtime) is wrong because it does not cover postprandial glucose. C (Glibenclamide alone) is wrong because oral hypoglycaemics alone are usually inadequate at this stage. D (Acarbose alone) is wrong because acarbose has limited efficacy.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics; Chapter: Diabetes Mellitus)</em>`},
    {q:'During labor, insulin requirements in diabetic women usually:',o:['Increase dramatically','Remain unchanged','Decrease due to reduced caloric intake and exertion','Become unpredictable and cannot be estimated'],a:2,
    e:`During labour, insulin requirements in diabetic women usually decrease due to reduced caloric intake (NPO during active labour) and increased exertion (skeletal muscle glucose uptake). Insulin requirements drop further to near zero immediately after placental delivery (loss of placental insulin-resistance hormones).<br><br>Management during labour includes IV insulin infusion adjusted to capillary glucose every 1 to 2 hours, IV dextrose for caloric support and continuous CTG monitoring. After delivery, insulin requirements return to pre-pregnancy levels within 24 to 72 hours.<br><br>C (Decrease due to reduced caloric intake and exertion) is correct because labour reduces insulin needs. A (Markedly increase) is wrong because requirements decrease, not increase, during labour. B (Remain unchanged) is wrong because requirements change significantly. D (Triple compared to third trimester) is wrong because requirements decrease, not increase.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics; Chapter: Diabetes Mellitus)</em>`},
    {q:'Which insulin analog is considered a long-acting basal insulin with relatively stable 24-hour activity?',o:['Insulin glargine','Insulin lispro','Regular insulin','Insulin aspart'],a:0,
    e:`Insulin glargine is a long-acting basal insulin analog that provides relatively constant 24-hour insulin coverage. It is modified to have low solubility at neutral pH (acid solution at injection precipitates in subcutaneous tissue), producing slow gradual absorption with no significant peak.<br><br>Onset is 1 to 2 hours, peak is essentially absent (peakless), duration is 22 to 24 hours. Used as once-daily basal insulin in basal-bolus regimens. Other long-acting analogs include detemir (12 to 24 hours) and degludec (>40 hours). All are used as alternatives to NPH for more even basal coverage.<br><br>A (Insulin glargine) is correct because it is the long-acting basal analog. B (Insulin lispro) is wrong because it is rapid-acting. C (NPH insulin) is wrong because it is intermediate-acting with a peak. D (Regular insulin) is wrong because it is short-acting.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Pancreatic Hormones and Antidiabetic Drugs)</em>`},
    {q:'A pregnant woman on insulin therapy develops recurrent early morning hyperglycemia due to nocturnal growth hormone surge. This phenomenon is known as:',o:['Somogyi effect','Insulin rebound syndrome','Reactive hyperglycemia','Dawn phenomenon'],a:3,
    e:`A pregnant woman on insulin therapy developing recurrent early morning hyperglycaemia has the dawn phenomenon. Early morning rise in cortisol, growth hormone and other counter-regulatory hormones increases hepatic glucose production around 4 to 8 AM, raising blood glucose.<br><br>The dawn phenomenon is distinct from the Somogyi effect (rebound morning hyperglycaemia after overnight hypoglycaemia). Distinguishing them requires checking 3 AM blood glucose: low (Somogyi) versus normal/high (dawn). Treatment of dawn phenomenon is to give basal insulin later in the evening or use an insulin pump to increase pre-dawn delivery.<br><br>D (Dawn phenomenon) is correct because counter-regulatory hormone surge causes early morning hyperglycaemia. A (Somogyi effect) is wrong because Somogyi is rebound from overnight hypoglycaemia, distinguished by 3 AM low glucose. B (Hyperinsulinemia) is wrong because the issue is hyperglycaemia, not hyperinsulinaemia. C (Insulin resistance) is wrong because while insulin resistance contributes, the specific early morning pattern is the dawn phenomenon.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Pancreatic Hormones and Antidiabetic Drugs)</em>`},
    {q:'The Somogyi effect in insulin-treated pregnant diabetics refers to:',o:['Persistent daytime hyperglycemia','Morning hyperglycemia after nocturnal hypoglycemia','Severe post-prandial hypoglycemia','Insulin resistance due to placental hormones'],a:1,
    e:`The Somogyi effect refers to morning hyperglycaemia after nocturnal hypoglycaemia. Overnight hypoglycaemia (often from excessive evening basal insulin) triggers counter-regulatory hormone release (cortisol, growth hormone, glucagon, epinephrine), causing rebound hyperglycaemia by morning.<br><br>Distinguished from dawn phenomenon (early morning rise from counter-regulatory hormones without overnight hypoglycaemia) by checking 3 AM blood glucose: low (Somogyi) versus normal/high (dawn). Treatment of Somogyi is to reduce evening basal insulin, not increase it (which would worsen hypoglycaemia and rebound).<br><br>B (Morning hyperglycemia after nocturnal hypoglycemia) is correct because Somogyi is rebound from overnight hypoglycaemia. A (Persistent hyperglycemia throughout the day) is wrong because Somogyi is specifically a morning rebound phenomenon. C (Insulin resistance only) is wrong because Somogyi involves rebound from hypoglycaemia, not just insulin resistance. D (Postprandial hyperglycemia) is wrong because Somogyi is a fasting morning phenomenon, not postprandial.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Pancreatic Hormones and Antidiabetic Drugs)</em>`},
    {q:'Which of the following insulin preparations has NO pronounced peak effect and provides relatively constant basal insulin levels?',o:['NPH insulin','Regular insulin','Insulin glargine','Insulin lispro'],a:2,
    e:`Insulin glargine has no pronounced peak and provides relatively constant 24-hour insulin coverage. It is modified to have low solubility at neutral pH (acid solution at injection precipitates in subcutaneous tissue), producing slow gradual absorption with no significant peak.<br><br>Onset is 1 to 2 hours, peak is essentially absent (peakless), duration is 22 to 24 hours. Used as once-daily basal insulin in basal-bolus regimens. NPH insulin has a peak at 4 to 8 hours; rapid-acting analogs peak at 1 to 2 hours; regular insulin peaks at 2 to 4 hours.<br><br>C (Insulin glargine) is correct because it is the peakless long-acting basal analog. A (NPH insulin) is wrong because it has a pronounced peak at 4 to 8 hours. B (Insulin lispro) is wrong because it has a rapid peak at 1 to 2 hours. D (Regular insulin) is wrong because it has a peak at 2 to 4 hours.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Pancreatic Hormones and Antidiabetic Drugs)</em>`},
    {q:'A pregnant woman with gestational diabetes is started on insulin. Which factor most significantly increases the risk of maternal hypoglycemia?',o:['Late pregnancy insulin resistance','Skipping meals after insulin injection','Increased placental lactogen','Fetal macrosomia'],a:1,
    e:`A pregnant woman with gestational diabetes started on insulin should avoid skipping meals after insulin injection because this will cause hypoglycaemia. Insulin lowers blood glucose; if a meal is skipped, glucose drops too low.<br><br>Patient education includes: take insulin only when planning to eat (rapid-acting before meals), recognise hypoglycaemia symptoms (sweating, tremor, palpitations, hunger, confusion), keep glucose tablets/sweets available, monitor glucose regularly, do not exercise without a snack if pre-exercise glucose is low.<br><br>B (Skipping meals after insulin injection) is correct because insulin without food causes hypoglycaemia. A (Eating high-fibre foods) is wrong because high-fibre foods are good for diabetic management. C (Regular exercise with caution) is wrong because exercise is beneficial with appropriate precautions. D (Self-monitoring blood glucose) is wrong because monitoring is essential, not avoided.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics; Chapter: Diabetes Mellitus)</em>`},
    {q:'In diabetic ketoacidosis during pregnancy, the insulin of choice for initial treatment is:',o:['Subcutaneous insulin glargine','Subcutaneous NPH insulin','Intramuscular insulin detemir','Intravenous regular insulin'],a:3,
    e:`Diabetic ketoacidosis (DKA) during pregnancy is treated with intravenous regular (soluble) insulin infusion. Initial loading is 0.1 unit/kg IV bolus followed by 0.1 unit/kg/hour infusion, adjusted to glucose response.<br><br>Other DKA management includes IV fluid resuscitation (large volumes of normal saline, then half-normal saline), potassium replacement (insulin shifts K+ intracellularly, causing hypokalaemia), and bicarbonate only if pH <6.9. Glucose is added to fluids when blood glucose drops to <250 mg/dL to prevent hypoglycaemia while continuing insulin to clear ketones.<br><br>D (Intravenous regular insulin) is correct because IV regular insulin is the standard for DKA. A (Subcutaneous insulin lispro) is wrong because absorption is unreliable in DKA (dehydration, poor perfusion). B (Oral metformin) is wrong because oral therapy cannot achieve rapid control in DKA. C (Subcutaneous NPH insulin) is wrong because absorption is unreliable in DKA.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Pancreatic Hormones and Antidiabetic Drugs)</em>`},
    {q:'Which insulin analog is most commonly used as rapid-acting insulin in pregnancy for meal coverage?',o:['Insulin lispro','Insulin detemir','Insulin glargine','NPH insulin'],a:0,
    e:`Insulin lispro is the most commonly used rapid-acting insulin analog before meals (\'mealtime\' or \'prandial\' insulin). It has fast onset (5 to 15 minutes), peak at 1 to 2 hours and short duration (3 to 4 hours), better matching postprandial glucose rise than regular insulin.<br><br>Other rapid-acting analogs include insulin aspart and insulin glulisine. Rapid-acting analogs are preferred over regular insulin in pregnancy for postprandial glucose control because they better mimic physiological insulin secretion and reduce hypoglycaemia risk.<br><br>A (Insulin lispro) is correct because it is the standard rapid-acting prandial insulin. B (NPH insulin) is wrong because it is intermediate-acting basal. C (Insulin glargine) is wrong because it is long-acting basal. D (Regular insulin) is wrong because while it can be used prandially, lispro is preferred for the rapid action.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Pancreatic Hormones and Antidiabetic Drugs)</em>`},
    {q:'The primary mechanism by which insulin lowers blood glucose is:',o:['Inhibition of hepatic glycogen formation','Stimulation of peripheral glucose uptake via GLUT-4','Increased renal glucose excretion','Increased intestinal glucose absorption'],a:1,
    e:`Insulin lowers blood glucose primarily through stimulation of peripheral glucose uptake via GLUT-4 transporters in muscle and adipose tissue. Insulin binds to its tyrosine kinase receptor, triggering signalling cascades (IRS-1/2, PI3K, Akt) that translocate GLUT-4 transporters from intracellular vesicles to the cell membrane.<br><br>Insulin also suppresses hepatic gluconeogenesis and glycogenolysis, stimulates hepatic glycogen synthesis, and promotes lipogenesis and protein synthesis. Insulin\'s overall effect is anabolic: it shifts glucose into storage forms (glycogen, triglycerides) and promotes growth.<br><br>B (Stimulation of peripheral glucose uptake via GLUT-4) is correct because GLUT-4 translocation is the primary glucose-lowering mechanism. A (Direct inhibition of liver) is wrong because while insulin suppresses hepatic glucose production, peripheral GLUT-4 effect is the primary glucose-lowering action. C (Stimulation of pancreatic glucagon) is wrong because insulin suppresses, not stimulates, glucagon. D (Increased glucose absorption from gut) is wrong because insulin does not act on intestinal absorption.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Pancreatic Hormones and Antidiabetic Drugs)</em>`},
    {q:'Which maternal complication is most directly associated with excessive insulin therapy during pregnancy?',o:['Maternal hypoglycemia','Maternal hyperglycemia','Polyhydramnios','Fetal macrosomia'],a:0,
    e:`Maternal hypoglycaemia is the maternal complication most directly associated with insulin therapy. Insulin lowers blood glucose, and excessive dosing, missed meals or unaccustomed exertion can cause hypoglycaemia.<br><br>Symptoms include sweating, tremor, palpitations, hunger, confusion progressing to seizures and coma. Treatment is oral glucose if conscious, IV dextrose or IM glucagon if unconscious. Hypoglycaemia awareness may be reduced in long-standing diabetes. Insulin doses must be adjusted carefully throughout pregnancy as requirements change.<br><br>A (Maternal hypoglycemia) is correct because hypoglycaemia is the most common insulin complication. B (Hyperkalemia) is wrong because insulin lowers, not raises, potassium. C (Hyperglycemia) is wrong because insulin lowers glucose. D (Hypothyroidism) is wrong because insulin does not affect thyroid function.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Pancreatic Hormones and Antidiabetic Drugs)</em>`},
    {q:'A pregnant diabetic woman develops unexplained fasting hyperglycemia despite adequate evening insulin dosing. Continuous glucose monitoring reveals nocturnal hypoglycemia. The appropriate management is:',o:['Increase evening insulin dose','Omit evening insulin','Start metformin','Reduce evening insulin dose'],a:3,
    e:`A pregnant diabetic woman developing unexplained fasting hyperglycaemia with overnight hypoglycaemia (Somogyi effect) should reduce evening insulin dose, not increase it. Excessive evening basal insulin causes overnight hypoglycaemia, triggering counter-regulatory hormone surge and rebound morning hyperglycaemia.<br><br>Distinguished from dawn phenomenon (early morning rise from counter-regulatory hormones without overnight hypoglycaemia) by checking 3 AM blood glucose: low (Somogyi) versus normal/high (dawn). Increasing evening insulin would worsen the rebound. Reducing evening insulin and giving a bedtime snack often resolves the issue.<br><br>D (Reduce evening insulin dose) is correct because Somogyi requires reducing, not increasing, evening insulin. A (Increase evening insulin dose) is wrong because this would worsen overnight hypoglycaemia and rebound. B (Add metformin) is wrong because metformin is not first-line in pregnancy when insulin is established. C (Continue same regimen) is wrong because the regimen needs adjustment.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics; Chapter: Diabetes Mellitus)</em>`},
    {q:'Which insulin preparation has the longest duration of action among the following?',o:['Insulin lispro','Regular insulin','Insulin glargine','NPH insulin'],a:2,
    e:`Insulin glargine has the longest duration of action among traditional insulin preparations (22 to 24 hours), providing relatively constant 24-hour coverage with no pronounced peak. Insulin degludec (an ultra-long-acting analog) has duration over 40 hours.<br><br>Onset of glargine is 1 to 2 hours, peak is essentially absent (peakless), duration is 22 to 24 hours. Used as once-daily basal insulin in basal-bolus regimens. NPH (intermediate, 12 to 18 hours), regular (short, 6 to 8 hours) and rapid-acting analogs (3 to 4 hours) all have shorter duration.<br><br>C (Insulin glargine) is correct because it has the longest duration among standard analogs. A (Insulin lispro) is wrong because it has the shortest duration (3 to 4 hours). B (Regular insulin) is wrong because duration is 6 to 8 hours. D (NPH insulin) is wrong because duration is 12 to 18 hours.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Pancreatic Hormones and Antidiabetic Drugs)</em>`},
    {q:'In pregnancy, the most common indication for initiating insulin therapy in gestational diabetes is:',o:['Presence of fetal macrosomia','Failure of diet and exercise to maintain euglycemia','Maternal obesity','Family history of diabetes'],a:1,
    e:`In pregnancy, the most common indication for initiating insulin in gestational diabetes is failure of diet and exercise to maintain euglycaemia. Glycaemic targets are fasting glucose <95 mg/dL, 1-hour postprandial <140 mg/dL or 2-hour postprandial <120 mg/dL.<br><br>Diet and exercise are first-line. If glucose targets are not achieved within 1 to 2 weeks, pharmacologic therapy is added. Insulin remains the gold standard. Metformin is also widely used as alternative. Glyburide is used in some centres. Pioglitazone is avoided due to limited safety data.<br><br>B (Failure of diet and exercise to maintain euglycemia) is correct because diet failure is the standard indication. A (Diagnosis of gestational diabetes alone) is wrong because diet and exercise are tried first. C (Maternal age >35 years) is wrong because age alone is not an indication. D (Family history of diabetes) is wrong because family history alone is not an indication.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics; Chapter: Diabetes Mellitus)</em>`},
    {q:'Which fetal complication is most strongly associated with maternal hyperglycemia despite insulin therapy?',o:['Neural tube defect','Fetal growth restriction','Oligohydramnios','Fetal macrosomia'],a:3,
    e:`Maternal hyperglycaemia in pregnancy is most strongly associated with fetal macrosomia (birth weight >4 kg or >90th centile). Maternal hyperglycaemia crosses the placenta, stimulating fetal pancreatic insulin secretion (Pedersen hypothesis). Fetal hyperinsulinaemia drives accelerated growth, particularly truncal fat deposition.<br><br>Other diabetes-related fetal complications include congenital anomalies (cardiac, neural tube) from first-trimester hyperglycaemia, polyhydramnios (fetal polyuria from hyperglycaemia), and neonatal hypoglycaemia after delivery. Tight glycaemic control reduces these risks.<br><br>D (Fetal macrosomia) is correct because maternal hyperglycaemia causes fetal hyperinsulinaemia and macrosomia. A (Microcephaly) is wrong because microcephaly is associated with infections (Zika, CMV), not maternal hyperglycaemia. B (Pulmonary hypoplasia) is wrong because pulmonary hypoplasia is associated with oligohydramnios. C (Skeletal dysplasia) is wrong because skeletal dysplasia is genetic, not from hyperglycaemia.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics; Chapter: Diabetes Mellitus)</em>`},
    {q:'A pregnant woman at 28 weeks presents with acute pyelonephritis. Which antibiotic is most appropriate as first-line empirical therapy?',o:['Tetracycline','Ciprofloxacin','Ceftriaxone','Chloramphenicol'],a:2,
    e:`A pregnant woman at 28 weeks with acute pyelonephritis is treated with ceftriaxone (third-generation cephalosporin) 1 to 2 g IV daily as empirical first-line therapy. Ceftriaxone covers most uropathogens (E. coli, Klebsiella, Proteus) and is safe in pregnancy.<br><br>Other suitable agents include cefuroxime, cefotaxime and ampicillin plus gentamicin. Ciprofloxacin is generally avoided due to cartilage toxicity. Trimethoprim-sulfamethoxazole is avoided in first trimester (folate antagonism) and near term (kernicterus). Treatment is typically IV until afebrile for 24 to 48 hours, then oral for 14 days total.<br><br>C (Ceftriaxone) is correct because it is first-line for acute pyelonephritis in pregnancy. A (Tetracycline) is wrong because tetracyclines are contraindicated in pregnancy (tooth staining, bone effects). B (Ciprofloxacin) is wrong because fluoroquinolones are avoided due to cartilage toxicity. D (Doxycycline) is wrong because it is also a tetracycline.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics; Chapter: Renal and Urinary Tract Disorders)</em>`},
    {q:'Which antibiotic is contraindicated in pregnancy because it causes permanent discoloration of fetal teeth and inhibition of bone growth?',o:['Tetracycline','Cephalexin','Erythromycin','Amoxicillin'],a:0,
    e:`Tetracycline is contraindicated in pregnancy because it causes fetal tooth discoloration (yellow-brown staining) and inhibition of bone growth. Tetracycline binds calcium and chelates to developing bone and teeth from approximately the fourth month of gestation.<br><br>The drug crosses the placenta freely and concentrates in calcifying tissues. It is avoided in pregnancy and during breastfeeding, and in children under 8 years. Penicillins, cephalosporins and macrolides are safer alternatives. Doxycycline shares the same effects.<br><br>A (Tetracycline) is correct because tooth staining and bone effects are established teratogenic effects. B (Penicillin) is wrong because penicillin is safe in pregnancy. C (Erythromycin) is wrong because macrolides are safe. D (Cephalexin) is wrong because cephalosporins are safe.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Tetracyclines, Macrolides, Clindamycin, Chloramphenicol, Streptogramins, and Oxazolidinones)</em>`},
    {q:'A pregnant woman with asymptomatic bacteriuria caused by E. coli requires treatment. Which oral antibiotic is commonly recommended?',o:['Ciprofloxacin','Doxycycline','Chloramphenicol','Nitrofurantoin'],a:3,
    e:`A pregnant woman with asymptomatic bacteriuria caused by E. coli is treated with nitrofurantoin (50 to 100 mg PO 4 times daily for 5 to 7 days). Nitrofurantoin is concentrated in urine and effective against most uropathogens with minimal systemic effects.<br><br>Asymptomatic bacteriuria in pregnancy is treated to prevent progression to pyelonephritis. Other suitable agents include amoxicillin, cephalexin and cefpodoxime. Trimethoprim-sulfamethoxazole is avoided in first trimester and near term. Nitrofurantoin is avoided in late pregnancy (after 36 weeks) due to risk of neonatal haemolytic anaemia.<br><br>D (Nitrofurantoin) is correct because it is a standard agent for asymptomatic bacteriuria in pregnancy. A (Tetracycline) is wrong because tetracyclines are contraindicated. B (Doxycycline) is wrong because it is also a tetracycline. C (Ciprofloxacin) is wrong because fluoroquinolones are avoided due to cartilage toxicity.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics; Chapter: Renal and Urinary Tract Disorders)</em>`},
    {q:'Nitrofurantoin is generally avoided in late pregnancy because of the risk of:',o:['Neonatal hemolytic anemia','Persistent pulmonary hypertension','Fetal hypothyroidism','Neural tube defects'],a:0,
    e:`Nitrofurantoin is generally avoided in late pregnancy (after 36 weeks) because of risk of neonatal haemolytic anaemia. Nitrofurantoin generates oxidative stress in red cells; mature neonatal red cells with reduced glutathione activity (especially in G6PD-deficient infants) are susceptible to oxidative haemolysis.<br><br>Nitrofurantoin is safe earlier in pregnancy and is an established first-line for asymptomatic bacteriuria and uncomplicated UTI. Other agents preferred near term include amoxicillin and cephalexin. Acute pyelonephritis is treated with IV ceftriaxone, cefuroxime or ampicillin/gentamicin.<br><br>A (Neonatal hemolytic anemia) is correct because nitrofurantoin\'s oxidative stress causes neonatal haemolysis. B (Tooth staining) is wrong because that is the tetracycline effect. C (Bone growth inhibition) is wrong because that is also tetracycline. D (Cartilage toxicity) is wrong because that is the fluoroquinolone effect.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Sulfonamides, Trimethoprim, and Quinolones)</em>`},
    {q:'Which antibiotic is the drug of choice for intrapartum prophylaxis against Group B Streptococcus?',o:['Ampicillin','Vancomycin','Penicillin G','Clindamycin'],a:2,
    e:`Penicillin G is the drug of choice for intrapartum prophylaxis of neonatal Group B Streptococcus (GBS) infection in women with positive vaginal-rectal GBS culture (or unknown status with risk factors). Initial dose is 5 million units IV, then 2.5 to 3 million units every 4 hours until delivery.<br><br>Ampicillin is an alternative (2 g IV initial then 1 g every 4 hours). For severe penicillin allergy, cefazolin (if low risk of anaphylaxis), clindamycin (if susceptible), or vancomycin are used. Adequate prophylaxis (≥4 hours before delivery) reduces neonatal GBS sepsis.<br><br>C (Penicillin G) is correct because it is the first-line agent for GBS prophylaxis. A (Tetracycline) is wrong because tetracyclines are contraindicated. B (Doxycycline) is wrong because it is also a tetracycline. D (Ciprofloxacin) is wrong because fluoroquinolones are avoided.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics; Chapter: Infectious Diseases)</em>`},
    {q:'A woman with severe penicillin allergy requires intrapartum GBS prophylaxis. Which antibiotic is preferred if the organism is susceptible?',o:['Ceftriaxone','Clindamycin','Azithromycin','Amoxicillin'],a:1,
    e:`A woman with severe penicillin allergy requiring intrapartum GBS prophylaxis receives clindamycin (900 mg IV every 8 hours) if the GBS isolate is susceptible. Clindamycin susceptibility testing is essential because of variable resistance.<br><br>If clindamycin is not susceptible or unknown, vancomycin (20 mg/kg IV every 8 hours) is used. Cefazolin can be used if penicillin allergy is mild (no anaphylaxis history). Erythromycin is no longer recommended due to resistance and pharmacokinetic concerns.<br><br>B (Clindamycin) is correct because it is used in severe penicillin allergy if GBS susceptible. A (Tetracycline) is wrong because tetracyclines are contraindicated. C (Doxycycline) is wrong because it is also a tetracycline. D (Ciprofloxacin) is wrong because fluoroquinolones are avoided.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics; Chapter: Infectious Diseases)</em>`},
    {q:'Which antibiotic class acts by inhibiting bacterial cell wall synthesis by binding to penicillin-binding proteins?',o:['Macrolides','Aminoglycosides','Beta-lactams','Sulfonamides'],a:2,
    e:`Beta-lactam antibiotics (penicillins, cephalosporins, carbapenems, monobactams) act by inhibiting bacterial cell wall synthesis. They bind to penicillin-binding proteins (PBPs), inhibiting the transpeptidation reaction in peptidoglycan cross-linking, weakening the bacterial cell wall and causing osmotic lysis.<br><br>Beta-lactams are bactericidal and active against rapidly dividing bacteria. Resistance occurs through beta-lactamase production (broken by beta-lactamase inhibitors like clavulanate), altered PBPs (MRSA), or reduced permeability. Penicillins and cephalosporins are safe in pregnancy.<br><br>C (Beta-lactams) is correct because cell wall synthesis inhibition is their mechanism. A (Aminoglycosides) is wrong because they bind 30S ribosome (protein synthesis). B (Macrolides) is wrong because they bind 50S ribosome. D (Tetracyclines) is wrong because they also bind 30S ribosome.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Beta-Lactam and Other Cell Wall- and Membrane-Active Antibiotics)</em>`},
    {q:'Which antibiotic is commonly used for prophylaxis during cesarean section to reduce postoperative infection?',o:['Tetracycline','Metronidazole alone','Chloramphenicol','Cefazolin'],a:3,
    e:`Cefazolin (a first-generation cephalosporin) is commonly used for prophylaxis during caesarean section to reduce postoperative infection (endometritis, wound infection). Single dose of 2 g IV (3 g if BMI >30 or weight >120 kg) is given within 60 minutes before skin incision.<br><br>Cefazolin covers most skin and soft tissue pathogens (Staphylococcus, Streptococcus, some E. coli). For severe penicillin allergy, clindamycin plus gentamicin or vancomycin is used. Prophylactic antibiotics significantly reduce caesarean infection rates.<br><br>D (Cefazolin) is correct because it is the standard prophylactic agent for caesarean section. A (Tetracycline) is wrong because tetracyclines are contraindicated in pregnancy. B (Doxycycline) is wrong because it is also a tetracycline. C (Ciprofloxacin) is wrong because fluoroquinolones are avoided.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics; Chapter: Cesarean Delivery)</em>`},
    {q:'Which antibiotic is particularly effective against anaerobic organisms and is frequently used in pelvic infections?',o:['Metronidazole','Ciprofloxacin','Gentamicin','Ampicillin'],a:0,
    e:`Metronidazole is particularly effective against anaerobic infections, including Bacteroides fragilis, Clostridium species, anaerobic streptococci and Trichomonas vaginalis. It is also active against Helicobacter pylori, Giardia lamblia and Entamoeba histolytica.<br><br>Metronidazole acts by being reduced to a toxic metabolite by anaerobic organisms\' nitroreductase enzymes. The metabolite damages DNA and proteins, killing the organism. It is widely used in obstetric infections (chorioamnionitis, endometritis), bacterial vaginosis and pelvic inflammatory disease. Generally considered safe in pregnancy after first trimester.<br><br>A (Metronidazole) is correct because anaerobic activity is its hallmark. B (Penicillin) is wrong because penicillin is mainly active against aerobic organisms (limited anaerobic activity). C (Cephalexin) is wrong because cephalexin (first-generation cephalosporin) is mainly aerobic. D (Erythromycin) is wrong because erythromycin is mainly active against aerobic Gram-positive organisms.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Antiprotozoal Drugs)</em>`},
    {q:'Pelvic inflammatory disease commonly requires combination therapy because:',o:['Infection is usually viral','Infection is polymicrobial','Organisms are aerobic only','Antibiotics poorly penetrate pelvic tissues'],a:1,
    e:`Pelvic inflammatory disease (PID) commonly requires combination therapy because the infection is polymicrobial. Causative organisms include Neisseria gonorrhoeae, Chlamydia trachomatis, anaerobes (Bacteroides, Prevotella), Gram-negative bacilli, Gardnerella vaginalis and other vaginal flora.<br><br>Standard outpatient regimen: ceftriaxone 500 mg IM single dose plus doxycycline 100 mg PO BD for 14 days plus metronidazole 500 mg PO BD for 14 days. Inpatient regimen: cefoxitin or cefotetan IV plus doxycycline. Combination covers gonorrhoea (ceftriaxone), chlamydia (doxycycline) and anaerobes (metronidazole).<br><br>B (Infection is polymicrobial) is correct because PID involves multiple organisms requiring broad-spectrum coverage. A (Single organism) is wrong because PID is not monomicrobial. C (Always due to E. coli only) is wrong because PID is rarely E. coli alone. D (Always due to Mycobacterium) is wrong because TB PID is rare.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics; Chapter: Sexually Transmitted Infections)</em>`},
    {q:'Which antibiotic is most associated with the risk of ototoxicity and nephrotoxicity?',o:['Azithromycin','Amoxicillin','Gentamicin','Cefuroxime'],a:2,
    e:`Gentamicin (an aminoglycoside) is most associated with the risk of ototoxicity (and nephrotoxicity). Aminoglycosides accumulate in cochlear and vestibular hair cells, causing irreversible sensorineural hearing loss and balance disturbance.<br><br>Risk increases with high doses, prolonged use (>10 days), high troughs, concurrent loop diuretics or vancomycin, and renal impairment. Once-daily dosing reduces toxicity. Gentamicin crosses the placenta and can cause fetal ototoxicity (eighth nerve damage) when used long-term, but short courses for serious maternal infection are acceptable.<br><br>C (Gentamicin) is correct because aminoglycosides are most associated with ototoxicity. A (Penicillin) is wrong because penicillin does not cause ototoxicity. B (Cefazolin) is wrong because cephalosporins do not cause ototoxicity. D (Erythromycin) is wrong because high-dose IV erythromycin can rarely cause reversible ototoxicity but it is far less common than gentamicin.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Aminoglycosides and Spectinomycin)</em>`},
    {q:'Which antibiotic is recommended for treatment of chlamydial infection during pregnancy?',o:['Azithromycin','Ciprofloxacin','Doxycycline','Tetracycline'],a:0,
    e:`Azithromycin (1 g PO single dose) is recommended for treatment of chlamydial cervicitis in pregnancy. It has good intracellular activity against Chlamydia trachomatis and is well tolerated. Treatment is followed by test of cure 3 to 4 weeks later.<br><br>Doxycycline (the standard outside pregnancy) is contraindicated in pregnancy due to tooth staining. Erythromycin is an alternative but causes more GI side effects. Amoxicillin is also acceptable. Sexual partners should be treated. Untreated chlamydial infection during pregnancy can cause neonatal conjunctivitis and pneumonia.<br><br>A (Azithromycin) is correct because it is first-line for chlamydia in pregnancy. B (Doxycycline) is wrong because it is contraindicated in pregnancy. C (Tetracycline) is wrong because it is also contraindicated. D (Ciprofloxacin) is wrong because fluoroquinolones are avoided and not first-line for chlamydia.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics; Chapter: Sexually Transmitted Infections)</em>`},
    {q:'Sulfonamides should generally be avoided near term because they may cause:',o:['Neonatal hypoglycemia','Neonatal kernicterus','Persistent pulmonary hypertension','Fetal bradycardia'],a:1,
    e:`Sulfonamides should generally be avoided near term because they may cause neonatal kernicterus. Sulfonamides displace bilirubin from albumin (high-affinity competition), increasing free unconjugated bilirubin which can deposit in the basal ganglia of jaundiced or premature neonates, causing kernicterus.<br><br>Sulfonamides also cause haemolysis in G6PD-deficient infants through oxidative stress. They are therefore avoided in late pregnancy (after 32 weeks). Trimethoprim-sulfamethoxazole is also avoided in the first trimester due to folate antagonism (NTD risk).<br><br>B (Neonatal kernicterus) is correct because sulfonamides displace bilirubin and risk kernicterus in neonates. A (Tooth staining) is wrong because that is the tetracycline effect. C (Bone growth inhibition) is wrong because that is also tetracycline. D (Cartilage toxicity) is wrong because that is the fluoroquinolone effect.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Sulfonamides, Trimethoprim, and Quinolones)</em>`},
    {q:'Which antibiotic is commonly used in combination with clindamycin to treat severe pelvic infections?',o:['Cefixime','Amoxicillin','Doxycycline','Gentamicin'],a:3,
    e:`Gentamicin is commonly used in combination with clindamycin for the treatment of postpartum endometritis. Standard regimen: clindamycin 900 mg IV every 8 hours plus gentamicin 5 mg/kg IV once daily until afebrile for 24 to 48 hours.<br><br>Clindamycin covers anaerobes and Gram-positive cocci; gentamicin covers Gram-negative bacilli. Endometritis is typically polymicrobial (anaerobes, Gram-negative bacilli, Streptococcus). Alternative regimens include ampicillin-sulbactam or piperacillin-tazobactam. Treatment continues until afebrile and clinically improved.<br><br>D (Gentamicin) is correct because gentamicin plus clindamycin is the standard endometritis regimen. A (Penicillin) is wrong because while ampicillin is sometimes added, penicillin alone is not the standard combination with clindamycin. B (Cefazolin) is wrong because cefazolin is for prophylaxis, not endometritis treatment. C (Erythromycin) is wrong because erythromycin is not standard in endometritis.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics; Chapter: The Puerperium)</em>`},
    {q:'The bactericidal action of aminoglycosides results from:',o:['Inhibition of DNA replication','Inhibition of cell wall synthesis','Binding to the 30S ribosomal subunit','Inhibition of folate synthesis'],a:2,
    e:`The bactericidal action of aminoglycosides results from binding to the 30S ribosomal subunit. Aminoglycosides bind irreversibly to the 30S subunit, causing misreading of mRNA codons and producing aberrant non-functional proteins. They also block initiation of protein synthesis.<br><br>Aminoglycosides require oxygen-dependent uptake into bacterial cells, making them ineffective against anaerobes. Examples include gentamicin, amikacin, tobramycin, streptomycin and kanamycin. Major adverse effects are nephrotoxicity (proximal tubular damage) and ototoxicity (cochlear and vestibular hair cells). Streptomycin causes congenital deafness in pregnancy.<br><br>C (Binding to the 30S ribosomal subunit) is correct because aminoglycosides bind 30S, causing mRNA misreading. A (Inhibiting cell wall synthesis) is wrong because that is the beta-lactam mechanism. B (Inhibiting DNA gyrase) is wrong because that is the fluoroquinolone mechanism. D (Inhibiting folate synthesis) is wrong because that is the sulfonamide/trimethoprim mechanism.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Aminoglycosides and Spectinomycin)</em>`},
    {q:'Which antibiotic is most strongly associated with pseudomembranous colitis due to Clostridioides difficile?',o:['Clindamycin','Azithromycin','Nitrofurantoin','Amoxicillin'],a:0,
    e:`Clindamycin is most strongly associated with pseudomembranous colitis (Clostridium difficile colitis). Clindamycin\'s broad-spectrum anti-anaerobic activity disrupts colonic flora, allowing overgrowth of toxin-producing C. difficile.<br><br>Symptoms include diarrhoea (sometimes bloody), abdominal pain, fever and pseudomembrane formation visible on colonoscopy. Treatment is to stop the offending antibiotic, give oral vancomycin or fidaxomicin, and avoid anti-motility drugs. Severe cases (toxic megacolon) may require surgery.<br><br>A (Clindamycin) is correct because clindamycin is most associated with C. difficile colitis. B (Penicillin) is wrong because penicillin is less commonly associated. C (Erythromycin) is wrong because while it can cause C. difficile, clindamycin is most strongly associated. D (Cefazolin) is wrong because while broad-spectrum cephalosporins are also associated, clindamycin is the classic offender.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Tetracyclines, Macrolides, Clindamycin, Chloramphenicol, Streptogramins, and Oxazolidinones)</em>`},
    {q:'Which antibiotic is commonly used in combination regimens for septic abortion because of strong anaerobic coverage?',o:['Amoxicillin','Metronidazole','Cefixime','Erythromycin'],a:1,
    e:`Metronidazole is commonly used in combination regimens for postpartum endometritis to provide anaerobic coverage. Endometritis is typically polymicrobial; clindamycin or metronidazole covers anaerobes; gentamicin covers Gram-negative bacilli; penicillin-class agents cover Streptococcus.<br><br>Standard regimen: clindamycin 900 mg IV every 8 hours plus gentamicin 5 mg/kg IV once daily until afebrile for 24 to 48 hours. Alternative regimens include ampicillin-sulbactam, piperacillin-tazobactam, or metronidazole-containing combinations.<br><br>B (Metronidazole) is correct because metronidazole provides anaerobic coverage in endometritis. A (Ciprofloxacin) is wrong because fluoroquinolones are avoided. C (Doxycycline) is wrong because tetracyclines are contraindicated. D (Tetracycline) is wrong for the same reason.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics; Chapter: The Puerperium)</em>`},
    {q:'Which mechanism best explains bacterial resistance to beta-lactam antibiotics?',o:['Increased bacterial metabolism','Reduced bacterial mutation','Increased drug absorption','Production of beta-lactamase enzymes'],a:3,
    e:`Bacterial resistance to beta-lactam antibiotics is most commonly explained by production of beta-lactamase enzymes. Beta-lactamases hydrolyse the beta-lactam ring, inactivating the antibiotic. Examples include penicillinase (Staphylococcus), TEM/SHV (Gram-negative), AmpC and ESBLs (extended-spectrum beta-lactamases).<br><br>Beta-lactamase inhibitors (clavulanic acid, sulbactam, tazobactam) are combined with beta-lactams (e.g. amoxicillin-clavulanate) to overcome this resistance. Other resistance mechanisms include altered penicillin-binding proteins (MRSA), reduced permeability and efflux pumps. Carbapenems are stable against most beta-lactamases but increasing carbapenemases threaten this.<br><br>D (Production of beta-lactamase enzymes) is correct because beta-lactamases are the main resistance mechanism. A (Increased efflux pumps) is wrong because while efflux pumps contribute, beta-lactamases are most common. B (Altered ribosomes) is wrong because that is for protein synthesis inhibitors. C (Inhibition of DNA gyrase) is wrong because that is the action of fluoroquinolones, not a resistance mechanism.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Beta-Lactam and Other Cell Wall- and Membrane-Active Antibiotics)</em>`},
    {q:'Which antibiotic is considered safe for treatment of urinary tract infections during pregnancy?',o:['Ciprofloxacin','Nitrofurantoin','Chloramphenicol','Tetracycline'],a:1,
    e:`Nitrofurantoin is considered safe for treatment of urinary tract infections in pregnancy (50 to 100 mg PO 4 times daily for 5 to 7 days). It is concentrated in urine and effective against most uropathogens (E. coli, Enterococcus, Staphylococcus saprophyticus) with minimal systemic effects.<br><br>Other safe agents include amoxicillin, cephalexin and cefpodoxime. Trimethoprim-sulfamethoxazole is avoided in first trimester (folate antagonism, NTD risk) and near term (kernicterus). Nitrofurantoin is avoided in late pregnancy (after 36 weeks) due to risk of neonatal haemolytic anaemia.<br><br>B (Nitrofurantoin) is correct because it is safe and first-line for UTI in pregnancy. A (Tetracycline) is wrong because tetracyclines are contraindicated. C (Doxycycline) is wrong because it is also a tetracycline. D (Ciprofloxacin) is wrong because fluoroquinolones are avoided due to cartilage toxicity.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics; Chapter: Renal and Urinary Tract Disorders)</em>`},
    {q:'Which antibiotic inhibits bacterial protein synthesis by binding to the 50S ribosomal subunit?',o:['Cephalosporins','Aminoglycosides','Penicillins','Macrolides'],a:3,
    e:`Macrolides (erythromycin, azithromycin, clarithromycin) inhibit bacterial protein synthesis by binding to the 50S ribosomal subunit. This blocks translocation of peptidyl-tRNA, preventing elongation of the protein chain.<br><br>Macrolides are bacteriostatic at standard concentrations and bactericidal at high concentrations. They are active against Gram-positive cocci, atypical organisms (Mycoplasma, Chlamydia, Legionella) and some Gram-negative organisms. Generally safe in pregnancy. Side effects include GI upset (especially erythromycin), QT prolongation and rare hepatotoxicity.<br><br>D (Macrolides) is correct because they bind 50S ribosome and block protein synthesis. A (Beta-lactams) is wrong because they inhibit cell wall synthesis. B (Aminoglycosides) is wrong because they bind 30S ribosome. C (Tetracyclines) is wrong because they also bind 30S ribosome.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Tetracyclines, Macrolides, Clindamycin, Chloramphenicol, Streptogramins, and Oxazolidinones)</em>`},
    {q:'A pregnant woman with bacterial vaginosis is treated with which antibiotic most commonly?',o:['Metronidazole','Ciprofloxacin','Tetracycline','Gentamicin'],a:0,
    e:`A pregnant woman with bacterial vaginosis is treated with metronidazole (500 mg PO BD for 7 days, or 2 g PO single dose). Metronidazole is highly active against the anaerobes (Gardnerella vaginalis, Prevotella, Bacteroides, Atopobium vaginae) involved in bacterial vaginosis.<br><br>Topical metronidazole gel (0.75 percent intravaginally daily for 5 days) and topical clindamycin (2 percent cream intravaginally for 7 days) are alternatives. Treatment is recommended in symptomatic women and asymptomatic women with prior preterm birth (BV is associated with preterm labour). Metronidazole is generally considered safe in pregnancy after first trimester.<br><br>A (Metronidazole) is correct because it is first-line for bacterial vaginosis. B (Tetracycline) is wrong because tetracyclines are contraindicated and not active against anaerobes. C (Doxycycline) is wrong because it is also a tetracycline. D (Ciprofloxacin) is wrong because fluoroquinolones are not first-line for BV.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics; Chapter: Sexually Transmitted Infections)</em>`},
    {q:'Which antibiotic crosses the placenta and may cause gray baby syndrome in neonates?',o:['Ceftriaxone','Amoxicillin','Chloramphenicol','Azithromycin'],a:2,
    e:`Chloramphenicol crosses the placenta and may cause gray baby syndrome in the neonate. Symptoms include pallor, abdominal distension, vomiting and circulatory collapse, due to immature glucuronidation in the neonate causing chloramphenicol accumulation.<br><br>Chloramphenicol also inhibits mitochondrial protein synthesis and may cause idiosyncratic bone marrow suppression and aplastic anaemia (dose-independent, can be fatal). Use is therefore avoided in pregnancy and in neonates. Penicillins, cephalosporins and macrolides are safer alternatives.<br><br>C (Chloramphenicol) is correct because chloramphenicol causes gray baby syndrome. A (Penicillin) is wrong because penicillin is safe. B (Cefazolin) is wrong because cephalosporins are safe. D (Erythromycin) is wrong because macrolides are safe.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Tetracyclines, Macrolides, Clindamycin, Chloramphenicol, Streptogramins, and Oxazolidinones)</em>`},
    {q:'Which antibiotic class is characterized by concentration-dependent killing?',o:['Aminoglycosides','Macrolides','Tetracyclines','Sulfonamides'],a:0,
    e:`Aminoglycosides (gentamicin, amikacin, tobramycin, streptomycin) are characterised by concentration-dependent killing. Higher peak concentrations produce greater bactericidal activity, supporting once-daily dosing (5 to 7 mg/kg IV once daily for gentamicin) for adults.<br><br>Once-daily dosing achieves high peak concentrations (maximising killing) and prolonged trough levels approaching zero (allowing renal recovery and reducing nephrotoxicity). The post-antibiotic effect (continued growth suppression after drug levels fall) supports once-daily dosing. Streptomycin causes congenital deafness in pregnancy.<br><br>A (Aminoglycosides) is correct because they show concentration-dependent killing. B (Beta-lactams) is wrong because they show time-dependent killing (importance of T>MIC). C (Macrolides) is wrong because they show time-dependent killing. D (Tetracyclines) is wrong because they show time-dependent killing.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Aminoglycosides and Spectinomycin)</em>`},
    {q:'Which antibiotic is recommended for prophylaxis in premature rupture of membranes to prolong latency?',o:['Tetracycline','Chloramphenicol','Ciprofloxacin','Ampicillin'],a:3,
    e:`Ampicillin is recommended for prophylaxis in premature rupture of membranes (PROM) at preterm gestation, in combination with erythromycin. The standard regimen for preterm PROM is IV ampicillin 2 g every 6 hours plus IV erythromycin 250 mg every 6 hours for 48 hours, followed by oral amoxicillin 250 mg every 8 hours plus oral erythromycin 333 mg every 8 hours for 5 days.<br><br>This regimen prolongs latency, reduces chorioamnionitis and reduces neonatal infection. Antibiotic prophylaxis is also indicated for GBS-positive women in labour, and during caesarean section. Penicillin allergy alternatives include clindamycin, vancomycin or cefazolin (mild allergy).<br><br>D (Ampicillin) is correct because ampicillin (with erythromycin) is the standard for preterm PROM prophylaxis. A (Tetracycline) is wrong because tetracyclines are contraindicated. B (Doxycycline) is wrong because it is also a tetracycline. C (Ciprofloxacin) is wrong because fluoroquinolones are avoided.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics; Chapter: Prelabor Rupture of Membranes)</em>`},
    {q:'The mechanism of action of metronidazole involves:',o:['Inhibition of ribosomal protein synthesis','DNA strand breakage in anaerobic organisms','Inhibition of cell wall synthesis','Inhibition of folic acid synthesis'],a:1,
    e:`The mechanism of action of metronidazole involves DNA strand breakage in anaerobic organisms. Metronidazole is reduced to a toxic metabolite by anaerobic organisms\' nitroreductase enzymes. The metabolite forms covalent bonds with DNA, causing strand breakage and cell death.<br><br>Aerobic organisms lack the nitroreductase activity needed to activate metronidazole, so the drug is selectively toxic to anaerobes. Active against Bacteroides fragilis, Clostridium species, anaerobic streptococci, Trichomonas vaginalis, Helicobacter pylori, Giardia lamblia and Entamoeba histolytica.<br><br>B (DNA strand breakage in anaerobic organisms) is correct because reduced metronidazole metabolite causes DNA damage. A (Cell wall inhibition) is wrong because that is the beta-lactam mechanism. C (Protein synthesis inhibition) is wrong because that is the macrolide/aminoglycoside mechanism. D (Folic acid synthesis inhibition) is wrong because that is the sulfonamide mechanism.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Antiprotozoal Drugs)</em>`},
    {q:'Which antibiotic is associated with cartilage toxicity and therefore avoided in pregnancy?',o:['Penicillins','Cephalosporins','Fluoroquinolones','Macrolides'],a:2,
    e:`Fluoroquinolones (ciprofloxacin, levofloxacin, moxifloxacin) are associated with cartilage toxicity (causing arthropathy in animal studies) and tendinopathy/tendon rupture in humans, especially Achilles tendon rupture. Risk increases with concurrent corticosteroids, age >60 and renal impairment.<br><br>Fluoroquinolones are avoided in pregnancy due to cartilage toxicity concerns from animal studies, although some human safety data are accumulating. They are also avoided in children. Other adverse effects include CNS effects (seizures, headache, dizziness), QT prolongation, hypoglycaemia, and rare aortic dissection/aneurysm.<br><br>C (Fluoroquinolones) is correct because cartilage toxicity and tendinopathy are characteristic. A (Penicillin) is wrong because penicillin does not cause cartilage toxicity. B (Erythromycin) is wrong because macrolides do not cause this. D (Cefazolin) is wrong because cephalosporins do not cause this.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Sulfonamides, Trimethoprim, and Quinolones)</em>`},
    {q:'Which antibiotic is commonly used for treatment of gonorrhea in pregnancy?',o:['Chloramphenicol','Tetracycline','Ciprofloxacin','Ceftriaxone'],a:3,
    e:`Ceftriaxone (500 mg IM single dose) is the recommended treatment for gonorrhoea in pregnancy and outside pregnancy. Combined treatment with doxycycline (or azithromycin in pregnancy) covers possible co-infection with chlamydia. Treatment should be tailored to local resistance patterns.<br><br>Ceftriaxone overcomes the increasing resistance of Neisseria gonorrhoeae to penicillins, tetracyclines and fluoroquinolones. Sexual partners should be treated. Test of cure is recommended 2 weeks after treatment for pharyngeal gonorrhoea. Untreated maternal gonorrhoea can cause neonatal ophthalmia neonatorum.<br><br>D (Ceftriaxone) is correct because it is first-line for gonorrhoea in pregnancy. A (Tetracycline) is wrong because tetracyclines are contraindicated. B (Doxycycline) is wrong because it is also a tetracycline. C (Penicillin G) is wrong because gonorrhoea now has high resistance to penicillin.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics; Chapter: Sexually Transmitted Infections)</em>`},
    {q:'Which antibiotic is considered safe and commonly used for postpartum endometritis as part of combination therapy?',o:['Clindamycin','Tetracycline','Ciprofloxacin','Chloramphenicol'],a:0,
    e:`Clindamycin is considered safe and commonly used for postpartum endometritis (in combination with gentamicin) and for severe penicillin allergy in obstetric infections. It is active against Gram-positive cocci and anaerobes.<br><br>Standard endometritis regimen: clindamycin 900 mg IV every 8 hours plus gentamicin 5 mg/kg IV once daily until afebrile for 24 to 48 hours. Side effects include diarrhoea (most common), pseudomembranous colitis (C. difficile), and rare hepatotoxicity. Generally well tolerated.<br><br>A (Clindamycin) is correct because clindamycin is safe and commonly used. B (Tetracycline) is wrong because tetracyclines are contraindicated. C (Doxycycline) is wrong because it is also a tetracycline. D (Ciprofloxacin) is wrong because fluoroquinolones are avoided.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics; Chapter: The Puerperium)</em>`},
    {q:'Which antibiotic class inhibits folic acid synthesis in bacteria?',o:['Aminoglycosides','Sulfonamides','Macrolides','Cephalosporins'],a:1,
    e:`Sulfonamides inhibit folic acid synthesis in bacteria by competing with PABA (para-aminobenzoic acid) for dihydropteroate synthase, the enzyme that converts PABA to dihydrofolate. Bacteria require de novo folate synthesis (humans absorb folate from diet, so are not affected).<br><br>Trimethoprim, often combined with sulfonamides (trimethoprim-sulfamethoxazole, co-trimoxazole), inhibits dihydrofolate reductase, blocking the next step. The combination is synergistic (sequential blockade of folate synthesis). Sulfonamides are avoided in first trimester (folate antagonism, NTD risk) and near term (kernicterus from bilirubin displacement).<br><br>B (Sulfonamides) is correct because they inhibit folate synthesis at the dihydropteroate synthase step. A (Beta-lactams) is wrong because they inhibit cell wall synthesis. C (Macrolides) is wrong because they inhibit protein synthesis. D (Aminoglycosides) is wrong because they also inhibit protein synthesis.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Sulfonamides, Trimethoprim, and Quinolones)</em>`},
    {q:'Which antibiotic is preferred for treatment of syphilis during pregnancy?',o:['Doxycycline','Azithromycin','Penicillin G','Ciprofloxacin'],a:2,
    e:`Penicillin G is preferred for treatment of syphilis during pregnancy. Treponema pallidum remains highly sensitive to penicillin. Treatment regimens depend on stage: primary, secondary or early latent syphilis: benzathine penicillin G 2.4 million units IM single dose; late latent or unknown duration: same dose weekly for 3 doses.<br><br>Penicillin is the only effective treatment for syphilis in pregnancy that prevents fetal infection (congenital syphilis). Pregnant women with penicillin allergy require desensitisation, as alternatives (doxycycline, tetracycline) are contraindicated and erythromycin does not adequately treat fetal infection. Jarisch-Herxheimer reaction can cause preterm labour after first dose.<br><br>C (Penicillin G) is correct because it is the established and only effective treatment for syphilis in pregnancy. A (Tetracycline) is wrong because tetracyclines are contraindicated. B (Doxycycline) is wrong because it is also a tetracycline. D (Ciprofloxacin) is wrong because fluoroquinolones are not effective for syphilis.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics; Chapter: Sexually Transmitted Infections)</em>`},
    {q:'Which antibiotic combination is commonly used in pelvic inflammatory disease?',o:['Amoxicillin + metformin','Ceftriaxone + doxycycline','Gentamicin + insulin','Ciprofloxacin + warfarin'],a:1,
    e:`Ceftriaxone plus doxycycline is the antibiotic combination commonly used in pelvic inflammatory disease (PID) outpatient treatment. Standard regimen: ceftriaxone 500 mg IM single dose plus doxycycline 100 mg PO BD for 14 days plus metronidazole 500 mg PO BD for 14 days.<br><br>Ceftriaxone covers Neisseria gonorrhoeae; doxycycline covers Chlamydia trachomatis; metronidazole covers anaerobes (Bacteroides, Prevotella). PID is polymicrobial. Inpatient regimens use cefoxitin or cefotetan IV plus doxycycline PO. Doxycycline cannot be used in pregnancy; alternatives include azithromycin.<br><br>B (Ceftriaxone + doxycycline) is correct because this is the standard PID outpatient regimen. A (Penicillin G + gentamicin) is wrong because it does not cover chlamydia and is not the standard PID regimen. C (Tetracycline + sulfa) is wrong because tetracycline alone is not standard. D (Vancomycin + metronidazole) is wrong because this is not a standard PID regimen.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics; Chapter: Sexually Transmitted Infections)</em>`},
    {q:'Which antibiotic acts by inhibiting bacterial DNA gyrase?',o:['Penicillins','Macrolides','Fluoroquinolones','Aminoglycosides'],a:2,
    e:`Fluoroquinolones (ciprofloxacin, levofloxacin, moxifloxacin) act by inhibiting bacterial DNA gyrase (topoisomerase II) and topoisomerase IV. DNA gyrase introduces negative supercoils into bacterial DNA; inhibition prevents DNA replication and transcription, killing the organism.<br><br>Fluoroquinolones are bactericidal and active against Gram-negative organisms (E. coli, Pseudomonas), some Gram-positive (Streptococcus pneumoniae for newer agents) and atypical organisms. They are avoided in pregnancy due to cartilage toxicity in animal studies.<br><br>C (Fluoroquinolones) is correct because they inhibit DNA gyrase. A (Beta-lactams) is wrong because they inhibit cell wall synthesis. B (Macrolides) is wrong because they inhibit protein synthesis. D (Sulfonamides) is wrong because they inhibit folate synthesis.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Sulfonamides, Trimethoprim, and Quinolones)</em>`},
    {q:'Which antibiotic is associated with dose-dependent nephrotoxicity and requires monitoring of serum levels?',o:['Gentamicin','Azithromycin','Amoxicillin','Cefalexin'],a:0,
    e:`Gentamicin is associated with dose-dependent nephrotoxicity. Aminoglycosides accumulate in renal proximal tubular cells, causing acute tubular necrosis. The damage is usually reversible if detected early and the drug is discontinued.<br><br>Risk factors include high doses, prolonged use (>10 days), high troughs, concurrent nephrotoxins (vancomycin, amphotericin B, NSAIDs, contrast media), and pre-existing renal impairment. Once-daily dosing reduces nephrotoxicity (peak-dependent killing with prolonged trough recovery). Monitoring serum creatinine and aminoglycoside levels is essential.<br><br>A (Gentamicin) is correct because aminoglycoside nephrotoxicity is dose-dependent. B (Penicillin) is wrong because penicillin does not cause dose-dependent nephrotoxicity (interstitial nephritis is idiosyncratic). C (Cefazolin) is wrong because cephalosporins rarely cause significant nephrotoxicity. D (Erythromycin) is wrong because erythromycin does not cause nephrotoxicity.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Aminoglycosides and Spectinomycin)</em>`},
    {q:'Which antibiotic is most effective against anaerobic bacteria in pelvic infections?',o:['Ciprofloxacin','Amoxicillin','Tetracycline','Metronidazole'],a:3,
    e:`Metronidazole is most effective against anaerobic bacteria. It is highly active against Bacteroides fragilis, Clostridium species, anaerobic streptococci, Fusobacterium and Peptostreptococcus.<br><br>Metronidazole acts by being reduced to a toxic metabolite by anaerobic organisms\' nitroreductase enzymes. The metabolite damages DNA, killing the organism. Aerobic organisms lack the nitroreductase activity needed, so the drug is selectively toxic to anaerobes. Also active against Trichomonas, Helicobacter pylori, Giardia and Entamoeba histolytica.<br><br>D (Metronidazole) is correct because anaerobic activity is its hallmark. A (Penicillin) is wrong because penicillin is mainly active against aerobic organisms. B (Cephalexin) is wrong because cephalexin is mainly aerobic. C (Erythromycin) is wrong because erythromycin is mainly active against aerobic Gram-positive organisms.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Antiprotozoal Drugs)</em>`},
    {q:'Which antibiotic is a macrolide commonly used in pregnancy?',o:['Doxycycline','Ciprofloxacin','Azithromycin','Gentamicin'],a:2,
    e:`Azithromycin is a macrolide commonly used in pregnancy. It has good activity against atypical organisms (Mycoplasma, Chlamydia, Legionella), some Gram-positive cocci and Mycobacterium avium complex. It is generally well tolerated in pregnancy.<br><br>Azithromycin (1 g PO single dose) is first-line for chlamydial cervicitis in pregnancy. It is also used for community-acquired pneumonia, bronchitis and atypical infections. Erythromycin is an alternative but causes more GI side effects. Clarithromycin is generally avoided in pregnancy due to limited safety data and animal teratogenicity at high doses.<br><br>C (Azithromycin) is correct because it is the most commonly used macrolide in pregnancy. A (Tetracycline) is wrong because it is not a macrolide and is contraindicated. B (Doxycycline) is wrong because it is also a tetracycline. D (Ciprofloxacin) is wrong because it is a fluoroquinolone, not a macrolide.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Tetracyclines, Macrolides, Clindamycin, Chloramphenicol, Streptogramins, and Oxazolidinones)</em>`},
    {q:'Which antibiotic is associated with photosensitivity reactions?',o:['Macrolides','Penicillins','Cephalosporins','Tetracyclines'],a:3,
    e:`Tetracyclines are associated with photosensitivity reactions in addition to their teratogenic effects (tooth staining, bone growth inhibition). Tetracyclines absorb UV light, generating reactive species that damage skin tissues, causing severe sunburn-like reactions on sun exposure.<br><br>Patients should be advised to use sun protection (clothing, sunscreen, avoid prolonged sun exposure) during tetracycline therapy. Tetracyclines are contraindicated in pregnancy and children under 8 years due to tooth staining and bone effects. Other side effects include GI upset, oesophageal ulceration (take with water and stay upright), hepatotoxicity and rare benign intracranial hypertension.<br><br>D (Tetracyclines) is correct because tetracyclines cause photosensitivity. A (Penicillins) is wrong because penicillins do not cause photosensitivity. B (Macrolides) is wrong because macrolides do not cause photosensitivity. C (Cephalosporins) is wrong because cephalosporins do not cause photosensitivity.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Tetracyclines, Macrolides, Clindamycin, Chloramphenicol, Streptogramins, and Oxazolidinones)</em>`},
    {q:'Which antibiotic interferes with bacterial peptidoglycan cross-linking?',o:['Macrolides','Penicillins','Aminoglycosides','Sulfonamides'],a:1,
    e:`Penicillins interfere with bacterial peptidoglycan cross-linking, the final step in bacterial cell wall synthesis. They bind to penicillin-binding proteins (PBPs), inhibiting the transpeptidation reaction in peptidoglycan cross-linking, weakening the bacterial cell wall and causing osmotic lysis.<br><br>Penicillins are bactericidal and active against rapidly dividing bacteria. Resistance occurs through beta-lactamase production (broken by beta-lactamase inhibitors like clavulanate), altered PBPs (MRSA), or reduced permeability. Penicillins are safe in pregnancy.<br><br>B (Penicillins) is correct because peptidoglycan cross-linking inhibition is their mechanism. A (Aminoglycosides) is wrong because they bind 30S ribosome. C (Tetracyclines) is wrong because they also bind 30S ribosome. D (Macrolides) is wrong because they bind 50S ribosome.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Beta-Lactam and Other Cell Wall- and Membrane-Active Antibiotics)</em>`},
    {q:'Which antibiotic is commonly used for surgical prophylaxis in gynecologic surgery?',o:['Cefazolin','Chloramphenicol','Tetracycline','Ciprofloxacin'],a:0,
    e:`Cefazolin (a first-generation cephalosporin) is commonly used for surgical prophylaxis in obstetrics, particularly for caesarean section. Single dose of 2 g IV (3 g if BMI >30 or weight >120 kg) is given within 60 minutes before skin incision.<br><br>Cefazolin covers most skin and soft tissue pathogens (Staphylococcus, Streptococcus, some E. coli). For severe penicillin allergy, clindamycin plus gentamicin or vancomycin is used. Prophylactic antibiotics significantly reduce caesarean infection rates (endometritis, wound infection).<br><br>A (Cefazolin) is correct because cefazolin is the standard surgical prophylaxis agent. B (Tetracycline) is wrong because tetracyclines are contraindicated in pregnancy. C (Doxycycline) is wrong because it is also a tetracycline. D (Ciprofloxacin) is wrong because fluoroquinolones are avoided.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics; Chapter: Cesarean Delivery)</em>`},
    {q:'Which antibiotic is most associated with gastrointestinal intolerance among macrolides?',o:['Azithromycin','Erythromycin','Roxithromycin','Clarithromycin'],a:1,
    e:`Erythromycin is most associated with gastrointestinal intolerance among the macrolides. It is a motilin receptor agonist, stimulating gastrointestinal motility and causing nausea, vomiting, abdominal pain and diarrhoea. Side effects are common (10 to 30 percent of users).<br><br>Azithromycin and clarithromycin are better tolerated. Other erythromycin side effects include reversible ototoxicity at high doses, QT prolongation, cholestatic hepatitis (especially with erythromycin estolate) and pyloric stenosis in neonates exposed in early infancy. Drug interactions include CYP3A4 inhibition (warfarin, statins, theophylline, ergot alkaloids).<br><br>B (Erythromycin) is correct because erythromycin causes most GI intolerance among macrolides. A (Azithromycin) is wrong because azithromycin is much better tolerated. C (Clindamycin) is wrong because while clindamycin can cause diarrhoea, GI intolerance is more characteristic of erythromycin. D (Cefazolin) is wrong because cephalosporins are generally well tolerated.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Tetracyclines, Macrolides, Clindamycin, Chloramphenicol, Streptogramins, and Oxazolidinones)</em>`},
    {q:'Which antibiotic is most appropriate for treatment of bacterial vaginosis in pregnancy?',o:['Gentamicin','Doxycycline','Ciprofloxacin','Metronidazole'],a:3,
    e:`Metronidazole is the most appropriate antibiotic for treatment of bacterial vaginosis. Standard regimens: oral metronidazole 500 mg PO BD for 7 days, or 2 g PO single dose, or topical metronidazole gel 0.75 percent intravaginally daily for 5 days.<br><br>Metronidazole is highly active against the anaerobes involved (Gardnerella vaginalis, Prevotella, Bacteroides, Atopobium vaginae). Topical clindamycin (2 percent cream intravaginally for 7 days) is an alternative. Treatment is recommended in symptomatic women and asymptomatic women with prior preterm birth (BV is associated with preterm labour).<br><br>D (Metronidazole) is correct because it is first-line for bacterial vaginosis. A (Tetracycline) is wrong because tetracyclines are contraindicated and not active against the BV organisms. B (Doxycycline) is wrong because it is also a tetracycline. C (Ciprofloxacin) is wrong because fluoroquinolones are not first-line for BV.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics; Chapter: Sexually Transmitted Infections)</em>`},
    {q:'Which antibiotic combination is commonly used in treatment of postpartum endometritis?',o:['Doxycycline + insulin','Ciprofloxacin + metformin','Clindamycin + gentamicin','Amoxicillin + warfarin'],a:2,
    e:`Clindamycin plus gentamicin is the antibiotic combination commonly used in treatment of postpartum endometritis. Standard regimen: clindamycin 900 mg IV every 8 hours plus gentamicin 5 mg/kg IV once daily until afebrile for 24 to 48 hours.<br><br>Clindamycin covers anaerobes (Bacteroides, Peptostreptococcus) and Gram-positive cocci (Streptococcus). Gentamicin covers Gram-negative bacilli (E. coli). Endometritis is typically polymicrobial. Alternative regimens include ampicillin-sulbactam or piperacillin-tazobactam. Treatment continues until afebrile and clinically improved.<br><br>C (Clindamycin + gentamicin) is correct because this is the standard endometritis regimen. A (Penicillin + tetracycline) is wrong because tetracyclines are contraindicated and not standard. B (Erythromycin + ciprofloxacin) is wrong because fluoroquinolones are avoided. D (Doxycycline + metronidazole) is wrong because doxycycline is contraindicated.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics; Chapter: The Puerperium)</em>`},
    {q:'Which antibiotic acts primarily as a bacteriostatic agent by inhibiting protein synthesis?',o:['Tetracyclines','Cephalosporins','Carbapenems','Penicillins'],a:0,
    e:`Tetracyclines act primarily as bacteriostatic agents by binding to the 30S ribosomal subunit, blocking attachment of aminoacyl-tRNA to the A site of the ribosome and preventing protein synthesis elongation.<br><br>Tetracyclines are broad-spectrum (Gram-positive, Gram-negative, atypicals like Chlamydia, Rickettsia, Mycoplasma). Doxycycline is the most commonly used outside pregnancy. Tetracyclines are contraindicated in pregnancy and children under 8 years due to tooth staining and bone effects. Other side effects include photosensitivity, GI upset and oesophageal ulceration.<br><br>A (Tetracyclines) is correct because they are bacteriostatic 30S binders. B (Penicillins) is wrong because penicillins are bactericidal cell wall inhibitors. C (Aminoglycosides) is wrong because aminoglycosides are bactericidal 30S binders (different mechanism than tetracyclines). D (Cephalosporins) is wrong because cephalosporins are bactericidal cell wall inhibitors.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Tetracyclines, Macrolides, Clindamycin, Chloramphenicol, Streptogramins, and Oxazolidinones)</em>`},
    {q:'Which antibiotic is recommended for treatment of trichomoniasis in pregnancy?',o:['Ciprofloxacin','Tetracycline','Metronidazole','Cefuroxime'],a:2,
    e:`Metronidazole is recommended for treatment of trichomoniasis (Trichomonas vaginalis). Standard regimen: metronidazole 2 g PO single dose, or 500 mg PO BD for 7 days. Tinidazole 2 g PO single dose is an alternative.<br><br>Metronidazole is generally considered safe in pregnancy after first trimester. Sexual partners should be treated simultaneously to prevent reinfection. Untreated trichomoniasis in pregnancy is associated with preterm labour and low birth weight. Patients should avoid alcohol during and 24 hours after treatment (disulfiram-like reaction).<br><br>C (Metronidazole) is correct because it is first-line for trichomoniasis. A (Tetracycline) is wrong because tetracyclines are contraindicated and not active against trichomonas. B (Doxycycline) is wrong because it is also a tetracycline. D (Ciprofloxacin) is wrong because fluoroquinolones are not effective against trichomonas.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Antiprotozoal Drugs)</em>`},
    {q:'Which antibiotic class includes drugs such as ceftriaxone and cefazolin?',o:['Aminoglycosides','Cephalosporins','Macrolides','Sulfonamides'],a:1,
    e:`Cephalosporins include drugs such as ceftriaxone and cefazolin. They are beta-lactam antibiotics with cell wall synthesis inhibition through penicillin-binding protein (PBP) binding.<br><br>Cephalosporins are classified by generation: first-generation (cefazolin, cephalexin) cover Gram-positive cocci; second-generation (cefuroxime) extend Gram-negative coverage; third-generation (ceftriaxone, cefotaxime) cover most Gram-negatives including Pseudomonas (ceftazidime); fourth-generation (cefepime) cover both Gram-positive and Pseudomonas; fifth-generation (ceftaroline) covers MRSA. All are generally safe in pregnancy.<br><br>B (Cephalosporins) is correct because ceftriaxone and cefazolin are cephalosporins. A (Penicillins) is wrong because penicillins are different beta-lactams. C (Macrolides) is wrong because macrolides include erythromycin, azithromycin. D (Fluoroquinolones) is wrong because they include ciprofloxacin, levofloxacin.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Beta-Lactam and Other Cell Wall- and Membrane-Active Antibiotics)</em>`},
    {q:'Which antibiotic is used in treatment regimens for septic abortion due to its strong anaerobic activity?',o:['Metronidazole','Tetracycline','Amoxicillin','Ciprofloxacin'],a:0,
    e:`Metronidazole is used in treatment regimens for septic abortion to provide anaerobic coverage. Septic abortion is typically polymicrobial; broad-spectrum coverage including anaerobes is essential.<br><br>Standard regimen: ampicillin plus gentamicin plus metronidazole (or clindamycin) IV until afebrile and clinically improved. Surgical evacuation of retained products is essential. Late presentations may have endotoxic shock requiring intensive care. Without prompt antibiotic and surgical management, septic abortion has high mortality.<br><br>A (Metronidazole) is correct because anaerobic coverage is essential in septic abortion. B (Tetracycline) is wrong because tetracyclines are contraindicated. C (Doxycycline) is wrong because it is also a tetracycline. D (Ciprofloxacin) is wrong because fluoroquinolones are not first-line in septic abortion.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics; Chapter: First-Trimester Pregnancy Loss)</em>`},
    {q:'Which antibiotic mechanism involves inhibition of dihydropteroate synthase?',o:['Beta-lactams','Aminoglycosides','Macrolides','Sulfonamides'],a:3,
    e:`Sulfonamides involve inhibition of dihydropteroate synthase. They compete with PABA (para-aminobenzoic acid) for dihydropteroate synthase, the enzyme that converts PABA to dihydrofolate. Bacteria require de novo folate synthesis (humans absorb folate from diet, so are not affected).<br><br>Trimethoprim, often combined with sulfonamides (trimethoprim-sulfamethoxazole, co-trimoxazole), inhibits dihydrofolate reductase, blocking the next step. The combination is synergistic (sequential blockade of folate synthesis). Sulfonamides are avoided in first trimester (folate antagonism, NTD risk) and near term (kernicterus from bilirubin displacement).<br><br>D (Sulfonamides) is correct because they inhibit dihydropteroate synthase in folate synthesis. A (Penicillin) is wrong because it inhibits cell wall synthesis. B (Erythromycin) is wrong because it inhibits protein synthesis. C (Ciprofloxacin) is wrong because it inhibits DNA gyrase.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Sulfonamides, Trimethoprim, and Quinolones)</em>`},
    {q:'Which antibiotic class demonstrates time-dependent bactericidal activity?',o:['Aminoglycosides','Beta-lactams','Metronidazole','Fluoroquinolones'],a:1,
    e:`Beta-lactams (penicillins, cephalosporins, carbapenems) demonstrate time-dependent bactericidal activity. Killing increases with the duration that drug concentration exceeds the MIC (T>MIC), not with peak concentrations. Optimal dosing maintains levels above MIC for as much of the dosing interval as possible.<br><br>This pharmacodynamic principle supports frequent dosing or continuous infusion of beta-lactams in serious infections. In contrast, aminoglycosides and fluoroquinolones show concentration-dependent killing (higher peaks produce greater killing), supporting once-daily dosing.<br><br>B (Beta-lactams) is correct because their killing is time-dependent. A (Aminoglycosides) is wrong because they are concentration-dependent. C (Fluoroquinolones) is wrong because they are also concentration-dependent. D (Macrolides) is wrong because while macrolides are mainly time-dependent, beta-lactams are the classic time-dependent example.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Beta-Lactam and Other Cell Wall- and Membrane-Active Antibiotics)</em>`},
    {q:'Which antibiotic is preferred for treatment of chorioamnionitis as part of combination therapy?',o:['Tetracycline','Chloramphenicol','Ciprofloxacin','Ampicillin'],a:3,
    e:`Ampicillin is preferred for treatment of chorioamnionitis (intra-amniotic infection) in combination with gentamicin. Standard regimen: ampicillin 2 g IV every 6 hours plus gentamicin 5 mg/kg IV once daily until delivery and afebrile for 24 to 48 hours.<br><br>Chorioamnionitis is typically polymicrobial (anaerobes, Gram-negatives, Group B Streptococcus). After caesarean delivery, clindamycin or metronidazole is added for anaerobic coverage. Maternal sepsis can develop rapidly; expedited delivery is part of management. Failure to treat causes maternal endometritis and neonatal sepsis.<br><br>D (Ampicillin) is correct because ampicillin (with gentamicin) is the standard chorioamnionitis regimen. A (Tetracycline) is wrong because tetracyclines are contraindicated. B (Doxycycline) is wrong because it is also a tetracycline. C (Ciprofloxacin) is wrong because fluoroquinolones are avoided.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics; Chapter: Premature Rupture of Membranes)</em>`},
    {q:'Which antibiotic is associated with inhibition of mitochondrial protein synthesis leading to gray baby syndrome?',o:['Cefazolin','Amoxicillin','Chloramphenicol','Azithromycin'],a:2,
    e:`Chloramphenicol is associated with inhibition of mitochondrial protein synthesis. Chloramphenicol binds to the 50S ribosomal subunit of bacteria and similarly to mitochondrial ribosomes (which are similar to bacterial ribosomes), causing dose-related bone marrow suppression.<br><br>Other chloramphenicol toxicities include idiosyncratic aplastic anaemia (dose-independent, can be fatal) and gray baby syndrome in neonates (immature glucuronidation causing chloramphenicol accumulation, with pallor, abdominal distension, vomiting and circulatory collapse). Chloramphenicol is rarely used due to these toxicities.<br><br>C (Chloramphenicol) is correct because it inhibits mitochondrial protein synthesis. A (Penicillin) is wrong because penicillin acts on bacterial cell walls. B (Cefazolin) is wrong because cephalosporins act on cell walls. D (Erythromycin) is wrong because while macrolides also bind 50S, chloramphenicol is the classic mitochondrial protein synthesis inhibitor.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Tetracyclines, Macrolides, Clindamycin, Chloramphenicol, Streptogramins, and Oxazolidinones)</em>`},
    {q:'Which antibiotic combination is classically used in severe pelvic sepsis?',o:['Clindamycin + gentamicin','Amoxicillin + paracetamol','Ciprofloxacin + insulin','Doxycycline + warfarin'],a:0,
    e:`Clindamycin plus gentamicin is the antibiotic combination classically used in severe pelvic infections (including postpartum endometritis, postoperative pelvic infections and septic abortion). Standard regimen: clindamycin 900 mg IV every 8 hours plus gentamicin 5 mg/kg IV once daily.<br><br>Clindamycin covers anaerobes (Bacteroides, Peptostreptococcus) and Gram-positive cocci. Gentamicin covers Gram-negative bacilli. The combination provides broad polymicrobial coverage. Alternative regimens include ampicillin-sulbactam, piperacillin-tazobactam or carbapenems for severe infections. Treatment continues until afebrile and clinically improved for 48 hours.<br><br>A (Clindamycin + gentamicin) is correct because this is the classic severe pelvic infection regimen. B (Penicillin + tetracycline) is wrong because tetracyclines are contraindicated. C (Doxycycline + erythromycin) is wrong because doxycycline is contraindicated. D (Ciprofloxacin + ampicillin) is wrong because fluoroquinolones are avoided.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics; Chapter: The Puerperium)</em>`},
    {q:'Which analgesic is considered the drug of choice for mild to moderate pain during pregnancy due to its safety profile?',o:['Ibuprofen','Aspirin','Paracetamol','Ketorolac'],a:2,
    e:`Paracetamol is the analgesic of choice for mild to moderate pain throughout pregnancy. It has minimal anti-inflammatory effect and does not significantly inhibit COX in peripheral tissues. Standard dose is 500 to 1000 mg PO every 4 to 6 hours (maximum 4 g/day).<br><br>NSAIDs (aspirin, ibuprofen, diclofenac) are avoided in the third trimester due to risk of premature ductus arteriosus closure, oligohydramnios and prolonged labour. Aspirin at antiplatelet doses (75 to 150 mg) is used for pre-eclampsia prevention but full doses are avoided. Opioids are reserved for severe pain.<br><br>C (Paracetamol) is correct because it is the safest analgesic in pregnancy. A (Diclofenac) is wrong because it is an NSAID with third-trimester concerns. B (Aspirin) is wrong because full analgesic doses are avoided. D (Ibuprofen) is wrong because it is also an NSAID.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Common medical disorders in pregnancy)</em>`},
    {q:'Non-steroidal anti-inflammatory drugs (NSAIDs) are generally avoided in the third trimester because they may cause:',o:['Premature closure of ductus arteriosus','Neural tube defects','Fetal tachycardia','Polyhydramnios'],a:0,
    e:`NSAIDs are generally avoided in the third trimester because they cause premature closure of the ductus arteriosus. NSAIDs inhibit prostaglandin synthesis (especially PGE2 maintaining ductal patency), causing premature closure with right ventricular hypertrophy and pulmonary hypertension.<br><br>NSAIDs are therefore avoided after 30 weeks gestation. Other late-pregnancy concerns include oligohydramnios (reduced fetal renal perfusion) and prolonged labour. Paracetamol is preferred for analgesia and antipyresis throughout pregnancy. Aspirin at antiplatelet doses (75 to 150 mg) is used for pre-eclampsia prevention but full doses are avoided.<br><br>A (Premature closure of ductus arteriosus) is correct because COX inhibition removes prostaglandin maintenance of ductal patency. B (Patent ductus arteriosus) is wrong because NSAIDs close, not open, the ductus. C (Ventricular septal defect) is wrong because it is unrelated to NSAIDs. D (Coarctation of aorta) is wrong because it is unrelated to NSAIDs.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Nonsteroidal Anti-Inflammatory Drugs)</em>`},
    {q:'Which opioid analgesic is commonly used for pain relief during labor?',o:['Diclofenac','Ketorolac','Ibuprofen','Pethidine'],a:3,
    e:`Pethidine (meperidine) is commonly used for pain relief during labour. Standard dose is 50 to 100 mg IM, repeated every 4 hours as needed. Onset is 10 to 20 minutes IM, duration 2 to 4 hours.<br><br>Pethidine acts on μ-opioid receptors. It produces analgesia, sedation and euphoria. Side effects include maternal nausea, vomiting, sedation and rare respiratory depression. The active metabolite norpethidine has a long half-life (15 to 20 hours) and may cause neonatal sedation, poor feeding and reduced Apgar scores when given within 1 to 4 hours before delivery.<br><br>D (Pethidine) is correct because it is a commonly used labour opioid. A (Tetracycline) is wrong because it is an antibiotic. B (Insulin) is wrong because it is for diabetes. C (Methyldopa) is wrong because it is an antihypertensive.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Opioid Analgesics and Antagonists)</em>`},
    {q:'Neonatal respiratory depression following maternal opioid administration during labor can be reversed by:',o:['Diazepam','Naloxone','Atropine','Metoclopramide'],a:1,
    e:`Neonatal respiratory depression following maternal opioid administration is reversed with naloxone (0.1 mg/kg IV, IM or IT). Naloxone is a competitive μ-opioid receptor antagonist that displaces opioids from receptors, restoring respiratory drive within 1 to 2 minutes.<br><br>Repeat doses may be needed because naloxone\'s half-life (60 to 90 minutes) is shorter than most opioids\'. Continuous infusion may be required for long-acting opioids. Avoid in infants of opioid-dependent mothers (precipitates withdrawal). Maternal opioid doses should be timed to avoid administration within 1 to 4 hours before delivery.<br><br>B (Naloxone) is correct because it reverses opioid-induced respiratory depression. A (Insulin) is wrong because it is for diabetes. C (Atropine) is wrong because atropine is for bradycardia/secretions. D (Ephedrine) is wrong because ephedrine is for hypotension.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Opioid Analgesics and Antagonists)</em>`},
    {q:'Which analgesic mechanism primarily explains the action of paracetamol?',o:['Opioid receptor activation','Peripheral COX-1 inhibition','Central inhibition of prostaglandin synthesis','Serotonin receptor blockade'],a:2,
    e:`Paracetamol\'s analgesic action primarily involves central inhibition of prostaglandin synthesis. Paracetamol inhibits COX (cyclooxygenase) in the central nervous system but has minimal effect on peripheral COX. This explains its analgesic and antipyretic effects without significant anti-inflammatory or peripheral side effects (no gastric ulceration, no antiplatelet effect, no renal effects).<br><br>The mechanism may involve COX-3 inhibition or interaction with TRPV1, cannabinoid CB1 and serotonergic descending pain pathways. Paracetamol is the safest analgesic in pregnancy due to minimal teratogenic potential and no third-trimester concerns. Hepatotoxicity occurs at doses >4 g/day or in alcohol abusers.<br><br>C (Central inhibition of prostaglandin synthesis) is correct because paracetamol acts centrally on COX. A (Direct opioid receptor activation) is wrong because paracetamol does not bind opioid receptors. B (Peripheral cyclooxygenase inhibition) is wrong because paracetamol\'s peripheral COX effect is minimal. D (Sodium channel blockade) is wrong because that is the local anaesthetic mechanism.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Nonsteroidal Anti-Inflammatory Drugs)</em>`},
    {q:'A pregnant woman with severe renal colic requires analgesia. Which opioid is often preferred due to its rapid onset and high potency?',o:['Codeine','Tramadol','Pethidine','Fentanyl'],a:3,
    e:`A pregnant woman with severe renal colic requiring analgesia may receive fentanyl. Strong opioids (morphine, fentanyl, pethidine) are appropriate for severe pain. Fentanyl is preferred for its rapid onset, short duration and good safety profile.<br><br>NSAIDs (which are usually first-line for renal colic outside pregnancy) are avoided in third trimester due to ductal closure risk. Paracetamol alone is inadequate for severe renal colic. Opioids should be timed to avoid administration within 1 to 4 hours before delivery to prevent neonatal respiratory depression.<br><br>D (Fentanyl) is correct because strong opioids are appropriate for severe renal colic in pregnancy. A (Aspirin) is wrong because aspirin (NSAID) is avoided in pregnancy. B (Ibuprofen) is wrong because it is an NSAID. C (Paracetamol) is wrong because paracetamol alone is inadequate for severe renal colic.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Opioid Analgesics and Antagonists)</em>`},
    {q:'Prolonged maternal opioid use during pregnancy is most likely to result in which neonatal complication?',o:['Neonatal abstinence syndrome','Neonatal hypothyroidism','Neural tube defects','Polycythemia'],a:0,
    e:`Prolonged maternal opioid use during pregnancy is most likely to cause neonatal abstinence syndrome (NAS) in the newborn. NAS results from sudden withdrawal from in-utero opioid exposure after delivery, with hyperirritability, high-pitched cry, tremor, hypertonia, poor feeding, vomiting, diarrhoea, sweating, tachypnoea and rare seizures.<br><br>Onset is within 24 to 72 hours of birth (longer for methadone and buprenorphine). Treatment includes supportive care (swaddling, low stimulation environment, frequent small feeds) and pharmacological treatment (oral morphine or methadone) if severe. Most infants recover fully with appropriate care.<br><br>A (Neonatal abstinence syndrome) is correct because chronic opioid exposure causes neonatal withdrawal. B (Cardiac defects) is wrong because opioids are not strongly associated with cardiac defects. C (Cleft lip) is wrong because opioids are not strongly associated with cleft lip. D (Neural tube defects) is wrong because NTDs are associated with valproate, methotrexate, folate antagonists.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics; Chapter: Substance Use and Abuse)</em>`},
    {q:'Which NSAID works primarily by inhibiting cyclooxygenase and reducing prostaglandin synthesis?',o:['Morphine','Ibuprofen','Tramadol','Codeine'],a:1,
    e:`Ibuprofen works primarily by inhibiting cyclooxygenase (COX-1 and COX-2) and reducing prostaglandin synthesis. Reduced prostaglandins decrease inflammation, pain and fever.<br><br>Ibuprofen is non-selective (inhibits both COX-1 and COX-2). COX-1 inhibition causes gastric ulceration (loss of mucosal protection) and antiplatelet effect. COX-2 inhibition mediates anti-inflammatory action. Ibuprofen is safer for occasional use in early pregnancy but avoided after 30 weeks due to ductal closure risk.<br><br>B (Ibuprofen) is correct because it is a non-selective COX inhibitor. A (Paracetamol) is wrong because paracetamol acts centrally with minimal peripheral COX effect. C (Aspirin) is wrong because while aspirin is also a COX inhibitor, ibuprofen is the better-known reversible non-selective inhibitor (aspirin is irreversible). D (Fentanyl) is wrong because fentanyl is an opioid agonist.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Nonsteroidal Anti-Inflammatory Drugs)</em>`},
    {q:'During labor analgesia, pethidine produces its analgesic effect mainly through:',o:['NMDA receptor blockade','Dopamine receptor antagonism','μ-opioid receptor activation','Serotonin receptor inhibition'],a:2,
    e:`Pethidine produces its analgesic effect primarily through μ-opioid receptor activation. μ-opioid receptors are G-protein coupled receptors located in the brain, spinal cord and periphery. Activation produces analgesia, euphoria, sedation, respiratory depression and miosis.<br><br>Pethidine has lower potency than morphine (about 1/10) but similar pharmacological profile. The active metabolite norpethidine has a long half-life (15 to 20 hours) and CNS-stimulant properties (can cause seizures with accumulation, especially in renal impairment). Pethidine should be timed to avoid administration within 1 to 4 hours before delivery.<br><br>C (μ-opioid receptor activation) is correct because pethidine is a μ-opioid agonist. A (Cyclooxygenase inhibition) is wrong because that is the NSAID mechanism. B (Sodium channel blockade) is wrong because that is the local anaesthetic mechanism. D (NMDA receptor antagonism) is wrong because NMDA antagonism is the ketamine mechanism.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Opioid Analgesics and Antagonists)</em>`},
    {q:'Which opioid analgesic also inhibits serotonin and norepinephrine reuptake?',o:['Morphine','Tramadol','Pethidine','Codeine'],a:1,
    e:`Tramadol also inhibits serotonin and norepinephrine reuptake in addition to its weak μ-opioid agonist activity. The dual mechanism gives it analgesic effects through both opioid and monoaminergic pain pathways.<br><br>Tramadol is a weak μ-agonist (about 1/6000 the potency of morphine for the parent drug; the M1 metabolite is more potent). The serotonin and norepinephrine reuptake inhibition contributes substantially to analgesia. Side effects include nausea, vomiting, dizziness, seizures (lower threshold) and serotonin syndrome with concurrent SSRIs/SNRIs.<br><br>B (Tramadol) is correct because it has dual opioid and monoaminergic activity. A (Morphine) is wrong because morphine is a pure μ-opioid agonist. C (Fentanyl) is wrong because fentanyl is a pure μ-opioid agonist. D (Pethidine) is wrong because pethidine is mainly a μ-opioid agonist (with some sodium channel and other minor effects, but not significant monoamine reuptake inhibition).<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Opioid Analgesics and Antagonists)</em>`},
    {q:'Administration of opioids shortly before delivery most commonly leads to which neonatal complication?',o:['Hyperglycemia','Hyperthermia','Hypertension','Respiratory depression'],a:3,
    e:`Administration of opioids shortly before delivery most commonly causes neonatal respiratory depression. Opioids cross the placenta and depress the neonate\'s respiratory drive at birth. Apgar scores may be reduced, and resuscitation may be needed.<br><br>Naloxone (0.1 mg/kg IV, IM or IT) reverses opioid-induced neonatal respiratory depression. Pethidine (meperidine) is particularly known for prolonged neonatal effects (its active metabolite norpethidine has a long half-life). Limiting opioid doses near delivery (avoid within 1 to 4 hours) and timing administration appropriately reduce risk.<br><br>D (Respiratory depression) is correct because opioids cross the placenta and depress the neonate. A (Hyperglycemia) is wrong because opioids do not raise glucose. B (Hyperkalemia) is wrong because opioids do not raise potassium. C (Hyperthermia) is wrong because opioids do not cause hyperthermia.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Opioid Analgesics and Antagonists)</em>`},
    {q:'NSAID-induced oligohydramnios in late pregnancy is primarily due to:',o:['Reduced fetal renal perfusion','Increased placental blood flow','Increased fetal urine output','Enhanced uterine contractility'],a:0,
    e:`NSAID-induced oligohydramnios in late pregnancy is primarily due to reduced fetal renal perfusion. Prostaglandins maintain fetal renal blood flow; their inhibition reduces glomerular filtration and urine output, depleting amniotic fluid (which is mainly fetal urine after 20 weeks).<br><br>Other NSAID-related fetal effects include premature ductus arteriosus closure (right heart failure) and necrotising enterocolitis in preterm infants. NSAIDs are therefore avoided in the third trimester. Reversibility depends on duration of exposure; early discontinuation usually allows recovery of amniotic fluid volume.<br><br>A (Reduced fetal renal perfusion) is correct because COX inhibition reduces fetal renal blood flow and urine production. B (Increased fetal swallowing) is wrong because NSAIDs do not affect fetal swallowing. C (Decreased fetal cardiac output) is wrong because the primary mechanism is renal not cardiac. D (Increased amniotic fluid production) is wrong because NSAIDs reduce, not increase, amniotic fluid.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Nonsteroidal Anti-Inflammatory Drugs)</em>`},
    {q:'Which analgesic is most associated with gastric mucosal irritation due to irreversible COX inhibition?',o:['Morphine','Paracetamol','Tramadol','Aspirin'],a:3,
    e:`Aspirin is most associated with gastric mucosal irritation. Aspirin irreversibly inhibits COX-1 in gastric mucosa, reducing prostaglandin-mediated mucosal protection (PGE2 stimulates mucus and bicarbonate secretion, maintains mucosal blood flow). The result is gastric erosions, ulceration and bleeding.<br><br>Aspirin\'s antiplatelet effect (irreversible COX-1 inhibition in platelets, lasting the platelet lifespan of 7 to 10 days) compounds the bleeding risk. Other side effects include rare Reye syndrome in children, salicylate toxicity at overdose and bronchospasm in aspirin-sensitive patients. Low-dose aspirin (75 to 150 mg) is used for pre-eclampsia prevention.<br><br>D (Aspirin) is correct because aspirin causes gastric mucosal irritation through COX-1 inhibition. A (Paracetamol) is wrong because paracetamol does not significantly inhibit peripheral COX-1 and is gastric-safe. B (Fentanyl) is wrong because opioids do not cause gastric mucosal damage. C (Morphine) is wrong because opioids cause constipation, not gastric ulceration.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Nonsteroidal Anti-Inflammatory Drugs)</em>`},
    {q:'Which opioid analgesic is the most potent among the following?',o:['Codeine','Fentanyl','Pethidine','Morphine'],a:1,
    e:`Fentanyl is the most potent opioid analgesic (about 100 times more potent than morphine on a milligram basis). Standard dose is 50 to 100 μg IV for analgesia (about 5 to 10 mg morphine equivalent).<br><br>Fentanyl is highly lipophilic with rapid onset (within 1 minute IV) and short duration (30 to 60 minutes for analgesic doses). It is widely used in obstetric epidurals and spinals (10 to 25 μg combined with local anaesthetic). Side effects include respiratory depression, sedation, nausea, vomiting and rare chest wall rigidity at high doses.<br><br>B (Fentanyl) is correct because fentanyl is the most potent opioid in the listed options. A (Morphine) is wrong because morphine is the reference standard with potency 1. C (Pethidine) is wrong because pethidine is about 1/10 as potent as morphine. D (Tramadol) is wrong because tramadol is much weaker than morphine.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Opioid Analgesics and Antagonists)</em>`},
    {q:'Codeine produces analgesia primarily after hepatic conversion to:',o:['Morphine','Hydromorphone','Oxycodone','Methadone'],a:0,
    e:`Codeine produces analgesia primarily after hepatic conversion to morphine. About 10 percent of codeine is converted to morphine by CYP2D6 (cytochrome P450 2D6); morphine is the main analgesic mediator.<br><br>CYP2D6 polymorphism affects codeine response: ultra-rapid metabolisers (1 to 7 percent of population, varying by ethnicity) produce excess morphine and risk respiratory depression; poor metabolisers (5 to 10 percent of Caucasians) produce inadequate morphine and have poor analgesia. In breastfeeding mothers, ultra-rapid metabolism has caused infant deaths from morphine accumulation in milk.<br><br>A (Morphine) is correct because codeine is converted to morphine for analgesic effect. B (Insulin) is wrong because codeine has no relationship to insulin. C (Acetylcholine) is wrong because codeine does not act through acetylcholine. D (Dopamine) is wrong because codeine does not act through dopamine.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Opioid Analgesics and Antagonists)</em>`},
    {q:'Which analgesic is most appropriate for postpartum perineal pain after vaginal delivery?',o:['Fentanyl','Morphine','Ibuprofen','Ketamine'],a:2,
    e:`Ibuprofen is most appropriate for postpartum perineal pain analgesia. NSAIDs are first-line for postpartum pain because they provide effective analgesia for inflammatory pain (perineal trauma, episiotomy, uterine contractions). Standard dose is 400 to 600 mg PO every 6 to 8 hours.<br><br>NSAIDs are now considered safe in postpartum period including for breastfeeding mothers. Paracetamol is also commonly used in combination. Opioids are reserved for severe pain. The third-trimester NSAID restrictions (ductus arteriosus closure, oligohydramnios) no longer apply once the baby is delivered.<br><br>C (Ibuprofen) is correct because NSAIDs are first-line for postpartum pain. A (Insulin) is wrong because it is for diabetes. B (Penicillin) is wrong because it is an antibiotic. D (Methyldopa) is wrong because it is an antihypertensive.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics; Chapter: The Puerperium)</em>`},
    {q:'The principal receptor responsible for opioid analgesia is:',o:['κ receptor','δ receptor','σ receptor','μ receptor'],a:3,
    e:`The principal receptor responsible for opioid analgesia is the μ (mu) receptor. μ-opioid receptors are G-protein coupled receptors located in brain, spinal cord and periphery. Activation produces analgesia, euphoria, sedation, respiratory depression, miosis, constipation and physical dependence.<br><br>Other opioid receptors include κ (kappa) receptors (analgesia, sedation, dysphoria), δ (delta) receptors (analgesia, mood modulation) and nociceptin/orphanin FQ receptors. Most clinically used opioids (morphine, fentanyl, pethidine, codeine) are primarily μ agonists. Naloxone is a competitive μ antagonist used to reverse opioid toxicity.<br><br>D (μ receptor) is correct because μ-opioid receptors mediate the principal opioid analgesic effects. A (κ receptor) is wrong because while κ receptors mediate some analgesia, μ is principal. B (δ receptor) is wrong because δ receptors mediate mood modulation more than analgesia. C (Sigma receptor) is wrong because sigma receptors are no longer classified as opioid receptors.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Opioid Analgesics and Antagonists)</em>`},
    {q:'Paracetamol overdose in pregnancy should be treated with which antidote?',o:['Flumazenil','N-acetylcysteine','Naloxone','Atropine'],a:1,
    e:`Paracetamol overdose in pregnancy is treated with N-acetylcysteine (NAC), the standard antidote. NAC replenishes hepatic glutathione, which is depleted by paracetamol\'s toxic metabolite NAPQI (N-acetyl-p-benzoquinone imine).<br><br>Standard regimen: IV NAC (150 mg/kg over 1 hour, then 50 mg/kg over 4 hours, then 100 mg/kg over 16 hours) for serious overdose. Treatment is most effective if started within 8 to 10 hours of overdose. Pregnancy does not change the regimen; NAC is not teratogenic and treats both maternal and fetal toxicity. Severe paracetamol overdose risks fetal hepatic injury.<br><br>B (N-acetylcysteine) is correct because NAC is the standard paracetamol overdose antidote. A (Naloxone) is wrong because naloxone reverses opioid overdose. C (Flumazenil) is wrong because flumazenil reverses benzodiazepine overdose. D (Atropine) is wrong because atropine reverses muscarinic toxicity.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Nonsteroidal Anti-Inflammatory Drugs)</em>`},
    {q:'Which adverse effect is most frequently associated with opioid analgesics?',o:['Constipation','Diarrhea','Hypertension','Hyperglycemia'],a:0,
    e:`Constipation is the most frequently associated adverse effect with opioid use. Opioids activate μ-opioid receptors in the gastrointestinal tract, reducing gut motility, increasing fluid absorption and causing constipation. Tolerance to constipation does not develop unlike most other opioid effects.<br><br>Other common opioid side effects include nausea, vomiting (chemoreceptor trigger zone activation), sedation, respiratory depression, miosis, urinary retention and itching. Tolerance develops to most effects (analgesia, sedation, respiratory depression) but not to constipation. Stool softeners and stimulant laxatives are commonly co-prescribed with chronic opioid use.<br><br>A (Constipation) is correct because constipation is the most common opioid side effect. B (Diarrhea) is wrong because opioids cause constipation, not diarrhoea. C (Hyperthermia) is wrong because opioids do not raise temperature. D (Hyperglycemia) is wrong because opioids do not raise glucose.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Opioid Analgesics and Antagonists)</em>`},
    {q:'NSAIDs produce analgesia mainly by inhibiting which enzyme?',o:['Phospholipase A2','Adenylate cyclase','Cyclooxygenase','Lipoxygenase'],a:2,
    e:`NSAIDs produce analgesia mainly by inhibiting cyclooxygenase (COX), reducing prostaglandin synthesis. Reduced prostaglandins decrease inflammation, pain sensitisation of peripheral nociceptors and febrile response in the hypothalamus.<br><br>Non-selective NSAIDs (aspirin, ibuprofen, indomethacin, diclofenac) inhibit both COX-1 and COX-2. COX-2-selective inhibitors (celecoxib) reduce GI side effects from COX-1 inhibition but increase cardiovascular risk. NSAIDs are avoided in third trimester due to ductal closure risk.<br><br>C (Cyclooxygenase) is correct because NSAIDs inhibit COX. A (Sodium channels) is wrong because that is the local anaesthetic mechanism. B (Calcium channels) is wrong because that is the calcium channel blocker mechanism. D (Acetylcholine receptors) is wrong because that is not the NSAID mechanism.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Nonsteroidal Anti-Inflammatory Drugs)</em>`},
    {q:'Which analgesic causes platelet inhibition due to irreversible COX-1 blockade?',o:['Aspirin','Paracetamol','Morphine','Tramadol'],a:0,
    e:`Aspirin causes platelet inhibition due to irreversible cyclooxygenase (COX-1) inhibition in platelets. Aspirin acetylates a serine residue in COX-1, permanently inactivating the enzyme. Platelets cannot synthesise new COX (lacking nuclei), so the antiplatelet effect lasts the platelet lifespan (7 to 10 days).<br><br>This irreversible mechanism distinguishes aspirin from other NSAIDs (which reversibly inhibit COX). Low-dose aspirin (75 to 150 mg) is used for cardiovascular prevention and pre-eclampsia prevention. Aspirin is avoided at full analgesic doses in pregnancy due to bleeding and ductus closure risks. Other antiplatelet drugs (clopidogrel, ticagrelor) act on different platelet pathways.<br><br>A (Aspirin) is correct because aspirin irreversibly inhibits platelet COX-1. B (Ibuprofen) is wrong because ibuprofen reversibly inhibits COX. C (Paracetamol) is wrong because paracetamol does not significantly affect peripheral COX or platelet function. D (Diclofenac) is wrong because diclofenac is also a reversible COX inhibitor.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Nonsteroidal Anti-Inflammatory Drugs)</em>`},
    {q:'Which opioid analgesic is frequently used for severe postoperative pain due to strong analgesic effect?',o:['Codeine','Pethidine','Tramadol','Morphine'],a:3,
    e:`Morphine is frequently used for severe postoperative pain after caesarean section. Standard regimen includes intrathecal morphine 0.1 to 0.2 mg added to spinal anaesthesia (provides 12 to 24 hours of postoperative analgesia), or IV/SC morphine via PCA, or oral morphine.<br><br>Multimodal analgesia is preferred: paracetamol (1 g every 6 hours) plus NSAID (ibuprofen 400 mg every 6 hours) plus opioids (morphine, oxycodone, codeine) for breakthrough pain. Side effects include sedation, nausea, vomiting, constipation, pruritus and rare respiratory depression. Naloxone reverses respiratory depression.<br><br>D (Morphine) is correct because morphine is widely used for postoperative pain. A (Insulin) is wrong because it is for diabetes. B (Penicillin) is wrong because it is an antibiotic. C (Methyldopa) is wrong because it is an antihypertensive.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Opioid Analgesics and Antagonists)</em>`},
    {q:'Which maternal adverse effect commonly follows pethidine administration during labor?',o:['Polyuria','Nausea and vomiting','Hyperglycemia','Severe hypertension'],a:1,
    e:`Pethidine (meperidine) administration commonly causes maternal nausea and vomiting. Opioid activation of the chemoreceptor trigger zone in the area postrema causes nausea. Pethidine also has antimuscarinic activity that can cause additional GI effects.<br><br>Other pethidine side effects include sedation, dizziness, constipation, dry mouth and rare respiratory depression. Antiemetics (metoclopramide, ondansetron) may be co-administered to reduce nausea. Pethidine should be timed to avoid administration within 1 to 4 hours before delivery to prevent neonatal respiratory depression and norpethidine accumulation.<br><br>B (Nausea and vomiting) is correct because nausea and vomiting are common opioid (pethidine) side effects. A (Hypertension) is wrong because pethidine does not cause hypertension. C (Hypothermia) is wrong because pethidine does not lower temperature. D (Hyperglycemia) is wrong because pethidine does not raise glucose.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Opioid Analgesics and Antagonists)</em>`},
    {q:'Which analgesic is least likely to cause respiratory depression?',o:['Morphine','Fentanyl','Paracetamol','Pethidine'],a:2,
    e:`Paracetamol is least likely to cause respiratory depression. Paracetamol acts centrally on COX with minimal peripheral effects and does not affect respiratory drive at therapeutic doses. It is the safest analgesic in pregnancy due to minimal teratogenic potential and no third-trimester concerns.<br><br>Opioids (morphine, fentanyl, pethidine, codeine) all cause dose-dependent respiratory depression through μ-opioid receptor activation in brainstem respiratory centres. Severe overdose can cause apnoea and death. Naloxone reverses opioid-induced respiratory depression. NSAIDs do not cause respiratory depression directly but can cause asthma exacerbation in aspirin-sensitive patients.<br><br>C (Paracetamol) is correct because paracetamol does not cause respiratory depression. A (Morphine) is wrong because morphine causes dose-dependent respiratory depression. B (Pethidine) is wrong because pethidine causes respiratory depression. D (Fentanyl) is wrong because fentanyl causes respiratory depression.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Nonsteroidal Anti-Inflammatory Drugs)</em>`},
    {q:'Which drug is the specific antagonist used to reverse opioid overdose?',o:['Naloxone','Flumazenil','Metoclopramide','Atropine'],a:0,
    e:`Naloxone is the specific antagonist used to reverse opioid-induced respiratory depression. It is a competitive μ-opioid receptor antagonist that displaces opioids from receptors, restoring respiratory drive within 1 to 2 minutes.<br><br>Standard dose is 0.4 to 2 mg IV repeated every 2 to 3 minutes as needed. For neonatal respiratory depression: 0.1 mg/kg IV, IM or IT. Repeat doses may be needed because naloxone\'s half-life (60 to 90 minutes) is shorter than most opioids\'. Continuous infusion may be required for long-acting opioids. Avoid in opioid-dependent patients (precipitates withdrawal).<br><br>A (Naloxone) is correct because naloxone is the specific opioid antagonist. B (Flumazenil) is wrong because flumazenil reverses benzodiazepines. C (Atropine) is wrong because atropine reverses muscarinic toxicity. D (Calcium gluconate) is wrong because calcium gluconate reverses magnesium toxicity.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Opioid Analgesics and Antagonists)</em>`},
    {q:'Which analgesic is commonly used in multimodal analgesia following cesarean section?',o:['Codeine','Paracetamol','Morphine','Fentanyl'],a:1,
    e:`Paracetamol is commonly used in multimodal analgesia following caesarean section. Standard regimen: paracetamol 1 g PO/IV every 6 hours plus NSAID (ibuprofen 400 mg every 6 hours) plus opioids (morphine via PCA or oral) for breakthrough pain.<br><br>Multimodal analgesia targets multiple pain pathways with synergistic analgesia, reduced opioid requirements and fewer side effects. Paracetamol provides effective baseline analgesia with minimal side effects. NSAIDs add anti-inflammatory action. Opioids add strong analgesia for breakthrough pain. Intrathecal morphine added to spinal anaesthesia provides 12 to 24 hours of postoperative analgesia.<br><br>B (Paracetamol) is correct because paracetamol is a multimodal analgesia mainstay. A (Insulin) is wrong because it is for diabetes. C (Methyldopa) is wrong because it is an antihypertensive. D (Penicillin) is wrong because it is an antibiotic.<br><br><em>(Williams Obstetrics; Chapter: Cesarean Delivery)</em>`},
    {q:'The rapid onset of fentanyl is primarily due to its:',o:['Slow hepatic metabolism','Low potency','Poor protein binding','High lipid solubility'],a:3,
    e:`The rapid onset of fentanyl is primarily due to its high lipid solubility. Fentanyl is highly lipophilic, allowing rapid crossing of the blood-brain barrier and rapid distribution to brain tissue. Onset is within 1 minute IV.<br><br>High lipid solubility also allows rapid redistribution from brain back to peripheral tissues, contributing to short duration of action (30 to 60 minutes for analgesic doses). Fentanyl is widely used in obstetric epidurals and spinals (10 to 25 μg combined with local anaesthetic) due to its rapid onset, predictable potency and short duration. Side effects include respiratory depression, sedation, nausea and rare chest wall rigidity at high doses.<br><br>D (High lipid solubility) is correct because lipophilicity drives rapid CNS penetration. A (High molecular weight) is wrong because fentanyl is small (336 Da). B (Strong ionization) is wrong because heavily ionised drugs cross BBB poorly. C (Active metabolism) is wrong because fentanyl rapidity is not from metabolic activation.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Opioid Analgesics and Antagonists)</em>`},
    {q:'Prolonged NSAID exposure late in pregnancy may cause:',o:['Neural tube defects','Fetal anemia','Ductus arteriosus constriction','Fetal hypothyroidism'],a:2,
    e:`Prolonged NSAID exposure late in pregnancy may cause ductus arteriosus constriction (premature closure). NSAIDs inhibit prostaglandin synthesis (especially PGE2 maintaining ductal patency), causing premature closure with right ventricular hypertrophy and pulmonary hypertension.<br><br>NSAIDs are therefore avoided after 30 weeks gestation. Other late-pregnancy concerns include oligohydramnios (reduced fetal renal perfusion) and prolonged labour. Reversibility depends on duration; early discontinuation usually allows recovery. Indomethacin used as a tocolytic is similarly limited to under 32 weeks for less than 48 hours.<br><br>C (Ductus arteriosus constriction) is correct because COX inhibition removes PGE2 maintenance of ductal patency. A (Patent ductus arteriosus) is wrong because NSAIDs close, not open, the ductus. B (Ventricular septal defect) is wrong because it is unrelated to NSAIDs. D (Coarctation of aorta) is wrong because it is unrelated to NSAIDs.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Nonsteroidal Anti-Inflammatory Drugs)</em>`},
    {q:'Which opioid analgesic is relatively weak and often used for mild to moderate pain?',o:['Codeine','Morphine','Fentanyl','Methadone'],a:0,
    e:`Codeine is a relatively weak opioid often used for mild to moderate pain. About 10 percent of codeine is converted to morphine by CYP2D6; morphine is the main analgesic mediator. Codeine is roughly 1/10 the potency of morphine.<br><br>CYP2D6 polymorphism affects codeine response: ultra-rapid metabolisers produce excess morphine and risk respiratory depression; poor metabolisers have inadequate analgesia. In breastfeeding mothers, ultra-rapid metabolism has caused infant deaths from morphine accumulation in milk. Codeine is often combined with paracetamol (co-codamol) for moderate pain.<br><br>A (Codeine) is correct because codeine is a relatively weak opioid for mild to moderate pain. B (Morphine) is wrong because morphine is a strong opioid for severe pain. C (Fentanyl) is wrong because fentanyl is the most potent opioid. D (Pethidine) is wrong because pethidine is intermediate potency.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Opioid Analgesics and Antagonists)</em>`},
    {q:'Naloxone reverses opioid toxicity by:',o:['Blocking dopamine receptors','Blocking μ-opioid receptors','Activating GABA receptors','Blocking serotonin receptors'],a:1,
    e:`Naloxone reverses opioid toxicity by blocking μ-opioid receptors. It is a competitive μ-opioid receptor antagonist that displaces opioids from receptors, restoring respiratory drive within 1 to 2 minutes.<br><br>Naloxone has higher affinity for μ-receptors than most clinical opioids, allowing rapid displacement. Standard dose is 0.4 to 2 mg IV repeated every 2 to 3 minutes as needed. For neonatal respiratory depression: 0.1 mg/kg IV, IM or IT. Repeat doses may be needed because naloxone\'s half-life (60 to 90 minutes) is shorter than most opioids\'. Continuous infusion may be required for long-acting opioids.<br><br>B (Blocking μ-opioid receptors) is correct because naloxone competitively antagonises μ-receptors. A (Stimulating respiratory centers) is wrong because naloxone does not directly stimulate respiration; it removes opioid-mediated suppression. C (Increasing prostaglandin synthesis) is wrong because naloxone does not affect prostaglandins. D (Releasing endorphins) is wrong because naloxone blocks, not releases, opioid system action.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Opioid Analgesics and Antagonists)</em>`},
    {q:'Which analgesic has both opioid agonist activity and monoamine reuptake inhibition?',o:['Morphine','Codeine','Fentanyl','Tramadol'],a:3,
    e:`Tramadol has both opioid agonist activity and monoaminergic effects. The dual mechanism gives it analgesic effects through both opioid (μ-receptor) and monoaminergic (serotonin and norepinephrine reuptake inhibition) pain pathways.<br><br>Tramadol is a weak μ-agonist (about 1/6000 the potency of morphine for the parent drug; the M1 metabolite is more potent). The serotonin and norepinephrine reuptake inhibition contributes substantially to analgesia. Side effects include nausea, vomiting, dizziness, lower seizure threshold and serotonin syndrome with concurrent SSRIs/SNRIs/MAOIs.<br><br>D (Tramadol) is correct because it has dual opioid and monoaminergic activity. A (Morphine) is wrong because morphine is a pure μ-opioid agonist. B (Fentanyl) is wrong because fentanyl is a pure μ-opioid agonist. C (Codeine) is wrong because codeine is a weak μ-opioid agonist (mostly via morphine metabolite) without significant monoaminergic effects.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Opioid Analgesics and Antagonists)</em>`},
    {q:'NSAID use may cause gastric ulceration due to:',o:['Increased gastrin release','Increased gastric acid secretion only','Inhibition of protective prostaglandins','Decreased bile secretion'],a:2,
    e:`NSAID-induced gastric ulceration is due to inhibition of protective prostaglandins (especially PGE2) in gastric mucosa. PGE2 stimulates mucus and bicarbonate secretion, maintains mucosal blood flow and reduces acid secretion - all protecting against acid damage.<br><br>NSAIDs (especially non-selective ones inhibiting COX-1) reduce these protective prostaglandins, causing gastric erosions, ulceration and bleeding. Risk factors include high doses, prolonged use, age >65, prior peptic ulcer, concurrent corticosteroids or anticoagulants, and Helicobacter pylori. Proton pump inhibitors (omeprazole) reduce risk. COX-2-selective inhibitors (celecoxib) cause less GI toxicity but more cardiovascular risk.<br><br>C (Inhibition of protective prostaglandins) is correct because reduced PGE2 reduces mucosal protection. A (Increased gastric secretion) is wrong because NSAIDs do not directly increase acid secretion. B (Direct gastric toxicity) is wrong because the primary mechanism is prostaglandin reduction. D (Increased Helicobacter pylori activity) is wrong because NSAIDs do not affect H. pylori activity.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Nonsteroidal Anti-Inflammatory Drugs)</em>`},
    {q:'Accumulation of which pethidine metabolite is associated with seizures?',o:['Normeperidine','Morphine-6-glucuronide','Codeine-6-glucuronide','Fentanyl citrate'],a:0,
    e:`Accumulation of normeperidine (norpethidine), the active metabolite of pethidine, is associated with neurotoxicity (CNS excitation, seizures). Normeperidine has a long half-life (15 to 20 hours) and CNS-stimulant properties, distinct from pethidine\'s analgesic effects.<br><br>Risk factors for normeperidine accumulation include prolonged or high-dose pethidine use, renal impairment (the metabolite is renally excreted) and elderly patients. Symptoms include agitation, tremor, myoclonus and seizures. Pethidine is therefore avoided for chronic pain management. In labour, doses should be limited and timed to avoid administration within 1 to 4 hours before delivery to prevent neonatal effects.<br><br>A (Normeperidine) is correct because the active metabolite causes neurotoxicity. B (Morphine-3-glucuronide) is wrong because that is a morphine metabolite. C (Norfentanyl) is wrong because norfentanyl is not significantly neurotoxic. D (Hydromorphone) is wrong because hydromorphone is itself a separate opioid, not a pethidine metabolite.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Opioid Analgesics and Antagonists)</em>`},
    {q:'Which analgesic is commonly used to treat dysmenorrhea due to inhibition of prostaglandin synthesis?',o:['Morphine','Codeine','Ibuprofen','Fentanyl'],a:2,
    e:`Ibuprofen is commonly used to treat dysmenorrhoea due to its inhibition of prostaglandin synthesis. Standard dose is 400 to 600 mg PO every 6 to 8 hours, started 1 to 2 days before expected menstruation and continued during menstruation.<br><br>Dysmenorrhoea is caused by excessive uterine prostaglandins (PGE2 and PGF2α) released from the secretory endometrium during menstruation, causing painful uterine contractions. NSAIDs reduce prostaglandin synthesis, relieving pain. Hormonal contraceptives (combined oral pills) are also effective by suppressing ovulation.<br><br>C (Ibuprofen) is correct because NSAIDs are first-line for dysmenorrhoea. A (Insulin) is wrong because it is for diabetes. B (Methyldopa) is wrong because it is an antihypertensive. D (Penicillin) is wrong because it is an antibiotic.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Nonsteroidal Anti-Inflammatory Drugs)</em>`},
    {q:'Which analgesic is considered safest for fever and pain during pregnancy?',o:['Diclofenac','Ketorolac','Aspirin','Paracetamol'],a:3,
    e:`Paracetamol is considered the safest analgesic for fever and pain during pregnancy. It has minimal anti-inflammatory effect and does not significantly inhibit COX in peripheral tissues. Standard dose is 500 to 1000 mg PO every 4 to 6 hours (maximum 4 g/day).<br><br>NSAIDs (aspirin, ibuprofen, diclofenac) are avoided in the third trimester due to risk of premature ductus arteriosus closure, oligohydramnios and prolonged labour. Aspirin at antiplatelet doses (75 to 150 mg) is used for pre-eclampsia prevention but full doses are avoided. Opioids are reserved for severe pain. Paracetamol is also the antipyretic of choice in pregnancy.<br><br>D (Paracetamol) is correct because it is the safest analgesic and antipyretic in pregnancy. A (Aspirin) is wrong because full doses are avoided in pregnancy. B (Ibuprofen) is wrong because NSAIDs are avoided in third trimester. C (Diclofenac) is wrong because it is also an NSAID.<br><br><em>(Obstetrics by Ten Teachers; Chapter: Common medical disorders in pregnancy)</em>`},
    {q:'Opioid-induced miosis occurs due to stimulation of which structure?',o:['Hypothalamus','Edinger-Westphal nucleus','Cerebellum','Basal ganglia'],a:1,
    e:`Opioid-induced miosis occurs due to stimulation of the Edinger-Westphal nucleus (parasympathetic nucleus controlling pupillary constriction). Opioids activate μ-receptors in this nucleus, stimulating parasympathetic outflow to the iris sphincter muscle and producing pupillary constriction.<br><br>Pinpoint pupils are characteristic of opioid intoxication and useful for clinical recognition. Tolerance does NOT develop to opioid-induced miosis (unlike most other opioid effects), making it a reliable sign of opioid use even in chronic users. Naloxone reverses opioid-induced miosis along with other effects. Severe opioid toxicity may show pinpoint pupils with respiratory depression and altered consciousness.<br><br>B (Edinger-Westphal nucleus) is correct because parasympathetic stimulation from this nucleus causes miosis. A (Locus coeruleus) is wrong because while opioids act on locus coeruleus, this is for autonomic effects, not directly miosis. C (Substantia nigra) is wrong because substantia nigra controls movement (Parkinson\'s pathway). D (Hypothalamus) is wrong because the hypothalamus does not directly control pupillary constriction.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Opioid Analgesics and Antagonists)</em>`},
    {q:'Which analgesic is commonly given intravenously for severe acute pain in obstetric emergencies?',o:['Paracetamol','Aspirin','Ibuprofen','Morphine'],a:3,
    e:`Morphine is commonly given intravenously for severe acute pain. It is the gold standard strong opioid against which others are compared. Standard IV dose is 2 to 5 mg every 5 minutes titrated to effect, or via PCA (patient-controlled analgesia) with 1 mg bolus and 5 to 10 minute lockout.<br><br>Onset is within 5 to 10 minutes IV; peak effect at 20 to 30 minutes; duration 3 to 4 hours. Side effects include sedation, nausea, vomiting, constipation, pruritus, urinary retention and rare respiratory depression. Naloxone reverses respiratory depression. Morphine is widely used in obstetrics for severe postoperative pain and intrathecal use during caesarean spinal anaesthesia.<br><br>D (Morphine) is correct because morphine is the standard strong IV opioid. A (Insulin) is wrong because it is for diabetes. B (Penicillin) is wrong because it is an antibiotic. C (Methyldopa) is wrong because it is an antihypertensive.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Opioid Analgesics and Antagonists)</em>`},
    {q:'The risk of serotonin syndrome with tramadol is primarily due to:',o:['Increased serotonin release','Dopamine receptor activation','Inhibition of serotonin reuptake','GABA receptor stimulation'],a:2,
    e:`The risk of serotonin syndrome with tramadol is primarily due to inhibition of serotonin reuptake. Tramadol blocks serotonin and norepinephrine reuptake (SNRI activity) in addition to its weak μ-opioid agonist activity. Concurrent use with other serotonergic drugs (SSRIs, SNRIs, MAOIs, lithium) can cause serotonin syndrome.<br><br>Serotonin syndrome features the triad of mental status changes (agitation, confusion), autonomic hyperactivity (tachycardia, hypertension, hyperthermia, diaphoresis) and neuromuscular abnormalities (tremor, clonus, hyperreflexia). Treatment is supportive, with cyproheptadine (serotonin antagonist) for severe cases. Tramadol also lowers seizure threshold.<br><br>C (Inhibition of serotonin reuptake) is correct because tramadol\'s serotonin reuptake inhibition causes serotonin syndrome risk. A (Direct serotonin agonism) is wrong because tramadol does not directly agonise serotonin receptors. B (Dopamine reuptake inhibition) is wrong because tramadol does not inhibit dopamine reuptake. D (μ-opioid agonism alone) is wrong because the μ-agonist effect alone does not cause serotonin syndrome.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Opioid Analgesics and Antagonists)</em>`},
    {q:'Which adverse effect is characteristic of high-dose opioid therapy?',o:['Respiratory depression','Hyperthyroidism','Polycythemia','Hypertension'],a:0,
    e:`Respiratory depression is characteristic of high-dose opioid toxicity. Opioids depress brainstem respiratory centres through μ-opioid receptor activation, reducing both rate and depth of respiration. At toxic doses, breathing may stop entirely (apnoea), causing hypoxia, cardiac arrest and death.<br><br>Other features of opioid toxicity include pinpoint pupils (miosis from Edinger-Westphal nucleus stimulation) and altered consciousness (sedation progressing to coma). The classic toxidrome is the triad of respiratory depression, miosis and altered consciousness. Naloxone reverses respiratory depression rapidly (within 1 to 2 minutes). Repeat doses may be needed because naloxone\'s half-life is shorter than most opioids\'.<br><br>A (Respiratory depression) is correct because respiratory depression is the lethal effect of opioid overdose. B (Hypertension) is wrong because opioids cause hypotension, not hypertension. C (Hyperthermia) is wrong because opioids do not raise temperature. D (Hyperglycemia) is wrong because opioids do not raise glucose.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Opioid Analgesics and Antagonists)</em>`},
    {q:'Which analgesic combination is commonly used in stepwise pain management in obstetrics?',o:['Morphine + insulin','Paracetamol + NSAID','Aspirin + warfarin','Codeine + heparin'],a:1,
    e:`Paracetamol plus NSAID is commonly used in stepwise pain management following the WHO analgesic ladder. Step 1 (mild pain): non-opioid analgesics (paracetamol, NSAIDs). Step 2 (moderate pain): weak opioids (codeine, tramadol) plus non-opioids. Step 3 (severe pain): strong opioids (morphine, fentanyl) plus non-opioids.<br><br>The combination of paracetamol with NSAID provides synergistic analgesia through different mechanisms (paracetamol acts centrally on COX; NSAIDs inhibit peripheral COX and reduce prostaglandin-mediated inflammation and pain sensitisation). This multimodal approach reduces opioid requirements and side effects. In postoperative obstetric pain, paracetamol plus NSAID plus opioid as needed is the standard approach.<br><br>B (Paracetamol + NSAID) is correct because this combination provides synergistic non-opioid analgesia. A (Paracetamol + insulin) is wrong because insulin is for diabetes, not pain. C (Paracetamol + penicillin) is wrong because penicillin is an antibiotic. D (Paracetamol + methyldopa) is wrong because methyldopa is an antihypertensive.<br><br><em>(Katzung Basic and Clinical Pharmacology; Chapter: Opioid Analgesics and Antagonists)</em>`}
  ];
})();